sc-appeal-61-2014	19 January 2022	Sumanawathie v. Susiripala	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Land Development Ordinance — Permit issuance — State land ownership — Alienation of land — Prevention of Frauds Ordinance — Rei vindicatio action — Bona fide possession — Ius retentionis — Ius tollendi — Compensation for improvements	Facts The plaintiff, D.M. Sumanawathie, instituted an action in the District Court of Monaragala seeking a declaration of title to a land based on a permit issued under the Land Development Ordinance and the ejectment of the defendant, D.M. Susiripala. The defendant contested the action, claiming ownership or possession of the land and seeking compensation for improvements made to the property. The District Court dismissed the plaintiff's action, concluding that the permit issued to the plaintiff was invalid under the Land Development Ordinance. Upon appeal, the High Court set aside the District Court's judgment and entered judgment in favor of the plaintiff, while permitting the defendant to remove the structures he had erected on the land. The defendant subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that the plaintiff proved her status as the permit-holder and established her rights to the land. Whether the High Court erred in law by failing to consider the plaintiff's age at the time of the initial permit issuance. Whether the High Court failed to apply the fundamental principles of rei vindicatio actions in determining the plaintiff's rights. Whether the High Court erred in law by denying the defendant compensation for improvements made to the land. Applicable Law Statutes: Land Development Ordinance Prevention of Frauds Ordinance Cases Referred to: Wasantha v. Premawathie - [sc-appeal-176/2014] Analysis Issue 1: Proof of permit and title Rule applied: Land Development Ordinance; rei vindicatio principles. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the permit P1 was issued by the Divisional Secretary, the lawful authority under the Land Development Ordinance. The document was not challenged via writ jurisdiction, and the Land Officer confirmed the plaintiff's position. The court held that the plaintiff discharged her burden of proof by demonstrating superior title on a balance of probabilities. Finding: The High Court did not err; the plaintiff sufficiently proved her status as the permit-holder. Issue 2: Age of the permit-holder Rule applied: Land Development Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The court examined the validity of the permit issuance. It found that the Divisional Secretary, as the competent authority, had conducted an inquiry into the dispute in 2000, leading to the issuance of P1 in 2001. The court determined that the validity of the permit could not be collaterally attacked in this civil proceeding. Finding: The contention regarding the plaintiff's age at the time of the original 1979 permit does not invalidate the current permit P1. Issue 3: Principles of rei vindicatio Rule applied: rei vindicatio principles; Wasantha v. Premawathie - [sc-appeal-176/2014]. Court's reasoning: The court clarified that in a rei vindicatio action, the court is not restricted to the plaintiff's evidence but must consider the defendant's case to determine competing claims. The defendant's claim of ownership via an informal writing (V1) was rejected as state land cannot be alienated by individuals, and such documents violate the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance. Finding: The High Court correctly applied the principles of rei vindicatio by evaluating the competing claims of the parties. Issue 4: Compensation for improvements Rule applied: ius tollendi (right to remove improvements). Court's reasoning: The court held that the defendant effected improvements at his own risk after being warned by the Divisional Secretary. As the plaintiff did not wish to retain the buildings and could not be compelled to pay compensation, the court found the ius tollendi appropriate. Finding: The High Court correctly allowed the defendant to remove the buildings rather than awarding monetary compensation. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected as the validity of the plaintiff's permit (Issue 1 and 2) established her superior title, which is the foundational requirement for a rei vindicatio action (Issue 3). Once the plaintiff's title was established and the defendant's claim of ownership was dismissed as legally void, the defendant's claim for compensation (Issue 4) became secondary, leading the court to apply the ius tollendi as a equitable resolution. Conclusion The Supreme Court answered the questions of law in the negative and dismissed the appeal. The judgment of the High Court in favor of the plaintiff is affirmed, with the defendant permitted to remove the improvements made to the land. Keywords Land Development Ordinance — Permit issuance — State land ownership — Alienation of land — Prevention of Frauds Ordinance — Rei vindicatio action — Bona fide possession — Ius retentionis — Ius tollendi — Compensation for improvements		SC/APPEAL/61/2014	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_61_2014.pdf
sc-appeal-131-2016	19 January 2022	Pushpalatha v. Suneetha and Abeywickrema	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Transfer of land — Constructive trust — Unjust enrichment — Evidence — Burden of proof — Fraudulent deeds — Informal agreements	Facts The Plaintiff, Rambandi Deveyalage Gamini Pushpalatha, initiated an action in the District Court against the Defendants, Wickrema Arachchilage Suneetha and Kapuwella Gamlath Ralalage Abeywickrema, seeking a decree based on the existence of a constructive trust or, alternatively, on the grounds of unjust enrichment. The Plaintiff alleged that she borrowed money from the 1st Defendant and transferred the subject property as security, supported by an informal agreement to retransfer the land upon repayment. The Plaintiff further alleged that the 1st Defendant failed to retransfer the property and instead transferred it to the 2nd Defendant. The 1st Defendant contended that the transfer was an absolute sale and denied the existence of any informal agreement or constructive trust. At trial, the Plaintiff provided inconsistent testimony, claiming for the first time that the deed was a forgery created from blank papers, contradicting her initial pleadings. The Plaintiff failed to produce the deed or the alleged informal agreement in evidence. The District Court dismissed the action due to the Plaintiff's failure to prove her case. The High Court subsequently affirmed the District Court's judgment. The Plaintiff appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court failed to consider that the deed in question was subject to an undertaking or condition of retransfer, thereby creating a constructive trust. Whether the High Court failed to consider that the District Court erred in law and fact in dismissing the Plaintiff's case. Applicable Law Statutes: Not specified Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Constructive trust and retransfer Rule applied: The court applied the principle that a party must prove the existence of a constructive trust through evidence, specifically by establishing the nature of the transfer and the existence of an agreement. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the Plaintiff failed to produce the deed or the informal agreement in evidence. Furthermore, the Plaintiffâ€™s testimony was contradictory, as she shifted her position from claiming the deed was a conditional transfer to alleging it was a forgery. Because the document was not produced and the evidence was unreliable, the court could not find that the transfer was conditional or subject to a constructive trust. Finding: The question is answered in the negative; the deed was an outright transfer, and no constructive trust was established. Issue 2: Error in law and fact Rule applied: The court applied the standard that a plaintiff bears the burden of proof in a civil action to establish their claim on a balance of probabilities. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the District Judge, as the trier of fact, found the Plaintiff's evidence to be unclear, inconsistent, and unsatisfactory. Since the Plaintiff failed to discharge the burden of proof, the District Court was correct in dismissing the action. The High Court acted properly in refusing to interfere with these findings of fact and law. Finding: The question is answered in the negative; the District Court did not err in dismissing the case due to the Plaintiff's failure to prove her claim. Interaction of Issues The findings on these issues are mutually reinforcing. The failure of the Plaintiff to provide consistent evidence or produce the necessary documents (Issue 1) directly resulted in her failure to meet the burden of proof required to sustain her action (Issue 2). The court's determination that the deed was an outright transfer rendered the alternative claim of unjust enrichment and the argument regarding the constructive trust legally unsustainable. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. No costs are awarded. Keywords Transfer of land — Constructive trust — Unjust enrichment — Evidence — Burden of proof — Fraudulent deeds — Informal agreements		SC/APPEAL/131/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_131_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-77-2013	20 January 2022	Galdeniyalage Ukkuwa v. Galdeniyalage Podina and Others	Achala Wengappuli, J.	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; K.K. Wickremasinghe, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Partition action — Kandyan law — Legitimacy — Illegitimacy — Paternal inheritance — Paraveni property — Associated marriage — Deega marriage — Burden of proof — Title investigation	Facts The Plaintiff instituted a partition action in the District Court of Kurunegala regarding a land called Udawattehena. The Plaintiff claimed a share of the corpus by paternal inheritance from his father, Singna. The Defendants, who were the Plaintiff's sister and her children, contested the action. The Defendants argued that the Plaintiff's father had mortgaged his share, which was later sold at an auction, and that the 1st Defendant had acquired prescriptive title to the land. The trial court rejected the Defendants' claims, finding that the 1st Defendant had failed to prove ouster or prescriptive title, and allocated shares based on the pedigree provided in the plaint. The Defendants appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal, arguing for the first time that the Plaintiff was an illegitimate child under Kandyan law because his parents' marriage was not registered, thereby disqualifying him from inheriting Paraveni property. The High Court dismissed the appeal, holding that the legitimacy issue was not raised at the trial and that the Plaintiff had established his status as a natural heir. The Defendants subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in its determination regarding the burden of proof concerning the Plaintiff's title. Whether the trial court failed to fulfill its statutory duty under the Partition Law to investigate the Plaintiff's title, specifically regarding his legitimacy. Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal misdirected itself on the classification of the property as Paraveni property under Section 10(1)(a) of the Kandyan Law Declaration and Amendment Act. Applicable Law Statutes: Partition Law No. 21 of 1977 Kandyan Law Declaration and Amendment Ordinance No. 39 of 1938 Evidence Ordinance No. 14 of 1895 Civil Procedure Code No. 2 of 1889 Births and Deaths Registration Act No. 17 of 1951 Cases Referred to: Raja v. Elisa - [1-sc-civ-min-27.05.1913] Kuma v. Banda - [21-nlr-294] Abubuker v. Fernando - [1987/v2-sri-lr-225] Appuhamy v. Punchihamy - [17-nlr-271] Cooray v. Wijesuriya - [62-nlr-158] Mudiyanse v. Ranaweera - [77-nlr-501] Sabaratnam v. Kandavanam - [60-nlr-35] Fernando v. Fernando - [2006/v2-sri-lr-188] Perera v. Fernando - [60-nlr-229] Mather v. Tamotharam Pillai - [6-nlr-246] Karunatatne v. Sirimalie - [53-nlr-444] Golagoda v. Mohideen - [40-nlr-92] Wijesekera v. Weliwiligoda - [61-nlr-133] Sturla v. Freccia - [5-ac-623] Perera v. Perera - [1986/v2-sri-lr-208] Ukku v. Kirihonda - [6-nlr-104] Ahugoda Ukku Etana v. Dombegoda Punchirala - [3-nlr-10] Maniapillai v. Sivasamy - [1980/v2-sri-lr-214] Sopinona v. Pitipanaaracchi - [2010/v1-sri-lr-87] Juliana Hamine v. Don Thomas - [59-nlr-546] Peiris v. Perera - [10-nlr-41] Silva v. Obeyesekera - [24-nlr-97] Mohammed v. Lebbe - [1996/v2-sri-lr-62] Seylan Bank Ltd v. Epasinghe - [sc-chc-39/2006] Hameed v. Cassim - [1996/v2-sri-lr-30] Nagubai Ammal v. Shama Rao - [air-sc-593] Thilagaratnam v. Athpunadan - [1996/v2-sri-lr-66] Attorney General v. Punchirala - [21-nlr-51] Analysis Issue 1: Burden of Proof Rule applied: The burden of proof in a partition action requires the plaintiff to establish their own title and the title of the defendants through legally admissible evidence. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that while a plaintiff must prove their title, the absence of a birth certificate is not fatal if other evidence establishes the family relationship. The Court relied on Sections 32(5) and 50 of the Evidence Ordinance, which allow for the admission of statements regarding family relationships when direct evidence is unavailable. The Defendants' own admissions regarding the family pedigree supported the Plaintiff's claim. Finding: The High Court did not err; the Plaintiff sufficiently discharged the evidentiary burden. Issue 2: Statutory Duty to Investigate Rule applied: Section 25 of the Partition Law requires the court to investigate the title of each party. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the duty to investigate under Section 25 is not a "voyage of discovery" but must be based on the pleadings, points of contest, and evidence presented. The Court found that the issue of legitimacy was not raised at trial, and there was no evidence warranting the court to frame an additional issue under Section 149 of the Civil Procedure Code. Finding: The trial court did not fail in its statutory duty as the issue of legitimacy was not a contested fact during the trial. Issue 3: Classification of Paraveni Property Rule applied: Section 10(1)(a) of the Kandyan Law Declaration and Amendment Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The Court determined that the evidence of a subsequent monogamous marriage between the Plaintiff's parents validated the union and the legitimacy of the children, regardless of any prior associated marriage. The Court applied the presumption of legitimacy and held that the property was correctly treated as Paraveni property inherited by the Plaintiff. Finding: The High Court did not misdirect itself; the property status was correctly determined based on the established pedigree and the validity of the parents' marriage. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected: the resolution of the legitimacy issue (Issue 3) confirms that the Plaintiff had a valid title to inherit, which in turn satisfies the burden of proof (Issue 1) and confirms that the trial court's failure to frame an issue on legitimacy (Issue 2) did not result in a miscarriage of justice, as the evidence supported the Plaintiff's status as a legitimate heir. Conclusion The Supreme Court affirmed the judgments of the High Court of Civil Appeal and the District Court of Kurunegala. The appeal of the Defendants was dismissed with costs. Keywords Partition action — Kandyan law — Legitimacy — Illegitimacy — Paternal inheritance — Paraveni property — Associated marriage — Deega marriage — Burden of proof — Title investigation		SC/APPEAL/77/2013	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_77_2013.pdf
sc-fr-55-2017	20 January 2022	Perera v. Dissanayake and Others	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Equal protection of the law — Lawful occupation — Public Service Commission — Efficiency Bar Examination — Probationary period — Service Minute — Administrative action — Concessionary period — Salary increments	Facts The Petitioner, an officer in the Sri Lanka Foreign Service, was appointed to Grade III on 10th July 1998 under the Sri Lanka Foreign Service Minute (P3). This required him to complete the First Efficiency Bar Examination within a three-year probationary period. The Petitioner passed five of six subjects in his first attempt in July 1999. He did not apply for the 2000 examination. In 2001, a new Service Minute (P4) was introduced, which required the examination to be held twice annually. The Petitioner sat for examinations in 2001 and 2002 but was unsuccessful. He eventually passed the examination in December 2003. The Public Service Commission (PSC) determined that the Petitioner had four examination opportunities to complete the requirement. Because he passed on his fifth attempt, the PSC applied Section 11:10 of Chapter II of the Establishments Code, which resulted in the deferment of his salary increments for the period between July 2002 and December 2003. The Petitioner challenged this decision, arguing he was entitled to more attempts and that the PSCâ€™s calculation was arbitrary and violated his fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the decision of the Public Service Commission to aggregate examination opportunities available under P3 and P4 on a pro-rated basis was arbitrary, irrational, or unreasonable. Whether the failure of the Petitioner to apply for the 2000 examination should be counted as an opportunity to complete the First Efficiency Bar Examination. Whether the Petitioner was treated differently from other officers, specifically Ms. Dhammika Semasinghe, in violation of Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 14(1)(g), 17, 126 Establishments Code, Chapter II, Sections 11:1, 11:2, 11:2:3, 11:7, 11:9, 11:10, 11:10:1, 15:1, 15:4:1 Cases Referred to: Karunathilaka v. Jayalath de Silva - [2003/v1-sri-lr-35] Wickremasinghe v. Ceylon Petroleum Corporation - [2001/v2-sri-lr-409] W.P.S. Wijerathna v. Sri Lanka Ports Authority - [sc-minutes-11th-december-2020] Damayanthi Namalee Haupe Liyanage Madawalagama v. H.P.S. Somasiri - [sc-minutes-26th-march-2012] Analysis Issue 1: Aggregation of examination opportunities Rule applied: Provisions of the Sri Lanka Foreign Service Minutes P3 and P4, and Section 11:10 of the Establishments Code. Court's reasoning: The court held that the Petitioner, having joined under P3, could not claim the benefits of P4 (which provided six opportunities) intended for later recruits. The PSC reasonably combined the remaining time under P3 with the increased frequency of exams under P4 to grant the Petitioner four opportunities. This pro-rated adjustment was a fair and objective method to transition the Petitioner between the two service minutes. Finding: The PSC's decision to aggregate opportunities was reasonable and not arbitrary. Issue 2: Counting the 2000 examination as an opportunity Rule applied: Section 11:10 of the Establishments Code. Court's reasoning: The court emphasized that public officers have a duty to act diligently. An officer cannot circumvent the requirement to pass an Efficiency Bar by failing to apply for an examination due to "pressure of work." The court noted that Section 11:10 serves as a merciful alternative to termination, and failure to utilize an available exam opportunity counts against the officer. Finding: The PSC's decision to count the 2000 examination as an opportunity was fair and consistent with the objectives of the Service Minute. Issue 3: Alleged discriminatory treatment Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution (Equality). Court's reasoning: The court reviewed the case of Ms. Dhammika Semasinghe and found that the PSC applied the same methodology to her as it did to the Petitioner. Both officers had their service under P3 accounted for in a pro-rated adjustment when P4 was introduced, and both had their failure to apply for exams counted as utilized opportunities. Finding: There was no evidence of discriminatory treatment; the Petitioner was treated consistently with other similarly situated officers. Interaction of Issues The findings on these issues are mutually reinforcing. The courtâ€™s determination that the PSCâ€™s methodology was reasonable (Issue 1) and that the Petitionerâ€™s own lack of diligence in 2000 was a valid factor (Issue 2) confirms that the PSC acted within its administrative discretion. This consistency negates the claim of arbitrary or discriminatory treatment (Issue 3), as the PSC applied a uniform, objective standard to all officers transitioning between the two Service Minutes. Conclusion The court held that the Petitionerâ€™s fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) were not infringed. The application is dismissed. No order is made as to costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Equal protection of the law — Lawful occupation — Public Service Commission — Efficiency Bar Examination — Probationary period — Service Minute — Administrative action — Concessionary period — Salary increments		SC/FR/55/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_55_2017.pdf
sc-fr-04/2017	20 January 2022	Perera v. Dissanayake and Others	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Equal protection of the law — Freedom to engage in a lawful occupation — Public Service Commission — Sri Lanka Foreign Service	Facts The Petitioner, an officer of the Sri Lanka Foreign Service, filed the present application alleging that the Respondents violated his fundamental rights to equality before the law and the equal protection of the law under Article 12(1) of the Constitution, as well as the freedom to engage in a lawful occupation under Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Subsequent to the filing of this application, the Public Service Commission made a further decision regarding the Petitioner, which led the Petitioner to file a second application, SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017, alleging similar violations of his fundamental rights. On 6th November 2019, the Supreme Court granted leave to proceed in both applications. As the grievances raised in the present application were subsumed within the scope of SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017, the court proceeded to hear the matters together. Upon the matter being taken up for argument, counsel for both the Petitioner and the Respondents informed the court that the parties would abide by the judgment delivered in SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017. Issues Whether the alleged violations of the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution in the present application are resolved by the determination in SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1) Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 14(1)(g) Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 17 Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 126 Cases Referred to: [sc-fr-55/2017] Analysis Issue 1: Resolution of claims via related application Rule applied: The court applied the principle of judicial economy and the agreement of the parties to be bound by the outcome of a related, more comprehensive proceeding. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the complaints raised in the present application were entirely subsumed within the subsequent application, SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017. Given that the parties explicitly consented to abide by the judgment in the latter case, the court determined that the disposition of the second application effectively addressed the merits of the present one. As the court dismissed SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017, it followed that the present application could not be sustained. Finding: The application is dismissed in light of the dismissal of the related application, SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017. Conclusion The application is dismissed without costs, consistent with the judgment delivered in the related matter of SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Equal protection of the law — Freedom to engage in a lawful occupation — Public Service Commission — Sri Lanka Foreign Service		SC/FR/4/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_4_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-6-2021	20 January 2022	Juwan Hettige Sriyalatha Silva v. Meemanage Duneetha Chandrakanthi Silva	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Partition Law — Co-ownership — Sale of land — Undivided share — District Court — High Court — Legal rights — Soil rights — Improvements — Trivial land extent — Judgment appeal — Practicality of partition — Evidence consideration	Facts The case revolves around a partition action concerning a small parcel of land measuring 1.86 perches, which is co-owned by the plaintiff, Juwan Hettige Sriyalatha Silva, and the defendant, Meemanage Duneetha Chandrakanthi Silva. Both parties concede their entitlement to equal shares of the land, but the defendant resides in a house built on the property, which complicates the partition process. The plaintiff's plaint indicates that if partitioning the land is deemed impractical, she is open to the court ordering the sale of the land in lots as per the Partition Law, No. 21 of 1977. The District Court initially ruled that both parties were entitled to a half share of the land, but due to the land's trivial size, it was impractical to physically divide it. Instead, the court ordered the sale of the plaintiff's half share to the defendant, who was already in possession of the house. The High Court later overturned this decision, arguing that the District Judge had misdirected herself by not considering the plaintiff's interest in soil rights and her intention to expand her roadway. This appeal to the Supreme Court arises from the High Court's judgment, with the plaintiff seeking to restore the District Court's order. Issues The primary issues in this case can be framed as follows: Whether the High Court's judgment defeats the purpose of section 26(3) of the Partition Law? Whether the High Court erred in law by failing to appreciate that the District Judge had correctly addressed issues regarding the sale of the plaintiff's share? Applicable Law Statutes: Partition Law, No. 21 of 1977 Cases Referred to: Hewavitharana v. Themis Silva (1961) 63 NLR 68; Ferdinands v. De Alwis (1957) 59 NLR 253; Ceylon Theatres Ltd v. Cinemas Ltd (1968) 70 NLR 337; Leelawathie v. Abeykoon [2005] 3 Sri LR 127. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the High Court's judgment defeats the purpose of section 26(3) of the Partition Law? Rule applied: Section 26(3) of the Partition Law, No. 21 of 1977. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court examined the High Court's ruling, which set aside the District Judge's order for the sale of the plaintiff's undivided half share to the defendant. The High Court's rationale was based on the assertion that the plaintiff had an interest in soil rights due to her ownership of adjacent land and her intention to expand her roadway. However, the Supreme Court emphasized that the plaintiff's own plaint indicated a willingness to accept a sale if partitioning was impractical. The court noted that the District Judge had correctly identified the impracticality of physically dividing the land due to its trivial size and had acted within the powers granted by section 26(3). The court referenced previous cases, including Hewavitharana v. Themis Silva, which affirmed the District Judge's authority to order a sale instead of a partition when the land's extent was insufficient for division. The Supreme Court concluded that the High Court had misinterpreted the implications of the plaintiff's claims regarding soil rights, which were irrelevant to the partition action at hand. Finding: The Supreme Court found that the High Court's judgment did indeed defeat the purpose of section 26(3) of the Partition Law. Issue 2: Whether the High Court erred in law by failing to appreciate that the District Judge had answered issue Nos. 9 and 10 correctly? Rule applied: The legal principles governing partition actions as outlined in the Partition Law. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court scrutinized the High Court's failure to recognize the District Judge's correct handling of the issues regarding the sale of the plaintiff's share. The District Judge had concluded that selling the plaintiff's undivided share to the defendant was the most practical solution to terminate the co-ownership of the land. The Supreme Court reiterated that the District Judge's findings were supported by the evidence presented during the trial, and the High Court's reversal lacked a solid legal foundation. The court highlighted that the plaintiff did not contest the procedure for the sale but rather the order itself, which was within the District Judge's discretion under the Partition Law. The Supreme Court also noted that the High Court had not provided sufficient justification for its decision to overturn the District Judge's order. Finding: The Supreme Court affirmed that the High Court had erred in law by failing to appreciate the correctness of the District Judge's findings. Interaction of Issues The two issues are interrelated as they both stem from the High Court's judgment, which the Supreme Court found to be flawed in its interpretation of the Partition Law and the facts of the case. The first issue addresses the overarching purpose of the law, while the second issue focuses on the specific application of that law in the context of the District Judge's findings. Both issues highlight the importance of adhering to the legal framework established by the Partition Law when determining the rights of co-owners in partition actions. Conclusion The Supreme Court ultimately set aside the High Court's judgment and restored the District Court's order for the sale of the plaintiff's undivided half share to the defendant. The court emphasized that the District Judge had acted within her legal authority and that the sale was the most practical solution given the circumstances. The appeal was allowed without costs, reaffirming the importance of adhering to the provisions of the Partition Law in partition actions. Keywords Partition Law — Co-ownership — Sale of land — Undivided share — District Court — High Court — Legal rights — Soil rights — Improvements — Trivial land extent — Judgment appeal — Practicality of partition — Evidence consideration	Shyamal A. Collure with Prabath S. Amarasinghe, A.P. Jayaweera and Raveendra Silva for the Defendant-Respondent-Appellant. Dr. Thashira Gunatilake for the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent.	SC/RULE/6/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_rule_6_2021.pdf
sc-fr-4-2017	21 January 2022	K. M. R. Perera v. Dharmadasa Dissanayake and Others	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	fundamental rights — equality before the law — equal protection of the law — lawful occupation — Public Service Commission — constitutional violations — leave to proceed — dismissal of application — costs — Sri Lanka Foreign Service — Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g)	Facts The Petitioner, K. M. R. Perera, an Officer of the Sri Lanka Foreign Service, filed an application under Articles 17 and 126 of the Constitution alleging violations of his fundamental rights. He claimed that the Respondents, which included members of the Public Service Commission and officials from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, had infringed upon his rights to equality before the law and the freedom to engage in a lawful occupation as guaranteed by Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. The background of the case reveals that after the filing of this application, the Public Service Commission made further decisions regarding the Petitioner, prompting him to file a second application, SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017, in February 2017. This second application also alleged violations of his fundamental rights under the same constitutional provisions. On 6th November 2019, the Supreme Court granted the Petitioner leave to proceed with both applications concerning the alleged infringements. However, it was noted that the complaints in the current application were subsumed within the issues raised in SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017. During the hearing on 26th July 2021, both parties agreed to abide by the judgment in the latter application. The Supreme Court subsequently delivered its judgment on SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017, dismissing it without costs, which consequently led to the dismissal of the current application as well. Issues The primary issues framed in this case include: Whether the actions of the Respondents constituted a violation of the Petitioner’s fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution? Whether the Respondents infringed upon the Petitioner’s right to engage in a lawful occupation as per Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution? Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 14(1)(g) Cases Referred to: SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017 - [citation not provided] Analysis Issue 1: Whether the actions of the Respondents constituted a violation of the Petitioner’s fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution? Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution Court's reasoning: The Court examined the allegations made by the Petitioner regarding the infringement of his fundamental rights. It was noted that the essence of Article 12(1) is to ensure equality before the law and equal protection of the law. The Petitioner argued that the decisions made by the Public Service Commission were arbitrary and discriminatory, thereby violating his rights. The Court emphasized the importance of the principle of equality and how it applies to public service appointments and decisions. The judgment highlighted that the Petitioner had not provided sufficient evidence to substantiate his claims of discrimination or arbitrary action by the Respondents. The Court also referenced previous cases where similar issues were raised, reinforcing the need for a clear demonstration of how the actions of the Respondents deviated from the principles of equality and fairness. The Court concluded that the Petitioner’s allegations did not meet the threshold required to establish a violation of Article 12(1). Finding: The Court found that the actions of the Respondents did not constitute a violation of the Petitioner’s fundamental rights under Article 12(1). Issue 2: Whether the Respondents infringed upon the Petitioner’s right to engage in a lawful occupation as per Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution? Rule applied: Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution Court's reasoning: The Court further analyzed the claims under Article 14(1)(g), which guarantees the right to engage in a lawful occupation. The Petitioner contended that the decisions made by the Respondents effectively barred him from fulfilling his professional duties and responsibilities as an officer of the Sri Lanka Foreign Service. The Court scrutinized the nature of the decisions taken by the Public Service Commission and whether they had a direct impact on the Petitioner’s ability to perform his role. The judgment noted that while the Petitioner had a right to engage in his occupation, this right is not absolute and can be subject to reasonable restrictions in the interest of public service efficiency and integrity. The Court found that the decisions made were within the purview of the Public Service Commission’s authority and did not amount to an infringement of the Petitioner’s rights under Article 14(1)(g). Finding: The Court concluded that the Respondents did not infringe upon the Petitioner’s right to engage in a lawful occupation as guaranteed by Article 14(1)(g). Interaction of Issues The issues of equality before the law and the right to engage in a lawful occupation are interrelated, as both stem from the fundamental rights enshrined in the Constitution. The Court’s analysis demonstrated that the failure to establish a violation of one right often mirrored the failure to establish a violation of the other. The Court’s reasoning indicated that the principles of fairness and equality are foundational to the functioning of public service and that any actions taken by the Public Service Commission must align with these principles. Conclusion The Supreme Court ultimately dismissed both SC (FR) Application No. 55/2017 and the current application without costs, affirming the decisions made by the Public Service Commission and underscoring the importance of adherence to constitutional provisions in public service matters. The judgment reinforced the notion that while fundamental rights are protected, they must be balanced against the operational needs and integrity of public service institutions. Keywords fundamental rights — equality before the law — equal protection of the law — lawful occupation — Public Service Commission — constitutional violations — leave to proceed — dismissal of application — costs — Sri Lanka Foreign Service — Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g)	Uditha Egalahewa, P.C., with Ranga Dayananda for the Petitioner. Nirmalan Wigneswaran, Deputy Solicitor General for the Respondents.	SC/FR/4/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_4_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-67-2017	10 February 2022	O.L.M. Macan Markar Limited v. Hambra Hotel Limited and Hambra Hotels Limited	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, J.; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; P. Padman Surasena, J.	Rent Act — Gazette Notification — Excepted premises — Retrospective effect — Companies Act — Tenancy — Applicability of regulations — Ultra vires — Rule making power	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent-Respondent, O.L.M. Macan Markar Limited, instituted an action in the District Court of Colombo against the Defendant-Petitioner-Appellant, Al-Hambra Hotels Limited, seeking the ejectment of the Appellant from the premises in suit and the recovery of damages. Both parties are limited liability companies registered under the Companies Act. The Appellant occupied the premises as a tenant prior to September 2003. The Plaintiff contended that the premises became "excepted premises" following the issuance of Extraordinary Gazette Notification No. 1305/17 dated 17 September 2003, which exempted premises where the landlord or tenant is a company registered under the Companies Act from the operation of the Rent Act No. 7 of 1972. The District Court ruled in favor of the Plaintiff, holding that the action was maintainable. The Court of Appeal subsequently dismissed the Appellant's appeal. The Appellant then appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal erred in concluding that the regulations in Gazette Notification No. 1305/17 were prospective and applicable to the tenancy in question, thereby entitling the Plaintiff to invoke them for ejectment. Whether the rule-making power conferred by the Rent Act was exercised within the statutory ambit or if the regulation was ultra vires. Whether the rights of the parties are to be determined as of the date of the institution of the action, thereby rendering the regulation applicable to a tenancy that commenced prior to the regulation's publication. Applicable Law Statutes: Rent Act No. 7 of 1972 Companies Act No. 17 of 1982 Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka 1978 Government Gazette (Publication) Ordinance of November 15, 1930 Cases Referred to: Baily v. De Crespigny - [1861-73-A.E.R-332] Peiris v. Rathnabatthi Aratchy - [50-nlr-138] Eastern Hardware Stores v. J.S. Fernando - [58-nlr-568] K. Mary Margret Fernando v. Beeta De Silva - [sc-appeal-193] Analysis Issue 1: Applicability and Prospectivity of the Regulation Rule applied: Section 43(2) of the Rent Act No. 7 of 1972. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the regulation was not retrospective because it did not impair vested rights acquired under existing laws prior to its enactment. Instead, it affected the future operation of the contract from the date of publication (09 September 2003). The Court reasoned that the Rent Act applies to premises, not to the contract of tenancy itself. Once the premises were declared "excepted," the Rent Act ceased to apply to them, and the parties' relationship became governed by private contract law. Finding: The regulation is prospective, and the Plaintiff is entitled to invoke it. Issue 2: Statutory Authority and Ultra Vires Rule applied: Section 2(5) and Section 43(1) of the Rent Act No. 7 of 1972; Article 168(4) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: The Court determined that the Minister acted within the statutory authority granted by Section 43(1) to give effect to the principles of the Rent Act, which includes defining the scope of "excepted premises." The power to amend the schedule of excepted premises is explicitly provided for in Section 2(5). The Court found no inconsistency or repugnancy that would render the regulation ultra vires. Finding: The regulation is valid and enforceable. Issue 3: Determination of Rights at Date of Action Rule applied: General principle that rights are determined at the time of the institution of the action. Court's reasoning: The action was filed on 20 May 2005, which is after the publication of the Gazette Notification on 09 September 2003. Relying on K. Mary Margret Fernando v. Beeta De Silva, the Court held that the legal status of the premises at the time of the institution of the action governs the proceedings. Since the premises were "excepted" by the time the plaint was filed, the Rent Act did not bar the ejectment. Finding: The rights of the parties are determined as of the date of the action, and the regulation applies. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing: the determination that the regulation is prospective (Issue 1) and validly enacted (Issue 2) confirms that the legal status of the premises changed as of 09 September 2003. This change in status directly informs the determination of rights at the time of the action (Issue 3), ensuring that the court applies the law as it existed when the litigation commenced. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The Supreme Court affirmed that the regulation was validly enacted and applicable to the premises at the time the action was instituted. Keywords Rent Act — Gazette Notification — Excepted premises — Retrospective effect — Companies Act — Tenancy — Applicability of regulations — Ultra vires — Rule making power		SC/APPEAL/67/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_67_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-130-2015	20 February 2022	Karunanayake and Others v. Mannapperuma	Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; P. Padman Surasena, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Lex Aquilia — Negligence — Duty of care — Damages — Roman-Dutch law — Judicial adaptation — Public examinations	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent, a student, sat for the G.C.E. Advanced Level examination in August 2001. She was duly admitted to sit for several subjects, including General English. On the day of the General English paper, she arrived at the examination center and occupied a desk. An invigilator informed her that her examination number was not on the list and directed her to the Chief Invigilator, the 1st Defendant-Appellant. The 1st Appellant questioned her entitlement to sit for the paper and demanded she produce her timetable. As she did not have the document with her, the 1st Appellant refused to allow her to sit for the examination and instructed her to return home. The Plaintiff-Respondent returned home, retrieved the timetable, and returned to the center, but was then denied entry to the afternoon session of the examination on the basis that she was marked absent and the time for commencement had passed. The Plaintiff-Respondent subsequently filed a District Court action claiming damages for the loss of opportunity to sit for the examination and for the resulting mental trauma. The District Court held that the 1st Appellant acted negligently by failing to verify the Plaintiff-Respondent's entitlement through the attendance sheet or her admission card, which was in his custody. The High Court affirmed this decision, awarding Rs. 1,000,000.00 in damages. The Defendants-Appellants appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the 1st Appellantâ€™s failure to verify the Plaintiff-Respondentâ€™s entitlement to sit for the examination before excluding her constituted actionable negligence under the Lex Aquilia. Whether the Lex Aquilia can be adapted to allow for the recovery of general damages for psychological trauma and prospective loss in the absence of proven patrimonial loss. Whether the award of Rs. 1,000,000.00 in damages was justified in law. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka Public Examinations Act No. 25 Adoption of Roman-Dutch Law Act (Chapter 12, Legislative Enactments of Ceylon 1956) Ordinance No. 5 of 1835 Cases Referred to: Prof. Priyani Soyza v. Rienzie Arsecularatne - [2001/v2-sri-lr-293] Gaffoor v. Wilson - [1990/v1-sri-lr-142] Union Government v. Warneke - [1911-ad-657] Matthews v. Young - [1922-ad-492] Lillicrap, Wassenaar and Partners v. Pilkington Brothers - [1985/v1-sa-475] Cape of Good Hope Bank v. Fischer - [1886-4-sc-368] Sultan v. Peiris - [35-nlr-57] Korossa Rubber Company v. Silva - [20-nlr-65] Suppramania Chetty v. The Fiscal, Western Province - [19-nlr-129] Attorney General v. Smith - [11-nlr-126] Parmsoty v. Veenayagamoorthy - [44-nlr-361] Wije Bus Co. Ltd. v. Soysa - [50-nlr-350] Kaluwalage Champika Kumari De Silva v. Kodithuwakku Arachchige Neville Kodithuwakku - [sc-appeal-172/2012] General Manager of Railways v. Bhadra De Silva Rajakaruna - [sc-appeal-62/2013] C. Kodeeswaran v. The Attorney-General - [72-nlr-337] Lily M. De Costa v. Bank of Ceylon - [72-nlr-457] The Government Agent, Central Province v. Letchiman Chetty - [24-nlr-36] McLoughlin v. O'Brian - [1983-1-ac-410] Chissel v. R.C. Chapman - [56-nlr-121] Bandahamy v. Senanayake - [62-nlr-313] Edwards v. Hyde - [1903-ts-381] Lord v. Gillwald - [1907-edc-65] Analysis Issue 1: Actionable Negligence Rule applied: The Lex Aquilia requires proof of a wrongful act, fault (negligence), and resulting loss. The standard of care is that of a diligens paterfamilias. Court's reasoning: The 1st Appellant, as Chief Invigilator, had a legal duty of care toward the candidate. He failed to check the attendance sheet or the admission card (which was in his custody) to verify the Plaintiff-Respondent's entitlement. His version of events was found to be improbable and lacked credibility, especially given his failure to record the incident in the required journal. Finding: The 1st Appellantâ€™s conduct was negligent and constituted a breach of his legal duty of care. Issue 2: Adaptation of Lex Aquilia Rule applied: The Roman-Dutch common law is a living system that may be adapted by the judiciary to suit contemporary requirements, provided it does not violate fundamental principles or legislative intent. Court's reasoning: The court held that the Lex Aquilia is not a static instrument. To prevent a failure of justice, the court recognized that victims of actionable negligence who suffer psychological trauma or infringement of legal rights are entitled to general damages, even if patrimonial loss is not strictly calculable. Finding: The Lex Aquilia can be adapted to allow for general damages in cases of psychological trauma and infringement of rights. Issue 3: Award of Damages Rule applied: Damages may be awarded as a cumulative effect of nominal, exemplary, and general damages to compensate for psychological harm and prospective loss. Court's reasoning: The court found that the Plaintiff-Respondent suffered significant psychological trauma and prospective loss of opportunity. The award of Rs. 1,000,000.00 was deemed a reasonable and equitable assessment of the cumulative harm. Finding: The award of Rs. 1,000,000.00 is lawful and justified. Interaction of Issues The findings on negligence and the adaptability of the Lex Aquilia are interdependent. By establishing that the 1st Appellantâ€™s conduct was a breach of duty, the court created the necessary foundation to apply the adapted Lex Aquilia to award damages for non-patrimonial loss, thereby ensuring the Plaintiff-Respondent was not left without a remedy. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The judgment of the High Court is affirmed, and the Appellants are held jointly liable to pay the awarded damages with legal interest from the date of the District Court judgment. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Lex Aquilia — Negligence — Duty of care — Damages — Roman-Dutch law — Judicial adaptation — Public examinations		SC/APPEAL/130/2015	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_130_2015.pdf
sc-fr-147-2018	20 February 2022	Re Rizna and Others v. Seneviratne and Others	Priyantha Jayawardena PC, J	Priyantha Jayawardena PC, J; Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Admission to school — Circular No. 22/2017 — Religious quota — Proximity category — Past Pupils category — Brothers category — Equality before the law — Allocation of vacancies	Facts The 1st petitioner filed this application on behalf of her minor son, the 2nd petitioner, alleging that the denial of his admission to Grade-1 of Vidyaloka College, Galle, for the 2018 academic year violated his fundamental rights. The petitioners contended that the school, being a government-vested institution, was bound by Ministry of Education circular No. 22/2017. They asserted that the school historically admitted three Muslim students per year, representing a 3% quota. The 2nd petitioner applied under both the Proximity and Brothers categories. Although he held the highest marks in the Brothers category, he was denied admission. The petitioners argued that because a Muslim applicant selected under the Past Pupils category declined the offer, that vacancy should have been reallocated to the Brothers category, thereby entitling the 2nd petitioner to admission. The 1st respondent, the Principal of the school, maintained that the Muslim quota was 2% of the total vacancies for students selected by interviews, which equated to two vacancies for the 2018 academic year. The respondents contended that the vacancy left by the student who declined admission should be allocated to the Proximity category in accordance with the circular's provisions, as the Brothers category was already full. Issues Whether the Muslim student quota for Grade-1 admissions at Vidyaloka College is 2% or 3% of the total vacancies for students selected by interviews. Whether the denial of admission to the 2nd petitioner under the Brothers category, following a vacancy in the Past Pupils category, constituted a violation of Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1) Assisted Schools and Training Schools (Special Provisions) Act No. 05 Assisted Schools and Training Schools (Supplementary Provisions) Act No. 08 Cases Referred to: Haputhantirige v. Attorney General - [2007/v1-sri-lr-101] Farook v. Dharmaratne - [2005/v1-sri-lr-133] Analysis Issue 1: Determination of the Muslim quota Rule applied: Ministry of Education Circular No. 22/2017. Court's reasoning: The court examined admission lists from 2009 to 2017, which demonstrated that only two Muslim students were admitted annually. Furthermore, documents from 2007, 2012, 2013, and 2014 explicitly stated the Muslim quota as 2%. The petitioners failed to provide evidence to support their claim of a 3% quota. Finding: The court held that the Muslim quota for Grade-1 at Vidyaloka College is 2% of the total vacancies for students selected by interviews. Issue 2: Allocation of vacancies and Article 12(1) Rule applied: Section 7.1 of Circular No. 22/2017 and Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: The court calculated that 2% of the 99 vacancies available for interview-selected students resulted in two vacancies for Muslim applicants. The evidence showed that all 15 vacancies allocated to the Brothers category were already filled. Therefore, the vacancy left by the student who declined admission could not be allocated to the Brothers category without exceeding the limit set by the circular. The court determined that the vacancy should be allocated to the Proximity category, where the 2nd petitioner only held the 7th highest marks among Muslim applicants. Finding: The court found no illegality or arbitrariness in the admission process, concluding that the 2nd petitioner was not entitled to the vacancy and that his fundamental rights under Article 12(1) were not violated. Interaction of Issues The resolution of the first issue regarding the 2% quota established the total number of available seats for Muslim applicants. This finding directly constrained the court's interpretation of the second issue, as it confirmed that the school had correctly identified the number of vacancies to be filled. Consequently, the strict adherence to the category-specific limits in the circular rendered the petitioners' request to reallocate the vacancy to the Brothers category legally impermissible. Conclusion The court held that the respondents did not violate the fundamental rights of the 2nd petitioner. The application is dismissed with no order as to costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Admission to school — Circular No. 22/2017 — Religious quota — Proximity category — Past Pupils category — Brothers category — Equality before the law — Allocation of vacancies		SC/FR/147/2018	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_147_2018.pdf
sc-fr-222-2016	21 February 2022	Abeyratne v. Ceylon Electricity Board and Others	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Way leave — Electricity supply — Public road — Private land — Discrimination — Article 12(1) of the Constitution — Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution	Facts The Petitioner is the owner of two blocks of land known as Walatahena and Aliyawetuna Hena. He constructed a private road connecting these lands to provide access to the beach. The 11th Respondent, who has been in forcible occupation of a portion of the Petitioner's land, sought to obtain an electricity connection by claiming that the Petitioner's private road was a public road. The Petitioner consistently objected to these attempts, notifying the 6th, 7th, and 8th Respondents that the road was private and that no consent for a way leave had been granted. Despite these objections, the 8th Respondent issued a letter stating that the road was a public road belonging to the Tangalle Pradeshiya Sabha and that there was no objection to the electricity supply. Relying on this letter, the 6th and 9th Respondents bypassed the mandatory statutory inquiry process required when a landowner objects to a way leave. The electricity lines were subsequently installed across the Petitioner's land. The Petitioner filed this fundamental rights application alleging that the actions of the 6th, 8th, and 9th Respondents violated his rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the failure of the 6th, 8th, and 9th Respondents to conduct a mandatory inquiry regarding the way leave application violated the Petitioner's right to equal protection of the law under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the actions of the Respondents constituted an infringement of the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1), 14(1)(g) Primary Courts Procedure Act, Section 66 Sri Lanka Electricity Act No. 20 of 2009 (as amended) Cases Referred to: C.W. Mackie & Co Ltd v. Hugh Molagoda - [1986/v1-sri-lr-300] Wijesinghe v. Attorney General - [1979/v1-sri-lr-102] Kaviratne v. Commissioner General of Examinations - [2012-blr-140] Ananda Dharmadasa v. Ariyaratne Hewage - [2008/v2-sri-lr-19] Elmore Perera v. Major Montague Jayawickrema - [1985/v1-sri-lr-285] Analysis Issue 1: Violation of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution and Schedule I of the Sri Lanka Electricity Act No. 20 of 2009 (as amended). Court's reasoning: The court found that the 6th, 8th, and 9th Respondents acted in collusion to bypass the mandatory statutory requirement to hold an inquiry when a landowner objects to a way leave. The 8th Respondent arbitrarily declared the private road to be a public road without evidence, and the 9th Respondent, despite being aware of the Petitioner's long-standing objections, dispensed with the inquiry process. The court held that this was not a mere error of judgment but a deliberate, calculated act of hostile discrimination against the Petitioner, denying him the equal protection of the law. Finding: The Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1) were infringed by the 6th, 8th, and 9th Respondents. Issue 2: Violation of Article 14(1)(g) Rule applied: Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: The Petitioner argued that the unlawful installation of electricity lines hindered his ability to attract investors for a luxury resort project. However, the court determined that there was insufficient evidence to establish that the Respondents' actions specifically infringed upon the Petitioner's freedom to engage in a lawful occupation or business beyond the established violation of Article 12(1). Finding: The court found it unnecessary to consider whether the acts constituted an infringement of Article 14(1)(g). Interaction of Issues The findings on the violation of Article 12(1) were sufficient to dispose of the application. The court's determination that the Respondents acted with a "deliberate design" to deny the Petitioner a fair inquiry rendered the secondary claim under Article 14(1)(g) moot, as the primary relief was granted based on the breach of equal protection. Conclusion The application is allowed. The court declares that the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1) were infringed and orders the 6th, 8th, and 9th Respondents to pay Rs. 300,000 each as compensation. The decision of the 8th Respondent declaring the road to be a public road is quashed, and the parties are directed to maintain the status quo until the 9th Respondent conducts a proper inquiry. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Way leave — Electricity supply — Public road — Private land — Discrimination — Article 12(1) of the Constitution — Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution		SC/FR/222/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_222_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-157-2019	22 February 2022	Avenra Gardens (Private) Limited v. AG and Others	Janak De Silva, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Janak De Silva, J.	Leave to appeal — Settlement agreement — Consent decree — Code of Civil Procedure — Mutuality of contract — Appearance of counsel — Execution of decree	Facts Avenra Gardens (Private) Limited, the Plaintiff-Respondent, initiated legal action in the Commercial High Court. On October 31, 2017, terms of settlement were recorded in open court. The journal entry and the subsequent order of the Commercial High Court judge specified that the settlement was between the Plaintiff and the 1st and 2nd Defendants only. The record of these proceedings was signed by the representatives of the Plaintiff and the 1st and 2nd Defendants, but not by any representative of the 4th Defendant-Appellant, Seylan Bank PLC. On December 14, 2017, the Commercial High Court judge observed that the 4th Defendant-Appellant had agreed to release money deposited against a letter of credit, despite the 4th Defendant-Appellant not being a party to the original settlement terms. Subsequently, the Plaintiff-Respondent filed a motion to execute the decree against the 4th Defendant-Appellant. The 4th Defendant-Appellant objected to this execution. The Commercial High Court judge allowed the application for execution of the writ against the 4th Defendant-Appellant on August 26, 2019, leading to the present appeal. Issues Whether the Commercial High Court judge erred in failing to recognize that the settlement recorded on October 31, 2017, was exclusively between the Plaintiff and the 1st and 2nd Defendants. Whether the Commercial High Court judge erred in failing to consider that no decree was entered against the 4th Defendant-Appellant pursuant to the settlement, thereby rendering the execution of the writ against the 4th Defendant-Appellant legally unjustified. Applicable Law Statutes: Code of Civil Procedure, Section 91 Code of Civil Procedure, Section 408 Provincial High Court (Special Provisions) Act No. 10 of 1996, Section 5(2) Cases Referred to: Faleel v. Argeen and Others - [2004/v1-sri-lr-48] Dassanaike v. Dassanaike - [30-nlr-385] Punchibanda v. Punchibanda et al - [42-nlr-382] Fernando v. Sinnoris Appu - [20-nlr-460] Sinna Veloo v. Messrs. Lipton Limited - [66-nlr-214] Abubakker v. Ismall Lebbe - [11-nlr-309] Perera v. Battaglia - [58-nlr-447] Cornel & Company Limited v. Mitsui & Company Limited and Others - [2000/v1-sri-lr-57] Analysis Issue 1: Scope of the settlement agreement Rule applied: Section 408 of the Code of Civil Procedure. Court's reasoning: The court emphasized that a consent decree requires consensus ad idem and must be notified to the court by motion signed by the registered attorneys of all parties concerned. The court found that the terms recorded on October 31, 2017, explicitly identified only the Plaintiff and the 1st and 2nd Defendants. Furthermore, the record was only signed by those specific parties. The court rejected the argument that the mere presence of the 4th Defendant-Appellant's attorney in court constituted consent to the settlement terms. Finding: The 4th Defendant-Appellant was not a party to the settlement agreement. Issue 2: Validity of the execution of the writ Rule applied: Section 408 of the Code of Civil Procedure. Court's reasoning: The court held that a decree must be passed in accordance with the agreement notified to the court. Since the 4th Defendant-Appellant was not a party to the settlement, no valid decree existed against it. The court noted that the trial judge's assertion that the 4th Defendant-Appellant had signed the record was factually incorrect. Additionally, the court affirmed that the 4th Defendant-Appellant was entitled to challenge the interlocutory order regarding the execution of the writ during the present appeal. Finding: The execution of the writ against the 4th Defendant-Appellant was legally invalid. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing; because the 4th Defendant-Appellant was not a party to the settlement under Section 408 of the Code of Civil Procedure, there was no legal basis for the trial court to enter or execute a decree against it. The failure to establish the 4th Defendant-Appellant's consent rendered the subsequent enforcement proceedings void. Conclusion The appeal is allowed and the order of the Commercial High Court dated August 26, 2019, is set aside. The application for the execution of the writ against the 4th Defendant-Appellant is dismissed. Keywords Leave to appeal — Settlement agreement — Consent decree — Code of Civil Procedure — Mutuality of contract — Appearance of counsel — Execution of decree		SC/APPEAL/157/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_157_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-74-2019	22 February 2022	Walimunidewage Indrasena v. Wijewardena and Others	Janak De Silva, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Janak De Silva, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Appeal — Notice of appeal — Time limit for filing — Journal entry — Date stamp — Section 114(d) of the Evidence Ordinance — Section 92 of the Civil Procedure Code — Presumption of regularity — Erroneous minute	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant instituted an action in the District Court of Pugoda seeking the ejectment of the Defendant-Appellant-Respondents from the corpus. The District Court entered judgment in favor of the Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant. The Defendants appealed this decision to the Court of Appeal. During the appellate proceedings, the Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant raised a preliminary objection, asserting that the notice of appeal was filed out of time. The date stamp on the notice of appeal indicated it was filed on 07.09.2000, which exceeded the statutory time limit. The Court of Appeal overruled this objection, relying on a minute in journal entry No. 82 which suggested the notice was filed within the stipulated time. The Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant subsequently appealed this order to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law by applying the presumption under Section 114(d) of the Evidence Ordinance to a journal entry that did not accurately reflect the date of filing. Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law by disregarding direct evidence of the filing date in favor of an erroneous journal entry. Applicable Law Statutes: Evidence Ordinance, Section 114(d) Civil Procedure Code, Section 92 Civil Procedure Code, Section 754(4) Constitution, Article 128 Cases Referred to: Nachchiduwa v. Mansoor - [1995/v2-sri-lr-273] S. Seebert Silva v. F. Aronona Silva - [60-nlr-272] Analysis Issue 1: Application of the presumption under Section 114(d) Rule applied: Section 114(d) of the Evidence Ordinance, which allows a court to presume that judicial and official acts have been performed regularly, and Section 92 of the Civil Procedure Code, which mandates the maintenance of a journal for all events in an action. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the act of a party filing a notice of appeal is not a judicial or official act; therefore, the presumption in Section 114(d) does not apply to the act of filing itself. While journal entries made in compliance with Section 92 of the Civil Procedure Code may attract the presumption of regularity, this only applies when the entry records an event as it occurred. Journal entry No. 82 merely stated the notice was filed within time without recording the actual date of the event. Consequently, the Court of Appeal erred in invoking this presumption to validate the filing date. Finding: The Court of Appeal incorrectly applied the presumption under Section 114(d) of the Evidence Ordinance. Issue 2: Reliance on direct evidence versus journal entries Rule applied: The principle that legal presumptions should only be invoked when the court is deprived of direct evidence. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that the District Court registry stamp clearly indicated the notice was received on 07.09.2000. Furthermore, the motion filed by the Defendants and the related postal articles were also dated 07.09.2000. The Court distinguished the present case from Nachchiduwa v. Mansoor, noting that in that case, the court relied on the date on the petition itself rather than a conflicting journal entry. The Court concluded that the journal entry was the result of an erroneous calculation by the clerk and that the direct evidence conclusively proved the notice was filed out of time. Finding: The Court of Appeal erred by disregarding cogent direct evidence in favor of an erroneous journal entry. Interaction of Issues The findings are intrinsically linked; the improper application of the presumption of regularity (Issue 1) led the Court of Appeal to ignore the direct evidence of the filing date (Issue 2). By correctly identifying that the presumption was inapplicable, the Court was able to properly weigh the direct evidence, which rendered the journal entry's inaccuracy manifest. Conclusion The Supreme Court set aside the order of the Court of Appeal dated 30.05.2018. The preliminary objection is upheld, and the appeal filed by the Defendants in the Court of Appeal is dismissed in limine. Keywords Appeal — Notice of appeal — Time limit for filing — Journal entry — Date stamp — Section 114(d) of the Evidence Ordinance — Section 92 of the Civil Procedure Code — Presumption of regularity — Erroneous minute		SC/APPEAL/74/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_74_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-199-2017	23 February 2022	Ramasamy and Vaitheeswaran v. Soundarajan	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; K.K. Wickremasinghe, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Trust Ordinance — Section 75 — Section 76 — Appointment of trustees — Bona fide purchaser — Intervention in appeal — Civil Procedure Code — Section 839 — Inherent powers of the court — Representative character — Hereditary rights	Facts Subramaniam Ramasamy and Balasubramaniam Vaitheeswaran filed an action in the District Court of Kandy under the Trusts Ordinance seeking to declare the office of trustees of the Sri Selvavinyagar Temple Trust vacant and to appoint new trustees. The District Court entered an order nisi, which was subsequently made absolute. V.R. Soundarajan, the respondent, appealed this decision to the Civil Appellate High Court. During the pendency of the appeal, Nadesan Sathasivam filed a petition under Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code seeking to intervene in the appeal, joined by V.R. Soundarajan. The petitioners alleged that the temple was managed under a specific trust instrument and that the original court failed to consider the interests of all beneficiaries or the wishes of those empowered to appoint trustees. The Civil Appellate High Court allowed the intervention, citing the need to exercise inherent powers to ensure justice. Subramaniam Ramasamy appealed this order to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Civil Appellate High Court erred in law by allowing a third party to intervene in appellate proceedings under Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code. Whether the Civil Appellate High Court misdirected itself by delving into the merits of the appeal while considering a mere application for intervention. Applicable Law Statutes: Trusts Ordinance Civil Procedure Code (Sections 16, 18, 19, 754, 755, 839) Cases Referred to: Banda v. Dharmaratne - [24-nlr-210] Ratwatte v. Bandara - [70-nlr-231] Rev. Kiralagama Suumanatissa Thero v. Aluwihare - [1985/v1-sri-lr-19] Meegama Gurunnanselage Don Sirisena Wijeyakoon v. Indrani Margret Wijeyakoon - [1986/v2-ca-lr-378] Kamala v. Andris - [41-nlr-71] Wakachicku Construction Co. Ltd. v. Road Development Authority - [2013/v1-sri-lr-164] All Ceylon Commercial and Industrial Workers Union v. Ceylon Petroleum Corporation - [1995/v2-sri-lr-295] Jeyaraj Fernandopulle v. De Silva - [1996/v1-sri-lr-70] Kaviratne v. Commissioner General of Examination - [2012-blr-139] Seneviratne v. Abeykoon - [1986/v2-sri-lr-2] Maha Nayaka Thero Malwatta Vihare v. Registrar General - [39-nlr-186] Analysis Issue 1: Intervention at the appellate stage Rule applied: Sections 18 and 19 of the Civil Procedure Code, which govern the addition of parties, and Section 839 regarding inherent powers. Court's reasoning: The court held that a direct appeal is a continuation of the original action. Statutory provisions for adding parties or intervention must be exercised before the final judgment in the original court. Section 839 cannot be used to override express provisions of the Civil Procedure Code or to create new jurisdictions. Inherent powers are adjunct to existing jurisdiction and cannot be used to transform an appellate court into a court of first instance. Finding: The Civil Appellate High Court acted outside its jurisdiction by allowing intervention at the appeal stage. Issue 2: Delving into merits Rule applied: Principles of appellate jurisdiction and summary procedure under the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The High Court accepted new factual allegations as true without them being tested in the original court. By doing so, it bypassed the procedural requirements of Sections 384-387 of the Civil Procedure Code, which govern the presentation of evidence and objections in summary proceedings. The court concluded that the High Court improperly assumed the role of an original court to adjudicate new stances. Finding: The High Court misdirected itself by delving into the merits of the case during an interlocutory application for intervention. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing: because the High Court lacked the legal authority to permit intervention at the appellate stage (Issue 1), its subsequent attempt to evaluate the merits of the new parties' claims (Issue 2) was inherently flawed and procedurally invalid. The resolution of the first issue rendered the second issue a consequence of the initial jurisdictional error. Conclusion The appeal is allowed, and the order of the Civil Appellate High Court dated 02.06.2016 is set aside and vacated. The application for intervention filed by Nadesan Sathasivam is dismissed with costs awarded to the petitioner. Keywords Trust Ordinance — Section 75 — Section 76 — Appointment of trustees — Bona fide purchaser — Intervention in appeal — Civil Procedure Code — Section 839 — Inherent powers of the court — Representative character — Hereditary rights		SC/APPEAL/199/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_199_2017.pdf
sc-hcca-la-378-17	08 March 2022	Ransegoda Wimalasiri Thero v. Dellawa Sisiela Thero (Deceased) and Others	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, CJ.; L.T.B Dehideniya, J.; Murdu N.B Fernando, PC, J.	substitution — deceased party — legal representative — Civil Procedure Code — appeal — Viharadhipathi — temple property — proper person — next of kin — higher ordination certificate — controlling Viharadhipathi — prima facie evidence — jurisdiction — Supreme Court Rules	Facts The case revolves around a dispute concerning the position of Viharadhipathi of Ganegoda Rajamahaviharaya, a temple located in Morawaka. The Plaintiff, Ransegoda Wimalasiri Thero, initiated proceedings in the District Court seeking a declaration that he is the rightful Viharadhipathi and an order to evict the Defendant, Dellawa Sisiela Thero. The District Court ruled in favor of the Plaintiff. However, during the proceedings, the Defendant passed away, leading to the substitution of Dellawa Suneetha Thero as the Defendant-Appellant-Respondent. The Respondent subsequently appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal, which overturned the District Court's decision. The Plaintiff then sought leave to appeal to the Supreme Court, challenging the High Court's ruling. The legal framework governing the substitution of deceased parties in civil proceedings is critical to this case. The Civil Procedure Code Amendment Law No. 20 of 1977 initially restricted substitution to next of kin, but subsequent amendments, particularly the Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 08 of 2017, broadened this scope to allow legal representatives to be substituted. This change is significant as it impacts the rights of parties in ongoing litigation when a party dies. Issues Whether the substitution of the deceased Defendant with the legal representative is valid under the current legal framework. Whether the Plaintiff has established his entitlement to be recognized as the Viharadhipathi and thus entitled to prosecute the appeal. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code Amendment Law No. 20 of 1977; Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 08 of 2017; Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 79 of 1988. Cases Referred to: Kusumawathie Vs. Kanthi - [2004] 1 Sri L.R 350; T.Pannanada Thero Vs. G. Sumangala Thero - 68 NLR 367. Analysis Issue 1: Validity of Substitution Rule applied: Section 760(A) of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court examined the legal provisions surrounding the substitution of parties in civil appeals, particularly focusing on Section 760(A) of the Civil Procedure Code, which allows for the substitution of a deceased party without the requirement of being a next of kin. The Court emphasized that the primary consideration is whether the person seeking substitution is deemed a 'proper person' to continue the proceedings. The judgment highlighted that the law has evolved to ensure that the rights of parties are preserved even in the event of a party's death. The Court referenced the case of Kusumawathie Vs. Kanthi, where it was established that the requirement for next of kin substitution does not apply in appellate proceedings. The Court noted that the Respondent's argument, which relied on the precedent set in T.Pannanada Thero Vs. G. Sumangala Thero, was flawed as it was based on a legal framework that had since changed. The Court reiterated that the substitution process is intended to facilitate the continuation of the appeal and that the Appellate Court has the discretion to determine who is a proper person for substitution. The Court found that the Petitioner, being the most senior pupil of the deceased Plaintiff, had established a prima facie case for substitution based on his claim to the position of Viharadhipathi. Finding: The Court concluded that the Petitioner was entitled to be substituted as the Substituted Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant for the purpose of prosecuting the appeal. Issue 2: Entitlement to Viharadhipathi Position Rule applied: Legal principles governing the succession of temple property. Court's reasoning: The Court further analyzed the implications of the Plaintiff's claim to the position of Viharadhipathi. It was noted that the title to temple property is vested in the controlling Viharadhipathi, and upon the death of the incumbent, the title automatically devolves to the next qualified individual. The Plaintiff's assertion that he is the rightful successor was supported by historical context regarding the succession of Viharadhipathi positions. The Court examined the evidence presented, including the Higher Ordination Certificate tendered by the Petitioner, which indicated his qualifications and standing within the Buddhist community. The Respondent's challenge to the authenticity of this certificate was acknowledged, but the Court determined that the primary focus should be on the legal entitlement to the position rather than the procedural aspects of the certificate's validity. The Court emphasized that the Petitioner had provided sufficient evidence to establish his claim to the position of Viharadhipathi, thereby reinforcing his right to be substituted in the appeal. Finding: The Court affirmed that the Petitioner had established his entitlement to the position of Viharadhipathi, which justified his substitution in the appeal. Interaction of Issues The issues of substitution and entitlement to the Viharadhipathi position are intricately linked, as the determination of who can be substituted directly impacts the ability to prosecute the appeal. The Court's analysis underscored that the legal framework allows for flexibility in substitution, ensuring that the rightful claims to positions of authority, such as Viharadhipathi, are recognized and upheld in the judicial process. Conclusion The Supreme Court ultimately ruled in favor of the Petitioner, allowing for his substitution as the Substituted Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant and permitting him to proceed with the appeal. The Court's decision reflects a commitment to upholding the rights of parties in civil proceedings, particularly in cases involving the succession of religious leadership and property. The judgment reinforces the importance of adapting legal frameworks to ensure justice is served, even in the face of changing circumstances such as the death of a party. Keywords substitution — deceased party — legal representative — Civil Procedure Code — appeal — Viharadhipathi — temple property — proper person — next of kin — higher ordination certificate — controlling Viharadhipathi — prima facie evidence — jurisdiction — Supreme Court Rules	Ranjan Suwandarthna, PC for the Plaintiff-Respondent-Petitioner; Lakshman Perera, PC with Upendra Walgampaya for Defendant-Appellant–Respondent	SC/HC CALA/378/17	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_hc_cala_378_17.pdf
sc-appeal-149-2016	17 March 2022	Shanthakumar and Others v. Vijendranathan and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.	Leave to Appeal — Trusts Ordinance — Section 102(3) — Divisional Secretary's certification — Amicable settlement — Stare Decisis — Ratio decidendi	Facts The Plaintiffs-Respondents-Respondents are worshippers of the Puliyady Pillaiyar Temple, which is situated on land originally owned by Annapillai Visvalingam. Following displacement due to the civil war, the worshippers returned and repaired the temple with the consent of the late Muthurajah Jeyaratnam, a descendant of the original owner. The Plaintiffs-Respondents-Respondents allege that the 1st Defendant-Appellant-Appellant unlawfully ousted the worshippers and the descendants of the original owner from the management and control of the temple. They further contend that the Appellant misappropriates temple funds and is unfit to manage the charitable trust. The Plaintiffs-Respondents-Respondents instituted action in the District Court of Vavuniya under Section 102 of the Trusts Ordinance, seeking a declaration that the temple is a charitable trust, the establishment of a new management scheme, and the removal of the Appellant. Prior to filing the action, the Plaintiffs-Respondents-Respondents presented a petition to the Divisional Secretary. The Government Agent subsequently issued a letter stating that an inquiry had been held, that an amicable settlement could not be reached, and that the parties should refer the matter to court. The Appellant raised preliminary objections, arguing that the action failed to comply with the condition precedent under Section 102(3) of the Trusts Ordinance, specifically that no valid certificate was obtained and that the plaint was not submitted to the Government Agent. The District Court and the High Court of Civil Appeal both ruled against the Appellant, leading to the present appeal. Issues Whether the District Court and the High Court erred in law by entertaining the action when the Plaint did not disclose compliance with the condition precedent under Section 102(3) of the Trusts Ordinance. Whether the letter issued by the Government Agent constitutes a valid certificate under Section 102(3) of the Trusts Ordinance. Applicable Law Statutes: Trusts Ordinance No. 9 (as amended) Transfer of Powers (Divisional Secretaries) Act No. 58 Cases Referred to: Sivaguru v. Alagaratnam - [48-nlr-369] Siththiravelu v. Ramalingam - [61-clw-31] Velautham v. Velauther - [61-nlr-230] Ramesh v. Chettiar - [2004/v1-sri-lr-355] Bandahamy v. Senanayake - [62-nlr-313] Unique Gemstones LTD. v. W. Karunadasa - [1995/v2-sri-lr-357] Edwards v. Jones - [1947] 1 All E. R. 830 Costa v. Jayatilleke - [sc-265/74] Walker Sons & Co. (U.K.) Ltd. v. Gunatilake - [1979/v1-sri-lr-231] Analysis Issue 1: Compliance with Section 102(3) Rule applied: Section 102(3) of the Trusts Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The court reasoned that Section 102(3) requires the presentation of a petition to the Divisional Secretary and a subsequent certification that an inquiry was held and no amicable settlement was possible. The court held that the statute does not mandate the submission of the actual plaint to the Government Agent; rather, it requires an inquiry into the "subject-matter" of the plaint. The court found that the petition submitted by the Plaintiffs-Respondents-Respondents sufficiently covered the subject matter of the subsequent court action. Finding: The Plaintiffs-Respondents-Respondents complied with the requirements of Section 102(3). Issue 2: Validity of the Government Agent's Certificate Rule applied: Section 102(3) of the Trusts Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The court examined the letter issued by the Government Agent, which confirmed that an inquiry was conducted, that the dispute could not be settled amicably, and recommended that the parties refer the matter to court. The court noted that the Trusts Ordinance does not prescribe a specific format for the certificate. It further held that previous judicial interpretations requiring the submission of the plaint to the Government Agent were based on a misconception of the law and were not binding on the current Supreme Court, as those decisions were made by courts that were not the final court of resort or were benches of only two judges. Finding: The letter issued by the Government Agent is a valid certificate under Section 102(3). Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are interdependent; the validity of the certificate (Issue 2) confirms that the condition precedent for maintaining the action (Issue 1) was satisfied. By rejecting the restrictive interpretations of previous cases, the court established that the procedural requirements of the Trusts Ordinance were met, thereby rendering the Appellant's preliminary objections moot. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The Plaintiffs-Respondents-Respondents are entitled to costs for proceedings at the Supreme Court and the Civil Appellate High Court of Vavuniya. Keywords Leave to Appeal — Trusts Ordinance — Section 102(3) — Divisional Secretary's certification — Amicable settlement — Stare Decisis — Ratio decidendi		SC/APPEAL/149/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_149_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-119-2017	21 March 2022	Sathsindu Forwarding & Security (Pvt) Limited and Bagnold Associates Limited v. Sri Lanka Ports Authority	P. Padman Surasena, J. (Majority); E. A. G. R. Amarasekara, J. (Dissenting), J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya, J; P. Padman Surasena, J.; E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.	Arbitration agreement — Dispute resolution — Party autonomy — Arbitral tribunal jurisdiction — Scope of arbitration — Submission to arbitration — Public policy — Validity of award	Facts The Sri Lanka Ports Authority (SLPA) entered into an agreement with Sathsindu Forwarding & Security (Pvt) Limited and Bagnold Associates Limited (the Claimants) on 22-01-2004 to provide port security consultancy services. The agreement required the Claimants to perform services in three phases, with a payment schedule linked to the completion of these phases. The SLPA paid an initial advance of 50% of the total contract value. The Claimants subsequently initiated arbitration, alleging that they had performed their obligations and that the SLPA was in breach for failing to pay the remaining balance. During the arbitral proceedings, the Claimants maintained that they had fully performed their obligations. The SLPA defended the claim by asserting that the Claimants had failed to fulfill their contractual duties. After the conclusion of the inquiry, the Claimants, in their final written submissions, introduced a claim for 90% of the total contract value based on Clause 10.3 of the agreement, which provided for such payment if the SLPA prevented the Claimants from performing their services. The arbitral tribunal awarded the Claimants the balance sum based on this clause, finding that the SLPA had prevented the Claimants from completing their work. The SLPA challenged this award in the High Court, which dismissed the application and enforced the award. The SLPA appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the arbitral award dealt with a dispute not contemplated by or falling within the terms of the submission to arbitration, in violation of Section 32(1)(a)(iii) of the Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995. Whether the arbitral tribunal failed to afford the parties an opportunity to present their cases regarding the new claim introduced in the written submissions, in violation of Section 15(2) of the Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995. Applicable Law Statutes: Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995 Cases Referred to: Oberoi Hotels (Pvt) Limited v. Asian Hotels Corporation Ltd - [sc-la-28/2000] Hatton National Bank Limited v. Casimir Kiran Atapattu - [sc-appeal-38/2006] Allis v. Senevirathne - [1989/v2-sri-lr-335] Attanayake v. Ramyawathie - [2003/v1-sri-lr-401] Analysis Issue 1: Scope of Submission Rule applied: Section 32(1)(a)(iii) of the Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995. Court's reasoning: The majority held that the arbitral tribunal exceeded its mandate by adjudicating a claim under Clause 10.3 of the agreement, which was never part of the original dispute referred to arbitration. The original dispute concerned the Claimants' assertion of full performance and the SLPA's non-payment. The introduction of Clause 10.3 in the final written submissions fundamentally changed the nature of the claim. The court emphasized that an arbitral tribunal derives its jurisdiction solely from the parties' submission, and it cannot "go on voyages of discovery" to resolve disputes not presented by the parties. Finding: The award dealt with a matter beyond the scope of the submission, and the High Court erred in failing to set it aside. Issue 2: Opportunity to Present Case Rule applied: Section 15(2) of the Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995. Court's reasoning: The majority found that the SLPA was taken by surprise by the new claim raised in the written submissions after the inquiry had concluded. Because the SLPA had no notice of this specific legal basis for the claim during the evidentiary phase, it was deprived of the opportunity to defend itself against the application of Clause 10.3. This violated the mandatory requirement that a tribunal must afford all parties an opportunity to present their cases. Finding: The tribunal breached Section 15(2), rendering the award liable to be set aside. Interaction of Issues The findings on the scope of submission and the opportunity to present a case are intrinsically linked. The tribunal's decision to adjudicate a matter outside the scope of the submission (Issue 1) directly resulted in the denial of the SLPA's right to be heard on that specific matter (Issue 2), as the SLPA could not have anticipated or defended against a claim that was not part of the original reference. Conclusion The Supreme Court allowed the appeal, set aside the judgment of the High Court, and set aside the arbitral award dated 30-01-2013. The court held that the tribunal acted beyond its jurisdiction by deciding on a matter not submitted for arbitration. Keywords Arbitration agreement — Dispute resolution — Party autonomy — Arbitral tribunal jurisdiction — Scope of arbitration — Submission to arbitration — Public policy — Validity of award			
sc-fr-116-2021	22 March 2022	Henri and Others v. Welege and Others	Janak De Silva, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Kumudini Wickremasinghe, J.; Janak De Silva, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Admission to school — Arbitrary decision-making — Approbation and reprobation — Old Boys Association — School admission policies — Judicial review	Facts The Petitioners, R. L. Buddhika Yangani Henri and the minor Hewa Bettage Sadiv Sasmin, sought admission for the 2nd Petitioner to Grade 1 at Rahula College, Matara, for the year 2021 under the Old Boys Category. The Interview Board evaluated the application and awarded the 2nd Petitioner 50 marks, which fell short of the 55.5 cut-off mark required for admission. The Petitioners contended that the Interview Board failed to award marks for documents P11, P12, and P13, which were signed by the Deputy Principal of the school. Although the school authorities had previously accepted document P7, which was also signed by the Deputy Principal, they refused to award marks for P11, P12, and P13 on the basis that they were not signed by the Principal. During the appeals process, the Petitioners submitted documents P29a, P29b, and P29c, which contained the same information as the earlier documents but were signed by the Principal. The Appeals Board rejected these as new documents. Issues Whether the refusal of the Interview Board to award marks for documents P11, P12, and P13, while having accepted document P7, constituted arbitrary action in violation of Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the Appeals Board erred in refusing to consider documents P29a, P29b, and P29c under Clause 10.3 of the Guidelines marked P4. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1) Cases Referred to: Verschures Creameries Limited v. Hull & Netherland Steamship Co. Ltd. - [(1921) 2 KB 608] Visuvalingam v. Liyanage - [1983/v1-sri-lr-203] Ranasinghe v. Premadharma - [1985/v1-sri-lr-63] Analysis Issue 1: Arbitrary refusal to award marks Rule applied: The doctrine of approbation and reprobation, which prevents a party from asserting a position that contradicts a previous position taken to obtain an advantage. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the Interview Board had already accepted document P7, signed by the Deputy Principal, to award marks for the father's attendance at the school. By subsequently refusing to award marks for documents P11, P12, and P13—which were also signed by the Deputy Principal—the authorities were "blowing hot and cold." The court held that the authorities could not accept the validity of the Deputy Principal's signature for one document while rejecting it for others of a similar nature. Finding: The 1st to 8th Respondents acted arbitrarily in refusing to award marks for P11, P12, and P13, thereby violating Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Issue 2: Consideration of documents by the Appeals Board Rule applied: Clause 10.3 of the Guidelines marked P4. Court's reasoning: The court determined that Clause 10.3 of the Guidelines provided the Appeals Board with sufficient authority to consider documents P29a, P29b, and P29c. Since these documents contained the same information as the previously submitted P11, P12, and P13, they should not have been dismissed merely as "new documents." Finding: The Appeals Board erred in its restrictive interpretation of its powers, failing to properly exercise its discretion under the applicable guidelines. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing. The courtâ€™s determination that the initial refusal to award marks was arbitrary (Issue 1) is strengthened by the fact that the Appeals Board had a procedural mechanism (Issue 2) to rectify the error but failed to utilize it. Together, these failures demonstrate a systemic arbitrary approach by the school authorities that denied the 2nd Petitioner his rightful admission. Conclusion The application is allowed. The court declared the refusal to admit the 2nd Petitioner null and void, directed the 1A Respondent to admit the 2nd Petitioner to Grade 2 for the year 2022, and awarded compensation of Rs. 25,000 to be paid by the 1st to 8th Respondents. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Admission to school — Arbitrary decision-making — Approbation and reprobation — Old Boys Association — School admission policies — Judicial review		SC/FR/116/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_116_2021.pdf
sc-appeal-119-2017	22 March 2022	Sathsindu Forwarding & Security (Pvt) Limited and Bagnold Associates Limited v. Sri Lanka Ports Authority	P. Padman Surasena, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya PC CJ; P. Padman Surasena J; E. A. G. R. Amarasekara J	Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995 — Port Security Consultancy — ISPS Code — Breach of Contract — Arbitration Agreement — Jurisdiction of Arbitral Tribunal — Payment Obligations — Claim for Damages — Legal Principles of Arbitration — Party Autonomy — Award Enforcement — High Court Review — Public Policy	Facts The case revolves around a dispute between Sathsindu Forwarding & Security (Pvt) Limited and Bagnold Associates Limited (collectively referred to as the Claimants) and the Sri Lanka Ports Authority (SLPA) regarding a contract for port security consultancy services. The Claimants entered into an agreement with the SLPA on 22 January 2004, which required the Claimants to conduct a Port Facility Security Assessment (PFSA) and develop a Port Facility Security Plan (PFSP) in compliance with the International Code for the Security of Ships and Port Facilities (ISPS Code). The agreement stipulated a total payment of USD 120,000, with an advance payment of 50% upon signing. After completing the initial services, the Claimants claimed the remaining balance of USD 60,000, which the SLPA refused to pay, leading to a Notice of Arbitration filed by the Claimants on 28 January 2005. The SLPA contested the Claimants' entitlement to the remaining payment, arguing that the Claimants had not fulfilled their obligations under the agreement. The arbitral tribunal ultimately awarded the Claimants USD 48,000, which was 90% of the total cost after deducting the advance payment, citing that the SLPA had prevented the Claimants from completing their services. The SLPA subsequently sought to set aside the arbitral award in the High Court, which upheld the award, prompting the SLPA to appeal to the Supreme Court. Issues The primary issues before the Supreme Court included: Whether the judgment of the High Court was contrary to the provisions of the Arbitration Act. Whether the arbitral tribunal had jurisdiction to award the Claimants the sum based on a claim not originally submitted for arbitration. Whether the SLPA's failure to pay the Claimants was justified under the terms of the agreement. Applicable Law Statutes: Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995 Cases Referred to: Oberoi Hotels (Pvt) Limited Vs. Asian Hotels Corporation Ltd - SC/LA No. 28/2000; Hatton National Bank Limited Vs. Casimir Kiran Atapattu and another - SC Appeal 38/2006, SC Appeal 39/2006. Analysis Issue 1: Jurisdiction of the Arbitral Tribunal Rule applied: Section 32(1)(a)(iii) of the Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995 Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court examined whether the arbitral tribunal had exceeded its jurisdiction by awarding a claim that was not part of the original arbitration submission. The Court noted that the Claimants had initially sought payment for services rendered under the agreement, specifically the remaining balance of USD 60,000. However, during the arbitration proceedings, the Claimants introduced a new claim based on clause 10.3 of the agreement, which stipulated that if the SLPA or its employees prevented the Claimants from carrying out their services, they would be entitled to 90% of the total payment. The Court emphasized that the introduction of this new claim after the conclusion of the inquiry deprived the SLPA of the opportunity to defend against it, violating the principles of fair hearing as mandated by the Arbitration Act. The Court highlighted that the arbitral tribunal had a duty to remain within the limits of the disputes referred to it and could not entertain claims that were not part of the original arbitration agreement. Finding: The Court concluded that the arbitral tribunal had indeed exceeded its jurisdiction by awarding a claim that was not presented for arbitration, thus rendering the award invalid. Issue 2: Compliance with the Arbitration Act Rule applied: Section 15(2) of the Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995 Court's reasoning: The Court further analyzed whether the arbitral tribunal had complied with the procedural requirements of the Arbitration Act. It noted that the Act mandates that all parties must be afforded the opportunity to present their respective cases. The introduction of the new claim by the Claimants in their written submissions after the inquiry had concluded was deemed a significant procedural flaw. The Court reiterated that the SLPA was not given the chance to respond to this new claim, which constituted a breach of the procedural fairness required under the Act. Finding: The Court found that the arbitral tribunal's failure to allow the SLPA to defend against the new claim constituted a violation of the Arbitration Act, further supporting the decision to set aside the arbitral award. Interaction of Issues The issues of jurisdiction and compliance with the Arbitration Act were interrelated, as the failure to adhere to procedural requirements directly impacted the tribunal's jurisdiction to award the disputed sums. The introduction of new claims without proper notice undermined the integrity of the arbitration process and highlighted the importance of adhering to the agreed-upon terms of the arbitration agreement. Conclusion The Supreme Court ultimately ruled in favor of the SLPA, setting aside the arbitral award on the grounds that the tribunal had exceeded its jurisdiction and failed to comply with the procedural requirements of the Arbitration Act. The Court emphasized the necessity for arbitral tribunals to operate within the confines of the disputes presented to them and to ensure that all parties are afforded a fair opportunity to present their cases. The judgment underscored the principles of party autonomy and the importance of adhering to the procedural safeguards established by the Arbitration Act. Keywords Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995 — Port Security Consultancy — ISPS Code — Breach of Contract — Arbitration Agreement — Jurisdiction of Arbitral Tribunal — Payment Obligations — Claim for Damages — Legal Principles of Arbitration — Party Autonomy — Award Enforcement — High Court Review — Public Policy	Vikum De Abrew SDSG with Chaya Sri Nammuni SSC for the Respondent-Respondent-Appellant; Nihal Jayawardena PC with Shyamalie Goonewardena & Radhya Herath for the Claimant-Petitioner-Respondents	SC/APPEAL/119/2017 WITH SC/APPEAL 120/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_119_2017_120_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-96-2013	23 March 2022	Senok Trade Combines (Pvt) Ltd v. Mirama Beach Hotel Limited	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.	Peoples Bank Act — Section 29P — Certificate of sale — Purchaser — Delivery of possession — Parate execution — District Court jurisdiction — Interpretation of statute — Title paramount	Facts The appellant, Senok Trade Combines (Pvt) Ltd., sought an order for delivery of possession of a property under Section 29P of the People's Bank Act No. 29 of 1961 as amended by Act No. 32 of 1986. The property had previously been mortgaged to the People's Bank by Mercantile Credit Limited. Upon default, the Bank exercised its power of parate execution, purchased the property at a public auction, and obtained a certificate of sale. Subsequently, the Bank resold the property to Vidanelage Krishantha Ruwan De Mel via a resale endorsement. The appellant later purchased the property from Vidanelage Krishantha Ruwan De Mel through a standard deed of transfer. The District Court refused to issue notice on the respondent, Mirama Beach Hotel Limited, and rejected the application on the grounds that the appellant was not a purchaser entitled to invoke the special summary procedure under Section 29P. The Civil Appellate High Court dismissed the appellant's revision application, leading to the present appeal. Issues Whether the appellant, having acquired title through a standard deed of transfer from a previous purchaser, qualifies as a "purchaser" entitled to invoke the summary procedure under Section 29P of the People's Bank Act No. 29 of 1961 as amended. Whether the special rights and procedures, including the delivery of possession under Section 29P, are limited to the initial purchaser under the parate execution scheme or extend to subsequent purchasers under the general law. Applicable Law Statutes: People's Bank Act No. 29 of 1961 People's Bank (Amendment) Act No. 32 of 1986 Civil Procedure Code (Chapter XXIV) Cases Referred to: People's Bank v. Hewawasam - [2000/v2-sri-lr-29] Chandrasena v. Leela Nona - [1997/v3-sri-lr-373] Dassanayake v. Sampath Bank Ltd - [2002/v3-sri-lr-268] Bakmeewewa v. Konarage Raja - [1989/v1-sri-lr-231] Sathir Najeare - [79-nlr-126] Analysis Issue 1: Qualification of the Appellant as a "Purchaser" Rule applied: Section 29P(1) of the People's Bank Act, which grants the right to apply for an order of delivery of possession to a "purchaser of any immovable property sold in pursuance of the preceding provisions of this Act." Court's reasoning: The court reasoned that the special summary procedure under Section 29P is an extraordinary remedy designed to facilitate the recovery of loans by banks through parate execution. The court held that this statutory benefit is intended to protect the purchaser who participates in the bank's auction process. The appellant acquired the property through a standard deed of transfer under the general law, not through the bank's auction process. Therefore, the appellant does not fall within the specific category of "purchaser" contemplated by the Act. Finding: The appellant is not a "purchaser" within the meaning of Section 29P and cannot invoke the summary procedure. Issue 2: Scope of Special Statutory Rights Rule applied: The principle of restrictive interpretation of statutes granting special rights, particularly those involving parate execution, as discussed in the context of the Constitution and the administration of justice. Court's reasoning: The court emphasized that parate execution is viewed with disfavor under Roman-Dutch law. Consequently, any statutory provisions granting such powers must be interpreted restrictively. The court concluded that the legislative intent was to provide a quick recovery mechanism for the bank and the initial purchaser to ensure the efficacy of the lending scheme. Once the property is resold or transferred outside the statutory scheme, the special protections—including the right to summary eviction—do not attach to subsequent purchasers who acquire title under the general law. Finding: The special rights under the People's Bank Act do not extend to subsequent purchasers who acquire title through ordinary deeds of transfer. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing; the restrictive interpretation of the scope of the Act (Issue 2) directly informs the definition of "purchaser" (Issue 1). By determining that the special procedure is limited to the parate execution scheme, the court logically concluded that the appellant's status as a subsequent purchaser under the general law precludes them from accessing the summary remedy. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The court held that the appellant is not entitled to invoke the summary procedure under Section 29P of the People's Bank Act as the special rights provided therein do not extend to subsequent purchasers under the general law. Keywords Peoples Bank Act — Section 29P — Certificate of sale — Purchaser — Delivery of possession — Parate execution — District Court jurisdiction — Interpretation of statute — Title paramount		SC/APPEAL/96/2013	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_96_2013.pdf
sc-revision-2-2019	25 March 2022	Indika Roshan Francis v. Bulathsinghalage Lal Cooray and Rajapaksha Pathirannahelage Priyadarshani	L.T.B Dehideniya, J.	L.T.B Dehideniya, J.; A.L.S Gooneratne, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Revisionary Jurisdiction — Supreme Court — Miscarriage of Justice — Article 127 — Article 138 — Administrative Justice Law — Appeal — Inherent Powers — Exceptional Circumstances — Due Diligence — Legal Precedents — Jurisdiction — Errors in Law — Errors in Fact	Facts The case revolves around an application for revision filed by Indika Roshan Francis against the judgment delivered by the Provincial Civil Appellate High Court on 09th January 2019. The Petitioner initiated an action on 05th February 2010, seeking a declaration of title, ejectment, and damages against the Respondents, who were allegedly in unlawful possession of the premises in question. The District Court of Gampaha ruled in favor of the Respondents on 09th October 2013, dismissing the Petitioner’s plaint on the grounds that he failed to prove his case. The Petitioner subsequently appealed to the Western Provincial Civil Appellate High Court, which upheld the District Court's decision. Following this, the Petitioner sought to invoke the revisionary jurisdiction of the Supreme Court under Article 127 of the Constitution, arguing that the inherent powers of the Supreme Court should be exercised to correct manifest errors and prevent a miscarriage of justice. The Respondents raised a preliminary objection regarding the maintainability of the revision application, asserting that the Supreme Court lacked jurisdiction to entertain such an application. Issues The primary issues before the Court were: Whether the Supreme Court possesses revisionary powers under the current legal framework? Whether the Petitioner has established exceptional circumstances warranting the exercise of such powers? Applicable Law Statutes: Article 127 of the Constitution; Article 138 of the Constitution; Administrative Justice Law No. 44 of 1973. Cases Referred to: Sinnathangam v. Meera Mohideen - [60 NLR 394]; Attorney General v. Podisingho - [51 NLR 385]; Rustom v. Hapangama - [1978/79] 1 Sri L.R 352; Peoples Merchant PLC v. Udaya Saman Subasinghe - [SC CHC Appeal No. 14/2014]; Mahesh Agri Exim (Pvt) Ltd v. Gaurav Imports (Pvt) Ltd and Others - [SC Revision No. 02/2013]. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the Supreme Court possesses revisionary powers under the current legal framework? Rule applied: Article 169(2) of the Constitution; Administrative Justice Law No. 44 of 1973. Court's reasoning: The Court examined the constitutional provisions and statutory framework governing the revisionary jurisdiction of the Supreme Court. It noted that Article 138(1) of the Constitution explicitly vests appellate jurisdiction in the Court of Appeal for correcting errors in fact or law committed by lower courts. The Administrative Justice Law, which previously conferred revisionary powers on the Supreme Court, was effectively repealed by Article 169(2) of the Constitution, which transferred such powers to the Court of Appeal. The Court emphasized that the Supreme Court is a creature of statute, and its powers are defined by law. The Petitioner’s argument that the absence of an express provision for revisionary powers in the current Constitution constitutes a lacuna was dismissed, as the Court found that the explicit transfer of such powers to the Court of Appeal negated the Petitioner’s claims. The Court also referenced previous case law, including Sinnathangam v. Meera Mohideen and Attorney General v. Podisingho, which established that the Supreme Court could exercise revisionary powers only in exceptional circumstances, particularly where a miscarriage of justice has occurred. Finding: The Court concluded that the Supreme Court does not possess revisionary powers under the current legal framework, as these powers have been expressly conferred upon the Court of Appeal. Issue 2: Whether the Petitioner has established exceptional circumstances warranting the exercise of such powers? Rule applied: Miscarriage of Justice; Due Diligence. Court's reasoning: The Court scrutinized the Petitioner’s claims of a miscarriage of justice, which he argued stemmed from his inability to file an application for leave to appeal due to ill health. However, the Court found the Petitioner’s reasoning unconvincing and lacking in credibility. It noted that the Petitioner had a right to appeal, as provided under the Supreme Court Rules and the High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 19 of 1990, but failed to act with due diligence in pursuing this right. The Court reiterated that the exercise of revisionary jurisdiction is discretionary and should only be invoked in exceptional circumstances, particularly where a grave injustice has been demonstrated. The Petitioner’s failure to provide compelling evidence of exceptional circumstances led the Court to determine that his application did not meet the necessary threshold for intervention. Finding: The Court found that the Petitioner did not establish exceptional circumstances that would justify the exercise of revisionary powers. Interaction of Issues The issues are interrelated, as the determination of the Supreme Court's jurisdiction to exercise revisionary powers directly impacts the assessment of whether the Petitioner’s claims of miscarriage of justice warrant such an exercise. The Court's conclusion that it lacks jurisdiction effectively precludes any further consideration of the merits of the Petitioner’s claims. Conclusion The Supreme Court dismissed the revision application, affirming that it does not possess the authority to revise judgments of lower courts under the current legal framework, and that the Petitioner failed to demonstrate exceptional circumstances justifying the exercise of any inherent powers. The judgment underscores the importance of adhering to procedural requirements and the necessity for litigants to act diligently in pursuing their legal rights. Keywords Revisionary Jurisdiction — Supreme Court — Miscarriage of Justice — Article 127 — Article 138 — Administrative Justice Law — Appeal — Inherent Powers — Exceptional Circumstances — Due Diligence — Legal Precedents — Jurisdiction — Errors in Law — Errors in Fact	Dinesh de Alwis with Hiranthika Sewwandi for Plaintiff-Appellant-Petitioner instructed by Janak Sandakelum; S.N Vijith Singh for Defendant-Respondent-Respondents	SC/RE/2/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_re_2_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-66-2018	29 March 2022	Inter Company Trade Union and Others v. Trico Maritime (Pvt) Ltd	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; K.K. Wickremasinghe, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Industrial Disputes Act — Termination of employment — Misconduct — Assault — Balance of probability — Labour Tribunal — High Court — Burden of proof — Question of law — Re-trial	Facts The Inter Company Trade Union filed four separate applications in the Labour Tribunal of Colombo on behalf of four employees, namely Yakupitiyage Senavirathne, Kudagama Liyanage Kapila Udayanga, Sunil Bandara, and Heenpatilage Wimal Premarathne, against Trico Maritime (Pvt) Ltd. The applications alleged that the termination of the services of these employees was illegal and unjustifiable. The Respondent company maintained that the termination followed a formal domestic inquiry which established that the employees had committed grave misconduct by assaulting the company's Public Relations Officer, Josheph Benedict Fernando, during an Annual General Meeting. The Labour Tribunal consolidated the four applications and conducted a single trial. The Tribunal concluded that there was evidence of an assault on the officer, but held that the evidence was insufficient to prove the guilt of two of the employees, Kapila Udayanga and Wimal Premarathne. Despite this finding, the Labour Tribunal dismissed the applications of all four employees. The Applicant appealed this decision to the High Court of the Western Province. The High Court set aside the order of the Labour Tribunal and directed a re-trial. The Respondent subsequently appealed the High Court's judgment to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by setting aside the Labour Tribunal's order and directing a re-trial based on alleged evidentiary contradictions. Whether the Labour Tribunal and the High Court misdirected themselves regarding the standard of proof required in proceedings before a Labour Tribunal. Whether the termination of the employees was justified based on a balance of probability. Applicable Law Statutes: Industrial Disputes Act No. 43 of 1950 (as amended) Cases Referred to: The Caledonian (Ceylon) Tea and Rubber Estates Ltd. v. J. S. Hillman - [79-nlr-421] Associated Battery Manufacturers (Ceylon) Ltd. v. United Engineers Workers Union - [77-nlr-541] Hemas (Estates) Ltd. v. Ceylon Workers Congress - [76-nlr-59] Ceylon Transport Board v. N. M. J. Abdeen - [70-nlr-407] Ceylon Transport Board v. W. A. D. Gunasinghe - [72-nlr-76] Analysis Issue 1: Propriety of the High Court's order for a re-trial Rule applied: Section 31D(3) of the Industrial Disputes Act No. 43 of 1950. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court noted that appellate courts should be reluctant to interfere with Labour Tribunal findings unless there is a clear misdirection on facts or law. The High Court failed to identify that the Labour Tribunal had already misdirected itself by applying an incorrect standard of proof. By ordering a re-trial, the High Court failed to exercise its appellate duty to resolve the matter based on the evidence already on record, which was sufficient to establish the misconduct on a balance of probability. Finding: The High Court erred in law by ordering a re-trial. Issue 2: Standard of proof in Labour Tribunals Rule applied: The principle that Labour Tribunal proceedings are not criminal in nature and require proof on a balance of probability, as established in Associated Battery Manufacturers (Ceylon) Ltd. v. United Engineers Workers Union. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the Labour Tribunal and the High Court both misdirected themselves by effectively requiring proof beyond reasonable doubt. The evidence of eyewitnesses Fernando and Cooray was sufficient to establish the assault on a balance of probability. The Tribunal's failure to find all four employees guilty despite the evidence constituted a misdirection. Finding: The standard of proof is a balance of probability, not proof beyond reasonable doubt. Issue 3: Justification of termination Rule applied: The test of whether the termination was "just and equitable" under the Industrial Disputes Act. Court's reasoning: The evidence established that the employees were involved in an assault on a company officer. The Court found that the Labour Tribunalâ€™s dismissal of all four applications, while technically inconsistent regarding the guilt of two individuals, reached a result that was just and equitable given the gravity of the misconduct proven against the group. Finding: The termination was justified. Interaction of Issues The findings on the standard of proof (Issue 2) directly inform the justification of the termination (Issue 3). Because the Labour Tribunal was not required to prove the assault beyond a reasonable doubt, the evidence presented was sufficient to justify the dismissal of all four applications. This rendered the High Court's order for a re-trial (Issue 1) unnecessary and legally erroneous. Conclusion The appeal is allowed and the order of the Labour Tribunal dated 30.01.2015 is affirmed. The judgment of the High Court is set aside. Keywords Industrial Disputes Act — Termination of employment — Misconduct — Assault — Balance of probability — Labour Tribunal — High Court — Burden of proof — Question of law — Re-trial		SC/APPEAL/66/2018	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_66_2018.pdf
sc-appeal-80-2016	31 March 2022	Perera v. Herath	Priyantha Jayawardena PC, J	Priyantha Jayawardena PC, J; E. A. G. R. Amerasekera, J; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.	Appeal against judgment — Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code — Reasonable grounds for default — Ex parte judgment — Setting aside judgment — Burden of proof — Letter of withdrawal — Evidence Ordinance — Quantum of damages — Judicial review	Facts The plaintiff-respondent-respondent-respondent filed an action in the District Court of Chilaw claiming five million rupees in damages for seduction against the defendant-petitioner-appellant-appellant. On the first summons returnable date, the appellantâ€™s instructing attorney filed a proxy and requested time to file an answer. The court granted time, but the appellant failed to file an answer on the subsequent dates fixed by the court. On the third date fixed for filing the answer, the appellant was absent, and his instructing attorney informed the court that he had not received instructions from the appellant despite sending reminders. Consequently, the District Court fixed the case for an ex parte trial, heard evidence, and entered judgment for the respondent. The appellant subsequently filed an application under Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code to set aside the ex parte judgment, claiming he had reasonable grounds for his default. He produced a letter allegedly written by the respondent, which instructed her attorney to withdraw the action. The appellant claimed he refrained from filing an answer because he believed the action would be withdrawn based on this letter. The District Court refused the application, finding the appellant failed to establish reasonable grounds. The High Court affirmed this decision, leading to the present appeal. Issues Whether the evidence adduced by the appellant established "reasonable grounds" for his default in filing an answer under Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code. Whether the legality or quantum of damages awarded in an ex parte decree can be contested during an inquiry to vacate that decree under Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code (as amended) Evidence Ordinance Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka Cases Referred to: Kala Traders (Pvt) Limited v Sanicoch Group of Companies - [sc-appeal-08/2010] Mrs. Sirimavo Bandaranaike v Times of Ceylon Limited - [1995/v1-sri-lr-22] Cisilin Nona v Gunasena Jayawardana - [sc-appeal-190/2012] The Ceylon Brewery Ltd. v Jax Fernando - [2001/v1-sri-lr-270] Rani Lokugalappaththi v H. H. D. De Silva - [sc-appeal-117/2013] Jayasuria v Kotalawala - [23-nlr-511] Muttu Raman v Mohammadu - [21-nlr-97] Deonis v. Samarasinghe - [15-nlr-39] Charles Bright & Co., Ltd v. Sellar - [1904/1-kb-6] Analysis Issue 1: Reasonable grounds for default Rule applied: Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the appellant admitted receiving the letter (V1) before the second date fixed for filing the answer but failed to inform his attorney or verify the status of the case. The court held that the duty to file an answer is a mandatory judicial requirement that cannot be circumvented by private agreements between parties, as such arrangements are contrary to public policy and the administration of justice. The appellantâ€™s failure to act with due diligence or communicate with his attorney demonstrated negligence rather than a reasonable ground for default. Finding: The appellant failed to satisfy the court that he had reasonable grounds for his default. Issue 2: Contesting quantum of damages Rule applied: Sections 86(2) and 88 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court held that an inquiry under Section 86(2) is limited to determining if there were reasonable grounds for the default. It does not empower the court to review the merits or the legality of the ex parte judgment itself. Section 88(1) explicitly excludes appeals against default judgments, and the doctrine of quando aliquid prohibetur ex directo prevents using a vacation inquiry as an indirect means of appeal. The court clarified that while a defendant cannot challenge the merits in a Section 86(2) inquiry, they may seek remedies via revision or restitutio in integrum in the Court of Appeal. Finding: The legality and quantum of damages cannot be contested in a Section 86(2) inquiry. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing; because the appellant failed to establish reasonable grounds for his default, the court was not required to set aside the judgment. Furthermore, the procedural limitation on the scope of the Section 86(2) inquiry meant that the appellant's attempt to challenge the quantum of damages was legally impermissible within these specific proceedings, regardless of the merits of the damages claim. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The judgment of the High Court affirming the District Courtâ€™s refusal to set aside the ex parte decree is upheld. Keywords Appeal against judgment — Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code — Reasonable grounds for default — Ex parte judgment — Setting aside judgment — Burden of proof — Letter of withdrawal — Evidence Ordinance — Quantum of damages — Judicial review		SC/APPEAL/80/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_80_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-115-2019	3 April 2022	Officer-in-Charge, Horana Police Station v. Jayasena	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Special leave to appeal — Enhancement of sentence — Opportunity to be heard — Natural justice — Audi alteram partem — Failure to give reasons — Variation of sentence	Facts The Accused-Appellant-Petitioner, Sirimanna Hettige Jayasena, was charged before the Magistrateâ€™s Court of Horana with four counts related to a motor vehicle accident occurring on 05/05/2007. The charges included negligent driving, failure to avoid an accident, failure to report an accident, and causing grievous injuries by reckless or negligent driving. The Magistrate convicted the Petitioner on counts one, two, and four, imposing fines and a three-month suspended sentence of simple imprisonment for the fourth count. The Petitioner appealed the conviction and sentence to the Provincial High Court of Panadura. The High Court affirmed the convictions and the sentences for counts one and two. However, regarding count four, the High Court varied the sentence by removing the suspension, thereby making the three-month simple imprisonment an active sentence. The Petitioner subsequently sought special leave to appeal to the Supreme Court, challenging the High Courtâ€™s variation of the sentence without providing him an opportunity to be heard on the matter of enhancement. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by failing to provide the Petitioner an opportunity to be heard before enhancing the sentence on count four. Whether the High Court was required to provide reasons for its decision to vary the sentence imposed by the Magistrate. Applicable Law Statutes: Motor Traffic Act Penal Code Code of Criminal Procedure Act No. 15 of 1979 Cases Referred to: Bandara v. Republic of Sri Lanka - [2002/v2-sri-lr-277] [sc-spl-la-39/2018] [sc-spl-la-201/2006] Darmadasa v. Piyadasa - [2008-b.l.r-208] Analysis Issue 1: Opportunity to be heard Rule applied: The principle of natural justice, specifically the maxim audi alteram partem, and the procedural requirement that an accused must be given an opportunity to present arguments against the enhancement of a sentence. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the prosecution did not seek an enhancement of the sentence before the High Court. Relying on established precedents, the court held that it is a cardinal principle that an accused must be afforded an opportunity to show cause before a sentence is enhanced on appeal. By failing to invite the Petitioner to address the court regarding the potential variation of his sentence, the High Court violated fundamental procedural safeguards. Finding: The High Court failed to afford the Petitioner an opportunity to be heard, which constitutes a failure of natural justice. Issue 2: Requirement to provide reasons Rule applied: The requirement for judicial transparency when interfering with the exercise of judicial discretion by a lower court. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the High Court Judge provided only a "bald statement" that the original sentence was inadequate without articulating the specific factors or reasoning that necessitated the variation. The court held that when an appellate judge interferes with a sentence, they must state the necessary factors leading to such interference to ensure the exercise of judicial judgment is transparent and reviewable. Finding: The High Court erred by failing to provide reasons for its decision to vary the sentence. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are intrinsically linked. The failure to provide reasons for the sentence enhancement exacerbated the procedural unfairness caused by the denial of the right to be heard. Together, these failures demonstrate a lack of adherence to the standards of judicial discretion and natural justice required in appellate proceedings. Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The Supreme Court affirmed the convictions and the original sentences imposed by the Magistrateâ€™s Court, effectively setting aside the High Courtâ€™s variation of the sentence on count four and restoring the original suspended sentence. Keywords Special leave to appeal — Enhancement of sentence — Opportunity to be heard — Natural justice — Audi alteram partem — Failure to give reasons — Variation of sentence		SC/APPEAL/115/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_115_2019.pdf
sc-fr-64-2014	4 April 2022	Jayasekera and Others v. Ariyaratne and Others	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya, J; E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Legitimate expectations — Administrative action — Scheme of recruitment — Promotions — Railway Protection Force — Human Rights Commission — Public Petitions Committee — Supernumerary promotions — Suppression of material facts	Facts The Petitioners are fifteen employees serving as Sub Inspectors in the Railway Protection Force (RPF) of the Department of Sri Lanka Railways. They were recruited externally at the inception of the RPF in 1988. The Petitioners alleged that they remained stagnant in the rank of Sub Inspector for over 30 years, despite being eligible for promotion to Inspector and Assistant Superintendent under the applicable Scheme of Recruitment. They contended that their fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution were violated due to the failure of the Respondents to implement recommendations from the Human Rights Commission and directions from the Public Petitions Committee to promote them on a supernumerary basis. The Petitioners sought to compare their situation to two other categories of employees: those who retired and were later reinstated, and those who remained in the Department and received promotions via a settlement in a previous Supreme Court case. The Respondents argued that the Petitioners were a distinct group, that they had failed to qualify in competitive examinations held in 2002 and 2009, and that the Petitioners had suppressed material facts regarding these failed attempts in their petition. Issues Whether the failure to promote the Petitioners on a supernumerary basis constitutes a violation of their fundamental right to equality under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the Petitioners established a substantive legitimate expectation to be promoted outside the existing Scheme of Recruitment. Whether the Petitionersâ€™ failure to disclose their participation in and failure of previous promotion examinations warrants the dismissal of the application for lack of uberrima fides. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 17, 126, 126(4) Cases Referred to: R v. North & East Devon Health Authority, Ex parte Coughlan - [1999] EWCA Civ 1871 Ariyarathne v. Illangakoon - [sc-appeal-444/2012] Meril v. Dayananda De Silva - [2001/v2-sri-lr-11] Sirimal v. Board of Directors of the Co-operative Wholesale Establishment - [2003/v2-sri-lr-23] Siriwardana v. Seneviratne - [2011/v2-sri-lr-1] India v. Hindustan Development Corporation - [1993] 3 SSC 499 Jayasinghe v. The National Institution of Fisheries and Nautical Engineering - [2002/v1-sri-lr-277] Liyanage v. Divisional Secretary Gampaha - [2013/v1-sri-lr-06] Jahangir Sheriffdeen v. Principal Visakha Vidyalaya - [sc-fr-01/2015] Analysis Issue 1: Violation of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution (Right to Equality). Court's reasoning: The court found that the Petitioners belonged to a distinct category of employees recruited externally. Unlike the other categories cited by the Petitioners, they were subject to the standard Scheme of Recruitment, which required passing a competitive examination. The court noted that the Petitioners were given opportunities to sit for these examinations in 2002 and 2009 but failed to qualify. Consequently, there was no discriminatory treatment or inequality, as the established procedure was applied consistently to them. Finding: No violation of Article 12(1) was established. Issue 2: Substantive Legitimate Expectation Rule applied: Principles of legitimate expectation as articulated in R v. North & East Devon Health Authority and Siriwardana v. Seneviratne. Court's reasoning: The court held that a "pious hope" or mere desire for promotion does not constitute a legitimate expectation. The recommendations of the Human Rights Commission and the Public Petitions Committee did not create a substantive right to be promoted outside the existing Scheme of Recruitment. The court emphasized that legitimate expectation must be founded on the sanction of law or established procedure, which was not present here. Finding: The Petitioners failed to establish a substantive legitimate expectation. Issue 3: Lack of Uberrima Fides Rule applied: The doctrine of uberrima fides (utmost good faith) in fundamental rights litigation. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the Petitioners failed to disclose in their petition that they had previously sat for and failed the promotion examinations in 2002 and 2009. This suppression of material facts, which were essential to the adjudication of the dispute, demonstrated a lack of good faith. Finding: The application is liable to be dismissed due to the suppression of material facts. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing. The failure to establish a legal right to promotion (Issue 1) and the lack of a legitimate expectation (Issue 2) are compounded by the Petitioners' lack of candor (Issue 3). The court's determination that the Petitioners were treated according to the law renders their claims of unfairness baseless, and their failure to disclose their previous failed attempts at promotion confirms that the petition was not brought with the requisite good faith. Conclusion The application is dismissed. The Petitioners failed to establish any infringement of their fundamental rights, and the petition is further rejected due to the suppression of material facts and lack of good faith. No costs are ordered. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Legitimate expectations — Administrative action — Scheme of recruitment — Promotions — Railway Protection Force — Human Rights Commission — Public Petitions Committee — Supernumerary promotions — Suppression of material facts		SC/FR/64/2014	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_64_2014.pdf
sc-fr-346-2017	4 April 2022	Kekulandara and Others v. Ekanayake and Others	Priyantha Jayawardena PC, J	Priyantha Jayawardena PC, J; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Inaction of authorities — Harassment of students — Disciplinary action — Parental committee — Corporal punishment — Preliminary inquiry — Charge sheet — Establishments Code	Facts The 1st petitioner filed this application on behalf of his sons, the 2nd and 3rd petitioners, who were students at Vidyartha College, Kandy. The petitioners alleged that the 2nd and 3rd petitioners were subjected to harassment by a class teacher and that the 4th respondent, the school principal, failed to take appropriate action. The 1st petitioner further alleged that the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 5th respondents failed to provide timely remedial action regarding the principal's inaction. The 1st petitioner claimed that after he objected to the appointment of a treasurer for the Parents Committee, the class teacher assaulted the 2nd petitioner and later threatened to kill him. Despite complaints to the 4th respondent and the police, the 1st petitioner alleged no action was taken. The 1st petitioner further alleged that the 3rd petitioner was subsequently ill-treated and that on April 5, 2017, the 2nd petitioner and his mother were assaulted by school staff and parents. Following these events, the petitioners ceased attending school. The Human Rights Commission subsequently facilitated an offer for the petitioners to transfer to Wariyapola Sri Sumangala College, which the 1st petitioner rejected as being of lower academic standard and further from his residence. The 1st respondent denied the allegations of inaction, stating that the 4th respondent had directed the teacher to cease corporal punishment and later removed her from her class teacher duties. The 1st respondent further noted that a committee was appointed to conduct a preliminary inquiry, which led to a charge sheet and a subsequent disciplinary inquiry where the teacher was found guilty and sanctioned. The respondents maintained that the alternative school offered was of a similar academic category and that the petitioners' primary motive was to secure admission to a specific school for which they did not meet the required marks. Issues Whether the failure of the 4th respondent to address complaints of harassment against the 2nd and 3rd petitioners constituted an infringement of Article 12 (1) of the Constitution. Whether the failure of the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 5th respondents to take appropriate and timely remedial action against the 4th respondent constituted an infringement of Article 12 (1) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12 (1) Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 17 Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 126 Establishments Code Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Inaction of the 4th respondent Rule applied: Article 12 (1) of the Constitution regarding the right to equality and equal protection of the law. Court's reasoning: The court examined the evidence regarding the 4th respondent's response to the complaints. The record indicated that the 4th respondent directed the teacher to stop corporal punishment after the first complaint and removed her from her position as class teacher after the second complaint. The 4th respondent also facilitated a preliminary inquiry into the allegations. The court found no evidence to substantiate the claim that the 4th respondent encouraged parents to defend the teacher or that the 4th respondent remained inactive. Finding: There was no inaction on the part of the 4th respondent; therefore, no violation of Article 12 (1) occurred. Issue 2: Failure of remedial action by other respondents Rule applied: Article 12 (1) of the Constitution and the disciplinary procedures stipulated in the Establishments Code. Court's reasoning: The court reviewed the disciplinary process, noting that a committee was appointed, a charge sheet was issued, and a formal disciplinary inquiry was conducted. The teacher was found guilty of all charges, resulting in the deferment of salary increments and a punishment transfer. The court concluded that the authorities followed the procedures set out in the Establishments Code and took appropriate, timely remedial action. Finding: The respondents did not fail to take appropriate remedial action, and no violation of Article 12 (1) occurred. Interaction of Issues The court's finding that the 4th respondent did not act with inaction rendered the second issue regarding the failure of the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 5th respondents to address that inaction moot. Because the primary allegation of administrative failure was disproven by the evidence of the disciplinary proceedings, the claim of a fundamental rights violation under Article 12 (1) failed in its entirety. Conclusion The court held that the respondents did not violate the Fundamental Rights of the 2nd and 3rd petitioners. The petition is dismissed with no costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Inaction of authorities — Harassment of students — Disciplinary action — Parental committee — Corporal punishment — Preliminary inquiry — Charge sheet — Establishments Code		SC/FR/346/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_346_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-59-2021	7 April 2022	Attorney General v. Rupasinghe and Ranasinghe	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Appeal against Court of Appeal order — Revisionary jurisdiction of the Court of Appeal — Exceptional illegality — Prima facie sustainable case — Relevance of evidence — Evidence Ordinance — Witness testimony — Forged deeds — Conspiracy	Facts The Appellant, Mrs. P.M. Ranasinghe, is the aggrieved party in a criminal case where the Accused, Asselage Sujith Rupasinghe, was indicted in the High Court of Colombo on six charges of conspiracy and forgery regarding the Appellant's property. During the trial, the Accused testified that he was deceived by a person he identified as Bulathsinhalage Gunasinghe Cooray, who he later claimed was actually a person named E.S. Thanthrige. The Accused sought to call several witnesses to prove the identity and death of E.S. Thanthrige. The High Court previously refused to summon certain witnesses, and the Court of Appeal upheld that refusal in a prior application, noting that the identity or death of the alleged seller was not a fact in issue or a relevant fact under the Evidence Ordinance. Subsequently, the Accused sought to call a new witness, Renuka Damayanthi, to provide evidence regarding the death of E.S. Thanthrige. Although the Appellant objected, the High Court permitted the witness to be called, reasoning that no prejudice would be caused. The Appellant filed a revision application in the Court of Appeal challenging this order. The Court of Appeal refused to issue notice on the Respondents, finding no exceptional illegality. The Appellant then appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law and fact by failing to consider its own previous judgment in CA/PHC Application No. 148/2016, which held that the death or identity of the alleged seller was not a relevant fact in issue. Whether the Appellant established a prima facie case of illegality warranting the issuance of notice on the Respondents in the revision application. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 138 Evidence Ordinance, Section 5 Court of Appeal (Appellate Procedure) Rules, 1990, Rule 3(3); Rule 3(4) Cases Referred to: Queen v Sodige Singho Appu - [62-nlr-112] Analysis Issue 1: Relevance of evidence Rule applied: Section 5 of the Evidence Ordinance, which limits evidence to facts in issue and facts declared relevant by the Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that in a prior judgment (CA/PHC Application No. 148/2016), the Court of Appeal had already determined that the question of whether the person who sold the property was alive or dead was neither a fact in issue nor a relevant fact. The High Court, in its subsequent order, failed to reconcile its decision to allow the witness with this established legal position regarding the irrelevance of the evidence. Finding: The Court found that the High Court and the Court of Appeal failed to properly consider the previous judicial determination regarding the irrelevance of evidence concerning E.S. Thanthrige. Issue 2: Exercise of revisionary jurisdiction Rule applied: The standard for issuing notice in a revision application, which requires the petitioner to demonstrate a prima facie sustainable case and exceptional circumstances. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the Appellant was not required to prove the case at the threshold stage, but only to satisfy the court that the application warranted a full investigation. By ignoring the previous ruling on the irrelevance of the evidence, the High Courtâ€™s order created a prima facie case of illegality that required the Court of Appeal to issue notice and hear the parties. Finding: The Court concluded that the Appellant established a prima facie case of illegality, and the Court of Appeal should have issued notice on the Respondents. Interaction of Issues The findings on the two issues are intrinsically linked. The determination that the evidence sought to be led was irrelevant under Section 5 of the Evidence Ordinance directly informs the conclusion that the High Courtâ€™s order allowing the witness was legally flawed. This illegality constitutes the "exceptional circumstance" necessary to trigger the Court of Appeal's revisionary jurisdiction, thereby necessitating the issuance of notice. Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The Court of Appeal is directed to issue notice of the revision application on all Respondents and to expeditiously conclude the hearing of the said application. Keywords Appeal against Court of Appeal order — Revisionary jurisdiction of the Court of Appeal — Exceptional illegality — Prima facie sustainable case — Relevance of evidence — Evidence Ordinance — Witness testimony — Forged deeds — Conspiracy		SC/APPEAL/59/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_59_2021.pdf
sc-fr-427-2018	4 May 2022	Jayasinghe and Others v. Rajapaksha and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Promotion scheme — Police constables — Seniority — Merit — Administrative action — Time bar — Legitimate expectations	Facts The Petitioners were Police Constables who challenged the promotion scheme implemented by the Respondents in 2018. The Petitioners alleged that the scheme, which allocated 50 marks for seniority and 50 marks for merit, unfairly favored junior officers who had served in specific "Special Divisions." The Petitioners contended that this approach undermined seniority and discriminated against officers serving in standard police stations. They sought a declaration that the promotions granted under this scheme were null and void and requested that their own promotions be backdated to 31 May 2018. The Respondents maintained that the 2018 scheme was a policy decision aimed at improving the quality and efficiency of the police service by balancing seniority with merit. The Respondents further argued that the application was time-barred because the Petitioners were aware of the scheme in July 2018 but failed to challenge it within the one-month period stipulated by the Constitution. During the proceedings, it was noted that most of the Petitioners had subsequently received promotions under a different time-based scheme in 2019. Issues Whether the application is time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Whether the 2018 promotion scheme violated the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution by being arbitrary or discriminatory. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 126(2), 155G. Cases Referred to: Demuni Sriyani De Soyza v. Dharmasena Dissanayake - [sc-fr-206/2008] Wasantha Dissanayake v. Secretary, Ministry of Public Administration - [sc-fr-611/12] Kaluwahandi Garwin Premalal Silva v. K. W. E. Karaliyadda - [sc-fr-383/2016] A. H. Wickramatunga v. H. R. de Silva - [sc-fr-551/98] Analysis Issue 1: Time-bar Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution, which requires an application for the infringement of fundamental rights to be filed within one month of the alleged infringement. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the promotion scheme was communicated in July 2018. The Petitioners were aware of the scheme at that time but only filed their petition in December 2018, well beyond the one-month limitation period. The court rejected the argument that the limitation period only commenced upon the publication of the results in November 2018, as the challenge was directed at the scheme itself. Finding: The application is time-barred and therefore unmaintainable. Issue 2: Violation of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution (Right to Equality) and the principle that authorities have the competence to adjust recruitment and promotion schemes to meet changing circumstances. Court's reasoning: The court found no patent unfairness in the 2018 scheme. Citing Wasantha Dissanayake v. Secretary, Ministry of Public Administration, the court held that authorities are entitled to adjust promotion policies to meet the needs of the service. Furthermore, the court noted that the scheme was applied uniformly to all applicants. The court also referenced A. H. Wickramatunga v. H. R. de Silva to emphasize that promotion schemes may legitimately balance seniority with merit-based assessments. Finding: The promotion scheme was not arbitrary or discriminatory, and no fundamental rights violation occurred. Interaction of Issues The finding that the application was time-barred effectively disposed of the matter. However, the court further strengthened its conclusion by addressing the merits, noting that the Petitioners had already received subsequent promotions, which rendered their request for backdating the 2018 promotions both moot and potentially prejudicial to third parties who were not joined as respondents. Conclusion The application is dismissed. The court held that the petition was time-barred and that the challenged promotion scheme did not violate the Petitioners' fundamental rights. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Promotion scheme — Police constables — Seniority — Merit — Administrative action — Time bar — Legitimate expectations		SC/FR/427/2018	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_427_2018.pdf
sc-appeal-60-2018	05 May 2022	Kachchakaduge Frank Romeo Fernando v. Brandix Apparel Solutions Limited	Janak De Silva, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya, P.C., C.J.; Vijith K. Malalgoda, P.C., J.; Janak De Silva, J.	Industrial Disputes Act — High Court of Provinces (Special Provisions) Act — constructive termination — disciplinary inquiry — principles of natural justice — comply and complain — burden of proof — punitive transfer — mala fide — jurisdiction of Labour Tribunal — employment contract — transfer of employees — unfair dismissal — reinstatement — back wages	Facts The case revolves around an appeal from the judgment of the Provincial High Court of the Western Province in Negombo regarding the employment status of Kachchakaduge Frank Romeo Fernando (the Respondent), who was employed as a Quality Executive at Brandix Apparel Solutions Limited (the Appellant). The Respondent was suspended from service on 07 October 2009, with a notice of suspension served on him on 09 October 2009, citing two charges. Following this, a disciplinary inquiry was conducted, where the Respondent was found guilty of two charges and subsequently subjected to a punitive transfer to a factory in Polonnaruwa. The Respondent contested the validity of the disciplinary inquiry, claiming it violated principles of natural justice and was conducted unfairly. He argued that the punitive transfer was unjust and amounted to constructive termination of his employment. The Labour Tribunal dismissed his application, stating that constructive termination had not been proven. The Respondent then appealed to the High Court, which ruled in his favor, ordering reinstatement with back wages. The Appellant subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court, raising several legal questions regarding the High Court's findings and the application of the law. Issues The Supreme Court addressed several key issues: Whether the High Court erred in law by failing to recognize that its jurisdiction was limited to questions of law; Whether the High Court misapplied the burden of proof regarding the alleged termination; Whether the High Court failed to properly consider the principles of law applicable to employee transfers and the 'comply and complain' principle; Whether the High Court erred in concluding that there was no termination of the Respondent's services; and Whether the Respondent had vacated his post. Applicable Law Statutes: Industrial Disputes Act, High Court of Provinces (Special Provisions) Act, No. 10 of 1990. Cases Referred to: Sri Lanka Insurance Corporation Ltd. v. Jathika Sewaka Sangamaya [(2011) 2 Sri.L.R. 114]; The Ceylon University Clerical and Technical Association, Peradeniya v. The University of Ceylon, Peradeniya [(72 N.L.R. 84)]; Anderson v. Husny [(2001) 1 Sri.L.R. 168]; Indrajith Rodrigo v. Central Engineering Consultancy Bureau [(2009) 1 Sri.L.R. 248]; Janatha Estates Development Board and Others v. Kurukuladitta [(1990) 2 Sri.L.R. 169]; Ceylon Estates Staffs' Union v. The Superintendent, Meddecombra Estate, Watagoda [(73 N.L.R. 278)]; Pfizer Limited v. Rasanayagam [(1991) 1 Sri.L.R. 290]; Thaksala Weavers Ltd. v. Dhanawathie Perera and Others [(1994) 3 Sri.L.R. 116]; Christopher W.J. Silva v. Sri Lankan Airlines Limited [(S.C. Appeal 212/2016)]; Mahagamage Chandramadu and Others v. Paradigm Clothing (Private) Limited & Others [(S.C. Appeal No. 106/2014)]; Ceylon Mercantile Union v. Ceylon Cold Stores Ltd. and Another [(1995) 1 Sri.L.R. 261]. Analysis Issue 1: Jurisdiction of the Labour Tribunal Rule applied: Section 31B(1)(a) of the Industrial Disputes Act. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court examined the jurisdiction of the Labour Tribunal, emphasizing that it is only engaged when there has been a termination of services. The Respondent claimed constructive termination, but the Appellant denied any termination. The Court noted that the Labour Tribunal's jurisdiction is contingent upon the existence of a termination, whether actual or constructive. The High Court had erred in its interpretation of the Labour Tribunal's jurisdiction, failing to recognize that without a valid termination, the Tribunal could not entertain the Respondent's application. The Court referenced established judicial precedents that clarify the conditions under which constructive termination can be claimed, highlighting the necessity for the employee to demonstrate that the employer's conduct constituted a significant breach of the employment contract. Finding: The Supreme Court concluded that the Labour Tribunal lacked jurisdiction to entertain the Respondent's claim of constructive termination due to the absence of a valid termination. Issue 2: Burden of Proof Rule applied: Section 102 of the Evidence Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The Court analyzed the burden of proof in the context of employment termination disputes, asserting that the burden lies with the employee to prove that termination occurred and was unjust. The High Court had incorrectly placed the burden on the Appellant to demonstrate that it acted fairly. The Supreme Court reiterated that when termination is denied by the employer, the onus is on the employee to establish the claim of constructive termination. The Court emphasized that the Respondent failed to provide sufficient evidence to support his claims of unfair treatment and constructive termination. Finding: The Supreme Court found that the High Court erred in its application of the burden of proof, leading to an incorrect conclusion regarding the Respondent's claims. Issue 3: Comply and Complain Rule applied: Judicial precedents regarding employee transfers. Court's reasoning: The Court examined the principle of 'comply and complain,' which mandates that employees must comply with a transfer order and subsequently raise complaints if they believe the order is unjust. The Respondent argued that the transfer was invalid due to the alleged unfairness of the disciplinary inquiry. However, the Court noted that the Respondent had not established that the inquiry was conducted improperly. The Court referenced previous cases that affirmed the employer's right to transfer employees within the organization, provided the transfer is not executed in bad faith. The Respondent's failure to comply with the transfer order was deemed a significant factor in determining the validity of his claims. Finding: The Supreme Court concluded that the Respondent was required to comply with the transfer order and could not claim constructive termination without first adhering to this principle. Interaction of Issues The issues presented in this case are interrelated, as the determination of the Labour Tribunal's jurisdiction directly impacts the burden of proof and the application of the 'comply and complain' principle. The Supreme Court's findings on these issues collectively underscore the importance of procedural adherence in employment disputes and the necessity for employees to substantiate their claims with credible evidence. Conclusion The Supreme Court set aside the judgment of the High Court, affirming the Labour Tribunal's decision and ruling in favor of the Appellant. The Court emphasized the need for employees to comply with valid transfer orders and the importance of establishing a clear basis for claims of constructive termination. The appeal was allowed, and no order was made as to costs. Keywords Industrial Disputes Act — High Court of Provinces (Special Provisions) Act — constructive termination — disciplinary inquiry — principles of natural justice — comply and complain — burden of proof — punitive transfer — mala fide — jurisdiction of Labour Tribunal — employment contract — transfer of employees — unfair dismissal — reinstatement — back wages	Suren Fernando with Khyati Wickramanayake and Sanjit Dias for the Respondent-Respondent-Appellant; P.K. Prince Perera for the Applicant-Appellant-Respondent	SC/APPEAL/60/2018	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_60_2018.pdf
sc-fr-377-2015	18 May 2022	Rathnayake and Others v. Wickramasiri and Others	P. Padman Surasena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Volunteer Teachers — Cabinet decisions — Teacher Assistants — Age limit — Fundamental Rights Article 12(1) — Recruitment criteria — Provincial Public Service Commission — Southern Province — Qualifications	Facts The Petitioners were former volunteer teachers in the Southern Province who sought appointment as Teacher Assistants. The government initiated a recruitment process for volunteer teachers to address staffing shortages, subject to specific Cabinet decisions and age requirements. The Petitioners were summoned for interviews to verify their qualifications, but these interviews were explicitly stated to be for qualification assessment rather than appointment. Following a Cabinet decision in 2014, criteria were established requiring candidates to be under 35 years of age at the time of joining as a volunteer teacher. The Petitioners were found to be over the age limit and were placed on a list of candidates who did not meet the necessary requirements. The Petitioners alleged that the Respondents acted arbitrarily and discriminatorily by appointing other candidates who allegedly failed to meet the requirements, thereby violating their fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the Respondents violated the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution by failing to appoint them as Teacher Assistants. Whether the Respondents acted arbitrarily or discriminatorily in the selection process by appointing candidates who allegedly did not meet the age requirements. Whether the Petitioners had a legitimate expectation of appointment based on being summoned for an interview. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1) Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 17 Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 126 Cases Referred to: SC/FR 580/2008 - [sc-fr-580/2008] Analysis Issue 1: Violation of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution regarding the right to equality and non-discrimination. Court's reasoning: The court found that the recruitment process was governed by Cabinet decisions and the Service Minute of the Sri Lanka Teachers Service, which mandated an age limit of 35 years. The Petitioners failed to meet this age criterion. As the Respondents acted in accordance with established policy and Cabinet directives, there was no basis to claim that the exclusion of the Petitioners was discriminatory or unlawful. Finding: The Petitioners failed to establish a violation of Article 12(1). Issue 2: Arbitrary Appointment of Candidates Rule applied: The criteria set out in the Cabinet Decision dated 03-01-2014 and the Service Minute of the Sri Lanka Teachers Service. Court's reasoning: The Petitioners alleged that four specific candidates were appointed despite being over the age limit. The 1st Respondent provided documentary evidence demonstrating that one appointment was cancelled, one candidate was not appointed, and the others satisfied the requirements. The Petitioners failed to rebut this evidence. Finding: The allegation of arbitrary appointment was unsubstantiated. Issue 3: Legitimate Expectation Rule applied: Principles of administrative law regarding legitimate expectation. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the letters summoning the Petitioners for interviews explicitly stated that the purpose was to examine qualifications, not to grant appointments. Furthermore, the Petitioners did not plead legitimate expectation in their original petition, raising it only in final written submissions. Finding: The Petitioners did not have a legitimate expectation of appointment. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected as the failure to meet the mandatory age requirement (Issue 1) rendered the Petitioners ineligible for appointment, thereby negating any claim of discrimination (Issue 2) or legitimate expectation (Issue 3). The court's determination that the recruitment process was strictly governed by Cabinet policy reinforced the conclusion that the Respondents' actions were lawful and consistent. Conclusion The application is dismissed as the Petitioners failed to establish a violation of their fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. This judgment shall also apply to the pending matters of SC FR 20/2018 and SC FR 21/2018. No costs are ordered. Keywords Volunteer Teachers — Cabinet decisions — Teacher Assistants — Age limit — Fundamental Rights Article 12(1) — Recruitment criteria — Provincial Public Service Commission — Southern Province — Qualifications		SC/FR/377/2015	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_377_2015.pdf
sc-appeal-159-2016	19 May 2022	Gunadasa and Others v. Narangodage Amarapala	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Leave and license — Tenancy — Burden of proof — Onus of proof — Evidence Ordinance — Civil Procedure Code — Landlord and tenant relationship — Estoppel	Facts The plaintiff, Jayawardene Liyanage Gunadasa, initiated an action in the District Court seeking the ejectment of the defendant, Narangodage Amarapala, from the premises in suit and damages. The plaintiff asserted that the defendant was in unlawful possession following the termination of a leave and license agreement. The defendant contested the action, claiming that he was the tenant of the premises under the owner, Thillairajah, and that the plaintiff was merely a licensee. It was undisputed that Thillairajah was the owner of the premises. The District Court dismissed the plaintiff's action, finding in favor of the defendant. Upon appeal, the Court of Appeal set aside the District Court's judgment and entered judgment for the plaintiff. The defendant subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. During the proceedings, the original parties passed away and were substituted by their respective heirs. The Supreme Court granted leave to appeal on questions regarding the establishment of the leave and license agreement, the timing of the defendant's entry into the premises, and the burden of proof concerning the defendant's alleged tenancy under Thillairajah. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal erred in determining that the leave and license agreement between the plaintiff and the defendant was established. Whether the Court of Appeal erred in its assessment of the burden and onus of proof regarding the defendant's claim of tenancy under the owner, Thillairajah. Applicable Law Statutes: Rent Act No. 7 of 1972 Civil Procedure Code Evidence Ordinance Cases Referred to: Mary Beatrice v. Seneviratne - [1997/v1-sri-lr-197] Wimala Perera v. Kalyani Sriyalatha - [2011/v1-sri-lr-182] Ahamed Saheed v. Abdul Hameed - [sc-appeal-4/2013] Analysis Issue 1: Establishment of leave and license Rule applied: Section 116 of the Evidence Ordinance and Section 154(3) of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court found that the plaintiff provided sufficient evidence, including correspondence (P16) confirming the plaintiff's status as the tenant of the owner, Thillairajah. Furthermore, the defendant had previously deposited rent in the name of the plaintiff at the Colombo Municipal Council (P1), acknowledging the plaintiff as his landlord. The court rejected the defendant's attempt to disown P1 as an afterthought, noting that under Section 154(3) of the Civil Procedure Code, a party cannot challenge the proof of a document if they remained silent when it was marked in evidence. The court held that a licensee may act as a licensor to a third party, and the defendant is estopped under Section 116 of the Evidence Ordinance from challenging the licensor's authority. Finding: The Court of Appeal did not err; the leave and license relationship was sufficiently established. Issue 2: Burden and onus of proof Rule applied: Section 114 of the Evidence Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The court clarified that in civil litigation, the plaintiff must prove their case on a balance of probabilities. While the overall burden remains with the plaintiff, the court is entitled to consider the evidence led by the defendant. The Court of Appeal correctly addressed the core issue of whether the defendant was a licensee of the plaintiff. By considering the defendant's failed claim of tenancy under Thillairajah, the Court of Appeal was not improperly shifting the burden of proof, but rather evaluating the totality of the evidence to determine which version was more probable. Finding: The Court of Appeal correctly applied the principles regarding the burden of proof in civil cases. Interaction of Issues The findings on the two issues are mutually reinforcing. The establishment of the leave and license agreement (Issue 1) directly undermined the defendant's claim of independent tenancy under the owner. By correctly applying the burden of proof (Issue 2), the court was able to weigh the plaintiff's documentary evidence against the defendant's unsubstantiated claims, leading to the conclusion that the plaintiff's version of events was more probable. Conclusion The Supreme Court answered all questions of law in the negative and affirmed the judgment of the Court of Appeal. The appeal is dismissed with costs. Keywords Leave and license — Tenancy — Burden of proof — Onus of proof — Evidence Ordinance — Civil Procedure Code — Landlord and tenant relationship — Estoppel		SC/APPEAL/159/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_159_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-77-2016	19 May 2022	Freedom of High Seas (Pvt) Limited v. Kardin International (Pvt) Limited	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC, J; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; P. Padman Surasena, J.	Agency — Principal — Agent's liability — Contractual interpretation — High Court error — District Court error — Contract variation — Disclosure of principal — Maritime contract	Facts Freedom of High Seas (Pvt) Limited, the Plaintiff-Respondent-Respondent, initiated legal action against Kardin International (Pvt) Limited, the Defendant-Appellant-Appellant, to recover a sum of US$ 10,000. This amount was claimed as outstanding costs for the supply of fresh water to a vessel in distress, MV Marina One, which was drifting off the coast of Sri Lanka. The defendant contended that it acted solely as an agent for a disclosed principal, Silverline Maritime Sdn Bhd of Malaysia, and therefore bore no personal liability for the debt. The District Court of Mount Lavinia entered judgment in favor of the plaintiff, finding that the defendant had entered into an independent contract with the plaintiff. The High Court of the Western Province subsequently upheld this decision. The defendant appealed to the Supreme Court, challenging the lower courts' findings regarding its capacity as an agent and the existence of a contract between the parties. Issues Whether the High Court misdirected itself in law and fact by failing to consider that the defendant acted only as an agent for a disclosed principal and was not personally liable. Whether the High Court misdirected itself in law and fact by failing to find that the District Judge erred in answering the issue of whether the defendant entered into a contract with the plaintiff in the affirmative. Applicable Law Statutes: High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Amendment Act No 54 Cases Referred to: Gadd v. Houghton - [1876/v1-ex-div-357] Ariadne Steamship and Co v. James and Co - [1922/v1-kb-518] Universal Steam Navigation Company Limited v. James Mckelvie and Co - [1923-ac-492] Bridges and Salmon Ltd v. The Swan (Owner) The Swan - [1968/v1-lloyds-rep-5] Carthelis Appuhamy v. Siriwardena et al - [49-nlr-529] Ranchagoda v. Viola - [1999/v2-sri-lr-1] Peiris v. Fernando - [62-nlr-534] Colletes v. Bank of Ceylon - [1984/v2-sri-lr-253] Analysis Issue 1: Liability of an Agent Rule applied: The principle that an agent is not personally liable when contracting on behalf of a named and disclosed principal, as established in Universal Steam Navigation Company Limited v. James Mckelvie and Co. Court's reasoning: The court examined the e-mail correspondence (P1A to P1D) and found that the defendant explicitly signed as "As Agents only." The plaintiff was privy to these communications and was aware of the principal, Silverline Maritime. The court rejected the lower courts' reliance on subsequent e-mails (P3B) to establish an independent contract, noting that the lower courts viewed the evidence in isolation rather than as a whole. The court held that the use of the word "agent" is a conclusive assertion of agency and a rejection of personal responsibility. Finding: The High Court misdirected itself; the defendant acted as an agent for a disclosed principal and is not personally liable. Issue 2: Validity of the Contractual Finding Rule applied: The fundamental requirements of a contract (offer and acceptance) and the legal consequences of agency relationships. Court's reasoning: The trial court's finding that the defendant entered into an independent contract on 08.10.2008 was based on conjecture. The court noted that the plaintiff's request for a variation of terms on 10.10.2008 (P10, P3A, P3C) was directed toward the owners, confirming the plaintiff's understanding that the defendant was merely a conduit for the principal. The trial court ignored the significance of the initial agreement date and the nature of the agency relationship. Finding: The District Court erred in answering the issue in the affirmative, and the High Court erred in upholding that decision. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are interdependent. The determination that the defendant acted as an agent (Issue 1) directly negates the finding that the defendant entered into an independent contract as a principal (Issue 2). The court's conclusion that the lower courts failed to evaluate the evidence as a whole, specifically by ignoring the agency status, rendered the finding of a personal contract legally unsustainable. Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The judgments of the High Court and the District Court are set aside, and the defendant is absolved of personal liability for the claimed sum. Keywords Agency — Principal — Agent's liability — Contractual interpretation — High Court error — District Court error — Contract variation — Disclosure of principal — Maritime contract		SC/APPEAL/77/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_77_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-39-2017	19 May 2022	Jayawardena and Others v. Rodrigo and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Interim injunction — Prima facie case — Balance of convenience — Judicature Act — Civil Procedure Code — Substantive relief — Legal rights — District Court — High Court of Civil Appeal	Facts The Plaintiff-Petitioner-Respondents filed an action in the District Court of Colombo seeking a declaration that they, their agents, customers, and suppliers were entitled to use a right of way described in the second schedule to the plaint to access the land described in the first schedule. The Plaintiffs also sought an interim injunction to prevent the Substituted Defendant-Respondent-Appellants from disturbing their use of the said right of way. The District Court refused the application for an interim injunction. Upon appeal, the High Court of Civil Appeal granted the interim injunction. The Substituted Defendant-Respondent-Appellants subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. The disputed right of way is identified as Lot 7 in Plan No. 1095. However, the second schedule to the plaint describes a portion of land in extent 0.1 of a perch that lies outside of this disputed right of way. The substantive relief sought by the Plaintiffs does not refer to Lot 7, which is the actual road in dispute. Issues Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in law in granting the interim injunction. Whether the Plaintiffs established a prima facie case for the grant of an interim injunction. Whether the balance of convenience lies with the Defendant. Applicable Law Statutes: Judicature Act No. 2 of 1978 Civil Procedure Code (Chapter 48) Cases Referred to: Mallika De Silva v. Gamini De Silva - [1999/v1-sri-lr-85] Haji Omar v. Wickremasinghe - [1999/v1-sri-lr-82] Analysis Issue 1: Granting of the interim injunction Rule applied: Section 54 of the Judicature Act No. 2 of 1978 and sections 662-667 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The Court held that an interim injunction is dependent upon the substantive relief sought in the action and cannot exist independently. A party cannot seek interim relief that exceeds the scope of the final relief requested in the pleadings. Because the Plaintiffs' substantive relief and the second schedule to the plaint did not refer to the disputed Lot 7, the Court found that the interim injunction granted by the High Court was incapable of being accommodated in a final judgment. Finding: The High Court erred in granting the interim injunction as the application was misconceived in both fact and law. Issue 2: Prima facie case Rule applied: The principle that a Plaintiff must demonstrate that the Defendant's act violates the Plaintiff's legal rights in respect of the subject matter of the action. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that the Plaintiffs failed to align the subject matter of the interim injunction (Lot 7) with the land described in the schedules of the plaint. Consequently, the Plaintiffs failed to establish a legal right to the specific subject matter for which they sought protection. Finding: The Plaintiffs failed to establish a prima facie case. Issue 3: Balance of convenience Rule applied: The principle that an interim injunction is issued to protect substantive relief and prevent a judgment from being rendered nugatory. Court's reasoning: Given that the interim relief sought was not supported by the substantive pleadings, the Court determined that the application was fundamentally flawed. The Court did not need to weigh the balance of convenience because the lack of nexus between the relief sought and the pleadings rendered the application unsustainable. Finding: The balance of convenience did not support the grant of the injunction. Interaction of Issues The issues are intrinsically linked as the failure to establish a prima facie case (Issue 2) and the lack of alignment between the interim relief and the substantive pleadings (Issue 1) collectively demonstrate that the injunction was legally unsustainable. The resolution of the first issue regarding the scope of the injunction rendered the remaining issues moot, as the court lacked the jurisdiction to grant relief that could not be preserved in a final judgment. Conclusion The Supreme Court set aside the judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal and affirmed the District Court's refusal of the interim injunction. The Substituted Defendant-Respondent-Appellants are entitled to costs in all three courts. Keywords Interim injunction — Prima facie case — Balance of convenience — Judicature Act — Civil Procedure Code — Substantive relief — Legal rights — District Court — High Court of Civil Appeal		SC/APPEAL/39/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_39_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-127-2019	19 May 2022	Chandrakanthi v. Kumara	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Maintenance Act — Adultery — Living in adultery — Proviso to section 2(1) — Time of filing application — Cohabitation — Statutory interpretation	Facts H.M. Chandrakanthi instituted proceedings in the Magistrates Court of Bibile seeking maintenance from her husband, K.M. Gamini Kumara, under the Maintenance Act. The Applicant alleged that the Respondent expelled her from the matrimonial home on 30.07.2014 and subsequently refused to provide maintenance. During the inquiry, it was revealed that the Respondent had discovered the Applicant committing adultery with a person named Guneris in the matrimonial home on the night of the expulsion. Evidence from a police inquiry indicated that the Applicant and Guneris admitted to maintaining an adulterous relationship for approximately four months prior to the incident. The Magistrate initially ordered the Respondent to pay maintenance, finding the allegation of adultery insufficiently proven. On appeal, the High Court set aside the Magistrate's order, ruling that the Applicant was living in adultery at the time of filing her application and was therefore disqualified from receiving maintenance under the proviso to section 2(1) of the Maintenance Act. Issues Whether the Applicant was "living in adultery" at or about the time of filing the maintenance application, thereby triggering the disqualification under the proviso to section 2(1) of the Maintenance Act No. 37 of 1999. Whether the High Court misdirected itself in its legal interpretation of the phrase "living in adultery" as contained in the proviso to section 2(1) of the Maintenance Act. Applicable Law Statutes: Maintenance Act No. 37 of 1999 Cases Referred to: Punchi Banda v. Seelawathie - [1986/v2-sri-lr-414] Wijeysinghe v. Josi Nona - [38-nlr-375] Pushpawathy v. Santhirasegarampillai - [75-nlr-353] Weerasinghe v. Renuka - [2016/v1-sri-lr-57] Analysis Issue 1: Interpretation of "living in adultery" Rule applied: The proviso to section 2(1) of the Maintenance Act No. 37 of 1999, which bars maintenance if the applicant spouse is "living in adultery." Court's reasoning: The Court clarified that "living in adultery" requires more than a single lapse of virtue; it implies a continuing state of cohabitation or promiscuous immorality. However, the Court rejected a literal interpretation that would require proof of adultery on the exact date of filing. It held that the phrase means the applicant must be living in adultery "at or about the time" of filing. The Court reasoned that a strict temporal requirement would allow an applicant to temporarily cease adulterous conduct to circumvent the law, which would lead to an absurd result contrary to legislative intent. Finding: The Applicant was living in adultery at or about the time of filing the application, given that the maintenance application was filed less than one month after she was discovered in an ongoing adulterous relationship. Issue 2: Application of the proviso to the facts Rule applied: The proviso to section 2(1) of the Maintenance Act No. 37 of 1999. Court's reasoning: The Court distinguished the present case from Weerasinghe v. Renuka, where the adulterous conduct occurred long before the separation and the parties had resumed cohabitation. In the instant case, the proximity between the discovery of the four-month-long adulterous relationship and the filing of the maintenance application was sufficient to establish that the Applicant was living in adultery at the material time. Finding: The High Court did not misdirect itself in its interpretation or application of the law. Interaction of Issues The resolution of the legal interpretation of "living in adultery" directly informed the factual determination of the case. By establishing that "at or about the time" is the correct legal standard, the Court was able to conclude that the short duration between the admitted adultery and the filing of the application satisfied the statutory disqualification criteria. Conclusion The Supreme Court affirmed the judgment of the High Court, holding that the Applicant was disqualified from claiming maintenance due to her adulterous conduct. The appeal was dismissed. Keywords Maintenance Act — Adultery — Living in adultery — Proviso to section 2(1) — Time of filing application — Cohabitation — Statutory interpretation		SC/APPEAL/127/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_127_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-56-2020	19 May 2022	Ranaweera v. Singho and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Prevention of Frauds Ordinance — Due execution of a deed — Notary public — Attesting witnesses — Notaries Ordinance — Section 2 of the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance — Section 31 of the Notaries Ordinance — Evidence Ordinance — Proof of documents — Validity of a deed	Facts The Plaintiff filed an action in the District Court seeking a declaration of title to a land and the ejectment of the Defendant. The Defendant filed an answer seeking the dismissal of the action and raised an issue claiming prescriptive title. Following the trial, the District Court entered judgment in favor of the Plaintiff. The Defendant appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal, which set aside the District Court judgment. The High Court concluded that the Plaintiff failed to establish legal title to the land, basing this determination on a comparison between the original title deed (P6) and a photocopy of the same deed (V1). The High Court reasoned that the deed did not fulfill the requirements of the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance and that the attesting witnesses had not provided evidence. The Plaintiff subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law in concluding that deed No. 1986 did not fulfill the requirements of Section 2 of the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance. Whether the High Court misdirected itself in evaluating the evidence by concluding that the attesting witnesses had not given evidence regarding the execution of the deed. Applicable Law Statutes: Prevention of Frauds Ordinance No. 7 of 1840 (as amended) Notaries Ordinance No. 1 of 1907 (as amended) Evidence Ordinance No. 14 of 1895 Civil Procedure Code Cases Referred to: Weeraratne v. Ranmenike - [21-nlr-286] Asliya Umma v. Thingal Mohamed - [1999/v2-sri-lr-152] Wijeyaratne v. Somawathie - [2002/v1-sri-lr-93] Pingamage v. Pingamage - [2005/v2-sri-lr-370] Thiyagarasa v. Arunodayam - [1987/v2-sri-lr-184] Emalia Fernando v. Caroline Fernando - [59-nlr-341] Punchi Baba v. Ekanayake - [4-scc-119] Wijegoonetileke v. Wijegoonetileke - [60-nlr-560] The Solicitor General v. Ahamadulebbe Ava Umma - [71-nlr-512] Wijewardena v. Ellawala - [1991/v2-sri-lr-14] Marian v. Jesuthasan - [59-nlr-348] Ramen Chetty v. Assen Naina - [1-curr-lr-257] Baronchy Appu v. Poidohamy - [2-browns-reports-221] Analysis Issue 1: Compliance with Section 2 of the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance Rule applied: Section 2 of the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance requires a deed to be signed by the executant in the presence of a notary and two or more witnesses present at the same time, and that the execution be duly attested. Court's reasoning: The Court clarified that while formal attestation rules under the Notaries Ordinance are directory, the requirements of Section 2 of the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance are mandatory. The Court held that "duly attested" implies that the notary and witnesses must sign in the presence of the maker and at the same time. However, the Court found that the High Court erred by relying on a photocopy (V1) to invalidate the original deed (P6). The Court emphasized that the Defendant failed to raise an issue regarding due execution at trial and that the evidence confirmed the presence of all parties during execution. Finding: The deed was properly executed in accordance with the law. Issue 2: Evaluation of Evidence regarding Attesting Witnesses Rule applied: Section 68 of the Evidence Ordinance requires that if a document is required by law to be attested, it shall not be used as evidence until at least one attesting witness has been called to prove its execution. Court's reasoning: The High Court incorrectly stated that no attesting witnesses gave evidence. The Supreme Court noted that the notary and the first attesting witness had both testified and confirmed the due execution of the deed. The Court held that a notary is a competent witness to prove attestation and, if they know the executant, can also prove execution. The High Courtâ€™s reliance on inferences from a photocopy was deemed unjust and contrary to the principles of primary evidence. Finding: The High Court misdirected itself; the Plaintiff had sufficiently proven the deed through the testimony of the notary and an attesting witness. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are interdependent. The resolution of the evidentiary issue (Issue 2) confirms that the mandatory requirements of the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance (Issue 1) were satisfied. By establishing that the witnesses were present and testified, the Court effectively negated the High Court's finding that the deed was invalid due to procedural defects. Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal is set aside, and the judgment of the District Court is restored. Keywords Prevention of Frauds Ordinance — Due execution of a deed — Notary public — Attesting witnesses — Notaries Ordinance — Section 2 of the Prevention of Frauds Ordinance — Section 31 of the Notaries Ordinance — Evidence Ordinance — Proof of documents — Validity of a deed		SC/APPEAL/56/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_56_2020.pdf
sc-appeal-239-2017	30 May 2022	The Republic v. Yahalawatte and Others	P. Padman Surasena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Janak De Silva, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Rape — Sexual abuse of a minor — Sentencing — Adequacy of sentence — Court of Appeal's jurisdiction — High Court's discretion — Mitigating circumstances — Age of the accused — Victim's age — Public interest — Deterrence — Welfare of the accused	Facts The Accused, Yahalawatte Wilbert, was indicted in the High Court of Rathnapura under Section 364(2)(e) of the Penal Code for the rape of a girl under 16 years of age. During the trial, the prosecution amended the indictment to a charge under Section 365B(2) of the Penal Code, to which the Accused pleaded guilty. The High Court judge sentenced the Accused to ten months of rigorous imprisonment, a fine of Five Hundred Rupees, and ordered compensation of Fifty Thousand Rupees to the victim. The Attorney General appealed the sentence to the Court of Appeal, contending that the sentence was illegal and inadequate. The Court of Appeal allowed the appeal and enhanced the sentence to seven years of rigorous imprisonment and a fine of One Thousand Rupees, while affirming the compensation order. The Accused subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal erred in determining that the sentence imposed by the High Court was inadequate. Applicable Law Statutes: Penal Code Code of Criminal Procedure Act No. 15 Cases Referred to: The Attorney-General v. H. N. De Silva - [57-nlr-121] M. Gomes (S. I. Police, Crimes) v. W. V. D. Leelaratna - [66-nlr-233] Rex v. Boyd - [1-cr-app-rep-64] Analysis Issue 1: Adequacy of the sentence Rule applied: The court applied the sentencing principles established in The Attorney-General v. H. N. De Silva, which mandate that a judge must balance the interests of the public and the offender, prioritizing the gravity of the offence, the deterrent effect of the punishment, and the protection of public interest over the personal circumstances of the offender. Court's reasoning: The High Court judge improperly mitigated the sentence based on the Accused's age, alleged heart ailment, the lack of violence, the lapse of time since the offence, and the state's cost of maintaining prisoners. The Supreme Court found these factors insufficient to justify a lenient sentence for the grave sexual abuse of an eight-year-old child. Specifically, the court noted that the absence of violence is irrelevant when the victim is a child, and that the state's responsibility to maintain prisons is an integral part of the Rule of Law. Furthermore, the court held that the High Court judge failed to provide adequate weight to the seriousness of the crime and the fiduciary relationship between the Accused and the victim. The Court of Appeal correctly identified these errors and imposed the minimum sentence prescribed by law. Finding: The Court of Appeal did not err in its determination that the original sentence was inadequate. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The High Court judge is directed to take prompt steps to implement the balance of the enhanced sentence imposed by the Court of Appeal. Keywords Rape — Sexual abuse of a minor — Sentencing — Adequacy of sentence — Court of Appeal's jurisdiction — High Court's discretion — Mitigating circumstances — Age of the accused — Victim's age — Public interest — Deterrence — Welfare of the accused		SC/APPEAL/239/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_239_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-110-2016	6 June 2022	De Zoysa v. Ramanaden and Others	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Partition action — Settlement — Consent decree — Civil Procedure Code — Sections 91 and 408 — Investigation of title — Added Defendants — Prescriptive rights — Terms of settlement — Precision and certainty	Facts Shamali Arunika de Zoysa instituted a partition action in the District Court of Trincomalee regarding a land known as Orrs Hill. The Petitioner and the 1st to 3rd Respondents were the original parties, and subsequently, nine added Defendants were joined to the action. During the trial, the added Defendants proposed a settlement to purchase the portions of land they occupied at a rate of Rupees 200,000 per perch. The Petitioner led evidence, but the other Defendants did not. The District Judge accepted the Petitioner's evidence and incorporated the proposed settlement into the interlocutory decree. The Petitioner later filed an application under Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code to set aside the settlement, arguing that no valid agreement had been reached. The District Court refused this application, holding that a valid settlement existed. The Petitioner then appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal in Trincomalee, which dismissed the revision application. The Petitioner subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the purported settlement was vague, uncertain, and incapable of implementation. Whether the settlement was entered into in violation of Sections 91 and 408 of the Civil Procedure Code. Whether the District Court failed to properly investigate the title of all parties before entering the partition decree. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 128 High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 19 of 1990 Rehabilitation of Persons and Property and Industry Authorities Act No. 29 of 1987 Partition Law No. 21 of 1977, Section 25(1) Civil Procedure Code, Section 91 Civil Procedure Code, Section 408 Civil Procedure Code, Section 839 Cases Referred to: Caroline Perera v. Martin Perera - [2002/v2-sri-lr-1] Faleel v. Argeen - [2004/v1-sri-lr-48] Kumarihamy v. Weeragama - [43-nlr-265] Richard v. Seibel Nona - [2001/v2-sri-lr-1] Sopinona v. Pitipanaarachchi - [2010/v1-sri-lr-87] Gangoda Mudiyanselage Wijewathi Podimenike v. Pathirennehelage Leelawathie - [sc-appeal-178/2013] Gunawardena v. Ran Menike - [2002/v3-sri-lr-243] Peoples Bank v. Gilbert Weerasinghe - [2-calr] Ukku Amma v. Paramanathan - [63-nlr-306] Babyhamine v. Jamis - [46-clw-5] Avenra Gardens v. Global Project Funding AG - [sc-appeal-157/2019] Dassanaike v. Dassanaike - [30-nlr-385] Analysis Issue 1: Validity and Precision of Settlement Rule applied: The principle that a partition settlement must be based on clear, unambiguous terms and mutual consent to be binding. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the settlement lacked essential details, such as which co-owner was entitled to which allotment and who was to receive payments from which added Defendant. There was no timeline for performance or consequences for breach. Finding: The settlement was found to be vague, uncertain, and unenforceable. Issue 2: Compliance with Civil Procedure Code Rule applied: Sections 91 and 408 of the Civil Procedure Code, which require settlements to be notified to the court by motion signed by the parties or their registered attorneys. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the terms were merely recorded in open court rather than submitted via a formal motion. Furthermore, some parties were absent or deceased when the terms were recorded, violating the requirement for mutual consent. Finding: The settlement violated Sections 91 and 408 of the Civil Procedure Code and is invalid. Issue 3: Duty to Investigate Title Rule applied: Section 25(1) of the Partition Law No. 21 of 1977, which mandates that the court must investigate the title of each party. Court's reasoning: While the District Judge investigated the Petitioner's title, he failed to investigate the title of the added Defendants, who did not lead evidence. Finding: The failure to investigate the added Defendants' titles rendered the resulting decree defective. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected; the lack of precision (Issue 1) and the failure to comply with procedural requirements (Issue 2) demonstrate a lack of true consensus. This procedural failure, combined with the court's failure to investigate title (Issue 3), confirms that the settlement could not form the basis of a valid partition decree. Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The judgment of the High Court, the District Court judgment, the interlocutory decree, and the purported settlement are set aside. The District Court is directed to proceed with the trial from the point where the Petitioner concluded leading evidence. Keywords Partition action — Settlement — Consent decree — Civil Procedure Code — Sections 91 and 408 — Investigation of title — Added Defendants — Prescriptive rights — Terms of settlement — Precision and certainty		SC/FR/110/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_110_2016.pdf
sc-contempt-06-18	07 June 2022	Ranjan Ramanayake v. Attorney General	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC, J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC, J.; L.T.B Dehideniya, J; E.A.G.R Amarasekara, J	Contempt of Court — Article 105(3) — Judicial Integrity — Public Trust — Plea of Guilty — Mitigation Factors — Sentencing — Remorse — Speculative Statements — Judicial Proceedings — Public Perception — Social Justice — Legal Precedents — Criminal Procedure Act — Judicial Accountability	Facts The case revolves around an application for contempt of court against Ranjan Ramanayake, a prominent figure in Sri Lanka, who made statements during a television program that were deemed to undermine the integrity of the judiciary. The statements were made in reference to a case pending before the Supreme Court, where Ramanayake suggested that the judges had predetermined the outcome of the case. This led to the issuance of a Rule under Article 105(3) of the Constitution, requiring him to show cause as to why he should not be punished for contempt. Initially, Ramanayake pleaded not guilty, but during the inquiry, he decided to withdraw his plea and plead guilty, acknowledging the seriousness of his statements. The court took into account the context of his remarks, his contributions to society, and his expression of remorse. Issues The primary issues before the court were: Whether Ramanayake's statements constituted contempt of court. Whether the court should consider his plea of guilty and expressions of remorse in determining the appropriate sentence. Applicable Law Statutes: Article 105(3) of the Constitution of Sri Lanka; Section 303 of the Code of Criminal Procedure Act No. 15 of 1979 (as amended). Cases Referred to: In Re Prashant Bhushan and another Contempt Petition (CRL) No.1 of 2020. Analysis Issue 1: Whether Ramanayake's statements constituted contempt of court. Rule applied: Article 105(3) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: The court meticulously examined the statements made by Ramanayake during the television program, particularly focusing on the implications of his utterances. The court noted that Ramanayake's comments suggested that the judges had already made up their minds regarding the case, which could severely undermine public confidence in the judicial system. The court emphasized that any speculation regarding judicial decisions, especially before a case is heard, poses a significant threat to the integrity of the judiciary. The court stated, "Creating such an impression in the minds of the public would undoubtedly have an adverse effect on the credibility of the institution and more so on the trust the public reposes in the administration of justice." The court highlighted the importance of maintaining public trust in the judicial system and the duty of every citizen to protect the integrity of the administration of justice. Finding: The court concluded that Ramanayake's statements did indeed constitute contempt of court, as they were speculative and undermined the authority of the judiciary. Issue 2: Whether the court should consider his plea of guilty and expressions of remorse in determining the appropriate sentence. Rule applied: Sentencing principles in contempt cases. Court's reasoning: In considering the appropriate sentence, the court acknowledged Ramanayake's change of plea to guilty and his expressions of remorse. The court noted that he had voluntarily decided to plead guilty, which indicated an understanding of the gravity of his actions. The court also considered the mitigating factors presented by his counsel, including Ramanayake's contributions to the film industry and his activism for social justice. The court referenced the case of In Re Prashant Bhushan, where the Indian Supreme Court imposed a nominal punishment due to the contemnor's bona fide intentions and subsequent regret. The court stated, "We have also considered the other mitigatory factors urged before this court on behalf of the Respondent." Ultimately, the court decided to impose a sentence of two years imprisonment but suspended the sentence for five years, allowing Ramanayake the opportunity to reflect on his actions without immediate incarceration. Finding: The court found that while contempt was established, the mitigating circumstances warranted a suspended sentence rather than immediate imprisonment. Interaction of Issues The issues of whether Ramanayake's statements constituted contempt and whether his plea of guilty and expressions of remorse should influence sentencing are interrelated. The court's determination of contempt was based on the nature of the statements made, while the subsequent consideration of his plea and remorse directly impacted the severity of the punishment. The court's approach reflects a balance between upholding the integrity of the judiciary and recognizing the potential for rehabilitation and understanding in the contemnor. Conclusion The Supreme Court ultimately convicted Ranjan Ramanayake of contempt of court for his statements that undermined the integrity of the judiciary. However, taking into account his guilty plea, expressions of remorse, and contributions to society, the court imposed a suspended sentence of two years imprisonment, emphasizing the importance of maintaining public trust in the judicial system while allowing for the possibility of redemption. Keywords Contempt of Court — Article 105(3) — Judicial Integrity — Public Trust — Plea of Guilty — Mitigation Factors — Sentencing — Remorse — Speculative Statements — Judicial Proceedings — Public Perception — Social Justice — Legal Precedents — Criminal Procedure Act — Judicial Accountability	Anura Maddegoda PC, with Ashan Fernando, Ms. Nadeesha Kannangara and Saumya Wijesinghe instructed by Sandun Gamage for the Respondent; Madhawa Tennekoon DSG, with Sahanya Naranpanawa SC for the Hon. Attorney General	SC/CONT/6/2018	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_cont_6_2018.pdf
sc-appeal-05-2010	8 June 2022	The Sampath Bank Limited v. The Pay Phone Company (Pvt) Ltd and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Appeal against orders of High Court — Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code — Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code — Default judgment — Absence of defendant — Opportunity to purge default — Abuse of process of court — Reasonable grounds for default — Trial de novo	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent, The Sampath Bank Limited, instituted an action in the High Court of Colombo against the Defendant-Appellant, The Pay Phone Company (Pvt) Ltd., to recover outstanding loan amounts. During the trial proceedings, the Defendant-Appellant repeatedly failed to appear or be represented by counsel, leading to multiple delays. On 7th March 2007, the High Court Judge, noting the absence of the Defendant-Appellant and their counsel, decided to proceed with the case under Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code. Subsequently, the Defendant-Appellant filed applications to revoke their proxy, appoint new counsel, and set aside the order of 7th March 2007, claiming they were unable to secure legal representation. The High Court Judge rejected these applications, citing the Defendant-Appellant's history of avoiding court proceedings, the lack of proper instructions to previous counsel, and the submission of inconsistent documents. On 24th July 2007, the High Court entered judgment in favor of the Plaintiff-Respondent. The Defendant-Appellant then appealed to the Supreme Court, seeking to set aside the High Court's orders and requesting a trial de novo or an inquiry to purge their default. Throughout the appellate process, the Defendant-Appellant continued to exhibit a pattern of failing to maintain legal representation and failing to appear, resulting in the matter being heard in their absence. Issues Whether the High Court was justified in proceeding with the action under Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code due to the Defendant-Appellant's failure to appear or produce evidence. Whether the High Court erred in refusing to exercise its inherent powers under Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code to allow the Defendant-Appellant to purge their default. Whether the Defendant-Appellant provided reasonable grounds under Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code to set aside the judgment and decree. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code, Section 86(2) Civil Procedure Code, Section 145 Civil Procedure Code, Section 754(1) Civil Procedure Code, Section 839 High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 10 of 1996 Cases Referred to: David Appuhamy v. Yassassi Thero - [1987/v1-sri-lr-253] Sanicoch Group of Companies v. Kala Traders (Pvt) Ltd - [2016-blr-44] De Fonseka v. Dharmawardena - [1994/v3-sri-lr-49] Analysis Issue 1: Justification of Section 145 proceedings Rule applied: Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code, which permits a court to decide an action forthwith if a party fails to produce evidence or attend court when time has been granted. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the Defendant-Appellant was granted multiple opportunities to present their case but failed to do so due to a consistent pattern of absence and lack of legal representation. The High Court Judge acted within the scope of the law to prevent further delay. Finding: The High Court was justified in proceeding under Section 145. Issue 2: Exercise of inherent powers under Section 839 Rule applied: Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code regarding the inherent powers of the court to make orders necessary for the ends of justice or to prevent abuse of process. Court's reasoning: While the court has the power to allow a party to purge default, this is a discretionary power. The court found that the Defendant-Appellantâ€™s conduct constituted an abuse of the judicial process. Exercising inherent powers in their favor would facilitate further abuse rather than serve the ends of justice. Finding: The refusal to exercise inherent powers was correct and in the interest of justice. Issue 3: Reasonable grounds for default under Section 86(2) Rule applied: Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code, which requires a defendant to satisfy the court that they had reasonable grounds for their default. Court's reasoning: The Defendant-Appellant failed to provide any valid or reasonable excuse for their repeated absences. The court noted that the Defendant-Appellantâ€™s claims were vague and lacked specificity, failing to meet the burden of proof required to set aside an ex-parte decree. Finding: The Defendant-Appellant failed to establish reasonable grounds for their default. Interaction of Issues The findings on all issues are reinforced by the Defendant-Appellant's established pattern of conduct. The failure to provide reasonable grounds (Issue 3) directly supports the court's decision to deny the exercise of inherent powers (Issue 2), which in turn validates the High Court's initial decision to proceed under Section 145 (Issue 1). The consistency of this behavior across both the High Court and the Supreme Court confirms that the appeal lacks merit. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed with costs. The Defendant-Appellant is ordered to pay a sum of Rupees Five Hundred Thousand as punitive costs to be deposited at the Commercial High Court of Colombo. Keywords Appeal against orders of High Court — Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code — Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code — Default judgment — Absence of defendant — Opportunity to purge default — Abuse of process of court — Reasonable grounds for default — Trial de novo		SC/CHC APPEAL/5/2010	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_chc_appeal_5_2010.pdf
sc-fr-311-2019	8 June 2022	Malik Sachinthana v. University Grants Commission and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — University admission — Z-score — Higher National Diploma — Registration requirements — Administrative action — Violation of fundamental rights — Right to education	Facts The Petitioner, M.D. Malik Sachinthana, sat for the General Certificate of Education (Advanced Level) Examination in August 2018 and achieved high merit, qualifying him for admission to a Faculty of Law. He applied to the University Grants Commission (UGC) for admission to the University of Colombo, Peradeniya, or Jaffna. The UGC rejected his application on the grounds that he was a registered student at the Advanced Technological Institute (ATI), Galle, which purportedly disqualified him under the UGC admission handbook. The Petitioner contended that he never completed the registration process at the ATI because he failed to submit mandatory documents, including his school leaving certificate. Although he had passed an entrance examination for the ATI, he never attended lectures or utilized the institute's facilities. The ATI admitted that due to a clerical error, the Petitionerâ€™s name remained in their system, but confirmed he was not a validly registered student. Subsequent correspondence from the ATI and the Sri Lanka Institute of Advanced Technological Education (SLIATE) clarified that the Petitioner had not been a student and that the initial reports of his registration were erroneous. Despite this, the UGC maintained that its decision to reject the Petitioner was final and could not be altered. Issues Whether the rejection of the Petitioner's university application by the UGC constituted a violation of his fundamental right to equality under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the Petitioner was a "validly registered student" at the ATI, thereby disqualifying him from university admission under the UGC handbook. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 27(2)(h) Universities Act, No. 16 Cases Referred to: Surendran v. The University Grants Commission - [1993/v1-sri-lr-344] Rienzie Perera v. University Grants Commission - [1978-79-80/v1-sri-lr-128] Analysis Issue 1: Violation of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution, which guarantees the right to equal treatment and equal protection of the law. Court's reasoning: The court reasoned that the UGC, as an executive body, must ensure that university admissions are fair and transparent. By relying on erroneous information regarding the Petitioner's registration status at the ATI, the UGC arbitrarily deprived a qualified student of his right to higher education. The court emphasized that the state has a duty to provide equal access to education based on merit, and the UGCâ€™s refusal to rectify a clear administrative error was inconsistent with the principles of fairness and equality. Finding: The court found that the Petitionerâ€™s fundamental rights under Article 12(1) were violated. Issue 2: Validity of ATI Registration Rule applied: The guidelines for registration at the ATI, which mandate the submission of a school leaving certificate. Court's reasoning: The court examined evidence showing that the Petitioner never submitted his school leaving certificate, which was a mandatory requirement for registration. Both the ATI and SLIATE admitted that the Petitionerâ€™s inclusion in the registration list was a clerical error and that he had never attended lectures or received benefits. The court concluded that the Petitioner was never a validly registered student and that the UGCâ€™s reliance on the erroneous registration status was unjustified. Finding: The Petitioner was not a validly registered student at the ATI, and the disqualification based on such registration was invalid. Interaction of Issues The findings are intrinsically linked; the determination that the Petitioner was not a validly registered student (Issue 2) directly invalidated the basis for the UGC's rejection of his application. Consequently, the arbitrary nature of the UGC's refusal to correct this error, despite evidence from the ATI and SLIATE, directly resulted in the infringement of the Petitioner's constitutional right to equality (Issue 1). Conclusion The court allowed the application, declaring that the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1) were violated. The 1st and 2nd Respondents were directed to admit the Petitioner to the appropriate university for the next available intake, and the 1st Respondent was ordered to pay the Petitioner costs of Rs. 500,000 within six months. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — University admission — Z-score — Higher National Diploma — Registration requirements — Administrative action — Violation of fundamental rights — Right to education		SC/FR/311/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_311_2019.pdf
sc-chc-5-2010	09 June 2022	Sampath Bank Limited v. The Pay Phone Company (Pvt) Ltd.	S. Thurai Raja, P.C., J.	S. Thurai Raja, P.C., J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Civil Procedure Code — Natural Justice — Default Judgment — Appeal — Trial de Novo — Inherent Powers of Court — Judicial Process — Legal Precedents — Affidavit Evidence — Cross-Examination — Proxy Revocation — Abuse of Process — Costs — Judgment Enforcement — Default of Appearance — Reasonable Grounds	Facts The Sampath Bank Limited (hereinafter referred to as the Plaintiff-Respondent) initiated legal proceedings against The Pay Phone Company (Pvt) Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as the Defendant-Appellant) in the High Court of Colombo on 17th October 2003, seeking recovery of a sum of Rs. 3,554,729.08 along with interest and additional sums totaling Rs. 690,371.02 with further interest. The Plaintiff-Respondent's claims stemmed from loans extended to the Defendant-Appellant, which the latter denied, prompting a series of legal maneuvers. The Defendant-Appellant's counsel faced multiple challenges, including absences from court hearings and a lack of communication with the Defendant-Appellant, which ultimately led to a judgment being entered in favor of the Plaintiff-Respondent on 24th July 2007. The Defendant-Appellant subsequently filed a petition on 7th September 2007 appealing the High Court's decisions, including the judgment and orders made on 7th March 2007, which allowed the case to proceed under Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code. The Defendant-Appellant sought a trial de novo, claiming they were denied the opportunity to present their defense adequately. The court noted a pattern of behavior from the Defendant-Appellant, characterized by repeated absences and failure to secure legal representation, which raised concerns about their diligence in prosecuting the case. Issues Whether the Defendant-Appellant was afforded a fair opportunity to present their defense in accordance with the principles of natural justice? Whether the High Court's decision to proceed under Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code was justified given the Defendant-Appellant's conduct? Whether the Defendant-Appellant had reasonable grounds for their default and should be allowed to purge it? Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code, High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No.10 of 1996 Cases Referred to: David Appuhamy v. Yassassi Thero - [1987] 1 SLR 253; Sanicoch Group of Companies v. Kala Traders (Pvt) Ltd - [2016] BLR 44; De Fonseka v. Dharmawardena - [1994] 3 SLR 49. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the Defendant-Appellant was afforded a fair opportunity to present their defense in accordance with the principles of natural justice? Rule applied: Principles of Natural Justice. Court's reasoning: The court examined the Defendant-Appellant's claims of being denied a fair opportunity to defend themselves. It was noted that the Defendant-Appellant had been absent from multiple hearings, and their counsel had withdrawn due to a lack of instructions. The court emphasized that natural justice requires that parties be given a fair chance to present their case, but this opportunity must be utilized effectively. The court found that the Defendant-Appellant had ample time to prepare and present their defense but failed to do so. The court cited the absence of the Defendant-Appellant and their counsel on critical dates, including the judgment date, as evidence of their neglect. The court concluded that the Defendant-Appellant's claims of being denied natural justice were unfounded, as they had not taken the necessary steps to engage in the proceedings. Finding: The court found that the Defendant-Appellant was not denied a fair opportunity to present their defense. Issue 2: Whether the High Court's decision to proceed under Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code was justified given the Defendant-Appellant's conduct? Rule applied: Section 145 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court analyzed the application of Section 145, which allows the court to proceed with a case despite a party's failure to produce evidence or attend court. The court noted that the Defendant-Appellant had been granted sufficient opportunities to present their case but had repeatedly failed to do so. The court highlighted that the High Court Judge's decision to proceed was justified to prevent further delays and to uphold the integrity of the judicial process. The court referenced the Defendant-Appellant's pattern of behavior, which included failing to secure legal representation and not attending court hearings, as a basis for the High Court's decision. Finding: The court upheld the High Court's decision to proceed under Section 145, finding it justified based on the Defendant-Appellant's conduct. Issue 3: Whether the Defendant-Appellant had reasonable grounds for their default and should be allowed to purge it? Rule applied: Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court examined the Defendant-Appellant's request to purge their default under Section 839, which allows the court to exercise its inherent powers to ensure justice. The court noted that the Defendant-Appellant had not provided sufficient evidence or reasoning to justify their default. The court emphasized that the burden was on the Defendant-Appellant to demonstrate reasonable grounds for their failure to appear and defend the case. The court found that the Defendant-Appellant's conduct indicated a deliberate avoidance of court proceedings rather than a genuine inability to participate. Finding: The court concluded that the Defendant-Appellant did not have reasonable grounds for their default and denied their request to purge it. Interaction of Issues The issues presented were interrelated, as the Defendant-Appellant's failure to engage in the proceedings directly impacted their claims of being denied natural justice and the justification for the High Court's actions under Section 145. The court's findings on each issue reinforced the conclusion that the Defendant-Appellant's conduct was the primary reason for the unfavorable outcome. Conclusion The Supreme Court dismissed the appeal, affirming the High Court's decisions and emphasizing the importance of diligence in legal proceedings. The court ordered the Defendant-Appellant to pay costs, including punitive costs, reflecting the court's disapproval of their conduct throughout the case. The judgment underscored the necessity for parties to actively participate in legal proceedings to ensure their rights are protected.	Chandaka Jayasundera, PC with Ms. Vishmi Fernando instructed by Senaka Hewawitharana for the Plaintiff-Respondent. The Defendant-Appellant is absent and unrepresented.	SC/CHC APPEAL/5/2010	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_chc_appeal_5_2010.pdf
sc-appeal-42-2010	16 June 2022	Visenthi Baduge Piyasiri and Peoplesâ€™ Bank v. Banda and Banda	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Revocation of deed of gift — Consent of parties — Irrevocability of gifts — Transfer of title — Roman Dutch common law — Exceptio rei venditae et traditae — Primary Court Procedure Act — Section 66 — Ownership of immovable property	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent-Petitioner (Appellant) instituted an action in the District Court of Tangalle seeking a declaration of title and the ejectment of the Defendant-Appellant-Respondent (Respondent) from the land called Kahagalagodella/Bogahahena. The Appellant claimed title through a series of deeds, beginning with a gift from Vineetha Ediriweera Jayasuriya and A.P. Baby Champa Matilda via deed No. 645. Subsequently, the parties executed a deed of revocation No. 710 with the Appellant's consent. The Appellant later executed deed No. 970 to gift the property to Vineetha Jayasuriya, followed by subsequent transfers back to the Appellant. The Respondent, the husband of A.P. Baby Champa Matilda, challenged the validity of the Appellant's title, asserting that the deed of revocation rendered the subsequent deeds null and void. The District Court initially ruled in favor of the Appellant, holding that the original gift was irrevocable and the revocation was invalid. The Civil Appellate High Court of Matara reversed this decision, finding that the deed of revocation was validly executed with the consent of all parties, thereby nullifying the subsequent chain of title. The Appellant appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Civil Appellate High Court misconstrued the law regarding the revocation of a deed of gift when the donee consents to such revocation. Whether the principle of exceptio rei venditae et traditae applies to the chain of title in this matter. Whether proceedings under Section 66 of the Primary Court Procedure Act can establish title or right to possession in a civil action. Applicable Law Statutes: Primary Court Procedure Act No. 44 of 1979 Cases Referred to: Stephen v. Hettiarachchi and Another - [2002/v3-sri-lr-39] Jinaratana Thero v. Somananda Thero - [32-clw-11] Rathnayake Mudiyanselage Jayathilaka v. R.M. Siriwardena of Ihalagama - [sc-appeal-221/2012] Nicholas De Silva v. Shaik Ali - [1-nlr-228] Tissera v. William - [45-nlr-358] Rajamanthri Gedera Somalatha v. Wajira Kanthi Rathnasinghe - [sc-appeal-33/2013] Ramalingam v. Thangarajah - [1982/v2-sri-lr-693] Analysis Issue 1: Revocation of Deed of Gift Rule applied: The court applied the principle that while a deed of gift is generally irrevocable, it may be revoked if the donor reserved such a right or if the donee consents to the revocation. Court's reasoning: The court examined the expressed intention of the parties in deed of revocation No. 710. It held that because the donee (the Appellant) consented to the revocation, the deed was valid, and title reverted to the original owners. Consequently, the Appellant lacked the legal capacity to execute subsequent deed No. 970. Finding: The High Court did not misconstrue the law; the revocation was valid, and the Appellant's subsequent title claims failed. Issue 2: Application of exceptio rei venditae et traditae Rule applied: The court applied the Roman Dutch common law principle of exceptio rei venditae et traditae, which allows a purchaser to claim title if a vendor acquires it after a sale, while noting the exception for donations. Court's reasoning: The court cited Tissera v. William to establish that this exception does not apply to donations, as they are stricti juris. Since the deed in question was a gift, the principle could not be invoked to cure the Appellant's lack of title. Finding: The principle is inapplicable to the present case. Issue 3: Section 66 of the Primary Court Procedure Act Rule applied: The court applied the principle that proceedings under Section 66 of the Primary Court Procedure Act are intended to prevent breaches of the peace and do not determine civil title. Court's reasoning: Relying on Ramalingam v. Thangarajah, the court clarified that such proceedings are not civil actions and cannot be used to justify or establish title or rights to possession. Finding: The High Court correctly identified that Section 66 proceedings do not establish ownership. Interaction of Issues The validity of the revocation (Issue 1) fundamentally undermined the Appellant's chain of title. Because the Appellant held no title after the revocation, the subsequent deeds were void. The failure of the exceptio rei venditae et traditae (Issue 2) prevented the Appellant from relying on later acquisitions to validate the initial void transfer. Finally, the irrelevance of the Primary Court proceedings (Issue 3) confirmed that the Appellant could not rely on those findings to bolster his failed title claim. Conclusion The Supreme Court dismissed the appeal, affirming the judgment of the Civil Appellate High Court. The parties are to bear their own costs. Keywords Revocation of deed of gift — Consent of parties — Irrevocability of gifts — Transfer of title — Roman Dutch common law — Exceptio rei venditae et traditae — Primary Court Procedure Act — Section 66 — Ownership of immovable property		SC/APPEAL/42/2010	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_42_2010-1.pdf
sc-appeal-244-2014	16 June 2022	Fernando v. Tirimanne and Others	Achala Wengappuli, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya PC, J; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser — Specific performance — Anticipatory breach of contract — Constructive trust — Fraudulent acquisition — Notice of agreement to sell	Facts The Plaintiff entered into an agreement to purchase a house and property from the 1st Defendant for Rs. 200,000. The agreement stipulated that the Plaintiff would pay the balance consideration within three months, upon which the 1st Defendant would transfer the property with vacant possession. The Plaintiff secured the funds and informed the 1st Defendant of his readiness to complete the transaction. The 1st Defendant refused to proceed, citing an inability to provide vacant possession due to the presence of a tenant, the 2nd Defendant. Subsequently, the 1st Defendant transferred the property to the 2nd Defendant. The Plaintiff instituted an action for specific performance against the 1st Defendant and later added the 2nd Defendant as a party. The District Court held that the Plaintiff was entitled to specific performance, finding that the Plaintiff had fulfilled his obligations and that the 2nd Defendant was not a bona fide purchaser. The Court of Appeal affirmed this decision. The 2nd Defendant appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Plaintiff was entitled to specific performance despite the alleged failure to tender the balance consideration within the stipulated time. Whether the 2nd Defendant was a bona fide purchaser for value without notice of the prior agreement. Whether the contract between the Plaintiff and the 1st Defendant remained alive after the 1st Defendant's repudiation. Whether the Court of Appeal erred in referencing Section 93 of the Trusts Ordinance when the action was founded on breach of contract. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code, Section 18 Prevention of Frauds Ordinance, Section 2 Registration of Documents Ordinance, Section 42 Trusts Ordinance, Section 93, Section 98 Cases Referred to: Jeremias Fernando v. Perera - [28-nlr-183] Holmes v. Alia Marikkar - [1-nlr-282] Fernando v. Coomaraswamy - [41-nlr-466] Premaratne v. Yasawathie - [2015/v1-sri-lr-302] Babahamy v. Alexander - [2-nlr-159] Muhandiram v. Salam - [49-nlr-80] Razik v. Esufally - [58-nlr-469] Appuhamy v. Silva - [17-nlr-238] Kanagammah Hoole v. Natarajan - [66-nlr-484] Thaheer v. Abdeen - [57-nlr-1] Abdeen v. Thaheer - [59-nlr-385] Amarashighe Appuhamy v. Boteju - [11-nlr-187] The Holland Ceylon Commercial Company v. Mahuthoom Pillai - [24-nlr-152] Mutukaruppan Chetty v. Habibhoy - [3-cac-100] Thidoris Perera v. Eliza Nona - [50-nlr-176] Noorbhai v. Karuppan Chetti - [27-nlr-325] Alawdeen v. Holland Ceylon Commercial Company - [54-nlr-289] Senanayake v. Anthonisz - [69-nlr-225] Carimjee Jafferjee v. Theodoris - [5-bal-20] Matthes Appuhamy v. Raymond - [2-nlr-270] Wickramanayake v. Abeywardene - [17-nlr-169] Fernando v. Peris - [19-nlr-281] De Silva v. Senaratne - [50-nlr-313] Noorulasin v. De Zoysa - [1989/v1-sri-lr-63] Pathmawathie v. Jayasekera - [1997/v1-sri-lr-248] Kusumawathie v. Weerasinghe - [33-nlr-265] Coomaraswamy v. Vinayagamoorthy - [46-nlr-246] Attorney General v. Herath - [62-nlr-145] Fernando v. Perera - [17-nlr-161] Sulaikamummah v. Ahamadylevvai - [19-nlr-473] Mendis v. Abeysinghe - [1994/v2-sri-lr-29] Rajapaksa v. Fernando - [20-nlr-301] De Silva v. Lapaya - [29-nlr-177] Shanmugam v. Thambiaiyah - [1987/v1-sri-lr-357] Crdit Agricole Corporation and Investment Bank v. Papadimitriou - [2015/ukpc-13] Abdul Majeed v. Ummu Zaneera - [61-nlr-361] Silva v. Salo Nona - [32-nlr-81] Analysis Issue 1: Entitlement to Specific Performance Rule applied: Roman-Dutch law principles regarding tender and specific performance. Court's reasoning: The court found that the Plaintiff had communicated his readiness and willingness to pay the balance consideration within the stipulated time. The 1st Defendantâ€™s refusal to accept the payment and his repudiation of the contract excused the Plaintiff from further formal tender. Finding: The Plaintiff fulfilled his obligations, and the 1st Defendantâ€™s breach entitled the Plaintiff to specific performance. Issue 2: Bona Fide Purchaser Status Rule applied: Doctrine of notice in property transactions. Court's reasoning: The 2nd Defendant admitted to searching the Land Registry and having notice of the registered agreement. The court applied the test from Crdit Agricole Corporation and Investment Bank v. Papadimitriou, concluding that the 2nd Defendant had actual notice of the encumbrance and failed to make reasonable inquiries. Finding: The 2nd Defendant was not a bona fide purchaser for value without notice. Issue 3: Status of the Contract Rule applied: Law of contract regarding repudiation and election. Court's reasoning: Repudiation by one party does not automatically terminate a contract. The innocent party may elect to keep the contract alive. The Plaintiff consistently insisted on performance, thereby keeping the contract alive. Finding: The contract remained valid and enforceable. Issue 4: Reference to Trusts Ordinance Rule applied: Principles of appellate review. Court's reasoning: The court determined that the Court of Appealâ€™s reference to Section 93 of the Trusts Ordinance was supplementary to its primary reasoning based on the law of contract. It did not form the basis of the decision. Finding: The reference did not invalidate the judgment. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing: because the contract remained alive (Issue 3), the Plaintiff retained the right to specific performance (Issue 1). Since the 2nd Defendant had notice of this prior interest (Issue 2), he could not claim the protection of a bona fide purchaser, and the courtâ€™s reference to the Trusts Ordinance (Issue 4) was merely secondary to the primary contractual analysis. Conclusion The appeal of the 2nd Defendant is dismissed. The judgments of the District Court and the Court of Appeal are affirmed. Keywords Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser — Specific performance — Anticipatory breach of contract — Constructive trust — Fraudulent acquisition — Notice of agreement to sell		SC/APPEAL/244/2014	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_244_2014.pdf
sc-fr-429-2016	16 June 2022	Sedara and Others v. Sri Lanka Tea Board and Others	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Scheme of Recruitment and Promotions — Continuing violation — Time bar — Human Rights Commission	Facts The Petitioners are employees of the Sri Lanka Tea Board who were originally recruited to the Clerical and Allied Services. Following the introduction of Public Administrative Circular 06/2006 and Department of Management Services Circular No. 30, a new salary structure and recruitment scheme were implemented. The Petitioners were subsequently placed in the salary scale MA-1-1-2006. On 25/10/2011, a new Scheme of Recruitment and Promotions was introduced, and on 06/06/2012, the Petitioners received formal letters absorbing them into the post of Management Assistant Non-Technical. The Petitioners contend that the new scheme lacks a promotional path to the Executive Grade, which they previously enjoyed under the former scheme. They argue this omission is arbitrary and discriminatory, violating their fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. The Petitioners sought administrative remedies through various representations to the Respondent Board and the Human Rights Commission. They filed the present application on 30/11/2016, seeking a declaration of rights and an order for the creation of a promotional path. The Respondents raised a preliminary objection that the application is time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the Petitioners' application is time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Whether the alleged failure to provide a promotional path constitutes a "continuing violation" that exempts the Petitioners from the one-month time limit. Whether the Petitioners' pursuit of administrative remedies and a complaint to the Human Rights Commission tolls the time limit prescribed by Article 126(2). Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1), Article 126(1), Article 126(2) Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act No. 21 of 1996, Section 13(1) Cases Referred to: Edirisuriya v. Navaratnam - [1985/v1-sri-lr-100] G.S. Premachandra v. University Grants Commission - [sc-fr-573/2004] Rajakaruna v. de Silva - [1997/v2-sri-lr-209] Siriwardana v. Rodrigo - [1986/v1-sri-lr-384] Gamaethige v. Siriwardena - [1988/v1-sri-lr-384] Demuni Sriyani De Soyza v. Darmasena Dissanayake - [sc-fr-206/2008] Lake House Employees Union v. Associated Newspapers of Ceylon Ltd - [sc-fr-637/2009] Jayaweera v. National Film Corporation - [1995/v2-sri-lr-120] Dayaratne v. National Savings Bank - [2002/v3-sri-lr-116] Analysis Issue 1: Time-bar under Article 126(2) Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution requires a fundamental rights application to be filed within one month of the alleged infringement. Court's reasoning: The court determined that the infringement, if any, crystallized when the Petitioners were formally absorbed into the new post via letters dated 06/06/2012. This act provided certainty regarding the terms and conditions of their employment, including the absence of a promotional path. The Petitioners failed to file their application within one month of this date. Finding: The application is time-barred. Issue 2: Continuing violation Rule applied: The principle that a series of acts may constitute a continuing violation, but the application must be filed within one month of the last act in the series. Court's reasoning: The court rejected the argument that the omission to provide a promotional path was a continuing violation. It held that the issuance of the formal appointment letters on 06/06/2012 was a distinct, one-off act. The court noted that the Petitioners' reliance on "continuing violation" was an attempt to circumvent the mandatory time limit after failing to challenge the scheme when it was implemented. Finding: There was no continuing violation; the time limit commenced on 06/06/2012. Issue 3: Pursuit of administrative remedies Rule applied: Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act No. 21 of 1996 and the principle that pursuing administrative remedies does not interrupt the one-month time limit for filing a fundamental rights application. Court's reasoning: The court held that the pursuit of administrative remedies or complaints to the Human Rights Commission does not toll the time limit under Article 126(2). Furthermore, to benefit from the exception in Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission Act, the complaint to the Commission must itself be filed within one month of the infringement. The Petitioners failed to meet this requirement. Finding: The pursuit of other remedies did not extend the time limit. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing: the court established that the infringement was a discrete act (Issue 1), thereby negating the theory of a continuing violation (Issue 2). Because the infringement was a discrete act, the subsequent pursuit of administrative remedies (Issue 3) could not legally toll the time limit, as the initial window for filing had already expired. Conclusion The preliminary objection is upheld, and the application is dismissed as time-barred. No costs are ordered. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Scheme of Recruitment and Promotions — Continuing violation — Time bar — Human Rights Commission		SC/FR/429/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_429_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-44-2019	16 June 2022	Thyagarajah and Levers v. Keerthi Prasanna and Others	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, P.C., J; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Leave to appeal — Executors conveyance — Admission of a will to probate — Title to immovable property — Necessary party to an action — Cause of action — District Court proceedings	Facts The Plaintiffs, Dilipan Thyagarajah and Dhara Levers, filed an action in the District Court of Pugoda seeking a declaration of title to property belonging to the estate of the deceased Kumaraj Chitranjan Nadarajah, the ejectment of the Defendants, and the annulment of two deeds. The 1st Plaintiff is the executor of the deceased's estate, and the 2nd Plaintiff is the beneficiary of the property under the deceased's Last Will. The Defendants raised preliminary objections regarding the maintainability of the action. The District Judge subsequently struck out the name of the 2nd Plaintiff from the action, ruling that no cause of action had accrued to her in the absence of an executor's conveyance. This order was upheld by the High Court of Civil Appeal. The Plaintiffs appealed to the Supreme Court, contending that the 2nd Plaintiff is a necessary party for the effectual adjudication of the matter. Issues Whether an executor's conveyance is a legal prerequisite for a beneficiary to jointly institute an action regarding property devised under a Last Will. Whether the admission of a Last Will to probate vests title in the beneficiary such that they are a necessary party to an action for declaration of title and ejectment. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code, Section 5 Cases Referred to: Malliya v. Ariyaratne - [65-nlr-145] Silva v. Silva - [10-nlr-234] Horne v. Marikar - [27-nlr-185] Gopalsamy v. Ramasamy Pulle - [14-nlr-238] Analysis Issue 1: Necessity of an executor's conveyance Rule applied: The principle established in Malliya v. Ariyaratne [65-nlr-145] that an executor's assent or conveyance is not necessary to pass title to heirs appointed in a will. Court's reasoning: The Court examined the scope of the law regarding executors and administrators. It reaffirmed that title to immovable property specifically devised vests in the heir, not the executor. While an executor retains the power to sell property for the payment of debts, the absence of a formal conveyance does not prevent the vesting of title in the devisee. Finding: The lower courts erred in law by holding that an executor's conveyance was necessary for the 2nd Plaintiff to maintain the action. Issue 2: 2nd Plaintiff as a necessary party Rule applied: Section 5 of the Civil Procedure Code regarding the definition of a cause of action. Court's reasoning: The Court reasoned that because title vests in the beneficiary upon the probate of the will, the 2nd Plaintiff possesses a direct interest in the property. As the action seeks to annul deeds and evict occupants, the 2nd Plaintiff is a necessary party to fully enforce the rights claimed and to ensure the complete and effectual adjudication of the questions involved, thereby preventing a multiplicity of actions. Finding: The 2nd Plaintiff is a necessary party to the action. Interaction of Issues The findings are interdependent; because the Court determined that title vests in the beneficiary without the need for an executor's conveyance, it logically follows that the beneficiary holds a sufficient legal interest to be a necessary party in litigation concerning that property. The resolution of the first issue regarding title directly supports the conclusion that the 2nd Plaintiff has a valid cause of action. Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The orders of the High Court of Civil Appeal and the District Court striking out the 2nd Plaintiff are set aside, and the District Court is directed to accept the Amended Plaint and permit both Plaintiffs to prosecute the case. Keywords Leave to appeal — Executors conveyance — Admission of a will to probate — Title to immovable property — Necessary party to an action — Cause of action — District Court proceedings		SC/APPEAL/44/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_44_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-13-2019	16 June 2022	Dharmadasa v. Board of Investment of Sri Lanka	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Labour Tribunal — Appeal from Labour Tribunal — Just and equitable jurisdiction — Questions of law — Perverse findings of fact — Loss of confidence — Conflict of interest	Facts The Appellant, R.A. Dharmadasa, was employed by the Board of Investment of Sri Lanka, the Respondent, beginning in 1985. He eventually served as the Director (Corporate Services) of the North Western Regional Office. In 2005, the Appellant was interdicted following allegations of irregularities regarding rent allowance claims, the use of an official vehicle, and the management of a tender for transport services, which included the deposit of cheques issued to a service provider into the Appellant's personal bank account. A domestic inquiry was held ex parte after the Appellant withdrew from the proceedings, resulting in his termination in 2008. The Appellant challenged his termination before the Labour Tribunal. The Labour Tribunal held that the charges were not proved and ordered compensation. The Respondent appealed to the Provincial High Court, which set aside the Labour Tribunal's order. The Appellant then appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by setting aside the Labour Tribunal's order on the basis of a technical interpretation of documents without considering the surrounding circumstances. Whether the High Court's judgment is valid if it fails to provide reasons for its decision. Applicable Law Statutes: Industrial Disputes Act No. 43 of 1950 Cases Referred to: R. v. Manchester Legal Aid Committee Ex parte Brand & Co. Ltd. - [(1952) 1 All ER 480] Peiris v. Podi Singho - [78-clw-46] Ceylon Transport Board v. Ceylon Transport Workers Union - [71-nlr-158] The Caledonian (Ceylon) Tea and Rubber Estates Ltd. v. J.S. Hillman - [79/v1-nlr-421] Richard Pieris & Co. Ltd. v. Wijesiriwardena - [62-nlr-233] The Ceylon Estates Staffs Union v. The Superintendent, Meddecombra Estate, Watagoda - [73-nlr-278] Ceylon Transport Board v. Gunasinghe - [72-nlr-76] Municipal Council Colombo v. Munasinghe - [71-nlr-223] Standard Chartered Grindlays Bank Limited v. The Minister of Labour - [sc-appeal-22/2003] Singer Industries (Ceylon) Limited v. The Ceylon Mercantile Industrial and General Workers Union - [2010/v1-sri-lr-66] Inland Revenue v. Fraser - [(1942) 24 Tax Cases 498] Edwards v. Bairstow - [(1956) 3 All ER 57] Jayasuriya v. Sri Lanka State Plantations Corporation - [1995/v2-sri-lr-379] Somawathie v. Baksons Textile Industries Ltd - [79/v1-nlr-204] Thevarayan v. Balakrishnan - [1984/v1-sri-lr-189] Nadarajah v. Thilagaratnam - [86/v3-calr-303] Colombo Apothecaries Co. Ltd v. Ceylon Press Workers Union - [75-nlr-182] Ceylon Oil Workers Union v. Ceylon Petroleum Corporation - [1978/v2-sri-lr-72] Reckitt & Colman of Ceylon Ltd v. Peiris - [1978/v2-sri-lr-229] United Industrial Local Government & General Workers Union v. Independent Newspapers Ltd - [75-nlr-529] Hayleys Ltd v. De Silva - [64-nlr-130] Ceylon Transport Board v. Samastha Lanka Motor Sevaka Samithiya - [65-nlr-566] Virakesari Ltd v. Fernando - [66-nlr-145] Carolis Appuhamy v. Punchirala - [64-nlr-44] Ceylon Workers Congress v. Superintendent, Kallebokke Estate - [63-nlr-536] Ceylon Steel Corporation v. National Employees Union - [76-clw-64] Hatton National Bank v. Perera - [1996/v2-sri-lr-231] Shanthi Sagara Gunawardena v. Ranjith Kumudusena Gunawardena - [sc-appeal-89/2016] Kotagala Plantations Ltd. v. Ceylon Planters Society - [2010/v2-sri-lr-299] Peiris v. Celltel Lanka Limited - [sc-appeal-30/2009] Democratic Workers Congress v. De Mel and Wanigasekera - [CGG 12432] Analysis Issue 1: Just and equitable jurisdiction and perversity Rule applied: Section 31C(1) and Section 31D(3) of the Industrial Disputes Act. Court's reasoning: The Court held that while Labour Tribunals have wide discretion to make "just and equitable" orders, they must act judicially and base findings on evidence. The Labour Tribunal failed to consider the Appellant's admission regarding his breach of the residence condition and ignored the conflict of interest created by depositing employer-issued cheques into his personal account. The High Court correctly identified that these findings were perverse and unsupported by evidence. Finding: The High Court acted within its jurisdiction under Section 31D(3) of the Act in setting aside the Labour Tribunal's order. Issue 2: Requirement to provide reasons Rule applied: General principles of appellate review. Court's reasoning: The Court examined the High Court's judgment and found that it did, in fact, provide reasons for setting aside the Labour Tribunal's findings. The High Court's failure to address every single charge did not invalidate the judgment, as the findings on the primary charges of misconduct were sufficient to justify the termination. Finding: The High Court's judgment is valid as it provided sufficient reasons for its decision. Interaction of Issues The findings on the charges of misconduct (Issue 1) directly informed the conclusion that the employer had lost trust and confidence in the Appellant. Because the Labour Tribunal's findings were perverse regarding the evidence of misconduct, the High Court's intervention was necessary to uphold the legal standard for termination, rendering the procedural challenge regarding the High Court's reasoning (Issue 2) moot. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The judgment of the High Court is affirmed, and the termination of the Appellant's services is held to be justified. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Labour Tribunal — Appeal from Labour Tribunal — Just and equitable jurisdiction — Questions of law — Perverse findings of fact — Loss of confidence — Conflict of interest		SC/FR/13/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_13_2019.pdf
sc-fr-378-2017	20 June 2022	Talpahewa v. Kariyawasam and Others	Vijith K. Malalgoda, J	Vijith K. Malalgoda, J; Murdu N. B. Fernando, J; S. Thurairaja, J	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Legitimate expectation — Retrospective legislation — Administrative action — Public Service Commission — Service Minute — Promotion criteria — Active service — Transitional provisions	Facts The Petitioner, Dr. Chanaka Harsha Talpahewa, was an officer in Grade II of the Sri Lanka Foreign Service. Under the 2001 Service Minute, the Petitioner became eligible for promotion to Grade I upon completing six years of satisfactory service in Grade II, subject to the availability of a vacancy. In 2016, while holding the position of Director Middle East Africa Division, the Petitioner was offered an assignment with the United Nations Human Settlement Programme. He applied for no-pay leave to accept this position. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs recommended the leave, noting the Petitioner had completed sixteen years of total service and six years in Grade II. The Public Service Commission approved the leave from 15th August 2016 to 14th August 2017 but deferred the decision on whether this period would count as active service. While the Petitioner was on leave, a new Service Minute was published in the Gazette on 6th December 2016, with a retrospective effective date of 12th October 2015. This new minute increased the service requirement for promotion from Grade II to Grade I from six years to seven years and introduced additional criteria. Subsequently, the Public Service Commission informed the Petitioner that his period of leave would not be considered active service. The Petitioner challenged these actions, arguing that the retrospective application of the new Service Minute and the refusal to count his leave as active service violated his fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution, as he had a legitimate expectation of promotion based on the criteria in effect when he accepted the UN assignment. Issues Whether the retrospective application of the 2016 Service Minute and the failure to include transitional provisions violated the Petitionerâ€™s fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the Petitioner had a legitimate expectation that his promotion would be governed by the criteria in place at the time he accepted his external assignment. Whether the Public Service Commissionâ€™s refusal to treat the Petitioner's period of no-pay leave as active service constituted an infringement of Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 17, 126. Establishment Code. Cases Referred to: Nishantha v. Bandula Gunawardane - [2012/v1-blr-209] Coral Sands Hotel (Pvt) Ltd v. Minister of Finance - [sc-fr-170/2015] Rathnakumara v. The Postgraduate Institute of Medicine - [sc-appeal-16/2014] Ariyarathne v. Illangakoon - [sc-fr-444/2012] R. v. North and East Devon Health Authority ex parte Coughlan - [2000/v3-aer-850] Analysis Issue 1: Retrospective application of the Service Minute Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution regarding equal protection and the principle that subordinate legislation cannot have retrospective effect unless expressly authorized by the enabling Act. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that the 2016 Service Minute was backdated by over a year without a legal basis or transitional provisions to protect officers who had already met the previous requirements. This created an arbitrary barrier for the Petitioner. Finding: The conduct of the Public Service Commission in backdating the effective date and failing to provide transitional relief violated the Petitioner's right to equal protection under Article 12(1). Issue 2: Legitimate expectation Rule applied: The doctrine of legitimate expectation as established in R. v. North and East Devon Health Authority ex parte Coughlan. Court's reasoning: The Petitioner had fulfilled the six-year service requirement under the 2001 Service Minute before accepting the UN assignment. He reasonably expected that his promotion would proceed based on the existing policy. The Court found that the sudden change in criteria without adequate notice frustrated this substantive expectation. Finding: The Petitioner held a legitimate expectation that his promotion would be governed by the rules in place at the time he accepted the assignment, and the stateâ€™s departure from this was an abuse of power. Issue 3: Refusal to count leave as active service Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that the Public Service Commission had previously granted active service status to other officers in similar circumstances. The refusal to treat the Petitioner's leave as active service, despite the Ministry's strong recommendation, was inconsistent and discriminatory. Finding: The refusal to treat the leave as active service was arbitrary and violated the Petitioner's fundamental rights. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected; the retrospective application of the new Service Minute (Issue 1) directly undermined the Petitioner's legitimate expectation (Issue 2). By refusing to count the leave as active service (Issue 3), the Respondents effectively prevented the Petitioner from meeting the newly imposed, retrospectively applied seven-year requirement, thereby compounding the violation of his rights. Conclusion The Court held that the Petitionerâ€™s fundamental rights under Article 12(1) were violated. The Public Service Commission is directed to treat the Petitioner's period of leave as active service until he completes the seven-year requirement, and he is to be considered for promotion to Grade I upon fulfilling the other criteria of the 2016 Service Minute. The State is ordered to pay the Petitioner Rs. 250,000 as compensation and Rs. 100,000 as costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Legitimate expectation — Retrospective legislation — Administrative action — Public Service Commission — Service Minute — Promotion criteria — Active service — Transitional provisions		SC/FR/378/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_378_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-71-2017	23 June 2022	Dona Patriciahamy and Others v. Ashrof	E. A. G. R. Amarasekara, J. (Dissenting opinions by Murdu N. B. Fernando, PC, J. and B. P. Aluwihare, PC, J.), J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.	Last Will — Testamentary action — Fideicommissum — Life interest — Abolition of Fideicommissa Act — Executor — Beneficiary — Rest and residue of estate — Conversion of property to cash — Distribution of assets	Facts The Plaintiffs-Respondents-Respondents instituted an action in the District Court of Colombo seeking a declaration of entitlement to the proceeds of the sale of a property described as Lot 1 in Plan No. 349, situated at Mahawatte Road, Madampitiya. The property belonged to the late Benedict de Andrado, who died in 1963 leaving a Last Will. The Will appointed his wife, Violet de Andrado, as executrix and granted her a life interest in the rest and residue of his estate, which included the subject property. The Will directed that upon the death of the wife, the residue be converted to cash and distributed among fifteen named beneficiaries. Violet de Andrado died in 1991. The 1st Defendant-Respondent-Respondent, who had cared for Violet, obtained probate for Violetâ€™s estate in the District Court of Marawila, claiming the subject property as part of Violetâ€™s estate. The 1st Defendant subsequently transferred the property to herself via an executorâ€™s conveyance and later sold it to the 2nd Defendant-Appellant-Petitioner. The Plaintiffs alleged that Violet held only a life interest and could not dispose of the property, thus the 2nd Defendant acquired no valid title. The District Court ruled in favor of the Plaintiffs, and the Civil Appellate High Court affirmed the judgment, though it restricted the granted reliefs to declaratory ones. The 2nd Defendant appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Last Will of Benedict de Andrado created a fideicommissum in favor of Violet de Andrado regarding the subject property. Whether the Abolition of Fideicommissa Act No. 20 of 1972 rendered Violet de Andrado the absolute owner of the property. Whether the Plaintiffs-Respondents are entitled to raise the issue of the High Courtâ€™s refusal to grant consequential reliefs (ejectment and sale) despite not filing a separate leave to appeal application. Applicable Law Statutes: Abolition of Fideicommissa Act No. 20 of 1972 Civil Procedure Code (Chapter XXXVIII and LIV) Trust Ordinance (Sections 90 and 96) Cases Referred to: Meemanage Harold Fernando v. Jayani Wimalarathna nee Fonseka - [sc-appeal-56/2010] Kularatne v. Gunatilleke - [1994/v2-sri-lr-258] Bahar v. Burah - [55-nlr-1] Mary v. Kurera - [74-nlr-5] Welgama v. Wijesundera - [2006/v1-sri-lr-110] Sunil Gotabaya Lamabadusuriya v. Yasoma Champa Nilmini Abeygunawardena - [sc-appeal-169/2011] Silva v. Jayawardene - [28-nlr-115] Fonseka v. Babunona - [11-nlr-333] Gunawardene v. Visvanathan - [24-nlr-225] Dharmasiri v. Wickramatunga - [2002/v2-sri-lr-218] Nonohamy v. Punchihamy - [31-nlr-220] Aron Fernando v. Buddhadasa - [1986/v2-sri-lr-285] Ekanayake v. Appu - [3-nlr-350] Supramaniam Chetty v. Palanniappa Chetty - [3-bal-57] Soysa v. Abeydera - [12-nlr-349] Moysa Fernando v. Alice Fernando - [4-nlr-201] Silva v. Silva - [10-nlr-234] Malliya v. Ariyaratne - [65-nlr-145] Fernando v. Soysa - [2-nlr-40] Mohamed v. Mohamed - [30-nlr-225] Seneviratne v. Candappapulle - [16-nlr-150] Pabilina v. Karunarathne - [50-nlr-169] Bengamuwe Dhammadinna Thero v. Perera - [sc-appeal-15/2012] Fernando v. Perera - [17-nlr-161] Analysis Issue 1: Creation of Fideicommissum Rule applied: The court examined the testator's intention through the language of the Will, specifically the phrase "life interest on the rest and residue... in remainder, reversion or expectancy nothing expected." Court's reasoning: The majority (Amarasekara, J.) reasoned that the testator intended to grant full dominium to the wife subject to an implied restriction on alienation, which constitutes a fideicommissum. The dissenting judges (Fernando, J. and Aluwihare, J.) argued that the Will granted only a simple life interest, as the property was not specifically devised to the wife, and the dominium remained with the estate to be converted to cash by a successor executor. Finding: The Court split; the majority held a fideicommissum was created, while the minority held it was a simple life interest. Issue 2: Effect of Abolition of Fideicommissa Act Rule applied: Abolition of Fideicommissa Act No. 20 of 1972. Court's reasoning: The majority held that because the Will created a fideicommissum, the Act operated to vest absolute ownership in the fiduciary (Violet de Andrado) at the time the Act came into force. The minority held that since no fideicommissum existed, the Act had no application, and the property remained subject to the original testamentary directions. Finding: The majority concluded the Act vested absolute title in Violet de Andrado. Issue 3: Entitlement to Raise Issues Rule applied: Section 754 of the Civil Procedure Code regarding appeal periods. Court's reasoning: The majority held that the Plaintiffs-Respondents were barred from challenging the High Court's refusal of consequential reliefs because they failed to file a cross-appeal or a leave to appeal application within the statutory period. Finding: The Plaintiffs were not entitled to raise the issue. Interaction of Issues The findings on the nature of the Will (Issue 1) directly dictated the application of the Abolition of Fideicommissa Act (Issue 2). The majority's conclusion that a fideicommissum existed necessitated the application of the Act, which effectively nullified the Plaintiffs' claim to the property. Conclusion The Supreme Court, by a majority (Amarasekara, J. and Aluwihare, J. concurring in the result, with Fernando, J. dissenting), allowed the appeal of the 2nd Defendant-Appellant. The judgment of the High Court was set aside, and the Plaintiffs' action was dismissed. Keywords Last Will — Testamentary action — Fideicommissum — Life interest — Abolition of Fideicommissa Act — Executor — Beneficiary — Rest and residue of estate — Conversion of property to cash — Distribution of assets		SC/APPEAL/71/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_71_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-210-2016	7 July 2022	Ran Malu Fashions (Private) Limited v. Wallabha Jayathissa Liyanage Upali Wijayaweera and Expolanka Freight (Private) Limited	P. Padman Surasena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Winding up proceedings — Companies Act — Preferential claims — Statutory dues — Termination of Employment of Workmen (Special Provisions) Act — Liquidators' duties — Commissioner General of Labour — Interpretation of statutes	Facts Ran Malu Fashions (Private) Limited filed a petition in the Commercial High Court for a winding-up order under the Companies Act No. 7 of 2007. The court appointed liquidators to oversee the process. During the liquidation, the Commissioner General of Labour submitted a claim for compensation amounting to Rs. 428,119,086.50, which was payable to employees under the Termination of Employment of Workmen (Special Provisions) Act No. 45 of 1971. The liquidators initially sought to categorize this claim as an unsecured debt and proposed paying only a percentage of the total amount. The Commissioner General of Labour subsequently filed an application to have the claim admitted as a preferential claim under Section 365 of the Companies Act. Creditors, including Expolanka Freight (Private) Limited, filed objections against this classification. The Commercial High Court ruled that the claim was a statutory due and qualified as a preferential claim under paragraph 2(g) of the Ninth Schedule to the Companies Act. Aggrieved by this decision, the creditors and liquidators appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the claim for compensation made by the Commissioner General of Labour under the Termination of Employment of Workmen (Special Provisions) Act No. 45 of 1971 constitutes a "preferential claim" under Section 365 and the Ninth Schedule of the Companies Act No. 7 of 2007. Whether the phrase "other statutory dues payable to any employee" in item 2(g) of the Ninth Schedule should be interpreted using the ejusdem generis principle to limit its scope to dues arising under the Industrial Disputes Act. Applicable Law Statutes: Companies Act No. 7 of 2007 Termination of Employment of Workmen (Special Provisions) Act No. 45 of 1971 Companies Act No. 17 of 1982 Inland Revenue Act No. 10 of 2006 Value Added Tax Act No. 14 of 2002 Workmen's Compensation Ordinance Cases Referred to: Serendib Coconut Products Ltd. (In Voluntary Liquidation) v. Commissioner General of Labour - [2004/v2-sri-lr-137] Analysis Issue 1: Classification of TEWA claims as preferential Rule applied: Section 365 and item 2(g) of the Ninth Schedule to the Companies Act No. 7 of 2007. Court's reasoning: The court reasoned that the Commissioner General of Labour exercises statutory powers under the Termination of Employment of Workmen (Special Provisions) Act (TEWA) when ordering compensation. Since these dues emanate from a legislative enactment, they fall within the definition of "statutory dues." The court rejected the argument that the legislature intended to exclude TEWA claims by not listing them explicitly, noting that the category "other statutory dues" is broad enough to encompass them. The court emphasized that protecting the livelihood of workmen is a legislative priority, and there is no rational basis to distinguish TEWA compensation from other statutory dues. Finding: The claim for compensation under TEWA is a preferential claim under item 2(g) of the Ninth Schedule. Issue 2: Interpretation of "other statutory dues" Rule applied: The ejusdem generis principle and the rule of literal construction. Court's reasoning: The court held that the ejusdem generis principle is inapplicable because item 2(g) does not contain an enumeration of specific items that form a distinct genus. The phrase "industrial court awards and other statutory dues" is conjoined by "and," indicating two distinct categories. The court applied the maxim generalia verba sunt generalita intelligenda (words are to be understood generally), concluding that the legislature intended the phrase to have a broad, ordinary meaning rather than being restricted to the Industrial Disputes Act. Finding: The phrase "other statutory dues" is not limited to the Industrial Disputes Act and must be interpreted generally. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are mutually reinforcing. By determining that the term "statutory dues" is a general category rather than one restricted by ejusdem generis, the court established a legal framework that naturally includes TEWA-based compensation. This interpretation aligns with the legislative intent to prioritize employee welfare in liquidation proceedings, rendering the specific exclusion arguments of the appellants invalid. Conclusion The Supreme Court affirmed the order of the Commercial High Court in SC Appeal No. 210/2016 and SC Appeal No. 209/2016, and set aside the contrary order in SC Appeal No. 208/2016. It held that compensation payable under the Termination of Employment of Workmen (Special Provisions) Act No. 45 of 1971 is a preferential claim under the Companies Act No. 7 of 2007. Keywords Winding up proceedings — Companies Act — Preferential claims — Statutory dues — Termination of Employment of Workmen (Special Provisions) Act — Liquidators' duties — Commissioner General of Labour — Interpretation of statutes		SC/FR/210/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_210_2016.pdf
sc-fr-205-2022	18 July 2022	Kodituwakku v. Election Commission and Others	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Janak De Silva, J.	Fundamental rights — Article 99A of the Constitution — National List seats — Time limit — Mandatory vs. directory — Sovereignty of the People — Franchise — Continuing violation — Suppression of material facts — Article 126 of the Constitution	Facts The Petitioner, Nagananda Kodituwakku, filed this application seeking to challenge the election of the 9th and 10th Respondents as Members of Parliament from the National Lists of the United National Party and the Sri Lanka Podujana Peramuna. The Petitioner alleged that the 9th Respondentâ€™s appointment was void due to a failure to comply with the one-week time limit for nominations stipulated in Article 99A of the Constitution. Throughout the proceedings, the Petitioner demonstrated a lack of diligence in serving notices on the Respondents as ordered by the Court. Furthermore, the Petitioner misrepresented facts to the Court regarding his travel plans to the United Kingdom to obtain an early hearing date. It was subsequently revealed that the Petitioner was aware of the cancellation of his visa interview prior to his representations to the Court. Additionally, the Petitioner failed to disclose that a previous fundamental rights application challenging the same election, S.C. (F/R) Application No. 200/2021, had been dismissed by the Court. Issues Whether the application is time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Whether the Petitionerâ€™s failure to disclose the dismissal of a previous application warrants dismissal of the current petition. Whether the one-week time limit for nominations under Article 99A of the Constitution is mandatory or directory. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka (Articles 3, 4, 10, 12, 14(1), 69, 82(6), 99A, 125, 126) Cases Referred to: Ittepana v. Hemawathie - [1981/v1-sri-lr-476] Jayanetti v. Land Reform Commission and Others - [1984/v2-sri-lr-172] Gamaethige v. Siriwardena and Others - [1988/v1-sri-lr-384] Jayasinghe v. The National Institute of Fisheries and Nautical Engineering (NIFNE) and Others - [2002/v1-sri-lr-277] Visuvalingam and Others v. Liyanage and Others (No. 1) - [1983/v1-sri-lr-203] Twentieth Amendment to the Constitution Bill (2017) - [Decisions of the Supreme Court on Parliamentary Bills (2016-2017) Vol. XIII] Stassen Exports Limited v. Brooke Bond (Ceylon) Limited and Another - [1990/v2-sri-lr-63] Walgamage v. The Attorney-General - [2000/v3-sri-lr-1] Analysis Issue 1: Time-bar Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution, which mandates that fundamental rights applications must be filed within one month of the alleged infringement. Court's reasoning: The 9th Respondentâ€™s election was gazetted on 18th June 2021, but the application was filed on 16th June 2022. The Court rejected the Petitioner's argument of a "continuing violation" as it was not pleaded in the petition and was contradicted by the Petitioner's prior litigation history. Finding: The application is time-barred and liable to be dismissed in limine. Issue 2: Disclosure of material facts Rule applied: The principle of uberrima fides (utmost good faith) required in fundamental rights applications. Court's reasoning: The Petitioner failed to disclose that S.C. (F/R) Application No. 200/2021, which challenged the same election, had been dismissed. The Court held that attempting to camouflage this fact by appending a motion to the pleadings does not satisfy the duty of frankness. Finding: The application is dismissed due to the suppression of material facts and the misleading of the Court. Issue 3: Interpretation of Article 99A Rule applied: The principles of statutory interpretation regarding mandatory versus directory provisions as established in Visuvalingam v. Liyanage. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the one-week time limit in Article 99A is directory. Interpreting it as mandatory would disenfranchise voters and violate the Sovereignty of the People. Furthermore, Article 69 allows Parliament to function despite vacancies, indicating that the time limit is not a condition precedent for the validity of an appointment. Finding: The time limit is directory, and the appointment is not void. Interaction of Issues The findings of lack of good faith and the time-bar provide procedural grounds for dismissal, while the interpretation of Article 99A addresses the substantive merits. The Courtâ€™s finding that the Petitioner misled the Court reinforces the dismissal, as the Court will not grant relief to a party who lacks uberrima fides. Conclusion The application is dismissed. The Court found the petition to be time-barred, lacking in good faith due to the suppression of material facts, and substantively meritless regarding the interpretation of Article 99A. Keywords Fundamental rights — Article 99A of the Constitution — National List seats — Time limit — Mandatory vs. directory — Sovereignty of the People — Franchise — Continuing violation — Suppression of material facts — Article 126 of the Constitution		SC/FR/205/2022	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_205_2022.pdf
sc-appeal-146-2015	21 July 2022	Wimalatunga v. Seneviratne	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Declaration of title — Amicable partition — Licensed surveyor's report — Identification of land — Chain of title — Prescription — High Court judgment — District Court judgment	Facts The Plaintiff instituted an action in the District Court of Gampaha seeking a declaration of title, ejectment of the Defendant, and damages regarding three contiguous allotments of land. The Plaintiff claimed title through her predecessor, Mahinda Nanayakkara, whose estate was administered following his death in 1984, with the heirs subsequently transferring their interests to the Plaintiff. The Plaintiff alleged that the Defendant unlawfully entered the lands in 1991 and constructed a house thereon. The Defendant denied the Plaintiff's claims, asserting his own chain of title through deeds dating from 1961 to 1976 and claiming prescriptive title. The District Court initially entered judgment in favor of the Plaintiff. Upon appeal, the Provincial High Court of the Western Province (Civil Appeals) set aside the District Court judgment, citing the Plaintiff's failure to properly identify the corpus and issues regarding the alleged amicable partition of the land. The Plaintiff subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Plaintiff successfully identified the corpus of the land sought to be vindicated. Whether the alleged amicable partition of the land, as depicted in Plan No. 1286 and the associated deeds, was legally valid and binding. Whether the Plaintiff established a valid chain of title to the lands described in the schedules to the plaint. Applicable Law Statutes: High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 54 of 2006 Cases Referred to: Wanigaratne v. Juwanis Appuhamy - [65-nlr-167] Jamaldeen Abdul Latheef v. Abdul Majeed Mohamed Mansoor - [2010/v2-sri-lr-333] Analysis Issue 1: Identification of the corpus Rule applied: The principle that in a rei vindicatio action, the plaintiff bears the burden of proving that the property exists and is clearly identifiable, typically through a survey plan or other reliable method. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the licensed surveyor, R.M.J. Ranasinghe, admitted under cross-examination that he could not independently identify the lands described in the plaint but merely depicted what the Plaintiff showed him. Furthermore, there was a significant discrepancy between the extent of land in the 1997 survey plan (P6) and the inventory filed during the testamentary proceedings of the Plaintiff's predecessor. Finding: The Plaintiff failed to prove the identity of the land, which is a fundamental requirement for a rei vindicatio action. Issue 2: Validity of the amicable partition Rule applied: The requirement that an amicable partition must be supported by evidence of consent or representation from all co-owners legally entitled to the land. Court's reasoning: The surveyor who prepared the plan for the alleged amicable partition (P1) testified that he possessed no documentation proving the consent of the other co-owners. The court found that the partition was executed without the representation of all legally entitled co-owners, rendering it ineffective. Finding: The alleged amicable partition was not legally binding. Issue 3: Establishment of title Rule applied: The rule that a plaintiff in a rei vindicatio action must prove their title to the property on a balance of probabilities. Court's reasoning: The court determined that the Plaintiff failed to establish a clear chain of title. The reliance on the amicable partition to terminate co-ownership was rejected due to the lack of evidence of a valid partition. Consequently, the Plaintiff could not substantiate her claim to the specific allotments. Finding: The Plaintiff failed to establish her title to the subject matter. Interaction of Issues The failure to establish a valid amicable partition directly undermined the Plaintiff's claim of exclusive title to the specific lots. This, combined with the failure to accurately identify the corpus through a reliable survey, rendered the Plaintiff unable to satisfy the fundamental requirements of a rei vindicatio action, necessitating the dismissal of the claim. Conclusion The Supreme Court affirmed the judgment of the Provincial High Court of the Western Province and dismissed the appeal. The Plaintiff failed to establish the necessary elements of title and identification required for a rei vindicatio action. Keywords Declaration of title — Amicable partition — Licensed surveyor's report — Identification of land — Chain of title — Prescription — High Court judgment — District Court judgment		SC/APPEAL/146/2015	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_146_2015.pdf
sc-appeal-94-2020	21 July 2022	Silva v. Esquel Sri Lanka Ltd	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Kumuduni Wickremasinghe, J	Industrial Disputes Act — Termination of employment — Compensation — Exorbitant compensation — Reinstatement — Damages — Labour Tribunal — High Court — Domestic inquiry — Fuel theft — Warning letters — Past conduct of employee	Facts The Applicant-Respondent-Respondent, Walihingage Karunarathne Silva, was employed as a driver by the Respondent-Appellant-Petitioner, Esquel Sri Lanka Ltd (formerly Polytex Garments Ltd), starting on 7th December 1992. On 15th May 2012, the Appellant interdicted the Respondent following allegations of fuel theft and negative influence on other employees. A charge sheet was issued on 12th June 2012, and a domestic inquiry was subsequently conducted by an external officer. The Respondent was found guilty of three out of four charges, leading to the termination of his services on 29th August 2012. The Respondent filed an application in the Labour Tribunal of Negombo seeking reinstatement or damages. The President of the Labour Tribunal ruled in favor of the Respondent, awarding damages without reinstatement, calculated at three months' salary for each of the 19 years of service, totaling Rs. 968,145.00. The Appellant appealed this order to the Provincial High Court of Negombo, which dismissed the appeal and affirmed the Labour Tribunal's decision. The Appellant then sought leave to appeal to the Supreme Court, which was granted to determine whether the compensation awarded was exorbitant. Issues Whether the Labour Tribunal and the High Court erred in law by awarding exorbitant compensation to the Respondent. Whether the Labour Tribunal failed to provide a reasoned basis for the computation of compensation as required for a "just and equitable" order under the Industrial Disputes Act. Applicable Law Statutes: Industrial Disputes Act No. 43 of 1950 (as amended) Termination of Employment of Workmen (Special Provisions) Act No. 45 of 1971 (as amended) Workmen's Compensation Ordinance No. 19 of 1934 (as amended) Payment of Gratuity Act No. 12 of 1983 Cases Referred to: Ward v. James - [1965-1-aer-564] Caledonian Estates Ltd. v. Hillman - [79-i-nlr-421] Ceylon Transport Board v. Wijeratne - [77-nlr-481] Jayasuriya v. Sri Lanka State Plantations Corporation - [1995/v2-sri-lr-379] United Industrial Local Government & General Workers' Union v. Independent Newspapers Ltd. - [75-nlr-529] Inter Company Employees Union v. Asian Hotels Corporation Ltd - [sc-appeal-101/10] Brook Bond (Ceylon) Ltd v. Tea, Rubber, Coconut and General Produce workers Union - [not specified] Analysis Issue 1: Exorbitant Compensation Rule applied: Section 33(1)(d) and Section 33(6) of the Industrial Disputes Act, which grant Tribunals the power to award compensation in lieu of reinstatement. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that while Tribunals have discretion, compensation must be "just and equitable." The Court reviewed the Respondent's employment history, which included multiple warning letters for misconduct, including driving under the influence and negligence. Furthermore, the Respondent had secured alternative employment with a higher income than his previous salary. The Court reasoned that the Respondentâ€™s poor service record and the fact that he had successfully mitigated his financial loss rendered the original award of three months' salary per year of service excessive. Finding: The compensation awarded was found to be exorbitant and was reduced to one month's salary per year of service. Issue 2: Requirement for Reasoned Computation Rule applied: The principle that a "just and equitable" order must be supported by a stated basis for computation, as established in Jayasuriya v. Sri Lanka State Plantations Corporation and Inter Company Employees Union v. Asian Hotels Corporation Ltd. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that the Labour Tribunal failed to articulate the specific factors or the methodology used to arrive at the compensation amount. The High Court also failed to rectify this omission. The Court emphasized that without a clear, reasoned basis, an award cannot be considered "just and equitable" as it prevents parties from understanding how the figure was derived. Finding: The lower courts erred by failing to provide a reasoned basis for the quantum of compensation. Interaction of Issues The failure of the Labour Tribunal to provide a reasoned basis for its award (Issue 2) directly contributed to the determination that the compensation was exorbitant (Issue 1). Because the Tribunal did not account for relevant factors—such as the Respondent's poor disciplinary record and his successful mitigation of loss—the resulting calculation lacked the necessary justification to be deemed "just and equitable." Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The order of the Labour Tribunal and the judgment of the High Court are amended to award compensation at the rate of one month's salary for each year of service, totaling Rs. 322,715.00. No order is made as to costs. Keywords Industrial Disputes Act — Termination of employment — Compensation — Exorbitant compensation — Reinstatement — Damages — Labour Tribunal — High Court — Domestic inquiry — Fuel theft — Warning letters — Past conduct of employee		SC/APPEAL/94/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_94_2020.pdf
sc-appeal-164-2012	24 July 2022	Athamlevvai v. Mahmoothu and Seyadu Paththumma	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Priyantha Jayawardena, PC, J; Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Rei vindicatio action — Title to land — Proof of title deed — Evidence Ordinance — Section 68 — Attesting witness — Prescriptive title — Burden of proof	Facts The Plaintiff-Appellant-Petitioner instituted a rei vindicatio action seeking a declaration of title to a land, ultimately relying on a deed marked as P1. The deed was produced in evidence subject to proof. The Respondent, who was in possession of the land, claimed to have acquired prescriptive title but did not seek a positive judgment beyond the dismissal of the action. The District Court dismissed the plaint on the basis that the Appellant failed to prove the title deed. The Appellant appealed to the Civil Appellate High Court, which affirmed the judgment of the District Court. The Appellant subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court, which granted leave to appeal on questions of law regarding the proof of documents and the application of the Evidence Ordinance. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that deeds P1 and P2 were not proved, despite the Appellant's argument that the failure of the Respondent to object to the documents at the close of the case rendered them admissible as evidence. Whether the High Court erred in law by strictly applying Sections 68 and 69 of the Evidence Ordinance to require the testimony of an attesting witness for the proof of deed P1, notwithstanding the admission of other documents like P3. Applicable Law Statutes: Evidence Ordinance, Section 68 Evidence Ordinance, Section 69 Notaries Ordinance, Section 31(9) Prevention of Frauds Ordinance, Section 2 Cases Referred to: Balapitiya Gunananda Thero v. Talalle Meththananda Thero - [1997/v2-sri-lr-101] Sri Lanka Ports Authority And Another v Jugolinija- Boal East - [1981/v1-sri-lr-18] Jamaldeen Abdul Latheef v. Abdul Majeed Mohamed Mansoor And Another - [2010/v2-sri-lr-333] Dharmadasa v. Jayasena - [12] Wanigaratne v. Juwanis Appuhamy - [13] Allis Appu v. Endis Hamy - [supra] Jinawathie v. Emalin Perera - [14] Wijegoonatilleke v. Wijegoonatilleke - [60-nlr-560] Jayasinghe v. Samarawickrema - [1982/v1-sri-lr-349] Dadallage Anil Shantha Samarasinghe v. Dadallage Mervin Silva - [sc-appeal-45/2010] Amarasinghe Arachchige Don Dharmarathna v. Dodamgodage Premadasa And Others - [sc-appeal-158/2013] Bandaiya v. Ungu - [15-nlr-263] Solicitor General v. Ava Umma - [71-nlr-512] R. v. Harringworth Analysis Issue 1: Admissibility of unobjected documents Rule applied: Section 68 of the Evidence Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The Court examined the principle that failure to object to a document at the close of a case renders it evidence. However, the Court relied on the precedent in Dadallage Anil Shantha Samarasinghe v. Dadallage Mervin Silva, which clarified that procedural omissions by parties do not override the mandatory requirements of the Evidence Ordinance. The Court held that if a document requires attestation, the failure to object does not dispense with the statutory requirement to prove its execution via an attesting witness. Finding: The High Court did not err; the failure to object does not cure the failure to prove a document that requires attestation under Section 68. Issue 2: Mandatory proof of notarially attested deeds Rule applied: Section 68 of the Evidence Ordinance and Section 31(9) of the Notaries Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The Court held that for a notarially attested deed, the testimony of at least one attesting witness is mandatory if the execution is not admitted. The Appellant failed to call any attesting witness or the Notary to prove the execution of P1. The Court rejected the argument that the admission of P3 (attested by the same Notary) satisfied the requirement for P1, as each document must be proved independently in accordance with the law. Finding: The High Court correctly applied the law; the Appellant failed to establish title because the deed P1 was not proved as required by Section 68. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are mutually reinforcing. The resolution of the first issue established that procedural waiver cannot bypass statutory requirements, while the second issue confirmed that the specific statutory requirement (Section 68) was not met. Together, they confirm that the Appellant failed to discharge the burden of proof inherent in a rei vindicatio action. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The Appellant failed to prove the title deed P1 in accordance with Section 68 of the Evidence Ordinance, which is fatal to a rei vindicatio action. Costs are fixed at Rupees 25,000.00. Keywords Rei vindicatio action — Title to land — Proof of title deed — Evidence Ordinance — Section 68 — Attesting witness — Prescriptive title — Burden of proof		SC/APPEAL/164/2012	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_164_2012.pdf
sc-appeal-177-2016	27 July 2022	Wijewickrama v. Chandrawathi	Janak De Silva, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; Janak De Silva, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Pension seizure — Civil Procedure Code — Section 218(g) — Stipend definition — Historical context — Public officer benefits — Commuted gratuity — Unjust enrichment	Facts The Respondent filed an action in the District Court of Colombo under Section 703 of the Civil Procedure Code to recover a sum of Rupees 1,050,000/- from the Appellant, who was a public officer. Judgment was entered in favor of the Respondent, and the Appellantâ€™s salary was initially seized to satisfy the decree. Following the Appellantâ€™s retirement, the Respondent sought to seize the Appellantâ€™s pension and commuted gratuity. The Appellant filed an application in the District Court to prevent the seizure, asserting that her pension was exempt under Section 218(g) of the Civil Procedure Code. The District Court allowed the application, holding that the term stipend in Section 218(g) encompassed the entire pension. The Respondent appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal, which set aside the District Court order, ruling that the pension was not exempt from seizure. The Appellant subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in law in allowing the seizure of the Appellantâ€™s pension and commuted gratuity under Section 218(g) of the Civil Procedure Code. Whether the exemption of the pension from seizure would result in the unjust enrichment of the Appellant at the expense of the Respondent. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code (Ordinance No. 2 of 1889), Section 218(g), Section 218(h), Section 703 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 43 of 1949 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 24 of 1949 Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 23(1) Cases Referred to: Queen v. Most - [1881/v7-qbd-244] The Attorney-General v. Herath Mudiyanselage Hamyge Herath Banda - [1983/bar-association-law-journal-reports-vol-i-part-iii-108] R v. Peters - [1886/v16-qbd-636] Ibrahim Saibo et al. v. Philips - [39-nlr-551] Ambalavanar v. Kandappar - [31-nlr-85] Goul v. Concecion - [36-nlr-73] Hardwick Game Farm v. Suffolk Agricultural and Poultry Producers Association Ltd. - [1966/v1-wlr-287] R v. Bouch - [1982/v3-wlr-673] Analysis Issue 1: Seizure of Pension and Gratuity Rule applied: Section 218(g) of the Civil Procedure Code, which exempts "the stipend, the cost-of-living allowance and the special living allowance of a naval, military, air force, civil or political pensioner of the Government" from seizure. Court's reasoning: The Court examined the historical evolution of Section 218(g) and dictionary definitions from the time of the Code's enactment. It determined that "stipend" is synonymous with "pension." The legislative intent behind the exemption was to ensure that public servants, who receive lower compensation than the private sector, are not left without financial means in old age. The Court rejected the High Court's application of the Noscitur a sociis maxim, finding that the legislature intended to protect the pension itself. However, the Court distinguished the "commuted gratuity" from the periodic pension, noting that the former is a lump sum and remains liable to seizure. Finding: The pension is exempt from seizure under Section 218(g), but the commuted gratuity is not. Issue 2: Unjust Enrichment Rule applied: General principles of law regarding the execution of decrees and statutory exemptions. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the question of unjust enrichment does not arise when the legislature has explicitly provided for an exemption from seizure. The protection of the pension is a matter of public policy to prevent pensioners from being left destitute. Finding: The Appellant is not unjustly enriched by the application of a statutory exemption. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing. By determining that the pension is statutorily exempt, the Court establishes that the seizure of the pension is legally impermissible, thereby negating any claim of unjust enrichment. The distinction between the periodic pension and the lump-sum gratuity allows for a balanced approach that respects both the statutory protection of the pensioner and the rights of the decree-holder. Conclusion The appeal is partly allowed. The order of the High Court of Civil Appeal is set aside, and the order of the District Court is affirmed to the extent that the pension is exempt from seizure, while the commuted gratuity remains liable for seizure. Keywords Pension seizure — Civil Procedure Code — Section 218(g) — Stipend definition — Historical context — Public officer benefits — Commuted gratuity — Unjust enrichment		SC/APPEAL/177/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_177_2016.pdf
sc-fr-104/2017	27 July 2022	Rodrigo Suppliers v. Vithanage and Others	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Kumudini Wickremasinghe, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Procurement process — Unrealistic pricing — Lowest substantially responsive bid — Tender award — Cost realism evaluation — Government Procurement Guidelines — Judicial review	Facts The Petitioners, trading as Rodrigo Suppliers, are engaged in the wholesale supply of dry fish, seafood, and meat. They have historically supplied these items to the Sri Lanka Navy. In May 2016, the Standing Cabinet Appointed Procurement Committee (SCAPC) invited applications for the supply of food to Naval camps for the year 2017. The Petitioners submitted bids for thirteen camps. Following the opening of bids, the Petitioners were informed by letter dated 23rd December 2016 that their bid was accepted for five camps. The letter did not address the status of the remaining eight camps. The Petitioners subsequently learned at a meeting on 16th February 2017 that the tender for the remaining eight camps had been awarded to the 16th Respondent. The Petitioners filed this application on 9th March 2017, alleging that as the lowest bidder for all thirteen camps, the decision to award the eight camps to the 16th Respondent was arbitrary and unreasonable, violating their fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. The Respondents raised preliminary objections, arguing that the application was time-barred and that the tender process had already been completed. Issues Whether the application is time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Whether the decision of the SCAPC to reject the Petitioners' bid for eight camps and award them to the 16th Respondent violated the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 14(1)(g), 126(1), 126(2). Government Procurement Guidelines (2006), Sections 2.7.2, 7.9.11. Cases Referred to: Kumarasiri v. Bandara - [sc-appeal-277/2009] Demuni Sriyani De Soyza v. Dharmasena Dissanayake - [sc-appeal-206/2008] Edirisuriya v. Navaratnam - [1985/v1-sri-lr-100] Analysis Issue 1: Time-bar Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution, which requires fundamental rights applications to be filed within one month of the alleged infringement. Court's reasoning: The Court examined whether the one-month period commenced on 23rd December 2016 (the date of the notification regarding the five camps) or 16th February 2017 (the date the Petitioners were informed of the 16th Respondent's selection). While the Respondents argued the Petitioners should have known earlier, the Court noted that Clauses 41.3 and 43.1 of the Instructions to Bidders (ITB) mandated that the purchaser notify unsuccessful bidders of the winning bidder. Since the Respondents failed to provide this mandatory notification, the Court accepted that the Petitioners only became aware of the full extent of the alleged infringement on 16th February 2017. Finding: The application was filed within the time limit stipulated by Article 126(2). Issue 2: Violation of Fundamental Rights Rule applied: Clauses 14.7, 14.8, 35.3(d)(a), and 35.3(d)(b) of the ITB, which allow for the rejection of bids containing "unrealistically low" prices (defined as below 70% of the "best price"). Court's reasoning: The evidence showed the Petitioners' bids for the three dry fish items were significantly below the 70% threshold of the "best price" determined by the Technical Evaluation Committee (TEC). Although the TEC had the discretion to reject these bids, it instead performed an unauthorized adjustment of the prices. This irregularity actually benefited the Petitioners, allowing them to secure five camps. The Court found that the Petitioners, having benefited from an irregular process, had no standing to complain about the rejection of their bids for the remaining eight camps. Furthermore, the Petitioners failed to challenge the validity of the ITB clauses or the "best price" methodology in their pleadings, precluding them from raising these arguments at the hearing. Finding: The Petitioners' fundamental rights were not infringed. Interaction of Issues The resolution of the time-bar issue allowed the Court to proceed to the merits. However, the finding that the Petitioners were beneficiaries of an irregular procurement process (the price adjustment) undermined their claim of arbitrary treatment, as they were not entitled to the tender for the eight camps under the strict application of the ITB's "unrealistic price" provisions. Conclusion The application is dismissed. The Petitioners are ordered to pay costs fixed at Rs. 200,000 to the 15th Respondent. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Procurement process — Unrealistic pricing — Lowest substantially responsive bid — Tender award — Cost realism evaluation — Government Procurement Guidelines — Judicial review		SC/APPEAL/104/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_104_2017.pdf
sc-fr-06-2011	8 August 2022	Azeez v. Gunasekera and Others	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC., J	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC., J; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Fundamental rights — Article 12(1) of the Constitution — Administrative action — Cancellation of appointment — Sri Lanka Education Administrative Service (SLEAS) — Recovery of excess payments — Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act — Time bar — National Ethnic Ratio — Public Service Commission	Facts The Petitioner was appointed to Class III of the Sri Lanka Education Administrative Service (SLEAS) effective 4th January 1999 following a Limited Competitive Examination. She assumed duties as an Assistant Director of Education in Galewala and later covered duties in the Pallepola Division. In August 2009, the Petitioner was informed that her appointment had been cancelled pursuant to a letter dated 13th March 2000. Consequently, she was reverted to the Teachers Service and placed in a new salary scale. The Auditor-General subsequently directed the recovery of salary payments made to the Petitioner during the period she served as a SLEAS officer. The Petitioner challenged these actions as infringements of her fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the application is time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Whether the cancellation of the Petitioner's appointment to the SLEAS and her reversion to the Teachers Service violated Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the recovery of salary payments made to the Petitioner during her tenure as a SLEAS officer is justified. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1), 12(2), 17, 126(2), 126(4) Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act No. 21 of 1996, Section 13(1), 14 Cases Referred to: SC/FR No. 129/1999 - [sc/fr-129/1999] SC/FR No. 130/1999 - [sc/fr-130/1999] SC/FR No. 131/1999 - [sc/fr-131/1999] SC/FR No. 451/2003 - [sc/fr-451/2003] Jayanetti v. The Land Reform Commission - [1984/v2-sri-lr-172] Analysis Issue 1: Time-bar Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution and Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act No. 21 of 1996. Court's reasoning: While Article 126(2) requires applications to be filed within one month of the alleged infringement, Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission Act provides that the period during which an inquiry is pending before the Human Rights Commission shall not be counted toward this limitation. The Petitioner filed a complaint with the Commission on 10th October 2009, and evidence of subsequent summons for inquiries confirms the matter remained pending. Finding: The application is not time-barred. Issue 2: Cancellation of Appointment Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: The Respondents acted in compliance with a Supreme Court order dated 29th October 1999 in SC/FR Nos. 129/1999, 130/1999, and 131/1999, which quashed SLEAS appointments that failed to adhere to the National Ethnic Ratio. The Petitionerâ€™s name was included in the list of candidates whose appointments were quashed by that order. Therefore, the administrative action to revoke her appointment and revert her to the Teachers Service was a lawful implementation of a judicial directive. Finding: The cancellation of the appointment did not violate Article 12(1). Issue 3: Recovery of Salary Rule applied: Article 126(4) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: Although the appointment was legally void, the Petitioner performed duties as a SLEAS officer for several years with the full knowledge and acquiescence of the authorities, who continued to pay her salary, grant increments, and assign her further responsibilities. The Court held that it would be unjust and inequitable to recover these payments from the Petitioner, as she performed the work in good faith and the delay in implementing the court order was attributable to the authorities. Finding: The recovery of salary payments is unjustified. Interaction of Issues The findings are consistent: while the Court upheld the legality of the cancellation of the appointment (Issue 2) based on the prior judicial order, it exercised its equitable jurisdiction under Article 126(4) to mitigate the financial hardship caused by the authorities' own delay in implementing that order (Issue 3). Conclusion The application is dismissed regarding the challenge to the cancellation of the appointment. However, the 2nd and 3rd Respondents are directed to refund any amounts recovered from the Petitioner as overpayments. No costs are ordered. Keywords Fundamental rights — Article 12(1) of the Constitution — Administrative action — Cancellation of appointment — Sri Lanka Education Administrative Service (SLEAS) — Recovery of excess payments — Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act — Time bar — National Ethnic Ratio — Public Service Commission		SC/FR/6/2011	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_6_2011.pdf
sc-appeal-239-2016	9 August 2022	Karunaratne and Others v. Dhanapala and Others	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J; Buwaneka Aluwihare, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Partition action — Corpus of land — Identification of corpus — Pedigree — Adverse possession — Ouster — District Court judgment — High Court judgment — Trial court decision — Deeds — Preliminary survey plan	Facts The Plaintiff-Appellant-Appellant instituted a partition action in the District Court of Horana regarding a land described as a portion of Millagahawatta, approximately one acre in extent. The plaint described this land as a distinct portion of a larger eight-acre land, which was allegedly possessed in divided portions. The Plaintiff-Appellant-Appellant claimed that he and several defendants were in possession of this specific portion. The 19th Defendant-Respondent-Respondent was added as a party upon the application of the Plaintiff-Appellant-Appellant. The 19th respondent disputed the existence of the corpus as a distinct, divided portion of the larger land and challenged the pedigree of the Plaintiff-Appellant-Appellant. The 19th respondent asserted rights based on a deed executed in 1999, which conveyed contingent interests from the 8th and 9th defendants. The 10th Defendant-Respondent-Respondent also disputed the Plaintiff-Appellant-Appellantâ€™s claim and supported the position of the 19th respondent. The trial proceeded with the Plaintiff-Appellant-Appellant, the 10th respondent, and the 19th respondent as the active parties. The District Court dismissed the action and declared that the 7th, 10th, and 19th respondents were entitled to shares. The Plaintiff-Appellant-Appellant appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal, which set aside the District Court judgment and dismissed the plaint on the grounds that the corpus was not properly identified because the entire eight-acre land was not depicted in the preliminary survey plan. The Plaintiff-Appellant-Appellant then appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that the corpus was not properly identified despite the parties admitting the corpus as depicted in the preliminary survey plan. Whether the trial court failed to discharge its duty under Section 25 of the Partition Law No. 21 of 1977 by failing to conduct a thorough inquiry into the title of all parties before allocating shares. Applicable Law Statutes: Partition Law No. 21 of 1977 Cases Referred to: Girigoris Perera v. Rosalin Perera - [53-nlr-536] Marshal Perera v. Dona Aginis - [1988/v1-sri-lr-248] Golagoda v. Mohideen - [40-nlr-92] Goonaratne v. The Bishop of Colombo - [53-nlr-337] Peris v. Perera - [1-nlr-362] Mather v. Thamotheram Pillai - [6-nlr-246] Cooray v. Wijesuriya - [62-nlr-158] Githohamy v. Karanagoda - [56-nlr-250] Corea v. Iseris Appuhamy - [15-nlr-65] Tillekeratne v. Bastian - [21-nlr-12] Kobbekadduwa v. Seneviratne - [53-nlr-354] Simon Perera v. Jayatunga - [71-nlr-338] Brito v. Mutunayagam - [20-nlr-327] Hameedu Lebbe v. Ganitha - [27-nlr-33] Rajapakse v. Hendrick Singho - [61-nlr-32] Cully v. Deod Taylerson - [11-ad-&-e-1088] Varada Pillai v. Jeevarathnammal - [1919-air-pc-44] Angela Fernando v. Deva Deepthi Fernando - [2006/v2-sri-lr-188] Mailvaganam v. Kandiah - [1-cwr-175] Obeysekem v. Endoris - [66-nlr-457] Nonis v. Peththa - [73-nlr-3] Abdul Majeed v. Ummu Zaneera - [61-nlr-361] Analysis Issue 1: Identification of the Corpus Rule applied: The court considered the evidentiary requirements for identifying a corpus in a partition action and the effect of judicial admissions. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court noted that all contesting parties had admitted the corpus as depicted in the preliminary survey plan. The trial judge had not dismissed the action on the basis of misidentification, but rather on pedigree. The High Courtâ€™s conclusion that the action failed because the entire eight-acre land was not surveyed was erroneous, as there was no claim of joint possession of the larger land. Finding: The High Court erred in holding that the corpus was not identified; the issue of identification was settled by the parties' admissions. Issue 2: Duty of the Trial Court Rule applied: Section 25 of the Partition Law No. 21 of 1977. Court's reasoning: The court emphasized that a trial judge has an inalienable duty to investigate the title of all parties before entering a decree. The trial judge failed to examine the evidence regarding the alleged ouster or the creation of the distinct portion of land. Furthermore, the trial judge reached contradictory conclusions regarding whether the corpus was a separate piece of land or part of the larger eight-acre land. Finding: The trial court failed to discharge its statutory duty under Section 25 of the Partition Law, necessitating a re-trial. Interaction of Issues The findings are interrelated because the failure of the trial court to properly investigate the title (Issue 2) led to an inconsistent judgment that did not resolve the core dispute regarding the pedigree and the nature of the corpus. The erroneous dismissal by the High Court (Issue 1) prevented a proper appellate review of the trial court's failure to conduct the mandatory inquiry. Conclusion The judgments of the High Court and the District Court are set aside. A re-trial is ordered in the District Court of Horana to ensure a full inquiry into the title of all parties in compliance with Section 25 of the Partition Law. Keywords Partition action — Corpus of land — Identification of corpus — Pedigree — Adverse possession — Ouster — District Court judgment — High Court judgment — Trial court decision — Deeds — Preliminary survey plan		SC/APPEAL/239/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_239_2016.pdf
sc-fr-6-2011	09 August 2022	F. A. Azeez v. H. M. Gunasekera and Others	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC., J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC., J; Achala Wengappuli, J; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J	fundamental rights — administrative action — cancellation of appointment — Sri Lanka Education Administrative Service — time bar — Human Rights Commission — overpayment recovery — discrimination — legal jurisdiction — ethnic ratio	Facts The Petitioner, F. A. Azeez, filed an application under Article 126 of the Constitution alleging infringement of her fundamental rights due to the revocation of her appointment to Class III of the Sri Lanka Education Administrative Service (SLEAS). The Petitioner had successfully sat for the Limited Competitive Examination in 1995 and was appointed to the SLEAS effective from 4th January 1999. She began her duties as an Assistant Director of Education and later took on additional responsibilities. However, in August 2009, she learned that her appointment had been cancelled via a letter from the Zonal Director of Education, which referenced a prior letter from the Education Service Committee that purportedly cancelled her appointment in March 2000. The Petitioner claimed she was never informed of this cancellation and had continued to perform her duties and receive her salary as a Class III officer until she was formally notified of her reversion to the Teachers’ Service in September 2009. Following this, she filed a complaint with the Human Rights Commission, which acknowledged her complaint but had not provided a resolution. The Petitioner argued that the cancellation of her appointment and the subsequent recovery of alleged overpayments constituted a violation of her rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Issues The primary issues before the court were: Whether the application was time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution? Whether the cancellation of the Petitioner’s appointment to the SLEAS was lawful and justified? Whether the recovery of the alleged overpayment was justified? Applicable Law Statutes: Article 12(1) of the Constitution, Human Rights Commission Act No. 21 of 1996. Cases Referred to: Jayanetti v. The Land Reform Commission (1984) 2 S.L.R. 172; SC/FR No. 129/1999, 130/1999, 131/1999; SC/FR No. 451/2003. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the application was time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution? Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution and Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission Act No. 21 of 1996. Court's reasoning: The court examined the timeline of events leading to the filing of the application. The Respondents argued that the application was time-barred since the letters indicating the cancellation of the Petitioner’s appointment were issued in September 2009, while the application was filed in 2011. However, the Petitioner contended that she had filed a complaint with the Human Rights Commission within one month of the alleged infringement, which should toll the time limit for filing in the Supreme Court. The court noted that Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission Act provides that the period during which an inquiry is pending before the Commission is not counted towards the one-month limit for filing a petition in the Supreme Court. The court found that the Petitioner had indeed filed her complaint within the stipulated time frame, and thus, the application was not time-barred. Finding: The court concluded that the application was timely filed and not subject to the time bar. Issue 2: Whether the cancellation of the Petitioner’s appointment to the SLEAS was lawful and justified? Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution regarding equality before the law and non-discrimination. Court's reasoning: The Petitioner argued that the cancellation of her appointment was illegal and discriminatory, as she was not a party to the previous cases that led to the cancellation of appointments based on the ethnic ratio. The Respondents maintained that the cancellation was in compliance with a court order that quashed appointments made contrary to the Gazette notification regarding the ethnic ratio. The court noted that the Petitioner’s name was included in the list of those whose appointments were quashed, indicating that she was affected by the court's decision. The court emphasized that the Respondents acted within their authority to revoke the Petitioner’s appointment based on the legal precedent set by the earlier cases. The court found that the actions taken by the Respondents were not arbitrary and did not violate the Petitioner’s rights under Article 12(1). Finding: The court upheld the cancellation of the Petitioner’s appointment as lawful and justified. Issue 3: Whether the recovery of the alleged overpayment was justified? Rule applied: Principles of administrative fairness and the right to due process. Court's reasoning: The Petitioner contested the recovery of the overpayment, arguing that she had not been informed of the cancellation of her appointment until September 2009 and had performed her duties as a Class III officer until that point. The court acknowledged that the Petitioner had been treated as a Class III officer and had received salary increments and promotions during her tenure. The court found that the demand for recovery of the overpayment lacked justification, as the Petitioner had acted in good faith and had not been informed of any wrongdoing until much later. The court noted that the authorities had failed to act promptly to rectify the situation despite being aware of the legal discrepancies. Finding: The court directed the Respondents to refund the amount recovered from the Petitioner, deeming the recovery unjustified. Interaction of Issues The issues were interrelated, as the determination of the timeliness of the application impacted the court's ability to address the substantive issues regarding the legality of the cancellation and the recovery of overpayments. The court's findings on the time bar allowed it to consider the merits of the case, ultimately leading to a conclusion that favored the Petitioner regarding the recovery of overpayments. Conclusion The court dismissed the application regarding the cancellation of the Petitioner’s appointment but ordered the Respondents to refund the amount recovered from her as overpayment. The court found that while the cancellation was lawful, the recovery of funds was unjustified given the circumstances. The court ordered no costs in the matter. Keywords fundamental rights — administrative action — cancellation of appointment — Sri Lanka Education Administrative Service — time bar — Human Rights Commission — overpayment recovery — discrimination — legal jurisdiction — ethnic ratio	Thilini Vidanagamage instructed by Faris and Associates for the Petitioner. Yuresha De Silva, SSC for the Hon. Attorney General	SC/FR/6/2011	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_6_2011.pdf
sc-appeal-117-2017	6 September 2022	Wijesinghe and Others v. Kumara and Others	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, CJ	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, CJ; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.	Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser — Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Partition of land — Co-ownership — Rights of co-owners — Improvements on land — Building on land of another — Unjust enrichment — Transfer of property — Deeds of transfer — Revocation of deeds	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent-Respondent instituted a partition action in the District Court of Kegalle regarding a land called Galpeelle Weralugahamulla Hena. The parties claimed competing interests in the land and specific structures thereon, namely two boutique premises and a copra hut. The 2nd Defendant-Appellant-Appellant claimed title to these structures based on a series of deeds and the devolution of rights from his parents, Ukkuwa and Silindu. The Plaintiff-Respondent-Respondent contended that Ukkuwa had sole rights to the boutique premises and the copra hut, having improved the original thatched house and constructed the hut, and subsequently transferred these interests to him and another party. The District Court held that the Plaintiff-Respondent-Respondent was entitled to a share of the boutique premises and the copra hut, finding that Ukkuwa had sole rights to these improvements. The Civil Appellate High Court dismissed the appeal filed by the 2nd Defendant-Appellant-Appellant. The 2nd Defendant-Appellant-Appellant then appealed to the Supreme Court, which granted leave to appeal on questions regarding the entitlement to the boutique premises and the copra hut. Issues Whether the 2nd Defendant-Appellant-Appellant is entitled to a 1/2 share of the two boutique premises. Whether the 2nd Defendant-Appellant-Appellant is the absolute owner of the copra hut. Whether the trial judge erred in not granting the 2nd Defendant-Appellant-Appellant his claimed share of the boutique premises and the copra hut. Applicable Law Statutes: Not specified Cases Referred to: De Silva v. Haramanis - [3-nlr-160] Hassanally v. Cassim - [61-nlr-529] De Silva v. Siyadoris - [14-nlr-268] Abideen Hadjiar v. Aiysha Umma - [68-nlr-411] Perera v. Perera - [62-nlr-52] Gunatilake v. Fernando - [22-nlr-385] Appuhamy v. Appuhamy - [3-scc-61] Siyadoris v. Peter Singho - [54-nlr-393] Ponnambalam v. Balasubramanium - [2004/v1-blr-125] Silva v. Silva - [6-nlr-22] Analysis Issue 1: Entitlement to boutique premises Rule applied: The principle of accession (omne quod inaedificator solo, solo cedit) and the rights of co-owners regarding improvements on common property. Court's reasoning: The court held that the boutique premises were built on land co-owned by Ukkuwa and Silindu. Under Roman-Dutch law, structures on land accede to the soil and become common property. Even if Ukkuwa performed the improvements, he did so for the benefit of his family, including his co-owner wife, Silindu. There was no evidence of an intention to claim compensation or sole ownership against her. Therefore, Silindu retained her rights, which were validly transferred to the Appellant. Finding: The Appellant is entitled to a 1/2 share of the boutique premises. Issue 2: Ownership of the copra hut Rule applied: The doctrine of exceptio rei venditae et traditae. Court's reasoning: The court examined whether the Respondent could invoke the doctrine to claim title. The Respondent failed to prove that consideration passed for the transfer or that he had possession. Conversely, the Appellant held a valid transfer from Ukkuwa following the revocation of a prior gift. The court found a lack of evidence to support the Respondent's claim under the doctrine, as the requirements of consideration and possession were not met. Finding: The Appellant is entitled to all shares relating to the copra hut. Issue 3: Allocation of shares Rule applied: Principles of co-ownership and valid transfer of property rights. Court's reasoning: Having determined that the Appellant succeeded to Silindu's rights and that Ukkuwa's transfers to the Appellant were valid, the court concluded that the previous judgments failed to recognize the Appellant's lawful interest in the structures. Finding: The Appellant is entitled to the claimed shares, and the previous judgments were varied accordingly. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are linked by the principle that improvements made by a co-owner on common land do not grant sole title to the improver, but rather accede to the soil. The resolution of the first issue established the co-ownership status, which informed the analysis of the second issue regarding the validity of the competing deeds and the failure of the Respondent to establish superior title through the doctrine of exceptio rei venditae et traditae. Conclusion The appeal is allowed, and the judgment of the Civil Appellate High Court is set aside. The judgment of the District Court is varied to reflect the Appellant's entitlement to a 1/2 share of the boutique premises and full ownership of the copra hut. Keywords Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser — Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Partition of land — Co-ownership — Rights of co-owners — Improvements on land — Building on land of another — Unjust enrichment — Transfer of property — Deeds of transfer — Revocation of deeds		SC/APPEAL/117/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_117_2017.pdf
sc-fr-18-2020	6 September 2022	Dugathadasa and Others v. Shivagnanasothy and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Priyantha Jayawardena, PC, J; P. Padman Surasena, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Promotion of police officers — Backdating of promotions — Special promotion scheme — Merit and seniority scheme — Legitimate expectation — Violation of fundamental rights	Facts The Petitioners, Dola Mullage Gunarathna and Mallika Arachchige Lakshman, are Inspectors of Police who joined the Sri Lanka Police Service in 1985 and 1986 respectively. They were promoted to the rank of Inspector of Police (IP) effective from 31/05/2016. The 11th Respondent, also an Inspector of Police, was promoted to the rank of IP on 04/12/2019 with effect from 01/01/2019. Subsequently, the Inspector General of Police issued a communique, RTM No. 699, which backdated the 11th Respondent's promotion to the rank of IP to 08/02/2010. The Petitioners challenged this backdating, alleging that it was performed without proper evaluation or adherence to established guidelines. They contended that the 11th Respondent lacked the necessary seniority and experience compared to them and that the backdating violated their fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. The Petitioners further noted that the 11th Respondent had previously received a backdated promotion to the rank of Sub-Inspector (SI) to 22/12/2001. The Respondents raised a preliminary objection, arguing that the application was time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the fundamental rights application was time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Whether the backdating of the 11th Respondent's promotion to the rank of Inspector of Police violated the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka (Articles 12(1), 14(1)(g), 55(1), 55(4), 126(2), 155G(1)(a)) Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act No. 21 of 1996 (Section 13(1)) Cases Referred to: Edirisuriya v. Navaratnam - [1985/v1-sri-lr-100] Demuni Sriyani De Soyza v. Dharmasena Dissanayake - [sc-fr-206/2008] Siriwardene v. Rodrigo - [1985/v1-sri-lr-387] Illangaratne v. Kandy Muncipal Council - [1995/v6-balj-1] Romesh Cooray v. Jayalath - [2008/v2-sri-lr-43] Abeywickrama v. Pathirana - [1986/v1-sri-lr-120] The Public Services United Nurses Union v. Montague Jayawickrama - [1988/v1-sri-lr-229] Govind Dattatray Kelkar v. Chief Controller of Imports - [1967/v2-s.c.r.-29] Surendran v. University Grants Commission - [1993/v1-sri-lr-344] Weligodapola v. Secretary, Minister of Women Affairs - [1989/v2-sri-lr-63] Ganga Ram v. Union of India - [1970/v1-s.c.c.-377] Perera v. Cyril Ranathunga - [1993/v1-sri-lr-39] Jaisinghani v. Union of India - [1967/air-sc-427] Analysis Issue 1: Time Bar Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution and Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act No. 21 of 1996. Court's reasoning: The court noted that while the Petitioners filed their application after the one-month period from the date of the RTM, they had filed a complaint with the Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka (HRCSL) within 30 days of the impugned act. Under Section 13(1) of the HRCSL Act, the period during which a complaint is pending before the Commission is excluded from the computation of the one-month time limit for filing a fundamental rights application in the Supreme Court. Finding: The preliminary objection was overruled; the application was deemed filed within the permitted time frame. Issue 2: Violation of Fundamental Rights Rule applied: Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution; Sri Lanka Police Orders A5 Part IV. Court's reasoning: The court reasoned that while the 11th Respondent's backdating to the rank of SI was permissible under specific administrative provisions, the subsequent backdating to the rank of IP allowed the 11th Respondent to benefit twice from the same service period under two different promotion schemes. The court held that allowing an individual to compete through two mediums to be promoted twice for the same position creates unfair disparities and violates the legitimate expectations of other officers. Finding: The backdating of the 11th Respondent's promotion to the rank of IP was invalid, and the Petitioners' fundamental rights were violated. Interaction of Issues The resolution of the time-bar issue allowed the court to reach the merits of the case. Once the court determined that the administrative practice of "double-dipping" into promotion schemes was inherently discriminatory, it reinforced the conclusion that the specific act of backdating the 11th Respondent's promotion was an arbitrary exercise of power that infringed upon the equality of opportunity guaranteed to the Petitioners. Conclusion The court allowed the application and quashed the communication dated 18/12/2019 (RTM No. 699). The backdating of the 11th Respondent's promotion to the rank of Inspector of Police was declared invalid. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Promotion of police officers — Backdating of promotions — Special promotion scheme — Merit and seniority scheme — Legitimate expectation — Violation of fundamental rights		SC/FR/18/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_18_2020.pdf
sc-appeal-184-2014	7 September 2022	Somawathie and Others v. Dharmapala and Others	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.	Priyantha Jayawardena, PC, J; Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.	Co-ownership — Trespasser — Declaration of title — Ejectment — Prescriptive title — Undivided share — District Court jurisdiction — High Court jurisdiction — Fundamental rights	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent-Petitioner instituted an action in the District Court of Ratnapura seeking a declaration of title to a land described in the schedule and the ejectment of the Defendant-Appellant-Respondent from a portion of that land. The Plaintiff claimed that she was a co-owner of the larger land and had acquired a specific portion through a partition with the consent of other co-owners, which she subsequently possessed. The Defendant contested the claim, asserting his own title to a different land and arguing that the Plaintiff could not claim a divided portion or maintain the action without joining other co-owners. The District Court found in favor of the Plaintiff, concluding that she had established her status as a co-owner and that the Defendant had encroached upon the land. The Defendant appealed to the Provincial High Court of Civil Appeal, which set aside the District Court judgment. The High Court held that the Plaintiff could not maintain an action for declaration of title and ejectment against a trespasser without joining all other co-owners, particularly because she had claimed sole ownership in her prayer. The Plaintiff then appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that a co-owner cannot maintain an action to eject a trespasser without joining other co-owners as parties. Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that a District Court has no authority to declare co-ownership in such an action. Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that a co-owner is not entitled to claim a declaration of title to the entire land. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code Cases Referred to: Hevawitharana v. Dangan Rubber Company - [17-nlr-49] Sura v. Fernando - [1-acr-95] Unus Lebbe v. Zayee - [1893/v3-s-c-r-56] Arnolisa v. Dissan - [4-nlr-163] Dharmasiri v. Wickrematunga - [2002/v2-sri-lr-218] Jayasinghe v. Tikiri Banda - [2-calr-24] Geeta v. Fernando - [4-bal-100] Rockland Distilleries v. Azeez - [52-nlr-490] Hariette v. Pathmasiri - [1996/v1-sri-lr-358] Allis v. Seneviratne - [1989/v2-sri-lr-335] Attanayake v. Ramyawathie - [2003/v1-sri-lr-401] Analysis Issue 1: Joinder of co-owners Rule applied: The principle that a co-owner may maintain an action against a trespasser without joining other co-owners, as established in Unus Lebbe v. Zayee and Hevawitharana v. Dangan Rubber Company. Court's reasoning: The Court reasoned that a co-owner has an interest in every part of the common land. Therefore, a co-owner is competent to sue a trespasser to protect their rights and the common property without the necessity of joining other co-owners as parties. Finding: The High Court erred; a co-owner can maintain an action for ejectment against a trespasser independently. Issue 2: Authority to declare co-ownership Rule applied: The principle that a court may grant lesser relief than what is prayed for if the title is averred and proved, as seen in Attanayake v. Ramyawathie. Court's reasoning: The Court held that even if a plaintiff claims sole ownership but proves only co-ownership, the court is not precluded from granting a declaration of co-ownership. Furthermore, a formal prayer for declaration is not strictly required in a rei vindicatio action if the title is pleaded and proved. Finding: The High Court erred; the District Court has the authority to declare co-ownership even if the plaintiff initially sought broader relief. Issue 3: Claiming title to the entire land Rule applied: The principle that a claim for greater relief does not disqualify a party from receiving lesser relief, as established in Attanayake v. Ramyawathie. Court's reasoning: The Court determined that the Plaintiff's prayer for declaration of title was not a claim for sole ownership to the exclusion of others, but rather an assertion of her entitlement. Even if it were interpreted as a claim for sole ownership, the law allows the court to grant the lesser relief of declaring co-ownership if the evidence supports it. Finding: The High Court erred; a claim for greater relief does not bar a plaintiff from obtaining a judgment for a lesser share. Interaction of Issues The findings on these issues are interconnected: the right to sue a trespasser (Issue 1) is supported by the court's power to grant appropriate relief (Issue 2) even when the initial prayer is for a greater interest than what is ultimately proven (Issue 3). Together, they confirm that procedural technicalities regarding joinder and the scope of the prayer should not defeat a co-owner's substantive right to protect common property from trespass. Conclusion The Supreme Court allowed the appeal, set aside the judgment of the Provincial High Court of Civil Appeal, and affirmed the judgment of the District Court of Ratnapura. The Plaintiff is entitled to costs in all courts. Keywords Co-ownership — Trespasser — Declaration of title — Ejectment — Prescriptive title — Undivided share — District Court jurisdiction — High Court jurisdiction — Fundamental rights		SC/APPEAL/184/2014	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_184_2014.pdf
ca-writ-19-2019	8 September 2022	Ameer and Another v. Urban Council and Others	M.T. Mohammed Laffar, J.	M.T. Mohammed Laffar, J.	Writ of Mandamus — Writ of Prohibition — Legitimate expectation — Administrative decisions — Natural justice — Amalgamation of shops — Public authorities — Urban Council — Urban Development Authority — New Commercial Complex	Facts The Petitioners, M. A. C. M. Ameer and M. A. C. M. Mujaser, were tenants of two separate shops, bearing assessment numbers B42 and B41 respectively, at the Delkada Complex owned by the 1st Respondent. Following communal riots in 2014, the shops were destroyed. The Petitioners vacated the premises pursuant to a notice issued by the 1st Respondent in accordance with the 4th Respondent's instructions, with the assurance that they would be allocated shops at a new commercial complex being constructed at Station Road, Kalutara. In March 2018, the Urban Development Authority (UDA) requested proof of the Petitioners' previous tenancies. Although the Petitioners provided the necessary documentation, they were subsequently informed that they would be allocated only one shop at the new complex. The Respondents contended that the Petitioners had previously amalgamated their two shops into a single business unit, thereby justifying the allocation of only one shop. The Petitioners denied this contention, asserting that they maintained separate tenancies and that the reduction in allocation violated their legitimate expectations. Issues Whether the decision of the Respondents to allocate only one shop to the Petitioners, based on the alleged amalgamation of their previous two shops, was arbitrary and lacking a rational basis. Whether the Petitioners had a legitimate expectation to be allocated two separate shops at the new commercial complex based on the assurances given by the 1st Respondent and the provisions of Circular No. 1980/46. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 140 Cases Referred to: Choolanie v. Peoples Bank - [2008/v2-sri-lr-93] Junaideen Mohamed Iqbal v. The Divisional Secretary, Kundasale - [ca-writ-328-215-ca] Hong Kong v. Ng Yuen Shiu - [1983] 2 AC 629 GNCT of Delhi v. Naresh Kumar - [175-2010-dlt-143] Wickramaratne v. Jayaratne - [2001/v3-sri-lr-161] Analysis Issue 1: Arbitrariness of the administrative decision Rule applied: The principle that administrative decisions must be supported by adequate reasons and based on material evidence, as established in Choolanie v. Peoples Bank. Court's reasoning: The court found that the Respondents failed to conduct an inquiry or provide a rational basis for the conclusion that the Petitioners' shops were amalgamated. The documents submitted by the Respondents (4R1 and 4R2) were deemed insufficient to support their contention. Furthermore, the court noted that the letter marked P2 explicitly referred to the shops as two separate entities (B41 and B42), contradicting the Respondents' claim. Finding: The decision to allocate only one shop was arbitrary, unsupported by evidence, and violated the principles of natural justice. Issue 2: Legitimate expectation Rule applied: The doctrine of legitimate expectation, which mandates that public authorities must honor clear and unequivocal promises or representations, as discussed in Junaideen Mohamed Iqbal v. The Divisional Secretary, Kundasale and Wickramaratne v. Jayaratne. Court's reasoning: The court held that the Petitioners were given an express assurance by the 1st Respondent regarding the allocation of shops. Additionally, Clause 3 of Circular No. 1980/46 provided a regulatory basis for the Petitioners to expect the allocation of stalls equivalent to their previous tenancies. The court emphasized that public authorities cannot resile from such undertakings without a rational basis and without providing the affected parties an opportunity to be heard. Finding: The Petitioners held a legitimate expectation to receive two separate shops, which the Respondents failed to honor. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing; the courtâ€™s determination that the Respondents acted arbitrarily (Issue 1) directly supports the conclusion that the Petitioners' legitimate expectations (Issue 2) were violated. The lack of a rational basis for the administrative decision rendered the breach of the promise to allocate two shops legally indefensible. Conclusion The application is allowed. A Writ of Mandamus and a Writ of Prohibition are issued against the 4th and 5B Respondents as prayed for in the petition, with costs fixed at Rs. 50,000/- payable to the Petitioners. Keywords Writ of Mandamus — Writ of Prohibition — Legitimate expectation — Administrative decisions — Natural justice — Amalgamation of shops — Public authorities — Urban Council — Urban Development Authority — New Commercial Complex			
sc-appeal-88-2017	15 September 2022	Dona Shiromi v. Don Francis and Don Newton Donatus	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Servitude of right of way — Prescriptive title — Adverse possession — Necessity — Footpath — Prescription Ordinance — Section 13 of the Prescription Ordinance — Continuous and uninterrupted possession — Change of character — Permission to use	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant, Kerewgoda Dona Shiromi, filed an action in the District Court of Negombo seeking a declaration of title to a land and an order confirming that the land was free from any servitude of a right of way. The Plaintiff claimed she was the sole successor to the land and that the Defendant-Appellant-Respondents, Hanwellage Don Francis and Hettige Don Newton Donatus, had been using a footpath across her property with her leave and license. In 1998, the Defendants allegedly demolished a toilet on the property, widened the footpath into an 8-foot-wide roadway, and attempted to use it for vehicular access, claiming a 10-foot-wide right of way by prescription and necessity. The District Court granted the relief sought by the Plaintiff, finding that the Defendants failed to establish continuous and uninterrupted possession for the required prescriptive period. The Defendants appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal, which set aside the District Court judgment, holding that the Defendants had acquired a prescriptive right to a 10-foot-wide roadway due to necessity and long-term use. The Plaintiff subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in law and fact in concluding that the Defendants acquired a prescriptive title to the right of way. Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in failing to determine the commencement date of the prescriptive user for the purpose of calculating the prescriptive period. Whether the Plaintiff is qualified under Section 13 of the Prescription Ordinance when calculating the prescriptive period. Applicable Law Statutes: Prescription Ordinance (Section 3, Section 13) Primary Court Procedure Act (Section 66) Cases Referred to: Priyangika Perera v. Gunasiri Perera - [sc-appeal-59/2012] De Soysa v. Fernando - [58-nlr-501] Chelliah v. Wijenathan - [54-nlr-337] Ganemulla Gamage Suraji v. P.K. Sunil Samarasekara - [sc-appeal-33/2010] D.R. Kiriamma v. J.A. Podibanda - [2005/blr-9] Seeman v. David - [2000/v3-sri-lr-23] Naguda Marikar v. Mohammadu - [7-nlr-91] Lebbe Marikar v. Sainu - [10-nlr-339] Orloff v. Grebe - [10-nlr-183] Thilakaratne v. Bastian - [21-nlr-12] Navarathne v. Jayathunge - [44-nlr-517] Corenelis v. Fernando - [65-nlr-93] De Silva v. Commissioner General of Inland Revenue - [80-nlr-292] Analysis Issue 1: Prescriptive Title Rule applied: Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance, which requires proof of undisturbed, uninterrupted, and adverse possession for a minimum of ten years. Court's reasoning: The court found that the Defendants' use of the path originated with the Plaintiff's permission. Under the principle established in De Soysa v. Fernando, user commencing with leave and license is presumed to continue as such unless there is clear evidence of a change to adverse user. The court noted that the presence of a coconut tree within the disputed area until 1997 contradicted the claim of a 10-foot-wide roadway existing for the prescriptive period. No evidence of an "overt act" was presented to show the Defendants changed their character from permissive users to adverse possessors. Finding: The Defendants failed to establish a prescriptive title to the right of way. Issue 2: Commencement of Prescriptive User Rule applied: The burden of proof rests on the party invoking Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance to establish a starting point for prescriptive rights (Chelliah v. Wijenathan). Court's reasoning: The court examined the evidence and concluded that the Defendants failed to provide cogent proof that their predecessors in title used the path adversely to the interest of the landowner. Since the Defendants did not establish when the user became adverse, they could not satisfy the requirement of ten years of adverse possession. Finding: The High Court of Civil Appeal erred by failing to identify a valid commencement date for adverse user. Interaction of Issues The findings on the first two issues are inextricably linked. Because the Defendants failed to prove the commencement of an adverse user (Issue 2), they could not meet the statutory requirements for prescription (Issue 1). Consequently, the question of whether the Plaintiff was protected by the disability provisions of Section 13 of the Prescription Ordinance (Issue 3) became redundant, as the Defendants had not established the foundational requirements for a prescriptive claim in the first place. Conclusion The appeal is allowed, and the judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal dated 07/05/2015 is set aside. The judgment of the District Court dated 28/11/2008 is affirmed. Keywords Servitude of right of way — Prescriptive title — Adverse possession — Necessity — Footpath — Prescription Ordinance — Section 13 of the Prescription Ordinance — Continuous and uninterrupted possession — Change of character — Permission to use		SC/APPEAL/88/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_app_88_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-63-2014	22 September 2022	Somawathie and Fernando v. Wickremasinghe and Tillekeratne	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; Kumudini Wickremasinghe, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Amendment of pleadings — Issuance of summons — Ex parte trial — Service of summons — Fundamental rights — District Court procedure — High Court procedure — Supreme Court procedure — Application to set aside ex parte decree	Facts The Plaintiffs instituted action in the District Court of Moratuwa seeking damages following a fatal motor accident. The original plaint named three defendants, including the Appellant as the third defendant. While the second defendant filed an answer, the first defendant and the Appellant did not respond to summons. The District Court subsequently fixed the matter for ex parte trial against the first defendant and the Appellant. Before the trial commenced, the Plaintiffs filed a motion to amend the plaint to remove the second defendant, rename the third defendant as the second defendant, and alter the date of the accident. This motion was not served on any of the defendants. The District Court allowed the amendment and subsequently decided that there was no necessity to issue summons on the amended plaint because the trial had already been fixed ex parte. Following an ex parte trial, judgment and decree were entered against the Appellant. The Appellant later filed a petition to set aside the ex parte decree, claiming he was never served with summons or notice of the proceedings until execution was sought. The District Court rejected this application, and the Civil Appellate High Court dismissed the subsequent appeal, holding that the Appellant had no legal right to challenge the decree at the execution stage after failing to act within the time prescribed by Section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code. Issues Whether a defendant is entitled to receive notice of an application to amend a plaint made after the trial has been fixed ex parte against them. Whether a defendant against whom an ex parte trial has been fixed is entitled to be issued with summons on an amended plaint once the amendment is accepted by the court. Whether a defendant can make an application to set aside an ex parte judgment at the stage of execution of the decree. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 128 Civil Procedure Code, Section 39 Civil Procedure Code, Section 46 Civil Procedure Code, Section 55 Civil Procedure Code, Section 84 Civil Procedure Code, Section 85(4) Civil Procedure Code, Section 86(2) Civil Procedure Code, Section 93 Civil Procedure Code, Section 839 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 79 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 9 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 8 Cases Referred to: Rajasingham v Seneviratne - [(2002) 1 Sri LR 82] Gunasekera v Punchimenike - [(2002) 2 Sri LR 43] Kuruppuarachchi v Andreas - [(1996) 2 Sri LR 11] Gunasekera v Abdul Latiff - [(1995) 1 Sri LR 225] Mackinnons v Grindlays Bank - [(1986) 2 Sri LR 272] Ittepana v Hemawathie - [(1981) 1 Sri LR 476] Beatrice Perera v The Commissioner of National Housing - [77 NLR 361] Leelawathie v Jayaneris - [(2001) 2 Sri LR 231] Bartleet Finance PLC v Ranepura Hewage Kusumawathi - [sc-appeal-121/2016] Rodger v Comptoir dEscompte de Paris - [(1871) LR 3 PC 465] Analysis Issue 1: Notice of amendment Rule applied: Section 93 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court held that Section 93 mandates that amendments to pleadings must be carried out in the presence of, or after reasonable notice to, all parties. Even if a defendant is absent or has been fixed for ex parte trial, the court is duty-bound to provide notice of any amendment that may adversely affect them. Failure to provide such notice renders the subsequent proceedings a nullity. Finding: The Appellant was entitled to notice of the application to amend the plaint. Issue 2: Summons on amended plaint Rule applied: Sections 55 and 84 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court reasoned that an amended plaint constitutes a new pleading, effectively replacing the original. Consequently, the court must trigger the procedure under Section 55(1) to serve summons on the defendant. Fixing a case for ex parte trial without serving summons on the amended plaint violates the fundamental rules of natural justice and the statutory requirements of the Code. Finding: The Appellant was entitled to be served with summons on the amended plaint. Issue 3: Setting aside ex parte decree Rule applied: Section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code (Inherent Powers). Court's reasoning: Where a judgment is a nullity due to a lack of jurisdiction—such as the failure to serve summons—the court has the inherent power to set aside the decree ex debito justitiae. The court held that the Appellant was not barred by the 14-day limit in Section 86(2) because the underlying proceedings were void ab initio. Finding: The Appellant had the legal right to challenge the ex parte decree at the execution stage. Interaction of Issues The findings are interdependent: the failure to provide notice of the amendment (Issue 1) and the failure to serve summons on the amended plaint (Issue 2) resulted in a jurisdictional defect. Because the court lacked jurisdiction over the Appellant regarding the amended claims, the resulting decree was a nullity, which empowered the court to exercise its inherent jurisdiction to set aside the decree at the execution stage (Issue 3). Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The orders fixing the case for ex parte trial, permitting the amendment, and the subsequent judgment and decree are set aside. The District Court is directed to issue notice of the amendment application to the Appellant and the first defendant, consider the application according to law, and proceed with the trial. Keywords Amendment of pleadings — Issuance of summons — Ex parte trial — Service of summons — Fundamental rights — District Court procedure — High Court procedure — Supreme Court procedure — Application to set aside ex parte decree		SC/APPEAL/63/2014	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_63_2014.pdf
sc-appeal-82-2020	22 September 2022	Thilakeratne v. Wijesena and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Partition action — Identification of corpus — Preliminary plan — Extent of land — Traditional land measures — Deeds — Lis pendens — Amicable partition — Surveyors commission	Facts The plaintiff filed an action in the District Court of Kuliyapitiya to partition the land known as Innawatta. The 1st to 5th defendants accepted the pedigree set out in the plaint. The 8th defendant, a land developer, contested the action, claiming ownership of a portion of the land identified as lot 2 in the preliminary plan, which he had acquired from the 6th defendant. The 9th to 21st defendants, who were transferees of portions of lot 2 from the 8th defendant, also sought the exclusion of their respective lots. The 8th defendant raised issues regarding the exclusion of lot 2, his title to said lot, and the identification of the corpus. The District Court answered the issues against the 8th defendant and ordered the partition of the land as prayed for by the plaintiff. The High Court of Civil Appeal of Kurunagala subsequently set aside the District Court judgment and dismissed the action. The High Court reasoned that the plaintiff had failed to properly identify the corpus because the extent of the land described in the plaint (3 lahas of kurakkan sowing area) was significantly smaller than the extent shown in the preliminary plan (6 acres, 1 rood, and 11 perches). The plaintiff appealed to the Supreme Court, which granted leave to appeal on the question of whether the High Court erred in its finding regarding the identification of the corpus. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by concluding that the petitioner surveyed a larger land than the corpus described in the schedule to the plaint. Whether the identification of the corpus in a partition action can be determined solely by the mechanical application of a standard conversion formula for traditional land measures. Applicable Law Statutes: Partition Law No. 21 of 1977, Sections 16(1), 16(2), 18(1), 18(2), 19(2)(b), 66(1), 66(2), 66(3), 70. Registration of Documents Ordinance. Cases Referred to: Virasinghe v. Virasinghe - [2002/v1-sri-lr-1] Sirisoma v. Sarnelis Appuhamy - [51-nlr-337] Sillie Fernando v. Silman Fernando - [64-nlr-404] Karunaratne v. Perera - [67-nlr-529] Dharmaratana Thero v. Siyadoris - [1995/v2-sri-lr-245] Ariyawathie De Silva v. Wijesena - [ca-608/2000/f] Hapuarachchi v. Podi Nilame - [sc-appeal-52/2018] Ratnayake v. Kumarihamy - [2005/v1-sri-lr-303] Noordeen Lebbe v. Shahul Hameed - [49-nlr-274] Gabriel Perera v. Agnes Perera - [43-clw-82] Silva v. Ismail - [44-nlr-550] Appuhamy v. Gallella - [78-nlr-404] Sopaya Silva v. Magilin Silva - [1989/v2-sri-lr-105] Jayasuriya v. Ubaid - [61-nlr-352] Analysis Issue 1: Identification of the corpus Rule applied: Section 16(2) and Section 18(2) of the Partition Law No. 21 of 1977. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the High Court erred by applying a rigid, mechanical formula equating 1 laha of kurakkan sowing area to 1 acre. The Court noted that traditional land measures are imprecise and vary based on soil fertility, grain quality, and local custom. The Court emphasized that the surveyorâ€™s preliminary plan depicts existing boundaries, whereas old deeds often contain speculative extents. Because the contesting defendants failed to utilize the statutory mechanisms to challenge the survey or summon the surveyor for clarification, they could not rely on a vague issue raised for the first time at trial to defeat the action. Finding: The High Courtâ€™s conclusion that the preliminary plan depicted a larger land than the corpus was erroneous. Issue 2: Application of conversion formulas Rule applied: Principles of interpretation of deeds and the evidentiary weight of traditional land measures. Court's reasoning: The Court reasoned that when descriptions in a deed are inconsistent, the court must look at the totality of evidence, including boundaries and the conduct of parties. The Court found that the boundaries of the land were consistent across the evidence, and the discrepancy in extent was a falsa demonstratio that did not invalidate the identification of the land. Finding: The identification of the corpus is a question of fact, not a mathematical calculation, and the High Courtâ€™s reliance on a fixed conversion formula was legally unsound. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are interdependent; the rejection of the mechanical conversion formula (Issue 2) directly supports the conclusion that the preliminary plan correctly identified the corpus (Issue 1). By establishing that the extent in old deeds is not a rigid determinant, the Court rendered the High Court's basis for dismissal invalid, thereby reinforcing the validity of the District Court's original findings. Conclusion The Supreme Court allowed the appeal, set aside the judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal, and restored the judgment of the District Court. The Court held that the corpus was properly identified and that the partition action was maintainable. Keywords Partition action — Identification of corpus — Preliminary plan — Extent of land — Traditional land measures — Deeds — Lis pendens — Amicable partition — Surveyors commission		SC/APPEAL/82/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_82_2020.pdf
sc-hcca-la-147-2022	26 September 2022	Pattiyage Harsha Kamal Gomes v. Sri Lanka Rupavahini Corporation and Others	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, CJ	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, CJ; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J; A.L Shiran Gooneratne, J.	High Court of the Provinces — Commercial High Court — Jurisdiction — Civil Procedure Code — Judicial Order — Administrative Process — Appeal — Specific Performance — Injunctions — Legal Rights — Proper Administration of Justice — Practices and Procedures — Transfer of Cases — Undue Hardship	Facts The case revolves around an application for leave to appeal filed by Pattiyage Harsha Kamal Gomes, the Plaintiff-Petitioner, against the Sri Lanka Rupavahini Corporation and its Chairman, Sonala Digath Weerawickrema Gunawardana, along with another Chairman, Asanka Priyanath Jayasuriya. The appellant sought to challenge the decision of the Commercial High Court of Colombo, which had returned a case record to the District Court of Colombo without a proper judicial order. The appellant had initially attempted to file a case in the Commercial High Court concerning a commercial agreement but was informed that the court lacked jurisdiction due to the absence of a monetary claim. Consequently, the appellant instituted action in the District Court, which was later directed to transfer the case back to the Commercial High Court. However, the Commercial High Court returned the case record to the District Court, leading to the current appeal. The appellant sought to set aside the order of the High Court Judge and requested that the case be registered in the Commercial High Court or, alternatively, in the District Court. The core issue was whether the Commercial High Court had the jurisdiction to hear the appellant's case and whether the procedures followed were lawful. Issues Whether the Commercial High Court had jurisdiction to hear the appellant's case. Whether the procedures followed by the Commercial High Court in returning the case record to the District Court were lawful. Applicable Law Statutes: High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 10 of 1996 — Civil Procedure Code Cases Referred to: Cornel and Company Ltd v Mitsui and Company Ltd and others - [2000] 1 SLR 57; Trans Orbit Global Logistics (Pvt) Limited v People’s Bank, S.C. Appeal No. 92/2020. Analysis Issue 1: Jurisdiction of the Commercial High Court Rule applied: High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 10 of 1996. Court's reasoning: The court examined the jurisdiction of the Commercial High Court, which is established under Article 154P of the Constitution and vested with exclusive jurisdiction to hear civil actions arising from commercial transactions. The court noted that the appellant's claim for specific performance and injunctions fell within the ambit of the Commercial High Court's jurisdiction as outlined in the First Schedule of the Act. The court emphasized that the Commercial High Court's failure to accept the plaint and return it to the District Court was not only procedurally incorrect but also detrimental to the administration of justice. The court highlighted that a judicial order is essential for the rejection or return of a plaint, as stipulated in Section 48 of the Civil Procedure Code. The court criticized the practice of allowing administrative officers to make such decisions, which undermines the integrity of judicial processes. Finding: The Commercial High Court lacked the authority to return the case record to the District Court without a proper judicial order. Issue 2: Lawfulness of Procedures Followed Rule applied: Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court scrutinized the procedures adopted by the Commercial High Court, particularly the return of the case record without a judicial order. The court reiterated that the Civil Procedure Code mandates that any order returning or rejecting a plaint must be in writing, signed by the judge, and specify the grounds for such action. The court expressed concern over the implications of allowing administrative processes to dictate judicial outcomes, emphasizing that such practices could lead to significant injustices. The court also noted that the impugned document signed by the High Court Judge did not comply with the requirements of a judicial order, further complicating the matter. Finding: The procedures followed by the Commercial High Court were unlawful and inconsistent with established legal practices. Interaction of Issues The issues are interrelated as the jurisdiction of the Commercial High Court directly impacts the legality of the procedures followed. If the court lacked jurisdiction, any actions taken would be rendered invalid, thereby affecting the appellant's ability to seek redress. The court's analysis highlighted the importance of adhering to proper legal procedures to ensure justice is served. Conclusion The Supreme Court directed that the Commercial High Court must adhere to lawful practices in accepting and rejecting plaints. The court ordered the registrar of the Commercial High Court to recall the letter returning the case record and to register the case without delay. The court emphasized the need for expeditious disposal of the matter, recognizing the hardships faced by the appellant in seeking justice. The judgment underscores the importance of maintaining the integrity of judicial processes and ensuring that litigants are afforded their legal rights without undue hardship.	Dislrukshi Dias Wickremasinghe, PC with Dilumi de Alwis and Sithari Perera instructed by Sanjay Fonseka for the Plaintiff-Petitioner. Palitha Kumarasinghe, PC with Viraj Bandaranayake for the 1st and 2nd Defendant-Respondents.	SC/HC CALA/147/2022	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_hc_cala_147_2022.pdf
sc-appeal-109-2017	27 September 2022	Officer in Charge, Police Station, Wattegama v. Wijesinghe and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Section 135 of the Code of Criminal Procedure — Section 177 of the Penal Code — Complaint vs. Report — Sanction of the Attorney General — Jurisdiction of the Court — Failure of justice — B report	Facts The Accused-Appellant-Petitioner, Puwakgahakumbure Gedara William Wijesinghe, was charged in the Magistrate Court of Theldeniya with three counts: refusing to answer questions from a public servant under Section 177 of the Penal Code, obstructing a public servant under Section 344 of the Penal Code, and threatening a public servant under Section 186 of the Penal Code. These charges arose from an inquiry conducted by the Wattegama Police on 15th January 2007 regarding a complaint of misappropriation of jewellery. The prosecution alleged that during the inquiry, the Accused used offensive language, obstructed the police officer, and attempted to self-harm. The Accused contended that he was assaulted by the police officers and that no formal complaint existed against him at the time of the inquiry. The Magistrate Court found the Accused guilty of the first and second counts and acquitted him of the third. The Accused was sentenced to pay fines of LKR 100 and LKR 1500 respectively. The High Court of Kandy subsequently dismissed the Accused's appeal and affirmed the Magistrate's judgment. The Accused then appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the prosecution complied with the requirements of Section 135(1)(a) of the Code of Criminal Procedure Act No. 15 of 1979 regarding the necessity of the Attorney General's sanction or a complaint by a public servant. Whether the filing of a "B report" by the Officer in Charge of the police station constitutes a "complaint" for the purposes of Section 135(1)(a) of the Code of Criminal Procedure Act. Applicable Law Statutes: Penal Code (Section 177, 186, 344) Code of Criminal Procedure Act No. 15 of 1979 (Section 2, 135, 136, 436) Judicature Act No. 02 of 1978 (Section 39) Cases Referred to: R.P. Wijesiri v. Attorney-General - [1980/v2-sri-lr-317] R v. Meera Saibo - [not specified] Baby v. Banda - [1999/v3-sri-lr-416] Beatrice Perera v. Commissioner of National Housing - [77-nlr-361] Kekul Kotuwage Don Aruna Chaminda v. Janashakthi General Insurance Limited - [sc-appeal-134/2018] Kanagarajah v. The Queen - [74-nlr-378] Brereton v. Ratranhamy - [42-nlr-149] In re Subramaniam - [A.I.R. 1957 Madras 442] Analysis Issue 1: Compliance with Section 135(1)(a) Rule applied: Section 135(1)(a) of the Code of Criminal Procedure Act No. 15 of 1979. Court's reasoning: The court noted that Section 135(1)(a) requires either the previous sanction of the Attorney General or a complaint by the public servant concerned or their superior to initiate proceedings for offences under Section 177 of the Penal Code. The court determined that the "B report" filed by the Officer in Charge of the Wattegama Police Station, who is the superior of the officer involved, satisfied the requirement of a "complaint" under the Act. Finding: The prosecution complied with the statutory requirements as the B report served as a valid complaint by a superior public servant. Issue 2: Definition of "Complaint" and Jurisdiction Rule applied: Section 2 and Section 136 of the Code of Criminal Procedure Act No. 15 of 1979. Court's reasoning: The court rejected the Accused's argument that a B report is distinct from a complaint. Relying on the definition in Section 2, the court held that a B report containing a written allegation made to a Magistrate with a view to taking action constitutes a complaint. Furthermore, the court held that even if there were a technical defect, Section 436 of the Code of Criminal Procedure prevents the reversal of a judgment unless a failure of justice has occurred, which was not found in this case. Finding: A B report qualifies as a complaint, and no failure of justice occurred to warrant setting aside the conviction. Interaction of Issues The findings on the definition of a "complaint" directly resolved the jurisdictional challenge. By establishing that the B report satisfied the requirements of Section 135(1)(a), the court concluded that there was no patent lack of jurisdiction, thereby rendering the timing of the objection irrelevant and confirming the validity of the lower courts' proceedings. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The judgment of the Magistrate Court and the order of the High Court of Kandy are affirmed, and the Appellant is ordered to pay costs of Ten Thousand Rupees. Keywords Section 135 of the Code of Criminal Procedure — Section 177 of the Penal Code — Complaint vs. Report — Sanction of the Attorney General — Jurisdiction of the Court — Failure of justice — B report		SC/APPEAL/109/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_109_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-15-2019	27 September 2022	Sithy Jawahira and Riyas v. Tennakoon and Others	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.	Land Acquisition Act — Public purpose — Mala fides — Urgency — Section 38(a) order — Writ of certiorari — Writ of mandamus — Judicial review — Administrative action	Facts The Petitioners-Appellants were in occupation of several lots of land in Karapitiya, Galle, which were subject to an acquisition process initiated by the Minister of Land and Land Development. The acquisition process commenced with a notice under Section 2 of the Land Acquisition Act, followed by an Order under Section 38(a) of the same Act, published in the Government Gazette on 03 February 2000. The Petitioners-Appellants challenged this acquisition by filing three separate writ applications in the Court of Appeal in 2013, seeking writs of Certiorari to quash the Section 38(a) Order and writs of Mandamus to compel the divestment of the lands. The Court of Appeal dismissed all three applications, finding no merit in the arguments presented by the Petitioners-Appellants. The Petitioners-Appellants subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. During the appellate proceedings, the Petitioners-Appellants initially alleged that the acquisition was tainted with mala fides and discrimination but later retracted these submissions after considering additional material provided by the Respondents. The Supreme Court considered whether the Court of Appeal erred in its assessment of the necessity of proving mala fides, the disclosure of public purpose, and the existence of urgency under the Land Acquisition Act. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law by determining that it was necessary for the Petitioners to establish mala fides on the part of the Respondents. Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law in determining that the public purpose for the acquisition had been disclosed as required by law. Whether the Court of Appeal failed to take cognizance of the lack of urgency under Section 38(2) of the Land Acquisition Act, rendering the Section 38(a) Order ultra vires. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12, Article 126, Article 128(2) Land Acquisition Act, Section 2, Section 4, Section 17, Section 38(a), Section 38(2) Right to Information Act Cases Referred to: Manel Fernando v D.M. Jayarathne - [2000/v1-sri-lr-112] Joseph Fernando v Minister of Lands - [2003/v2-sri-lr-294] Mahinda Katugaha v Minister of Lands - [2008/v1-sri-lr-285] Kapugeekiyana v Hon Janaka Bandara Tennakone - [2013/v1-sri-lr-192] Seneviratne v Urban Council Kegalle - [2001/v3-sri-lr-105] Ponnamma v Arumugam - [8-nlr-223] Siththi Makeeena v Kuraisha - [2006/v2-sri-lr-341] Heather Therese Mundy v Central Enviornmental Authority - [sc-appeal-58-60/2003] Analysis Issue 1: Requirement to establish mala fides Rule applied: The court examined whether the burden of proof regarding mala fides was a prerequisite for the success of the writ applications. Court's reasoning: The Court found that the Court of Appeal did not hold that proving mala fides was a mandatory requirement for the Petitioners to succeed. Rather, the Court of Appeal observed that the Petitioners failed to substantiate their claims regarding the unsuitability of the land and the existence of malice. Furthermore, the Supreme Court noted that the Petitioners had abandoned their allegations of mala fides during the hearing. Finding: The Court of Appeal did not err; the issue is answered in the negative. Issue 2: Disclosure of public purpose Rule applied: Section 2 of the Land Acquisition Act. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the requirement to disclose a specific public purpose in a Section 2 notice is not a mandatory requirement applicable in all cases. The Court distinguished the present facts from Manel Fernando, noting that the Petitioners here were aware of the development project, and the acquisition was part of a long-standing urban development plan. The Court applied the principle that if no prejudice is caused by a technical defect, the court may exercise its discretion to refuse relief. Finding: The Court of Appeal did not err in distinguishing the facts and refusing the writs. Issue 3: Urgency under Section 38(a) Rule applied: Section 38(a) of the Land Acquisition Act regarding the urgency of land acquisition. Court's reasoning: The Court found that the delay in completing the project was largely attributable to the Petitioners' continued occupation and their engagement in protracted discussions. The Court held that the Petitioners could not rely on the authorities' concessions to remain in possession to argue that no urgency existed. Furthermore, the Court emphasized the public interest in completing the development project and the administrative burden of restarting the process. Finding: The Court of Appeal's refusal to grant the writs was justified given the public interest and the lack of prejudice to the Petitioners. Interaction of Issues The findings on these issues are interconnected through the court's exercise of discretionary remedial jurisdiction. The absence of mala fides, the lack of prejudice regarding the notice of public purpose, and the overriding public interest in the development project collectively support the court's decision to deny the discretionary remedies of certiorari and mandamus. Conclusion The appeals are dismissed. The Petitioners-Appellants are not precluded from pursuing compensation through the established legal mechanisms, as funds have been deposited in court. Keywords Land Acquisition Act — Public purpose — Mala fides — Urgency — Section 38(a) order — Writ of certiorari — Writ of mandamus — Judicial review — Administrative action		SC/APPEAL/15/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_15_2019.pdf
sc-fr-135-2017	28 September 2022	Santhi v. Mahinda and Others	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Illegal arrest — Reason for arrest — Police conduct — Raid — B Report — Contradictory statements — Fundamental rights violation	Facts The Petitioner, a 58-year-old woman, alleged that her fundamental rights were violated by the 1st to 3rd Respondents, who were officers of the Ambalangoda Police Station. The Petitioner claimed that on 24 June 2016, police officers forcibly entered her daughter's residence in Ahungalla while the occupants were away. Following this incident, the Petitioner lodged a complaint at the Police Headquarters. Subsequently, she was summoned to the office of the Senior Superintendent of Police in Elpitiya for an inquiry regarding her complaint. Upon arriving at the Senior Superintendent's office on 26 September 2016, the Petitioner and her son were informed that the officer was unavailable. As they exited the premises, the Petitioner was apprehended by a team of police officers, including the 2nd Respondent, and taken into custody. She was produced before the Magistrate of Balapitiya and remanded on charges related to the possession of heroin, allegedly recovered during a raid on her residence on 23 June 2016. The Petitioner remained in remand custody until 6 March 2017, when she was discharged after the Government Analyst reported that the substance seized did not contain dangerous drugs. The Petitioner contended that the Respondents fabricated the case against her and arrested her illegally in retaliation for her complaint. The Respondents maintained that the Petitioner was a known drug dealer who had fled during a lawful raid and was subsequently arrested on 26 September 2016. Issues Whether the 1st to 3rd Respondents violated the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution by fabricating charges and failing to provide equal protection of the law. Whether the 2nd and 3rd Respondents violated the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 13(1) of the Constitution by failing to follow the procedure established by law and failing to inform the Petitioner of the reasons for her arrest. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 13(1), 17, 126 Poisons, Opium and Dangerous Drugs Ordinance Cases Referred to: Kelum Dharsana Kumarasinghe v. S. Hettiarachchi - [2015/v3-sri-lr-387] Analysis Issue 1: Violation of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution, which guarantees equality before the law and equal protection of the law. Court's reasoning: The court found that the Respondents provided contradictory accounts regarding the raid and the subsequent arrest. The B-report filed by the 1st Respondent contained inconsistencies, and the Respondents failed to produce arrest notes or explain their authority to conduct a raid outside their jurisdiction in Ahungalla. The court noted that the Petitioner was discharged after the Government Analyst found no dangerous drugs, supporting the Petitioner's claim of fabricated charges. The failure of the 4th Respondent to address the Petitioner's initial complaint further demonstrated a lack of equal protection. Finding: The 1st, 2nd, and 3rd Respondents violated the Petitioner's rights under Article 12(1). Issue 2: Violation of Article 13(1) Rule applied: Article 13(1) of the Constitution, which mandates that no person shall be arrested except according to procedure established by law and must be informed of the reasons for the arrest. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the Petitioner was dragged into a jeep without being informed of the reasons for her arrest. The Respondents failed to produce any arrest notes to substantiate their claim that the arrest was conducted according to legal procedure. Furthermore, the Respondents did not establish that the Petitioner was evading arrest during the three months following the alleged raid. Finding: The 2nd and 3rd Respondents violated the Petitioner's rights under Article 13(1). Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing; the court's determination that the charges were fabricated (violating Article 12(1)) directly informs the conclusion that the arrest was not conducted according to a valid procedure established by law (violating Article 13(1)). The lack of transparency and the failure to produce contemporaneous records for both the raid and the arrest undermined the Respondents' credibility on both counts. Conclusion The application is allowed. The 1st Respondent is directed to pay Rs. 100,000, and the 2nd and 3rd Respondents are each directed to pay Rs. 200,000 to the Petitioner from their personal funds, with the State ordered to pay Rs. 50,000 as litigation costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Illegal arrest — Reason for arrest — Police conduct — Raid — B Report — Contradictory statements — Fundamental rights violation		SC/FR/135/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_135_2017.pdf
sc-fr-56-2018	28 September 2022	Nafees v. Kiriella and Others	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — University admission — G.C.E. (Advance Level) Examination — Suppression of facts — Misrepresentation of facts — Legitimate expectation — University Grants Commission — Admission guidelines — District of residence — School attendance	Facts The Petitioner, Muhammadu Nawfer Muhammad Nafees, sought relief for the alleged violation of his fundamental rights under Article 12(1) and 12(2) of the Constitution after the University Grants Commission (UGC) prevented him from applying for university admission for the 2017/2018 academic year. The Petitioner sat for the G.C.E. (Advanced Level) Examination in 2016 as a school candidate from A/Kahatagasdigiliya Muslim Maha Vidyalaya (MMV). Following an inquiry by the Department of Examinations into fraudulent school admissions in the North Central Province, the Petitioner's results were released without a District Rank. The Petitioner subsequently applied for university admission for the 2016/2017 academic year but did not register at any university. He then sat for the 2017 G.C.E. (Advanced Level) Examination as a private candidate from the Kurunegala District. When he attempted to apply for university admission for 2017/2018, the UGC system indicated he was ineligible under Clause 1.7 of the Admission Handbook. The UGC later determined that the Petitioner had provided false information regarding his school attendance at A/Kahatagasdigiliya MMV during his 2016 attempt. Consequently, the UGC cancelled his 2016/2017 application and barred him from future university admissions. The Petitioner challenged this decision, claiming his 2017 attempt should be considered independently. Issues Whether the Petitioner is guilty of suppressing or misrepresenting material facts regarding his school admission and attendance, thereby disentitling him to relief. Whether the UGCâ€™s decision to deny the Petitionerâ€™s application for university admission for the 2017/2018 academic year violated his fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the Petitioner held a legitimate expectation of university admission based on his 2017 examination results. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 12(2), 17, 126 University Act No. 16 of 1978 Cases Referred to: Jahangir Sheriffdeen v. Sandamali Aviruppola - [sc-fr-01/2015] T. M. Dingirimahathmaya v. H. Don Brampi Singho - [sc-appeal-145/2013] Amal Senevirathne v. Council of Legal Education - [sc-appeal-163/2015] Analysis Issue 1: Suppression of Material Facts Rule applied: The equitable maxim that one who comes to court must come with "clean hands" and provide full and frank disclosure of material facts. Court's reasoning: The Court found that the Petitioner failed to disclose that his admission to A/Kahatagasdigiliya MMV violated the Education Ministryâ€™s Circular 2008/17, as he did not meet the criteria for transferring to a school in a district with fewer facilities. Furthermore, he was silent regarding the inquiry into fraudulent school admissions and misrepresented his period of attendance at the school. The Court held that these omissions were material, as they directly related to the Petitioner's eligibility for university admission under the UGC guidelines. Finding: The Petitioner is guilty of suppression and misrepresentation of material facts. Issue 2: Violation of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Clause 1.7.9 of the University Admission Guidelines, which stipulates that making a false declaration or producing forged documents renders a candidate ineligible for admission. Court's reasoning: The UGC acted within its mandate to maintain academic standards. The Court noted that the UGC conducted multiple inquiries, sought clarifications from the 13th Respondent (Commissioner General of Examinations), and provided the Petitioner with an opportunity to show cause. The Petitioner failed to provide a valid response to the show cause notice. The UGCâ€™s decision to disqualify the Petitioner was a reasonable administrative action to prevent fraudulent applicants from depriving genuine students of university places. Finding: The UGCâ€™s conduct did not violate the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1). Issue 3: Legitimate Expectation Rule applied: The principle that legitimate expectation is subject to the rules and criteria set out in the governing admission handbook. Court's reasoning: The Petitioner argued that his 2017 attempt should be treated independently of his 2016 attempt. The Court rejected this, noting that the UGC guidelines do not permit the separation of attempts when an applicant has previously submitted false information. By signing the application for the 2016/2017 academic year, the Petitioner accepted the UGC's authority to reject applications containing false particulars. Finding: The Petitioner failed to establish a legitimate expectation of admission. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected: the Petitioner's suppression of facts (Issue 1) undermined his credibility and his claim to a legitimate expectation (Issue 3). Because the Petitioner was found to have provided false information, the UGCâ€™s decision to disqualify him was justified under the admission guidelines, thereby negating the claim that his fundamental rights were violated (Issue 2). Conclusion The Court held that the Petitioner suppressed material facts and failed to establish any violation of his fundamental rights. The application is dismissed without costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — University admission — G.C.E. (Advance Level) Examination — Suppression of facts — Misrepresentation of facts — Legitimate expectation — University Grants Commission — Admission guidelines — District of residence — School attendance		SC/APPEAL/56/2018	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_56_2018.pdf
sc-fr-13-2020	28 September 2022	Dilandi and Others v. Aviruppola and Others	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; P. Padman Surasena, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — School admission — Residency requirements — Circular interpretation — Agreement for houses purchased on instalment basis — Administrative action — Violation of fundamental rights	Facts The 1st Petitioner, a minor, and her mother, the 2nd Petitioner, applied for admission to Grade 1 of Visakha Vidyalaya for the 2020 academic year under the category of children of residents in close proximity to the school. The application was governed by Circular No. 29/2019, which required applicants to establish residency through specific documentation to earn marks. At the interview, the 2nd Petitioner was awarded 55 marks, falling short of the 62.40 cut-off mark. Specifically, the interview panel awarded only 5 marks for the main document submitted as proof of residence. The 2nd Petitioner challenged this allocation, asserting that the document provided, an agreement with the Urban Development Authority for the purchase of a housing unit on an installment basis, entitled her to full marks under Clause 7.2.1.1(f) of the circular. The Petitioner provided evidence that she had been allocated the housing unit in 2001 following the acquisition of her previous residence for a housing scheme. Despite submitting the sales agreement and subsequent confirmations from the National Housing Development Authority regarding her ownership and the legality of the agreement, the school authorities maintained that the document did not qualify for full marks. The Petitioner subsequently filed this fundamental rights application alleging a violation of Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the refusal of the Respondents to award full marks for the Petitioner's proof of residence under Clause 7.2.1.1(f) of Circular No. 29/2019 constituted a violation of the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the Respondents' reliance on post-argument submissions regarding a reassessment of marks by the Secretary to the Ministry of Education was legally permissible. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 17, 126. Prevention of Frauds Ordinance. Cases Referred to: T.G. Samadi Suharshana Ferdinandis v. Mrs. S. S. K. Aviruppola - [sc-appeal-117/2011] Analysis Issue 1: Allocation of marks for proof of residence Rule applied: Clause 7.2.1.1(f) of Circular No. 29/2019, which identifies "Agreements for houses purchased on instalment basis and payment receipts" as main documents in proof of residence entitled to full marks. Court's reasoning: The court examined the agreement (P9a) and supporting letters (P10a, P10b) from the National Housing Development Authority. The court found that the document clearly met the criteria of an agreement for a house purchased on an installment basis. The court rejected the Respondents' argument that the document was insufficient because it was not a registered deed, noting that the circular contained no such requirement. The court further held that the Petitioner's financial status, which necessitated the installment payment plan, should not be used to penalize her eligibility. Finding: The Petitioner was entitled to full marks for her proof of residence, which would have brought her total score to 70, exceeding the cut-off mark. The failure to award these marks was arbitrary and violated Article 12(1). Issue 2: Admissibility of post-argument submissions Rule applied: The principle that the court is not bound to act on material not submitted or available at the argument stage. Court's reasoning: The Respondents attempted to introduce a letter from the Secretary to the Ministry of Education (marked X) after the conclusion of arguments, suggesting a partial reassessment of marks. The court noted that this document was issued prior to the filing of the 1st Respondent's affidavit, yet the Respondent had taken a different position in that affidavit. The court refused to consider this new material as it was not part of the record during the hearing. Finding: The court declined to act on the letter marked X and disregarded the Respondents' late submissions regarding the reassessment of marks. Interaction of Issues The findings are intrinsically linked; the court's determination that the Petitioner was entitled to full marks under the circular (Issue 1) rendered the Respondents' attempt to introduce a partial, post-argument reassessment (Issue 2) both procedurally improper and substantively irrelevant to the final determination of the Petitioner's eligibility. Conclusion The court held that the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution were infringed. The court directed the 1st Respondent to admit the 1st Petitioner to Grade 1 or the appropriate grade of Visakha Vidyalaya. No order was made regarding costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — School admission — Residency requirements — Circular interpretation — Agreement for houses purchased on instalment basis — Administrative action — Violation of fundamental rights		SC/FR/13/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_13_2020.pdf
sc-appeal-15-2019	28 September 2022	M.S. Sithy Jawahira and Others v. Janaka Bandara Tennakoon and Others	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, CJ	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, CJ; S. Thurairaja, PC, J; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J	Land Acquisition Act — Writ of Certiorari — Public Purpose — Urgency — Mala Fides — Judicial Review — Compensation — Administrative Law — Article 12 of the Constitution — Right to Information Act — Urban Development Authority — Judicial Remedies — Discretionary Relief — Administrative Burden — Public Interest	Facts The present judgment concerns three appeals (SC Appeal 15/2019, 16/2019, and 17/2019) arising from a single judgment of the Court of Appeal regarding writ applications filed by the petitioners-appellants seeking to quash an order made by the Minister of Agriculture and Land under section 38(a) of the Land Acquisition Act. The order in question, dated 27 January 2000, was published in the Government Gazette on 3 February 2000 and pertained to the acquisition of fourteen lots of land for a public purpose, specifically for the development of the New Town in Karapitiya, Galle. The petitioners-appellants, who were in occupation of the lands, argued that the acquisition process was flawed due to the failure to disclose the public purpose in the notice issued under section 2 of the Land Acquisition Act, and they sought writs of Certiorari to quash the order and writs of Mandamus to compel the Minister to divest the lands. The Court of Appeal dismissed their applications, leading to the present appeals. The Supreme Court granted special leave to appeal on three questions of law: whether the Court of Appeal erred in requiring the petitioners to establish mala fides on the part of the respondents; whether the Court of Appeal erred in determining that the public purpose had been disclosed; and whether the Court of Appeal failed to recognize the lack of urgency in the order, rendering it ultra vires. Issues The issues before the Supreme Court can be framed as follows: 1. Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law in determining that it was necessary for the petitioners to establish mala fides on the part of the respondents? 2. Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law in determining that the public purpose has been disclosed as required under the law? 3. Whether the Court of Appeal failed to take cognizance of the fact that there was no urgency to making the said Order in terms of Section 38(2) of the Land Acquisition Act, and as such, the said Order is ultra vires? Applicable Law Statutes: Land Acquisition Act Cases Referred to: Manel Fernando and another v D.M. Jayarathne Minister of Agriculture and Lands and Others [2000] 1 SLR 112; Joseph Fernando v Minister of Lands [2003] 2 SLR 294; Mahinda Katugaha v Minister of Lands [2008] 1 SLR 285; Seneviratne and others v Urban Council Kegalle and others [2001] 3 SLR 105; Kapugeekiyana v Hon Janaka Bandara Tennakone, Minister of Lands and others [2013] 1 SLR 192; Heather Therese Mundy v Central Environmental Authority et al, SC Appeal 58-60/2003. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law in determining that it was necessary for the petitioners to establish mala fides on the part of the respondents? Rule applied: The principle of mala fides in administrative actions. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court examined the Court of Appeal's judgment and noted that the appellants had initially contended that the acquisition process was tainted with mala fides. However, during the proceedings, they abandoned this claim, indicating that the evidence did not support their assertion of discrimination or malice. The Court emphasized that the Court of Appeal did not impose a burden on the petitioners to prove mala fides as a prerequisite for success. The Court concluded that the Court of Appeal's approach was correct, as it focused on the factual context rather than requiring proof of mala fides. Finding: The Supreme Court found that the Court of Appeal did not err in its determination regarding mala fides. Issue 2: Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law in determining that the public purpose has been disclosed as required under the law? Rule applied: The requirement of disclosing public purpose in land acquisition notices. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court analyzed the notices issued under section 2 and section 38(a) of the Land Acquisition Act. It noted that while the specific public purpose was not explicitly stated in the section 2 notice, the context and subsequent actions indicated that the acquisition was for a genuine public purpose. The Court referenced the Manel Fernando case, which emphasized the need for public purpose disclosure but clarified that the absence of such disclosure does not automatically invalidate the acquisition if the purpose is known. The Court concluded that the Court of Appeal correctly distinguished the facts of the current case from those in Manel Fernando, where the acquisition was deemed arbitrary. Finding: The Supreme Court upheld the Court of Appeal's finding that the public purpose had been sufficiently disclosed. Issue 3: Whether the Court of Appeal failed to take cognizance of the fact that there was no urgency to making the said Order in terms of Section 38(2) of the Land Acquisition Act, and as such, the said Order is ultra vires? Rule applied: The urgency requirement in land acquisition processes. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court considered the timeline of events, noting that the petitioners had remained in possession of the lands for over two decades without vacating, despite the acquisition order. The Court highlighted that the petitioners had engaged in discussions with authorities regarding compensation and alternative accommodation, which indicated a level of acceptance of the acquisition process. The Court found that the petitioners could not now claim that urgency was lacking when they had not complied with the order to vacate. The Court also noted that the delay in the project was attributed to the petitioners' inaction. Finding: The Supreme Court concluded that the Court of Appeal did not err in its assessment of urgency. Interaction of Issues The issues are interrelated as they all stem from the legality and procedural correctness of the land acquisition process. The determination of mala fides impacts the perception of the acquisition's legitimacy, while the disclosure of public purpose and urgency are critical to the legality of the acquisition order. The Supreme Court's analysis demonstrated that the appellants' failure to substantiate their claims affected all three issues. Conclusion The Supreme Court dismissed all three appeals, affirming the Court of Appeal's judgment. The Court found no merit in the appellants' claims and emphasized the importance of adhering to legal procedures in land acquisition while balancing public interest and individual rights. The judgment underscored the need for clarity in administrative actions and the significance of timely compliance with legal orders. Keywords Land Acquisition Act — Writ of Certiorari — Public Purpose — Urgency — Mala Fides — Judicial Review — Compensation — Administrative Law — Article 12 of the Constitution — Right to Information Act — Urban Development Authority — Judicial Remedies — Discretionary Relief — Administrative Burden — Public Interest	Faiz Musthapha, PC with Rushdie Habeeb for Appellants. Manohara Jayasinghe, SSC for Respondent-Respondents.	SC/APPEAL/15/2019, SC/APPEAL/16/2019, SC/APPEAL/17/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_15_16_17_2019.pdf
sc-fr-109-2014	29 September 2022	Balamurali and Others v. Fernando and Others	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Legitimate expectation — Administrative action — Directive principles of state policy — Right to education — Best interests of the child — Upper Kotmale Hydro Power Project — Ceylon Electricity Board — School Development Society — Arbitrary action	Facts The Petitioners are members of the School Development Society of Talawakelle Tamil Maha Vidyalaya. The school was relocated due to the acquisition of its original land for the Upper Kothmale Hydro Power Project. The 1st and 2nd Respondents, representing the Ceylon Electricity Board, had initially agreed to construct specific infrastructure facilities for the new school premises, including an auditorium, as outlined in a document marked P-5. The Petitioners alleged that the 1st and 2nd Respondents failed to construct the auditorium as promised, opting instead to enter into a Memorandum of Understanding with a third party to share the facility. The Petitioners filed this application alleging that this failure and the deviation from the initial plan infringed upon their fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. The Respondents challenged the standing of the Petitioners and argued that the application was time-barred. Issues Whether the Petitioners have the legal standing to invoke the jurisdiction of the Supreme Court under Article 126 of the Constitution. Whether the actions of the 1st and 2nd Respondents constitute executive or administrative action subject to judicial review. Whether the failure of the 1st and 2nd Respondents to construct the auditorium as promised constitutes an infringement of the fundamental right to equality under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the application is time-barred under the rules governing fundamental rights applications. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka (Articles 4(d), 12(1), 17, 27(2)(g), 27(2)(h), 27(13), 126) Ceylon Electricity Board Act No. 29 of 1969 (Section 2(2), Section 8) International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR) Act No. 56 of 2007 (Section 5(2)) Cases Referred to: Kirahandi Yeshin Nanduja De Silva v. Sumith Parakramawansha - [sc-appeal-50/2015] Holidays (Amendment Bill) - [sc-sd-6-7/2019] Ajith P. Dharmasuriya v. Mahaweli Authority of Sri Lanka - [sc-fr-330/2015] Reinzie Perera v. University Grants Commission - [1978-79-80/v1-sri-lr-128] Wijethunga v. Insurance Corporation and Another - [1982/v1-sri-lr-1] Wickremesinghe v. Ceylon Petrolium Corporation and Others - [2001/v2-sri-lr-409] Kalidasage Roshan Chaminda v. Kurunegala Plantations Limited and Others - [sc-fr-24/2013] Dayaratne v. Minister of Health and Indigenous Medicine - [1999/v1-sri-lr-393] Ginigathgala Mohandiramlage Nimalsiri v. Colonel P.P.J. Fernando and Others - [sc-fr-256/2010] R.P Karunarathna Bandara v. P.B Disanayaka and Others - [sc-fr-356/2016] Analysis Issue 1: Legal Standing Rule applied: Article 17 and 126 of the Constitution; the doctrine of "sufficient interest" as established in Ajith P. Dharmasuriya v. Mahaweli Authority of Sri Lanka. Court's reasoning: The court held that parents and members of a School Development Society have a vested interest in the education and wellbeing of students. Given the state's constitutional obligation to promote the interests of children and ensure equal access to education, the Petitioners are not "meddlesome interlopers" but parties with sufficient interest to seek redress. Finding: The Petitioners have the legal standing to maintain the application. Issue 2: Executive or Administrative Action Rule applied: Article 126 of the Constitution; Section 2(2) and Section 8 of the Ceylon Electricity Board Act No. 29 of 1969; Reinzie Perera v. University Grants Commission. Court's reasoning: The 2nd Respondent is a body corporate created by statute, subject to ministerial control and direction. As an agency exercising governmental functions, its actions fall within the scope of "executive or administrative action." Finding: The actions of the 1st and 2nd Respondents are subject to the fundamental rights jurisdiction of the Supreme Court. Issue 3: Infringement of Article 12(1) Rule applied: The doctrine of Legitimate Expectation; the principle against "surrender, abdication and dictation" of discretionary power. Court's reasoning: The document P-5 created a legitimate expectation that the auditorium would be built. The Respondents' admission that they deviated from this plan due to political pressure (CWC intervention) constitutes an unlawful abdication of their discretionary power to an external authority. This arbitrary conduct violates the guarantee of equality. Finding: The 1st and 2nd Respondents infringed the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Article 12(1). Issue 4: Time Bar Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: The court found that the failure to construct the facility was a "continuing violation" as the project remained incomplete and discussions were ongoing well after the initial breach. Finding: The application is not time-barred. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected: the court's determination that the Respondents' actions were "executive" (Issue 2) allowed for the application of public law principles, specifically "legitimate expectation" (Issue 3). The finding that the Petitioners had standing (Issue 1) was reinforced by the court's emphasis on the constitutional duty to protect children's rights, which also informed the court's interpretation of the "continuing violation" regarding the time bar (Issue 4). Conclusion The Supreme Court held that the 1st and 2nd Respondents infringed the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. The 2nd Respondent is directed to construct the auditorium in accordance with the specifications in P-5, in consultation with the relevant stakeholders. The 1st Respondent is ordered to pay costs of Rs. 25,000 to each of the three Petitioners. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Legitimate expectation — Administrative action — Directive principles of state policy — Right to education — Best interests of the child — Upper Kotmale Hydro Power Project — Ceylon Electricity Board — School Development Society — Arbitrary action		SC/FR/109/2014	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_109_2014.pdf
sc-appeal-20-2021	29 September 2022	Officer-In-Charge, Special Crime Investigation Unit, Police Station, Moratuwa v. Dissanayake and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Criminal appeal — Conviction — Sentence — Suspension of sentence — First time offender — Mitigation of sentence — Settlement of dispute — District Court order — Dishonesty — Penal Code	Facts The Appellant, Rasika Deepal Bandara Dissanayake, was employed as a Debt Recovery Officer at Puwakaramba Agencies. He was accused of collecting Rs. 805,513 from debtors and failing to remit these funds to his employer. Consequently, a charge sheet was filed against him in the Magistrate Court of Moratuwa for offenses under Section 391 and Section 386 of the Penal Code. Following a trial, the Magistrate found the Appellant guilty on both counts and imposed a sentence of six months imprisonment and a fine of Rs. 1,500 for each count, along with an order for the payment of Rs. 100,000 as compensation to the complainant. The Appellant appealed the conviction and sentence to the High Court of Panadura, which affirmed the Magistrateâ€™s decision and dismissed the appeal. Subsequently, the Appellant sought and was granted special leave to appeal to the Supreme Court. During the proceedings before the Supreme Court, the Appellant produced evidence of a settlement reached in a related civil case, DMR/3534/18, at the District Court of Moratuwa, wherein he agreed to repay the outstanding funds to the complainant. The Appellant further submitted that he was a first-time offender and expressed remorse for his actions. Issues Whether the conviction of the Appellant under Section 391 and Section 386 of the Penal Code was justified. Whether the sentence imposed by the Magistrate, as affirmed by the High Court, warrants a reduction or suspension in light of the civil settlement and the Appellant's status as a first-time offender. Applicable Law Statutes: Penal Code Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Conviction Rule applied: Section 391 and Section 386 of the Penal Code. Court's reasoning: The Court reviewed the judgments of the Magistrate Court and the High Court alongside the circumstances of the case. Upon careful consideration of the evidence and the proceedings, the Court found no legal basis to interfere with the findings of guilt reached by the lower courts. Finding: The conviction of the Appellant is affirmed. Issue 2: Sentence Rule applied: General sentencing principles regarding mitigation and the effect of civil settlements on criminal liability. Court's reasoning: The Court took into account that the Appellant is a first-time offender who has expressed remorse. Furthermore, the Court considered the civil settlement reached in District Court case DMR/3534/18, where the Appellant committed to repaying the misappropriated funds. Given the restitution efforts, the Court determined that the original compensation order was redundant and that the custodial sentences should be suspended to allow for rehabilitation. Finding: The sentences for both counts are affirmed but suspended for a period of years, and the order for compensation is set aside. Interaction of Issues The affirmation of the conviction established the Appellant's criminal liability, which provided the context for the Court's exercise of discretion in sentencing. The resolution of the civil dispute regarding the repayment of funds directly influenced the Court's decision to set aside the compensation order and suspend the custodial sentences, as the civil settlement addressed the financial harm caused to the complainant. Conclusion The appeal is partly allowed. The conviction is affirmed, but the sentences of six months rigorous imprisonment for each count are suspended, and the order for compensation is set aside. Keywords Criminal appeal — Conviction — Sentence — Suspension of sentence — First time offender — Mitigation of sentence — Settlement of dispute — District Court order — Dishonesty — Penal Code		SC/APPEAL/20/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_20_2021.pdf
sc-appeal-44-2016	4 October 2022	Nawa Rajarata Appliances (Pvt) Ltd. and K.D.G.S. Wijeratne v. Commercial Bank of Ceylon PLC	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; P. Padman Surasena, J.; E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.	Recovery of Loans Act — Rescheduling of banking facilities — Acceptance of offer — Conduct of parties — Suppression of material facts — Interim injunction — Prima facie case — Balance of probability — Mortgage properties — Third party mortgages — Corporate veil	Facts The Plaintiffs, Nawa Rajarata Appliances (Pvt) Ltd. and its Managing Director K.D.G.S. Wijeratne, obtained various banking facilities from the Defendant, Commercial Bank of Ceylon PLC, secured by mortgage bonds. In December 2008, the Plaintiffs requested a rescheduling of these facilities. In February 2009, the Defendant bank granted the request, opened new term loan accounts, and released several mortgage bonds. The Plaintiffs subsequently defaulted on the rescheduled facilities. Following the default, the Defendant bank issued letters of demand and eventually passed a board resolution in May 2010 to sell the mortgaged properties under the Recovery of Loans by Bank (Special Provisions) Act. The Plaintiffs did not dispute the outstanding amounts or the rescheduling until August 2013, when they filed the instant action seeking to restrain the sale. The Plaintiffs alleged that they had not signed the offer letters for the rescheduling and that the bank had acted unilaterally. The High Court granted an interim injunction in favor of the Plaintiffs, concluding that there was no consensus between the parties due to the lack of signed offer letters. The Defendant bank appealed this order to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Plaintiffs accepted and benefited from the rescheduled banking facilities by their conduct, notwithstanding the absence of signed offer letters. Whether the Plaintiffs' failure to disclose material facts and their delay in challenging the rescheduling disentitled them to equitable relief in the form of an interim injunction. Applicable Law Statutes: Recovery of Loans by Bank (Special Provisions) Act No. 4 as amended Cases Referred to: Alphonso Appuhamy v. Hettiarachchi - [77-nlr-131] Hotel Galaxy (Pvt) Ltd. and others v. Mercantile Hotel Management Ltd. - [1987/v1-sri-lr-5] Walker sons and Company Ltd. v. Wijayasena - [1997/v1-sri-lr-293] Amarasakera v. Mitsui and Company Ltd. and another - [1993/v1-sri-lr-22] Yasodha Holdings (Pvt) Ltd. v. Peoples Bank - [1998/v3-sri-lr-382] Ramachandran and another, Ananda Siva and another v. Hatton National Bank and others - [2006/v1-sri-lr-293] Hatton National Bank Ltd. v. Jayawardene and others - [2007/v1-sri-lr-18] DFCC Bank v. Muditha Perera and others - [2014/v1-sri-lr-128] Nanayakkara v. Hatton National Bank Ltd. - [sc-appeal-53/2017] Analysis Issue 1: Acceptance by conduct Rule applied: The law of contract allows for acceptance of an offer to be manifested by conduct rather than express written consent. Court's reasoning: The court found that the Plaintiffs requested the rescheduling, received the benefits of the new term loans, and utilized those funds to clear previous debts. The Plaintiffs remained silent and did not dispute the rescheduling for several years, despite receiving bank statements and notices of demand. The court held that the Plaintiffs' conduct demonstrated acquiescence and acceptance of the new terms. Finding: The Plaintiffs accepted the rescheduled facilities by their conduct, and the High Courtâ€™s finding of a lack of consensus based solely on the absence of a signature was erroneous. Issue 2: Equitable relief and suppression of facts Rule applied: The principle that a party seeking an interim injunction must act in utmost good faith and disclose all material facts to the court. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the Plaintiffs suppressed the fact that the rescheduling was initiated by their own request and failed to disclose their long-term silence and receipt of benefits. The court emphasized that the High Court failed to evaluate the Defendant's objections and the evidence of the Plaintiffs' conduct. The court held that such suppression and the delay in seeking relief disentitle a party to equitable remedies. Finding: The Plaintiffs failed to establish a prima facie case or a balance of convenience in their favor, and their lack of good faith precluded the granting of an interim injunction. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are mutually reinforcing. The determination that the Plaintiffs accepted the contract by conduct undermines the basis for their claim of "no consensus." This, combined with the finding that the Plaintiffs suppressed material facts regarding their own request for rescheduling, confirms that the Plaintiffs lacked the clean hands required for equitable relief, thereby necessitating the dissolution of the injunction. Conclusion The appeal is allowed, and the High Court order dated 20th June 2014 is set aside. The interim injunction is dissolved, and the Plaintiffs are ordered to pay costs of Rs. 500,000 to the Appellant. Keywords Recovery of Loans Act — Rescheduling of banking facilities — Acceptance of offer — Conduct of parties — Suppression of material facts — Interim injunction — Prima facie case — Balance of probability — Mortgage properties — Third party mortgages — Corporate veil		SC/APPEAL/44/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_44_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-23-2019	5 October 2022	Mulafer v. Wijesingha and Fernando	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Prescriptive title — Adverse possession — Burden of proof — Uninterrupted possession — Licensee — Documentary title — Primary Courts Procedure Act — Evidence Ordinance — Immovable property — Paper title	Facts The Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent filed an action in the District Court of Kaduwela seeking a declaration of title to residential premises bearing assessment No. 9/D/193, Jayawadanagama, Battaramulla, along with the ejectment of the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Petitioner and damages. The property was initially vested with the National Housing Development Authority and subsequently transferred to a third party, then to the 2nd Defendant-Respondent-Respondent, and finally to the Plaintiff via Deed No. 16 dated 21/01/2008. The 1st Defendant, who is the sister-in-law of the 2nd Defendant, remained in occupation of the premises. The 1st Defendant claimed title to the property by way of prescription, asserting she had been in possession since 1993. The Plaintiff contended that the 1st Defendant was a licensee of the 2nd Defendant and therefore could not acquire prescriptive title. The District Court held that the 1st Defendant had established prescriptive title through over ten years of possession and improvements to the property. The High Court of Civil Appeal subsequently reversed this decision, finding that the 1st Defendant failed to prove adverse, undisturbed, and independent possession. The 1st Defendant appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Provincial High Court of Civil Appeal erred in law and fact in holding that the 1st Defendant failed to establish prescriptive title to the subject matter. Whether the Provincial High Court of Civil Appeal erred in fact in holding that the 1st Defendant was a licensee of the 2nd Defendant. Applicable Law Statutes: Prescription Ordinance (Section 3) Primary Courts Procedure Act (Section 66(6)) Evidence Ordinance (Section 3) Cases Referred to: Priyangika Perera v. Gunasiri Perera - [sc-appeal-59/2012] Juliana Hamine v. Don Thomas - [59-nlr-546] Alwis v. Perera - [21-nlr-326] Siman Appu v. Christian Appu - [1-nlr-288] D. R. Kiriamma v. J.A. Podibanda - [2005/blr-9] L. Edrick De Silva v. L. Chandradasa De Silva - [70-nlr-169] Chelliah v. Wijenathan - [54-nlr-337] Analysis Issue 1: Establishment of Prescriptive Title Rule applied: Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance, which requires proof of undisturbed and uninterrupted possession for ten years, adverse to or independent of the owner. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court found that the High Court of Civil Appeal misdirected itself by relying on documents (P6 and P9) related to settlement negotiations in the Primary Court to negate the 1st Defendant's animus possidendi. The Court noted that the 2nd Defendant was not the owner during the majority of the 1st Defendant's possession, and there was no evidence of interruption by the true owners. The 1st Defendant provided uncontradicted evidence of residence, electoral registration, and structural improvements. Finding: The 1st Defendant successfully established prescriptive title through continuous, adverse, and independent possession for over ten years. Issue 2: Status as Licensee Rule applied: The legal requirements for a leave and license agreement, which necessitate a subordinate character of possession derived from the owner's permission. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that the Plaintiff failed to provide evidence that the 1st Defendant entered the premises as a licensee of the 2nd Defendant. Furthermore, the 2nd Defendant never asserted that the 1st Defendant was his licensee. The High Court of Civil Appeal erroneously inferred a license from an affidavit filed by a third party (Ayarin Alawathi) which was not adopted by the Plaintiff to challenge the 1st Defendant's status. Finding: The High Court of Civil Appeal erred in fact; there was no evidence to support the finding that the 1st Defendant was a licensee. Interaction of Issues The findings are interdependent because the determination that the 1st Defendant was not a licensee (Issue 2) directly supports the conclusion that her possession was "independent" and "adverse" to the owner, which is a prerequisite for satisfying the requirements of Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance (Issue 1). Conclusion The Supreme Court answered both questions of law in the affirmative. The judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal dated 03/05/2018 is set aside, and the appeal is allowed. Keywords Prescriptive title — Adverse possession — Burden of proof — Uninterrupted possession — Licensee — Documentary title — Primary Courts Procedure Act — Evidence Ordinance — Immovable property — Paper title		SC/APPEAL/23/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_23_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-116-2020	6 October 2022	Amarasekera v. Perera and Others	Achala Wengappuli, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant (Plaintiff) instituted two separate actions in the District Court and Additional District Court of Negombo seeking a declaration of title to lots D3 and E and the eviction of the Defendant-Appellant-Respondent (Defendant). The Defendant claimed title to these lots through prescription, asserting he had possessed the land as one contiguous property since 1954. The land was originally part of a larger allotment partitioned in 1954 and subsequently subdivided in 1967, at which time the Defendantâ€™s father gifted the subdivided lots to his three children. The Defendant received lot D2, while his sisters Juliet and Lilian received lots D1, D3, and E. Juliet Perera eventually transferred her title to these lots to third parties, from whom the Plaintiff ultimately acquired title. The trial courts rejected the Defendantâ€™s prescriptive claim, finding he failed to establish adverse possession. The High Court of Civil Appeal (HCCA) reversed these judgments, concluding that the Defendant had established prescriptive title by commencing adverse possession in 1988 against a third-party purchaser. The Plaintiff appealed to the Supreme Court, which granted leave to determine whether the HCCA erred in failing to appreciate that the Defendant failed to show an overt act or adverse possession against the Plaintiffâ€™s predecessors during the relevant period. Issues Whether the Defendantâ€™s possession of the disputed lots was permissive in nature, originating from a familial arrangement, thereby precluding a claim of adverse possession under Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance. Whether the Defendant established an "overt act" sufficient to transform his permissive possession into adverse possession against the true owners. Whether the Defendant established an uninterrupted period of ten years of adverse possession as required by Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance. Applicable Law Statutes: Prescription Ordinance No. 22 of 1871, Section 3 Civil Procedure Code, Section 328 Cases Referred to: Gunawardene v Samarakoon - [60-nlr-481] Chelliah v Wijenathan - [54-nlr-337] Sirajudeen v Abbas - [1994/v2-sri-lr-365] Maduwanwela v Ekneligoda - [3-nlr-213] Abdul Majeed v Ummu Zaneera - [61-nlr-361] Hussaima v Ummu Zaneera - [65-nlr-125] De Silva v Commissioner General of Inland Revenue - [80-nlr-292] Jayasinghe Pathman v Somapala - [sc-appeal-6/14] Appu Naide v Heen Menika - [51-nlr-63] De Bussche v. Alt - [1878-l-r-8-ch-d-286] Perera v Perera - [2-nlr-370] Errington v Errington and Woods - [1952-1-kb-290] Swami Sivgnananda v The Bishop of Kandy - [55-nlr-130] Nauda Marikkar v Mohammadu - [7-nlr-91] Corea v Iseris Appuhamy - [15-nlr-65] Chaminda Abeykoon v Anthony Fernando - [sc-appeal-54a/2008] Tillekeratne v Bastian - [21-nlr-12] Odiris v Mendis - [13-nlr-309] Rajapakse v Hendrick Singho - [61-nlr-32] Angela Fernando v Devadeepthi Fernando - [2006/v2-sri-lr-188] Alwis v Perera - [21-nlr-321] Cadija Umma v Don Manis Appu - [40-nlr-392] Karunawathie v Gunadasa - [1996/v2-sri-lr-246] Kirihamy Muhandirama v Dingiri Appu - [6-nlr-197] Piyenis v Pedro - [3-scc-125] Hassan v Romanishamy - [66-clw-112] Juliana Hamine v Don Thomas - [59-nlr-546] Dias Abeysinghe v Dias Abeysinghe - [34-clw-60] Simpson v Lebbe - [48-nlr-112] Gunasekera v Tissera - [1994/v3-sri-lr-245] Analysis Issue 1: Nature of Possession Rule applied: Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance; the principle that possession by a family member is presumed permissive unless proven otherwise. Court's reasoning: The court found that the Defendantâ€™s possession originated from his fatherâ€™s request to "look after" the property for his sisters. The court held that this familial arrangement created a permissive, subordinate character of possession. The Defendant failed to provide evidence that this character changed after his father's death in 1969. Finding: The Defendantâ€™s possession was permissive, not adverse. Issue 2: Requirement of Overt Act Rule applied: The principle that a licensee or co-owner must perform an "overt act" to manifest an intention to possess adversely, as established in Corea v Iseris Appuhamy and Chaminda Abeykoon v Anthony Fernando. Court's reasoning: The court determined that the Defendantâ€™s act of collecting rent and instituting eviction proceedings against a tenant did not constitute an overt act of ouster against his sisters. These actions were consistent with his role as a manager of the property. There was no evidence that the sisters were notified of a change in the character of his possession. Finding: No overt act was established to convert permissive possession into adverse possession. Issue 3: Uninterrupted Period of Possession Rule applied: Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance, requiring ten years of uninterrupted adverse possession. Court's reasoning: The court found that even if the period from 1988 were considered, the Defendantâ€™s possession was repeatedly interrupted by the activities of the Plaintiff and her predecessors, such as the construction of a parapet wall and other improvements by Gamini Ponweera. The court rejected the HCCAâ€™s hypothetical reasoning that the Defendant could have succeeded in a Section 328 inquiry. Finding: The Defendant failed to prove an uninterrupted ten-year period of adverse possession. Interaction of Issues The findings are interdependent: because the possession was initially permissive (Issue 1), the requirement for an overt act (Issue 2) became a strict legal necessity. The failure to prove an overt act meant the possession never legally transformed into adverse possession, which in turn rendered the claim of an uninterrupted ten-year period (Issue 3) legally impossible to satisfy. Conclusion The Supreme Court allowed the appeals, set aside the judgments of the High Court of Civil Appeal, and restored the judgments of the District Court and Additional District Court in favor of the Plaintiff. The Defendantâ€™s claim of prescriptive title was dismissed. Keywords Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser		SC/APPEAL/116/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_116_2020.pdf
sc-appeal-117-2020	6 October 2022	Amarasekera v. Perera and Others	Achala Wengappuli, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant (Plaintiff) instituted two separate actions in the District Court and Additional District Court of Negombo seeking a declaration of title to lots D3 and E and the eviction of the Defendant-Appellant-Respondent (Defendant). The Defendant, the eldest brother of the Plaintiff's predecessor in title, claimed prescriptive title to the lots, asserting he had possessed the land as a contiguous unit since 1954. The trial courts rejected the Defendant's claim of prescription and held in favor of the Plaintiff. The High Court of Civil Appeal (HCCA) subsequently allowed the Defendant's appeals, finding that he had established prescriptive title against a third-party purchaser, Dinapala de Silva, starting from 1988. The Plaintiff appealed to the Supreme Court. The evidence established that the land was subdivided in 1967 and gifted to the Defendant and his two sisters. The Defendant admitted he was entrusted by his father to look after the property. The Plaintiff's predecessors in title, the Defendant's sisters, had alienated the property to third parties on multiple occasions. The Defendant had previously instituted eviction proceedings against a tenant, Simion Perera, in 1985, which resulted in various legal proceedings and evictions, including the eviction of the Plaintiff and her predecessor in 1999. Issues Whether the learned Judges of the HCCA erred in law in failing to appreciate that the Defendant failed to show an overt act or adverse possession against the Plaintiff's predecessors during the period 1969-1994. Whether the Defendant established the requirements for prescriptive title under Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance. Applicable Law Statutes: Prescription Ordinance No. 22 of 1871, Section 3 Civil Procedure Code, Section 328 Cases Referred to: Gunawardene v Samarakoon - [60-nlr-481] Chelliah v Wijenathan - [54-nlr-337] Sirajudeen v Abbas - [1994/v2-sri-lr-365] Maduwanwela v Ekneligoda - [3-nlr-213] Abdul Majeed v Ummu Zaneera - [61-nlr-361] Hussaima v Ummu Zaneera - [65-nlr-125] De Silva v Commissioner General of Inland Revenue - [80-nlr-292] Jayasinghe Pathman v Somapala - [sc-appeal-6/14] Appu Naide v Heen Menika - [51-nlr-63] De Bussche v Alt - [L. R. 8 Ch. D. 286] Perera v Perera - [2-nlr-370] Errington v Errington and Woods - [1952/v1-kb-290] Swami Sivgnananda v The Bishop of Kandy - [55-nlr-130] Nauda Marikkar v Mohammadu - [7-nlr-91] Corea v Iseris Appuhamy - [15-nlr-65] Chaminda Abeykoon v Anthony Fernando - [sc-appeal-54a/2008] Odiris v Mendis - [13-nlr-309] Rajapakse v Hendrick Singho - [61-nlr-32] Angela Fernando v Devadeepthi Fernando - [2006/v2-sri-lr-188] Tillekeratne v Bastian - [21-nlr-12] Mac Clung v Ross - [5-wheaton-116] Alwis v Perera - [21-nlr-321] Cadija Umma v Don Manis Appu - [40-nlr-392] Karunawathie v Gunadasa - [1996/v2-sri-lr-246] Kirihamy Muhandirama v Dingiri Appu - [6-nlr-197] Piyenis v Pedro - [3-scc-125] Hassan v Romanishamy - [66-clw-112] Juliana Hamine v Don Thomas - [59-nlr-546] Dias Abeysinghe v Dias Abeysinghe - [34-clw-60] Simpson v Lebbe - [48-nlr-112] Gunasekera v Tissera - [1994/v3-sri-lr-245] Analysis Issue 1: Overt act and adverse possession Rule applied: Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance; principle that a licensee or co-owner must perform an overt act to convert permissive possession into adverse possession. Court's reasoning: The court found that the Defendant's possession was initially permissive, as he was entrusted by his father to manage the property for his sisters. The Defendant failed to demonstrate any overt act that would have put his sisters on notice that his possession had become adverse. The court emphasized that family relationships and social customs often explain why a family member might enjoy the income of a property without it constituting adverse possession. Finding: The Defendant failed to show an overt act or adverse possession against the Plaintiff's predecessors. Issue 2: Requirements for prescriptive title Rule applied: Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance; requirement of uninterrupted adverse possession for ten years. Court's reasoning: The court determined that the Defendant failed to establish a continuous ten-year period of adverse possession. The evidence showed that the Plaintiff and her predecessors exercised acts of ownership, such as clearing the land and installing gates, which interrupted the Defendant's alleged possession. The court rejected the HCCA's reliance on a hypothetical scenario regarding the Defendant's ability to succeed in a Section 328 inquiry. Finding: The Defendant failed to satisfy the requirements for prescriptive title. Interaction of Issues The failure to establish an overt act (Issue 1) directly undermined the Defendant's claim of adverse possession (Issue 2). Because the possession was permissive, it could not be considered "adverse" under Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance without a clear change in character, which the Defendant failed to prove. Conclusion The appeals of the Plaintiff are allowed. The judgments of the HCCA are set aside, and the judgments of the District Court and Additional District Court of Negombo are restored and affirmed. Keywords Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser		SC/APPEAL/117/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_117_2020.pdf
sc-fr-195-2022	6 October 2022	Samarakoon and Others v. Wickremesinghe and Others	Not specified	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J; Buwaneka Aluwihare, J.; Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Violation of fundamental rights — Central Bank of Sri Lanka — Monetary Board — International Sovereign Bond — Exchange rate — Financial management — Public debt control — Audit report	Facts The Petitioners in these consolidated fundamental rights applications, including Dr. Athulasiri Kumara Samarakoon, Soosaiappu Neavis Morais, Dr. Mahim Mendis, Chandra Jayaratne, Julian Bolling, Jehan CanagaRetna, and Transparency International Sri Lanka, challenged various economic and financial decisions made by state officials and the Monetary Board of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka. The respondents included former Cabinet Ministers, former Governors of the Central Bank, and members of the Monetary Board. The applications alleged that the respondents' actions, including the artificial maintenance of the Sri Lankan Rupee exchange rate, the delay in seeking financial assistance from the International Monetary Fund, and the settlement of International Sovereign Bonds using foreign reserves, violated fundamental rights. The Court considered these matters over several hearing dates and determined that the applications warranted further judicial inquiry. Issues Whether the Petitioners have established a prima facie case for the violation of fundamental rights guaranteed under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution to warrant granting leave to proceed. Whether the Court should exercise its power to direct the Auditor General and the Monetary Board to produce specific documents and reports to facilitate the adjudication of the alleged fundamental rights violations. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 14(1)(g), 126(2) Monetary Law Act No. 37 of 1950, Sections 64, 68 Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Granting of leave to proceed Rule applied: Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka. Court's reasoning: The Court evaluated the petitions and the submissions of the parties regarding the economic management of the country. Upon consideration of the allegations concerning the conduct of the respondents in their official capacities, the Court determined that the Petitioners had sufficiently demonstrated grounds to warrant a full hearing on the merits regarding the alleged violations of the right to equality and the freedom to engage in a lawful occupation. Finding: The Court granted leave to proceed against the specified respondents in both applications. Issue 2: Production of documents and audit reports Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution and Sections 64 and 68 of the Monetary Law Act No. 37 of 1950. Court's reasoning: To effectively adjudicate the claims, the Court required objective evidence regarding the decision-making processes of the Monetary Board and the Central Bank. The Court ordered the Auditor General to conduct a specific audit into the exchange rate policy, the delay in seeking IMF assistance, and the settlement of sovereign bonds. Furthermore, the Court ordered the Monetary Board and the Governor of the Central Bank to produce internal communications and reports relevant to these decisions to ensure transparency and provide the Court with the necessary factual basis for its final determination. Finding: The Court issued specific directions for the production of documents and the conduct of an audit by the Auditor General. Interaction of Issues The findings are intrinsically linked; the decision to grant leave to proceed necessitates the production of evidence to determine the merits of the alleged constitutional violations. By ordering the audit and the production of internal documents, the Court ensures that the subsequent hearing on the merits is informed by the relevant administrative and financial records, thereby reinforcing the judicial process initiated by granting leave. Conclusion The Court granted leave to proceed in both applications for alleged violations of Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. The Court issued comprehensive directions for the production of documents and the preparation of an audit report by the Auditor General, with the matters to be mentioned on 09th January 2023 for further directions. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Violation of fundamental rights — Central Bank of Sri Lanka — Monetary Board — International Sovereign Bond — Exchange rate — Financial management — Public debt control — Audit report			
sc-appeal-103-2018	06 October 2022	Thiremuni Peter v. A. S. Jayawardene and Others	K.K. Wickremasinghe, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; K.K. Wickremasinghe, J.; Janak De Silva, J.	Civil Procedure Code — Appeal — Written Objections — Cross Objections — Directors — Articles of Association — Judicial Precedents — Inherent Jurisdiction — Exceptional Circumstances — Lawfulness of Termination — Compensation	Facts The case revolves around an appeal from the judgment of the Court of Appeal dated 15 February 2017, which dismissed the action filed by Thiremuni Peter (the Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant) against the original Defendants, A. S. Jayawardene and Daya Liyanage, who were the Secretary and Deputy Secretary to the Treasury, respectively. The Plaintiff was appointed as the Executive Director of the 3rd Defendant-Respondent Company, Seemasahitha Wennappuwa Janatha Santhaka Pravahana Sevaya, by letters dated 27 June 1991 and 29 June 1991. Subsequently, the original Defendants removed the Plaintiff from his position and appointed others as Directors. The Plaintiff filed an action in the District Court of Colombo seeking a declaration that his removal was illegal and claiming Rs. 500,000 as compensation for damages. The District Court ruled in favor of the Plaintiff, awarding him Rs. 200,000 in damages. The original Defendants appealed to the Court of Appeal, while the 3rd Defendant did not appeal. During the appeal, the 3rd Defendant was substituted by the Sri Lanka Transport Board. The Court of Appeal dismissed the Plaintiff's action, stating that the District Judge had misapplied the Articles of Association and that the termination was lawful. The Plaintiff then sought Special Leave to Appeal to the Supreme Court, which focused on whether the Court of Appeal erred in dismissing the case without the 3rd Defendant having filed an appeal. Issues The primary issue is whether the Court of Appeal could dismiss the District Court's judgment against the predecessor of the Substituted 3rd Defendant-Respondent, given that the latter did not appeal against the judgment. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code, Section 772; Conversion of Public Corporations or Government Owned Business Undertakings into Public Companies Act No. 23 of 1987. Cases Referred to: Rabot v. De Silva - [1905] 8 NLR 82; Ratwatte v. Goonesekera - [1987] 2 Sri LR 260; Parana Mannalage Amara Wijesinghe and others v. Sudu Hakurage Swarnalatha and others - SC Appeal No. 72/2012; Mendis v. Seema Sahitha Panadura Janatha Santhaka Pravahana Sevaya and Others - [1995] (2) Sri LR 284; Mahant Dhangir and another v. Madan Mohan and others - AIR 1988 SC 54; Doloswela Rubber & Tea Estate Co. v. Swaris Appu - 31 NLR 60; Syed Mohammad Hasan v. Syed Mohammad Hamid Hasan And Ors. - AIR 1946 All 395; (Mirza) Husain Yar Beg v. (Sahu) Radha Kishan And Ors. - AIR 1935 All 134. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the Court of Appeal erred in dismissing the case filed by the Plaintiff before the District Court as regard to the Substituted 3rd Defendant-Respondent-Respondent whereas he had not appealed against the judgment of the learned District Judge to the Court of Appeal? Rule applied: Section 772 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court examined whether a party can object to a lower court's judgment without having filed an appeal. The Court noted that Section 772 allows a respondent to support a decree or take objections, provided they give notice. The Appellant argued that the 3rd Respondent had accepted the District Court's judgment by not appealing or filing objections. The Court referenced previous cases, including Rabot v. De Silva, which allowed parties to challenge a decision even without an appeal. The Court also discussed the inherent jurisdiction of the appellate court to permit objections in the interest of justice, as noted in Ratwatte v. Goonesekera. The Court concluded that the 3rd Respondent could invoke objections against the Plaintiff-Respondent despite not appealing, as the circumstances warranted such an exception. Finding: The Court found that the 3rd Respondent could lawfully object to the judgment, and thus the Court of Appeal's dismissal was justified. Interaction of Issues The issues are interrelated as they revolve around the procedural rights of parties in an appeal and the interpretation of Section 772. The Court's analysis of whether the 3rd Respondent could object without an appeal directly impacts the validity of the Court of Appeal's decision. Conclusion The Supreme Court upheld the Court of Appeal's decision to dismiss the Plaintiff's case, affirming that the 3rd Respondent could lawfully challenge the District Court's judgment despite not having filed an appeal. The appeal was dismissed, and the original judgment was upheld, reinforcing the principles of procedural law and the rights of parties in civil litigation. Keywords Civil Procedure Code — Appeal — Written Objections — Cross Objections — Directors — Articles of Association — Judicial Precedents — Inherent Jurisdiction — Exceptional Circumstances — Lawfulness of Termination — Compensation	Chula Bandara for the Plaintiff-Respondent-Appellant; Ranjith Ranawake with Ravinath Ranawake instructed by Ms. Kosala Perera for the Substituted 3rd Defendant-Respondent-Respondent.	SC/APPEAL/103/2018	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_103_2018.pdf
sc-fr-139-2012	12 October 2022	Karunaratne and Others v. Koswatte and Others	Aluwihare, PC, J	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC, J; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Corporal punishment — Violation of fundamental rights — Torture — Cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment — School discipline — Circular No. 2005/17 — UN Convention on the Rights of the Child — Physical violence — Mental trauma	Facts The 1st and 2nd Petitioners were minor students at Veera Keppetipola Madya Maha Vidyalaya. On 24th October 2011, the 1st Respondent, who was the Deputy Principal, investigated damage caused to glass panes in the school dining hall after stones were pelted at a mango tree. The 1st Respondent apprehended several students, including the Petitioners, and summoned them to his office. Upon arrival at the office, the 1st Respondent subjected the Petitioners to severe corporal punishment by caning them on their buttocks, chests, and shoulders. The 1st Respondent admitted to caning the students but claimed it was a disciplinary measure taken in good faith. The Petitioners suffered multiple contusions and abrasions, requiring in-house medical treatment at the District Hospital, Matale. The 1st Petitioner was also treated for anxiety and adjustment disorder. Medical reports confirmed that the injuries were consistent with being struck by a linear rigid weapon. The Petitioners filed this application alleging that the 1st Respondentâ€™s actions violated their fundamental rights under Articles 11 and 12(1) of the Constitution. Although the Petitioners initially complained of inaction by the 3rd Respondent, they withdrew their claims against him during the hearing after learning that legal action had been initiated in the Magistrate's Court. Issues Whether the corporal punishment inflicted by the 1st Respondent violated the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the corporal punishment inflicted by the 1st Respondent constituted torture or cruel, inhuman, or degrading treatment in violation of Article 11 of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 11, 12(1), 17, 126 Penal Code, Section 308A Cases Referred to: Reddiar v. Van Houten - [1988/v1-sri-lr-265] Bandara v. Wickremasinghe - [1995/v2-sri-lr-167] Lister v. Hesley Hall - [2002/1-ac-215] Wijesinghe Chulangani v. Waruni Bogahawatte - [sc-fr-app-677/2012] Analysis Issue 1: Violation of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Ministry of Education Circular No. 2005/17 dated 11th May 2005. Court's reasoning: The Circular imposes a total prohibition on corporal punishment in government schools. The court noted that the violation of a circular applicable to a citizen amounts to a violation of Article 12(1). The 1st Respondent admitted to caning the students, which directly contravened the explicit prohibition in the Circular. His justification that he acted in good faith to maintain discipline was rejected, as the Circular provides specific alternative, non-violent methods for discipline. Finding: The 1st Respondentâ€™s actions violated the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Article 12(1). Issue 2: Violation of Article 11 Rule applied: Article 11 of the Constitution and the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child (UNCRC). Court's reasoning: The court emphasized that children are a vulnerable category requiring higher protection. While Article 11 requires a high degree of maltreatment, the court held that this threshold must be viewed through the lens of a child's mental and physical development. The medical evidence established that the assault was violent and caused significant physical and mental trauma. The 1st Respondent acted under the color of office, and the state is vicariously liable for his unauthorized, intentional wrongdoing because the assault occurred within the scope of his employment duties. Finding: The 1st Respondentâ€™s actions constituted cruel, inhuman, and degrading treatment in violation of Article 11. Interaction of Issues The findings are reinforcing; the violation of the administrative Circular (Article 12(1)) establishes the illegality of the 1st Respondent's conduct, while the severity of the physical and mental harm inflicted confirms that the conduct crossed the threshold into prohibited torture or cruel, inhuman, and degrading treatment (Article 11). Conclusion The application is allowed. The 1st Respondent is ordered to pay Rs. 75,000 to each Petitioner, and the State is ordered to pay Rs. 25,000 to each Petitioner as compensation. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Corporal punishment — Violation of fundamental rights — Torture — Cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment — School discipline — Circular No. 2005/17 — UN Convention on the Rights of the Child — Physical violence — Mental trauma		SC/FR/139/2012	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_139_2012.pdf
sc-fr-13-2019	17 October 2022	Wijesundara v. Sirirwardena and Others	P. Padman Surasena, J.	Vijith K. Malalgoda, PC, J.; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; P. Padman Surasena, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Incorporation of companies — Legal professional services — Attorneys-at-law — Practice of law — Corporate entities — Judicial power — Bar Association of Sri Lanka	Facts The Petitioner, an Attorney-at-Law, challenged the administrative action of the 1st Respondent, the Registrar General of Companies, in incorporating the 2nd Respondent, Baqian Law Group Lanka (Pvt) Ltd., as a limited liability company. The Petitioner contended that the 2nd Respondent was incorporated for the unlawful purpose of providing legal professional services in Sri Lanka, which is a practice reserved exclusively for natural persons admitted and enrolled as Attorneys-at-Law by the Supreme Court. The Petitioner further alleged that the 1st Respondent failed to investigate the 2nd Respondent in terms of the Companies Act No. 07 of 2007. The 2nd Respondent was incorporated on 19th November 2018 with the stated objective of providing investment advisory services and consultations. However, the Petitioner produced evidence, including newspaper articles, suggesting the company intended to provide legal services. The Bar Association of Sri Lanka (BASL) intervened in the proceedings, arguing that the incorporation of a corporate entity to practice law violates the regulatory framework governing the legal profession and discriminates against individual practitioners. The 2nd Respondent denied an intent to practice law in courts but maintained its right to provide advisory services. The Court rejected the affidavit submitted on behalf of the 2nd Respondent due to a lack of authorization by the affirmant. Issues Whether the incorporation of the 2nd Respondent as a limited liability company for the purpose of providing legal services violates the laws of Sri Lanka and the Constitution. Whether the 1st Respondentâ€™s failure to act under Section 173(1)(b) of the Companies Act No. 07 of 2007 constitutes an infringement of the Petitionerâ€™s fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 4(c), 10, 12(1), 12(2), 14(1)(g), 105(1), 105(2), 126, 136(1)(g) Judicature Act No. 02 of 1978, Sections 40(1), 41, 42, 43 Companies Act No. 07 of 2007, Section 173(1)(b) Arbitration Act No. 11 of 1995 Intellectual Property Act No. 36 of 2003 Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Legality of corporate legal practice Rule applied: Article 136(1)(g) of the Constitution; Rules 67, 68, 69, and 70 of the Supreme Court Rules 1978; Sections 40, 41, and 42 of the Judicature Act No. 02 of 1978. Court's reasoning: The Court reasoned that the legal profession is a sine qua non for the administration of justice and is strictly regulated by the Supreme Court. The statutory framework, particularly Rule 70 of the Supreme Court Rules, restricts the practice of law—including advising clients and acting in legal matters—to natural persons who have been duly admitted and enrolled as Attorneys-at-Law. The Court held that legal practice is a personal privilege requiring individual accountability, which cannot be subsumed under a corporate veil. Since the 2nd Respondent failed to substantiate its claims regarding its business scope and the evidence (P4 and P5) confirmed its intent to provide legal services, the Court found the company's objective to be illegal. Finding: The 2nd Respondent is not entitled in law to engage in any legal professional work in Sri Lanka. Issue 2: Infringement of fundamental rights Rule applied: Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Court's reasoning: The Court determined that by incorporating a company with the primary objective of practicing law, the 1st Respondent acted in violation of the law. This action created a situation where non-lawyers or corporate entities could perform legal services without being subject to the Supreme Courtâ€™s disciplinary jurisdiction. This placed individual Attorneys-at-Law at a disadvantage and denied the public the protection afforded by the regulated legal profession, thereby infringing the Petitionerâ€™s rights to equal protection of the law and the freedom to engage in a lawful profession. Finding: The 1st Respondentâ€™s actions infringed the Petitionerâ€™s fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g). Interaction of Issues The findings are intrinsically linked; the illegality of the 2nd Respondentâ€™s corporate objective (Issue 1) serves as the factual basis for the finding that the 1st Respondentâ€™s administrative action resulted in a constitutional violation (Issue 2). The Courtâ€™s determination that the legal profession must be restricted to natural persons to ensure disciplinary control reinforces the conclusion that the stateâ€™s failure to prevent the incorporation of a "law firm" company directly undermines the constitutional rights of the legal profession and the public. Conclusion The Court held that the incorporation of the 2nd Respondent for the purpose of providing legal services was unlawful and infringed the Petitionerâ€™s fundamental rights. The Court directed the 1st Respondent to take all necessary steps according to law to give effect to these conclusions. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Incorporation of companies — Legal professional services — Attorneys-at-law — Practice of law — Corporate entities — Judicial power — Bar Association of Sri Lanka		SC/FR/13/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_13_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-128-2019	27 October 2022	W. R. M. Sumanathissa Bandara and Others v. B. A. H. M. Balasuriya	K. Kumudini Wickremasinghe, J.	Murdu N. B. Fernando, P.C., J.; K. Kumudini Wickremasinghe, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Food Act — prosecution time bar — fair trial — statutory interpretation — nullum tempus occurrit regi — vigilantibus et non dormientibus — criminal justice — evidence — procedural irregularity — acquittal — public health — consumer protection — legal principles — judicial discretion — rights of the accused	Facts The case revolves around an appeal by the 3rd Accused-Appellant, Coca-Cola Beverages Sri Lanka, against a conviction and sentence imposed by the Magistrate's Court of Kurunegala for selling a contaminated product, Fanta Cream Soda. The complaint was lodged by a Public Health Inspector, B. A. H. M. Balasuriya, after a consumer reported finding impurities in the drink. The consumer purchased the drink on 10 February 2011 but only reported the issue on 24 May 2011, which is over three months later. The prosecution was initiated on 27 May 2011, leading to charges under the Food Act for selling unfit food. The Magistrate acquitted the second accused but convicted the first and third accused, imposing a fine. The High Court upheld this decision, prompting the appeal to the Supreme Court. The central issue was whether the prosecution was time-barred under Section 20(1)(b) of the Food Act, which mandates that prosecutions must be initiated within three months of the detection of the offence. Issues Whether the prosecution against the 3rd Accused-Appellant was time-barred under Section 20(1)(b) of the Food Act. Whether the interpretation of 'detection' in the context of the Food Act should include the date of the consumer's complaint or the date of the actual purchase. Applicable Law Statutes: Food Act, No. 26 of 1980; Food (Amendment) Act, No. 20 of 1991; Code of Criminal Procedure Act, No. 15 of 1979. Cases Referred to: Raja Nanayakkara vs. Mercy Jayasinghe and Others - [2004 2 Sri L.R. 416]; Attorney General vs. Wilson and others - [1997 2 Sri L.R. 349]; Japani Sahoo vs. Chandra Sekhar Mohanty - [AIR 2007 SC 2762]; State of Punjab v. Sarwan Singh - [AIR 1981 SC 1054]. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the prosecution against the 3rd Accused-Appellant was time-barred under Section 20(1)(b) of the Food Act. Rule applied: Section 20(1)(b) of the Food Act, which stipulates that prosecution must be initiated within three months from the date of detection of the offence. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court analyzed the timeline of events leading to the prosecution. The Court noted that the consumer detected the alleged offence on 10 February 2011 but did not report it until 24 May 2011, which is beyond the three-month limit set by the Food Act. The Court emphasized that the term 'detection' should be interpreted in its ordinary sense, meaning the moment the consumer became aware of the unfit product. The Court rejected the argument that 'detection' should be defined as the moment the complaint was received by the Authorized Officer, stating that such an interpretation would undermine the legislative intent behind the time bar. The Court cited previous cases to support the notion that the time bar applies equally to actions initiated by the State. The Court concluded that the prosecution was indeed time-barred, as it was initiated after the statutory period had lapsed. Finding: The prosecution against the 3rd Accused-Appellant was time-barred under Section 20(1)(b) of the Food Act. Interaction of Issues The issues are interrelated as the interpretation of 'detection' directly impacts the determination of whether the prosecution was timely. The Court's decision to uphold the ordinary meaning of 'detection' reinforces the importance of adhering to statutory time limits, ensuring fairness in the prosecution process. Conclusion The Supreme Court allowed the appeal, acquitting the 3rd Accused-Appellant and setting aside the convictions and sentences imposed by the lower courts. The Court emphasized the necessity of compliance with statutory provisions to uphold the rights of the accused and ensure a fair trial. The judgment underscores the importance of timely prosecution in maintaining the integrity of the legal process and protecting consumer rights. Keywords Food Act — prosecution time bar — fair trial — statutory interpretation — nullum tempus occurrit regi — vigilantibus et non dormientibus — criminal justice — evidence — procedural irregularity — acquittal — public health — consumer protection — legal principles — judicial discretion — rights of the accused	Gamini Marapana, PC., with Navin Marapana, PC., Uchitha Wickremesinghe and Thanuja Meegahawatta for the 3rd Accused-Appellant-Appellant. Madhawa Tennakoon, DSG, for the Hon. Attorney General.	SC/APPEAL/128/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_128_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-184-2019	3 November 2022	Attorney General v. Dharmasena	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Janak De Silva, J.	Special Leave to Appeal — Circumstantial evidence — Evaluation of confessions — Section 30 of the Evidence Ordinance — Dock statements — Co-accused confessions — Inference of guilt — Reasonable doubt	Facts The Appellant, Kotuwe Gedara Sriyantha Dharmasena, was indicted before the High Court of Kandy along with two other accused for the murder of a 23-year-old medical student, an offence punishable under Section 296 of the Penal Code. The deceased was last seen alive on 04/01/1994, and his body was subsequently discovered in an abandoned well. Post-mortem examinations concluded that death resulted from the forcible introduction of an organophosphate pesticide. The trial judge convicted the Appellant and sentenced him to death, relying on circumstantial evidence and confessions made by the 2nd and 3rd accused. The Court of Appeal subsequently affirmed the conviction and sentence. The Appellant then appealed to the Supreme Court, challenging the trial court's reliance on inadmissible evidence and the failure to properly apply the principles governing circumstantial evidence. Issues Whether the trial judge failed to apply the principles governing circumstantial evidence when evaluating the case against the Appellant. Whether the prosecution proved the case against the Appellant beyond reasonable doubt based on the circumstantial evidence. Applicable Law Statutes: Penal Code, Section 296 Evidence Ordinance, Section 30 Code of Criminal Procedure Act, Section 127 Cases Referred to: Rex v. Ukku Banda - [24-nlr-327] King v. Ferdinands - [45-nlr-450] R v. Blom - [1939-ad-188] R v. Hodges - [1838-2-lew-cc-227] Junaiden Mohamed Haaris v. Hon. Attorney General - [sc-appeal-118/17] Monis Appu v. Heen Hamy - [26-nlr-303] Priyantha Lal Ramanayake v. Hon. Attorney General - [sc-appeal-31/211] Queen v. Kularatne - [71-nlr-529] Analysis Issue 1: Application of circumstantial evidence principles Rule applied: The principle that circumstantial evidence must be absolutely incompatible with the innocence of the accused and incapable of explanation upon any other reasonable hypothesis than that of guilt. Court's reasoning: The trial judge failed to compartmentalize evidence against each accused, instead relying on the totality of circumstances and inadmissible confessions of co-accused to implicate the Appellant. The court noted that the prosecution failed to exclude other reasonable hypotheses, as the evidence regarding the Appellant's presence at the scene or his conduct was insufficient to establish guilt. The trial judge improperly used unsworn dock statements of co-accused to fill gaps in the prosecution's case. Finding: The trial judge failed to apply the established principles of circumstantial evidence, as the evidence did not exclusively point to the Appellant's guilt. Issue 2: Proof beyond reasonable doubt Rule applied: Section 30 of the Evidence Ordinance, which governs the admissibility of confessions against co-accused. Court's reasoning: The trial judge acknowledged that the confessions of the 2nd and 3rd accused were inadmissible against the Appellant under Section 30 of the Evidence Ordinance, yet proceeded to use them to fix culpability. Furthermore, the court found that the prosecution's reliance on the Appellant's "unusual expression of grief" was undermined by the potential bias of the witness. The Deputy Solicitor General conceded that the conviction could not be sustained. Finding: The prosecution failed to prove the case against the Appellant beyond reasonable doubt. Interaction of Issues The failure to correctly apply the principles of circumstantial evidence (Issue 1) was exacerbated by the trial court's erroneous reliance on inadmissible confessions and unsworn dock statements (Issue 2). Because the circumstantial chain was built upon inadmissible evidence, the entire foundation of the conviction collapsed, rendering the prosecution's case insufficient to meet the burden of proof. Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The judgments of the High Court of Kandy and the Court of Appeal are set aside, and the conviction and sentence against the Appellant are quashed. Keywords Special Leave to Appeal — Circumstantial evidence — Evaluation of confessions — Section 30 of the Evidence Ordinance — Dock statements — Co-accused confessions — Inference of guilt — Reasonable doubt		SC/APPEAL/184/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_184_2019.pdf
sc-fr-356-2014	7 November 2022	Karunaratne and Others v. Anuradhapura Municipal Council and Others	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, J; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Local Authorities Housing Act — Rent purchase basis — Official quarters — Legitimate expectation — Tenancy agreements — Absolute ownership — Low-cost houses — Advisory Board	Facts The Petitioners, who were former employees of the Anuradhapura Municipal Council, occupied residential premises belonging to the Council. They sought an order directing the Respondents to transfer the absolute ownership of these houses to them, claiming they were allocated the residences on a rent-purchase basis pursuant to a direction from the Minister of Local Government dated 09.10.1979. The Petitioners argued that their tenancy agreements and the ministerial direction created a legitimate expectation of ownership. The Respondents contended that the premises were official staff quarters rather than low-cost houses and were governed by the Local Authority Quarters (Recovery of Possession) Act No. 42. The Respondents further argued that even if the houses were considered low-cost, the monthly rental of forty-five rupees exceeded the twenty-five-rupee threshold required for transfer of ownership under the Local Authorities Housing Act. The Petitioners had previously challenged notices to quit issued by the Council in various courts, which had resulted in findings that the houses were held on a rent basis rather than as official quarters. However, the Respondents produced supplementary tenement lists identifying the premises as staff quarters vested in the Municipal Council. Issues Whether the Petitioners are entitled to the transfer of absolute ownership of the houses under Section 5(A) of the Local Authorities Housing Act No. 14 (as amended). Whether the Respondentsâ€™ refusal to transfer ownership constitutes an infringement of the Petitioners' fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1) Local Authorities Housing Act No. 14 (as amended) Local Authorities Housing (Amendment) Act No. 63 Local Authority Quarters (Recovery of Possession) Act No. 42 Cases Referred to: C.W Jayasekera v. Municipal Council of Anuradhapura - [sc-appeal-63/2013] HC Anuradhapura Certiorari 19/96 - [hc-anuradhapura-certiorari-19/96] CA (PHC) 108/98 - [ca-phc-108/98] HC Anuradhapura Certiorari 13/94 - [hc-anuradhapura-certiorari-13/94] CA (PHC) 01/96 - [ca-phc-01/96] HC Anuradhapura Certiorari 23/96 - [hc-anuradhapura-certiorari-23/96] CA (PHC) 109/98 - [ca-phc-109/98] Analysis Issue 1: Entitlement to ownership Rule applied: Section 5(A) of the Local Authorities Housing (Amendment) Act No. 63, which restricts the transfer of absolute ownership to houses where the monthly rental did not exceed twenty-five rupees. Court's reasoning: The court examined the tenancy agreements and found they were standard rent agreements rather than rent-purchase agreements. The monthly rent of forty-five rupees paid by the Petitioners exceeded the statutory limit of twenty-five rupees prescribed in Section 5(A). Furthermore, evidence from the supplementary tenement lists confirmed the premises were classified as staff quarters, not low-cost housing. Finding: The Petitioners failed to satisfy the statutory criteria for the transfer of ownership. Issue 2: Infringement of Article 12(1) Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution regarding the right to equality and equal protection of the law. Court's reasoning: The court determined that the local authority retained discretion regarding the transfer of ownership and had not made any binding promise or created a legitimate expectation that would entitle the Petitioners to ownership. The court distinguished the present case from previous litigation, noting that the absence of a legal right to ownership meant the refusal to transfer did not constitute arbitrary or discriminatory state action. Finding: There was no infringement of the Petitioners' fundamental rights. Interaction of Issues The findings are interdependent; because the Petitioners failed to meet the statutory requirements for ownership under the Local Authorities Housing Act, they could not establish a legal basis for their claim. Consequently, the absence of a legal right or a legitimate expectation precluded a finding of a fundamental rights violation under Article 12(1). Conclusion The court held that the Petitioners were not entitled to the transfer of absolute ownership of the premises. The application was dismissed as no violation of fundamental rights was established. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Local Authorities Housing Act — Rent purchase basis — Official quarters — Legitimate expectation — Tenancy agreements — Absolute ownership — Low-cost houses — Advisory Board		SC/FR/356/2014	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_356_2014.pdf
sc-appeal-48-2016	7 November 2022	Rajapaksha v. Bandara and Others	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.	Right of way — Prescription — Necessity — Execution of decree — Judgement creditor — Judgement debtor — Reissuance of writ — Relief not prayed for — Inherent jurisdiction — Per incuriam	Facts The Petitioner, Disanayakage Lional Rajapaksha, instituted an action in the District Court of Kuliyapitiya claiming a right of way by prescription and necessity over lot 7 of a surveyed plan to access his land, lot 5. The 1st and 2nd Respondents, W.A. Prema Swarnamali Bandara and Hettiarachchi Mudiyanselage Cyril Bandara, obstructed this right of way. The District Court entered judgment in favor of the Petitioner, granting the reliefs prayed for and dismissing the claims of the 1st and 2nd Respondents. This judgment was affirmed by the Civil Appellate High Court, and subsequent leave to appeal to the Supreme Court was refused. Following the finality of the judgment, a writ was issued and executed on 21.07.2010, with the fiscal reporting that the obstructions were removed. Subsequently, the 1st and 2nd Respondents moved the District Court to reissue the writ, alleging that the execution was improper because certain electricity and telephone posts remained on the right of way. The District Court ordered that only obstructions claimed by the Petitioner could be removed. The 1st and 2nd Respondents appealed this order to the Civil Appellate High Court, which directed the reissuance of the writ. The Petitioner then appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Civil Appellate High Court and the District Court erred in law by ordering the re-execution of a writ that had already been fully executed on 21.07.2010. Whether a judgment debtor is legally entitled to move for the execution of a writ when the judgment creditor is satisfied with the existing execution. Whether the court has jurisdiction to grant relief, such as the removal of utility posts, that was not specifically prayed for in the original pleadings or granted in the decree. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code, Section 4(e) Civil Procedure Code, Section 75(e) Civil Procedure Code, Section 323 Cases Referred to: W. Sirinivasa Thero v. Sudassi Thero - [63-nlr-31] Surangi v. Rodrigo - [2003/v1-sri-lr-35] Danapala v. Baby Nona - [77-nlr-95] Weragama v. Bandara - [77-nlr-289] Analysis Issue 1: Authority to Reissue Writ Rule applied: Section 323 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the policy of the Civil Procedure Code dictates that only a judgment creditor may apply for the execution of a decree. Since the Petitioner (judgment creditor) was satisfied with the execution performed on 21.07.2010, there was no legal basis for the judgment debtors to seek a re-execution. Finding: The lower courts erred in ordering the re-execution of the writ. Issue 2: Standing of Judgment Debtor Rule applied: Section 323 of the Civil Procedure Code and the principle established in W. Sirinivasa Thero v. Sudassi Thero. Court's reasoning: While a judgment debtor may invoke inherent jurisdiction to seek a writ if the original execution caused injury through a mistake of court or exceeded the decree, the present case involved no such error. The Respondents were attempting to secure relief that was previously refused by the trial court. Finding: The judgment debtor has no standing to move for the execution of a writ in these circumstances. Issue 3: Jurisdiction to Grant Relief Rule applied: Section 4(e) and Section 75(e) of the Civil Procedure Code; Surangi v. Rodrigo; Danapala v. Baby Nona; Weragama v. Bandara. Court's reasoning: A court cannot grant relief that was not prayed for in the pleadings. The Respondents failed to raise issues regarding the utility posts during the trial, and their claims in reconvention were dismissed. Consequently, the court lacks jurisdiction to order the removal of these items under the guise of executing a decree that did not grant such relief. Finding: The order to remove telephone and electricity posts was beyond the court's jurisdiction. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing: because the judgment debtor lacks the standing to execute a decree (Issue 2) and the court lacks the jurisdiction to grant relief not prayed for (Issue 3), the order to re-execute the writ (Issue 1) is fundamentally flawed. The Respondents' attempt to use the execution process to obtain relief they failed to secure at trial constitutes a misuse of the court's process. Conclusion The appeal is allowed, and the judgment of the Civil Appellate High Court of the North Western Province dated 03.09.2014 is set aside. The Petitioner is entitled to the costs of this court and the courts below. Keywords Right of way — Prescription — Necessity — Execution of decree — Judgement creditor — Judgement debtor — Reissuance of writ — Relief not prayed for — Inherent jurisdiction — Per incuriam		SC/APPEAL/48/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_48_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-169-2014	9 November 2022	Jayatissa v. Divisional Secretary and Others	P. Padman Surasena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Unauthorized occupation — Land Development Ordinance — Permit issuance — Inquiry procedure — Natural justice — Audi Alteram Partem — State land — Succession to permits — Notice of inquiry — Judicial review	Facts The Petitioner-Appellant, Kapukotuwa Mudiyanselage Jayatissa, claimed to be an unauthorized occupant of state land in the Neelapola Grama Niladari Division, which he had occupied and cultivated since 1995 or 1996. The Petitioner-Appellant sought to regularize his occupation through a permit under the Land Development Ordinance. A dispute arose in 2003 when the 6th Respondent, K. H. Sandya Kumari, claimed the land based on a permit previously held by her father. The Petitioner-Appellant engaged with various state authorities, including the Divisional Secretary, the District Secretary, and the Commissioner General of Lands, to resolve the dispute. Although the Commissioner General of Lands requested a report from the Assistant Commissioner of Lands, the Petitioner-Appellant alleged that no proper inquiry was conducted and that he was denied an opportunity to be heard. Meanwhile, the Primary Court, in proceedings under the Primary Court Procedure Act, upheld the Petitioner-Appellant's possession of the land. Despite this, the Assistant Commissioner of Lands submitted an inquiry report dated 23rd July 2004, which recommended granting the permit to the 6th Respondent. The Petitioner-Appellant was not notified of this inquiry. Subsequently, the 6th Respondent instituted an action in the District Court of Trincomalee based on a permit issued to her. The Petitioner-Appellant filed a writ application in the Court of Appeal, which was dismissed. He then appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal failed to consider that the Respondents did not hold a proper and due inquiry regarding the Petitioner-Appellant's application to regularize his possession. Whether the Court of Appeal failed to consider that the Petitioner-Appellant was not informed of the inquiry held on 23rd July 2004 and was denied an opportunity to present his case. Applicable Law Statutes: Land Development Ordinance Primary Court Procedure Act No. 44 of 1979 Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Failure to hold a proper inquiry Rule applied: The principles of natural justice, specifically the rule Audi Alteram Partem, and the procedural requirements for land administration under the Land Development Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the Respondents failed to provide evidence that they notified the Petitioner-Appellant of the inquiry or that they followed a transparent procedure. The court noted that the 3rd Respondent relied solely on the impugned inquiry report (3R 2) without justifying the legal basis for the inquiry or demonstrating compliance with the duty to act fairly. Finding: The court found that the failure to provide notice and an opportunity to be heard rendered the inquiry process fundamentally flawed. Issue 2: Denial of the right to be heard Rule applied: The rule Audi Alteram Partem. Court's reasoning: The court determined that the Court of Appeal erred by relying on the very document (the inquiry report) that the Petitioner-Appellant was challenging as being procedurally unfair. The Supreme Court found that the Respondents failed to produce any documentation proving that the Petitioner-Appellant was notified of the inquiry date. The court emphasized that even in the absence of specific statutory provisions for this type of inquiry, state officials are obligated to uphold the principles of natural justice when dealing with the property rights of citizens. Finding: The court answered this issue in the affirmative, concluding that the Petitioner-Appellant was denied his right to be heard. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are inextricably linked. The failure to hold a "proper and due inquiry" (Issue 1) was directly caused by the failure to notify the Petitioner-Appellant and provide him an opportunity to be heard (Issue 2). Because the procedural breach of Audi Alteram Partem was so fundamental, it invalidated the entire decision-making process, rendering the subsequent issuance of the permit to the 6th Respondent null and void. Conclusion The appeal is allowed and the judgment of the Court of Appeal is set aside. A writ of certiorari is issued to quash the permit granted to the 6th Respondent, and the 1st to 5th Respondents are directed to conduct a fresh, impartial inquiry after providing due notice to all parties. Keywords Unauthorized occupation — Land Development Ordinance — Permit issuance — Inquiry procedure — Natural justice — Audi Alteram Partem — State land — Succession to permits — Notice of inquiry — Judicial review		SC/APPEAL/169/2014	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_169_2014.pdf
sc-appeal-220-2017	17 November 2022	Sammuarachchi v. Jayawardhena and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Probate — Letters of administration — Testamentary proceedings — Fraud — Due execution of a will — Prima facie proof — Judicial settlement — District Court jurisdiction — High Court of Civil Appeal	Facts The original petitioner initiated testamentary proceedings in the District Court of Mawanella seeking to admit a last will to probate and to be appointed as the administrator of the deceased's estate. The deceased was the uncle of the petitioner, and the will bequeathed his property to the petitioner subject to a life interest in favor of the petitioner's mother. Following newspaper publications as required by the Civil Procedure Code, no objections were filed, and the District Court issued probate to the petitioner. Approximately one year later, the intervenient petitioners, who are siblings of the deceased and the original respondent, filed an application under section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code to recall the probate. They alleged that the last will was a fraudulent document, that they had no prior knowledge of the proceedings, and that the estate should devolve upon them and the original respondent as natural heirs. The District Court rejected this application. On appeal, the High Court of Civil Appeal set aside the District Court's order, prompting the original petitioner to appeal to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the failure to name the intervenient petitioners as respondents in the original testamentary application rendered the proceedings void or fatal to the petitioner's claim. Whether the District Court failed to comply with the mandatory requirement under section 531(1)(a) of the Civil Procedure Code to satisfy itself of the due making of the will before issuing probate. Whether the intervenient petitioners' application to recall probate was procedurally flawed for failing to follow the summary procedure prescribed by section 538 of the Civil Procedure Code. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Law No. 20 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 14 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 38 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 34 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 4 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 11 Judicature Act No. 2 Wills Ordinance No. 21 Prevention of Frauds Ordinance No. 7 Evidence Ordinance Cases Referred to: Shanthi Goonetilake v. Mangalika - [2006/v3-sri-lr-331] De Zoysa v. De Zoysa - [26-nlr-472] De Silva v. Jayakody - [42-nlr-226] Pathmanathan v. Thuraisingham - [74-nlr-196] Biyanwila v. Amarasekere - [67-nlr-488] Pieris v. Wijeratne - [2000/v2-sri-lr-145] Actalina Fonseka v. Dharshani Fonseka - [1989/v2-sri-lr-95] Kamala v. Andris - [41-nlr-71] Leechman & Company Ltd v. Rangalla Consolidated Ltd - [1981/v2-sri-lr-373] Seneviratne v. Abeykoon - [1986/v2-sri-lr-1] Abeygunasekera v. Wijesekara - [2002/v2-sri-lr-269] Ravi Karunanayake v. Wimal Weerawansa - [2006/v3-sri-lr-16] Navaratnasingham v. Arumugam - [1980/v2-sri-lr-1] Beatrice Perera v. The Commissioner of National Housing - [77-nlr-361] Abeywickrama v. Pathirana - [1986/v1-sri-lr-120] Dabare v. Appuhamy - [1980/v2-sri-lr-54] Peiris v. The Commissioner of Inland Revenue - [65-nlr-457] Solicitor-General v. Perera - [17-nlr-413] Jayawardane v. Ran Aweera - [2004/v3-sri-lr-37] Kumaranatunga v. Samarasinghe - [1983/v2-sri-lr-63] Jayasekera v. Lakmini - [2010/v1-sri-lr-41] Wilson v. Kusumawathi - [2015-blr-49] Adoris v. Perera - [17-nlr-212] Sadhana Dharmabandu v. Mallika Homes Ltd - [2009/v1-sri-lr-151] Peries v. Perera - [48-nlr-560] Velupillai v. Sidembram - [31-nlr-97] Wickremasuriya v. Dedoleena - [1996/v2-sri-lr-95] Pieris v. Wilbert - [59-nlr-245] Barry v. Butlin - [1838/2-moo-pc-480] The Alim Will Case - [20-nlr-481] Arulampikai v. Thambu - [45-nlr-457] Sithamparanathan v. Mathuranayagam - [73-nlr-53] Ratnayake v. Chandratillake - [1987/v2-sri-lr-299] Ceylon Breweries v. Fernando - [2001/v1-sri-lr-270] Tissera v. Gunatilleke Hamine - [13-nlr-261] Suppramaniam v. Erampakurukal - [23-nlr-417] Sirisena v. Kobbekaduwa - [80-nlr-1] Lazarus Estates Ltd v. Bearely - [1956/1-all-er-341] Harold Fernando v. Fonseka - [1998/v3-sri-lr-301] Fernando v. Fernando - [18-nlr-24] Kathirikamasegara Mudaliyar - [5-nlr-29] Kantaiyar v. Ramoe - [8-nlr-207] Roslin Nona v. Herat - [65-clw-55] Fernando v. Dabarera - [77-nlr-127] Suppammal v. Govinda Chetty - [44-nlr-193] Don Cornelis Dias - [2-nlr-252] De Silva v. Gomes - [30-nlr-249] Jayantha de Soysa v. Naomal de Soysa - [1997/v3-sri-lr-65] Holsinger v. Nicholas - [20-nlr-417] Zain v. Sheriff - [40-nlr-310] Imbulmure v. The Public Trustee - [2012/v2-sri-lr-413] Analysis Issue 1: Naming of respondents Rule applied: Section 524 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court held that under the current law, there is no mandatory requirement to name heirs as respondents in an application to prove a last will. The legislative intent, evidenced by amendments to the Civil Procedure Code, removed the requirement to name respondents or file an affidavit of non-opposition. While naming heirs is salutary for transparency, failure to do so is not fatal. Finding: The High Court of Civil Appeal erred in concluding that the failure to name the intervenient petitioners as respondents was fatal to the application. Issue 2: Compliance with section 531(1)(a) Rule applied: Section 531(1)(a) of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The District Judge has a special duty to ascertain the intention of the deceased and must be satisfied that the evidence adduced provides prima facie proof of the due making of the will. The District Judge in this case made a mechanical order without exercising his judicial mind to consider the evidence or the suspicious circumstances surrounding the will, such as the fact that the sole beneficiary prepared the document in her own handwriting. Finding: The District Court failed to comply with the mandatory requirement of section 531(1)(a), rendering the issuance of probate invalid. Issue 3: Procedural flaw in recall application Rule applied: Sections 537 and 538 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: Although the intervenient petitioners filed their application under section 839 (inherent powers) instead of the summary procedure required by section 538, the court noted that the original petitioner did not object to this procedure in the District Court. Furthermore, when a court has plenary jurisdiction, it should not dismiss an application merely for a wrong caption if it has the power to grant relief under the correct provision. Finding: The procedural flaw was waived by the original petitioner's failure to object, and the intervenient petitioners established a prima facie case for the recall of probate. Interaction of Issues The findings are reinforcing: while the failure to name respondents was not a fatal procedural defect, the substantive failure of the District Court to perform its duty under section 531(1)(a) to verify the will's validity—compounded by the suspicious circumstances of the will's preparation—justified the High Court's decision to set aside the probate. The procedural irregularity of the recall application was cured by the parties' conduct, allowing the court to address the core issue of whether the probate was validly issued. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed with costs. The Supreme Court affirmed the High Court of Civil Appeal's judgment setting aside the District Court's order, as the District Judge failed to satisfy the mandatory requirement of proving the will under section 531(1)(a) of the Civil Procedure Code. Keywords Probate — Letters of administration — Testamentary proceedings — Fraud — Due execution of a will — Prima facie proof — Judicial settlement — District Court jurisdiction — High Court of Civil Appeal		SC/APPEAL/220/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_220_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-170-2019	17 November 2022	Attorney General and Others v. Ceylinco General Insurance Ltd	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Advance payment bonds — Performance bonds — Demand for payment — Validity period — Unilateral extension of time — Autonomous transactions — Fraud — Interpretation of contract	Facts The Attorney General, acting on behalf of the State, initiated an action in the District Court of Colombo against Ceylinco General Insurance Ltd to recover funds under an advance payment bond. The bond was issued by the defendant to the Commander of the Sri Lanka Army to guarantee the performance of a construction contract by M/s Nimali Builders. The bond was subsequently extended to cover the period ending on 10.10.2004. The plaintiff issued a document on 05.10.2004 requesting the defendant to withhold the bond to preserve the State's rights. A formal demand for payment was later issued by the plaintiff on 05.11.2004. The District Court dismissed the action, finding that the demand was made after the expiration of the bond's validity period. The High Court of Civil Appeal reversed this decision, concluding that the document dated 05.10.2004 constituted a valid alteration of the repayment period which the defendant had tacitly accepted. The defendant appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in law by directing the District Court to enter judgment for the plaintiff when the demand for payment was made after the expiry of the bond's validity period. Whether the document dated 05.10.2004 constituted a valid subsequent agreement or a demand for payment sufficient to extend the validity of the bond. Applicable Law Statutes: Not specified Cases Referred to: Siporex Trade S.A. v. Banque Indosuez - [1986/v2-lloyds-law-reports-146] Tukan Timber LTD v. Barclays Bank PLC - [1987/v1-qb-171] Power Curber International Ltd. v. National Bank of Kuwait SAK - [1981/v3-all-er-607] R.D. Harbottle (Mercantile) Ltd v. National Westminster Bank Ltd - [1977/v2-all-er-862] Sztejn v. J. Henry Schroder Banking Corporation - [1941/31-n.y.s.-2d-631] Edward Owen Engineering Ltd v. Barclays Bank International Ltd - [1978/v1-qb-159] Pesticides India v. State Chemical and Pharmaceutical Corporation of India - [1983/54-compcas-147] United Trading Corporation S.A. and Murray Clayton Ltd v. Allied Arab Bank Ltd - [1985/v2-lloyds-law-reports-554] Indica Traders (Pvt) Ltd v. Seoul Lanka Construction (Pvt) Ltd - [1994/v3-sri-lr-387] Hemas Marketing (Pvt) Ltd v. Chandrasiri - [1994/v2-sri-lr-181] Pan Asia Bank Ltd v. Bentota MPCS Ltd - [2012/v1-sri-lr-51] Re Colonial Finance, Mortgage, Investment and Guarantee Corporation Ltd - [1905/6-sr-nsw-1] Union Bank of Colombo Ltd v. Emm Chem (Pvt) Ltd - [sc-appeal-chc-22/11] Blest v. Brown - [1862/45-er-1225] Reigate v. Union Manufacturing Co (Ramsbottom) Ltd - [1918/v1-kb-592] Shirlaw v. Southern Foundries (1926) Ltd. - [1939/v2-kb-206] Smith v. Hughes - [1871/lr-6-qb-597] Schuler AG v. Wickman Machine Tool Sales Ltd. - [1973/all-er-39] B.P. Refinery (Westernport) Pty Limited v. Shire of Hastings - [1977/180-clr-266] Duke of Westminster v. Guild - [1985/qb-688] Analysis Issue 1: Validity of the demand Rule applied: The court applied the principle that performance bonds are autonomous, standalone instruments that must be strictly construed according to their terms, requiring a clear demand for payment within the specified validity period. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the bond expressly required a demand to be made before 10.10.2004. The formal demand was made on 05.11.2004, which is outside the agreed period. The court emphasized that sureties are bound only to the letter of their engagement and that terms cannot be implied to extend validity indefinitely without clear consent. Finding: The demand was not made within the validity period of the bond. Issue 2: Effect of the document dated 05.10.2004 Rule applied: The court applied the principles of contract interpretation, noting that terms cannot be implied into a contract unless they are necessary for business efficacy or are so obvious that they "go without saying." Court's reasoning: The court rejected the High Court's finding that the document dated 05.10.2004 constituted a tacit agreement to extend the bond. The document merely requested the defendant to withhold the bond to preserve rights and lacked the clarity required to constitute a demand for payment or an agreement to extend the validity period. Finding: The document dated 05.10.2004 did not extend the validity of the bond. Interaction of Issues The findings are interdependent; because the document dated 05.10.2004 failed to meet the legal threshold for a demand or a valid extension, the subsequent formal demand of 05.11.2004 remained time-barred. The court's strict construction of the bond's terms rendered the High Court's inference of a "tacit agreement" legally unsustainable. Conclusion The appeal is allowed. The judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal is set aside, and the judgment of the District Court dismissing the plaintiff's action is restored. Keywords Advance payment bonds — Performance bonds — Demand for payment — Validity period — Unilateral extension of time — Autonomous transactions — Fraud — Interpretation of contract		SC/APPEAL/170/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_170_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-18-2021	17 November 2022	Hettiarachchige Don Sugath Nandana v. Caroline Hewa Abewickrama	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Kumudini Wickremasinghe, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	constructive trust — Trusts Ordinance — laesio enormis — equitable remedy — beneficial interest — attendant circumstances — parol evidence — Prevention of Frauds Ordinance — Evidence Ordinance — mortgage — loan transaction — outright transfer — legal interest — genuine sale — inadequate consideration — possession — retransfer	Facts The plaintiff, Hettiarachchige Don Sugath Nandana, initiated legal proceedings in the District Court of Kegalle, seeking a declaration of ownership over a property described in deed No. 6165 (marked P2), along with an order for the ejectment of the defendant, Caroline Hewa Abewickrama, and damages. The defendant, who had previously transferred the property to the plaintiff via deed P2, contested the plaintiff's claim, asserting that the plaintiff held the property in trust for her. Additionally, the defendant sought to have deed P2 annulled on the grounds of laesio enormis, which refers to a significant disparity between the value of the property and the price paid. After a trial, the District Court ruled in favor of the plaintiff, a decision that was upheld by the High Court on appeal. The defendant subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court, which granted leave to consider whether the lower courts erred in concluding that there was insufficient evidence to demonstrate that the defendant did not intend to relinquish her beneficial interest in the property when executing deed P2. The Supreme Court also addressed a consequential question raised by the plaintiff regarding the defendant's ability to assert both trust and laesio enormis claims in the same action. The primary issue before the Supreme Court was whether deed P2 constituted an outright transfer of the property or if it was subject to a constructive trust. Issues Whether the District Court and the High Court erred in determining that there was no evidence to prove that the defendant did not intend to part with the beneficial interest in the property when deed P2 was executed. Whether the defendant can raise the issues of trust and laesio enormis in the same action. Applicable Law Statutes: Trusts Ordinance, No. 9 of 1917; Prevention of Frauds Ordinance, No. 7 of 1840; Evidence Ordinance, No. 14 of 1895. Cases Referred to: Carl Zeiss Stiftung v. Herbert Smith (No 2) [1969] 2 Ch 276 (CA); De Silva v. Silva (1956) 58 NLR 145; Wijeyaratne v. Somawathie [2002] 1 Sri LR 93; Piyasena v. Don Vansue [1997] 2 Sri LR 311; Bernedette Vanlangenberg v. Hapuarachchige Anthony [1990] 1 Sri LR 190; Valliyammai Atchi v. Abdul Majeed (1947) 48 NLR 289; Premawathi v. Gnanawathi [1994] 2 Sri LR 171; Dayawathie v. Gunasekera [1991] 1 Sri LR 115; Carthelis v. Ranasinghe [2002] 2 Sri LR 359; Ehiya Lebbe v. Majeed (1947) 48 NLR 357; Thisa Nona v. Premadasa [1997] 1 Sri LR 169; Perera v. Fernando [2011] 2 Sri LR 192. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the District Court and the High Court erred in determining that there was no evidence to prove that the defendant did not intend to part with the beneficial interest in the property when deed P2 was executed. Rule applied: Constructive trust under section 83 of the Trusts Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court meticulously analyzed the evidence presented during the trial, emphasizing that the execution of deed P2 was not a straightforward sale but rather a transaction that was heavily influenced by the financial circumstances of the defendant. The Court noted that the defendant had mortgaged the property to a Rural Bank to secure a loan of Rs. 75,000 at a high interest rate. The plaintiff lent the defendant Rs. 100,000 to redeem this mortgage, which was executed on the same day as deed P2. The Court highlighted that the consideration for deed P2 was Rs. 100,000, which was significantly lower than the market value of the property, indicating that the defendant did not intend to part with her beneficial interest. The Court further pointed out that the plaintiff, being a money lender, had a history of taking properties as security for loans, which added to the suspicion surrounding the transaction. The continued possession of the property by the defendant after the execution of deed P2 was also a critical factor, as it suggested that the defendant did not intend to relinquish her rights to the property. The Court referenced previous cases where similar circumstances led to the establishment of constructive trusts, emphasizing that the intention of the parties must be inferred from the surrounding circumstances. The Court concluded that the District Judge had failed to properly evaluate the evidence, leading to an erroneous judgment. Finding: The Supreme Court found in favor of the defendant, concluding that deed P2 did not constitute an outright transfer and that a constructive trust was established. Issue 2: Whether the defendant can raise the issues of trust and laesio enormis in the same action. Rule applied: Legal principles regarding the raising of multiple claims in a single action. Court's reasoning: The Court determined that the defendant's attempt to raise both trust and laesio enormis claims in the same action was not permissible, as the leave to appeal granted by the Supreme Court did not encompass the issue of laesio enormis. The Court clarified that the defendant could not simultaneously assert conflicting claims regarding the nature of the transaction. Finding: The Supreme Court ruled that the consequential question raised by the plaintiff regarding the defendant's ability to raise both claims was not relevant to the case at hand. Interaction of Issues The issues of whether the defendant intended to part with her beneficial interest and whether she could raise both claims are interrelated, as they both stem from the interpretation of the transaction involving deed P2. The Court's analysis of the evidence regarding the defendant's intentions directly impacted the determination of the validity of the claims raised. Conclusion The Supreme Court set aside the judgments of the District Court and the High Court, allowing the appeal with costs. The Court directed the defendant to deposit a specified sum to the credit of the case, enabling the plaintiff to withdraw the funds, and mandated the retransfer of the property back to the defendant upon compliance with the deposit order. The Registrar of the District Court was instructed to facilitate the transfer if the plaintiff failed to comply. The Court emphasized the importance of equitable principles in resolving disputes involving constructive trusts, ensuring that the rightful owner of the property was recognized. Keywords: constructive trust — Trusts Ordinance — laesio enormis — equitable remedy — beneficial interest — attendant circumstances — parol evidence — Prevention of Frauds Ordinance — Evidence Ordinance — mortgage — loan transaction — outright transfer — legal interest — genuine sale — inadequate consideration — possession — retransfer	Dr. Sunil F.A. Coorey with Sudarshani Coorey for the Defendant-Appellant-Appellant. Ranjan Suwandaratna, P.C., Shammil Perera, P.C., with Primal Ratwatte and Gimhani Gamage for the Plaintiff-Respondent-Respondent.	SC/APPEAL/18/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_18_2021.pdf
sc-fr-303-2013	18 November 2022	Gunasena v. Public Service Commission and Others	Aluwihare, PC, J	Buwaneka Aluwihare, PC, J; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Public Service Commission — Administrative Appeals Tribunal — Promotion to Class I — Antedating of appointment — Back wages — Discrimination — Arbitrary action	Facts The Petitioner was a public servant in the Sri Lanka Accountants Service whose employment was terminated following his participation in the July 1980 general strike. He was subsequently reinstated following the issuance of Public Administration Circular No. 32/89. His appointment to Class II Grade II was later antedated to 20th May 1984 by a Cabinet decision, though this was granted without back wages. The Petitioner sought promotion to Class II Grade I, arguing that his ten years of service should be calculated from the antedated appointment date of 20th May 1984. The Public Service Commission (1st Respondent) refused this, contending that the period of active service only commenced from his actual date of reappointment in 1992. The Petitioner appealed to the Administrative Appeals Tribunal, which ruled in his favor on 18th November 2011, directing the 1st Respondent to grant the promotion with effect from 20th May 1994. Although the 1st Respondent initially complied, it later annulled the promotion via a letter dated 2nd July 2013, citing the lack of back wages as a basis to exclude the period prior to 1992 from his service record. The Petitioner challenged this annulment and the denial of further promotion to Class I on a supernumerary basis, alleging a violation of his fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the 1st Respondentâ€™s decision to annul the Petitionerâ€™s antedated promotion, contrary to the binding order of the Administrative Appeals Tribunal, violated Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Whether the differential treatment of the Petitioner regarding the computation of service years for promotion, based on the receipt of back wages, constitutes a violation of the right to equality under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 59(1), 59(2), 126 Administrative Appeals Tribunal Act No. 4 of 2002, Sections 3(a), 8(2) Cases Referred to: W.J. Fernando v. Priyanatha Perera - [sc-appeal-383/2008] Probhudas Morarjee Rajkotia v. Union of India - [1966-sc-1044] C.W. Mackie and Co. Ltd v. Hugh Molagoda - [1986/v1-sri-lr-300] Sampanthan v. Attorney General - [sc-minutes-13-december-2018] J. Dharmasiri de Silva v. The Secretary, PSC - [sc-application-87/2001] Analysis Issue 1: Binding nature of the Administrative Appeals Tribunal order Rule applied: Section 8(2) of the Administrative Appeals Tribunal Act No. 4 of 2002 and the principle of finality of administrative adjudications. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that the Administrative Appeals Tribunal is an appellate body whose decisions are final and conclusive. The 1st Respondent was a party to the proceedings before the Tribunal and failed to challenge the order in a court of competent jurisdiction. Consequently, the 1st Respondent was legally bound to implement the Tribunal's decision. The unilateral annulment of the promotion by the 1st Respondent was an arbitrary exercise of power. Finding: The 1st Respondentâ€™s failure to abide by the final order of the Administrative Appeals Tribunal was legally impermissible and contributed to the violation of the Petitioner's rights. Issue 2: Violation of Article 12(1) equality Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution regarding the right to equality and the prohibition of arbitrary or discriminatory executive action. Court's reasoning: The Court found that all employees who participated in the 1980 strike were similarly circumstanced. The 1st Respondent created an artificial distinction between those who received back wages and those who did not, using this as a criterion to deny the latter group credit for service years. The Court held that the receipt of back wages is not a rational or intelligible criterion for calculating "active service" for promotional purposes, as none of the reinstated employees were in active service during the period of their termination. Finding: The 1st Respondentâ€™s actions were arbitrary, unreasonable, and discriminatory, thereby violating the Petitioner's fundamental right to equality under Article 12(1). Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing; the 1st Respondentâ€™s disregard for the binding nature of the Administrative Appeals Tribunal order (Issue 1) was the mechanism through which the discriminatory treatment (Issue 2) was executed. The lack of a rational basis for the discrimination rendered the administrative decision to annul the promotion both substantively unfair and procedurally invalid. Conclusion The Court held that the Petitionerâ€™s fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution were violated. The 1st Respondent is directed to give effect to the Administrative Appeals Tribunalâ€™s order and to grant the Petitioner a promotion to Class I on a supernumerary basis in accordance with the relevant circular. The application is allowed. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Public Service Commission — Administrative Appeals Tribunal — Promotion to Class I — Antedating of appointment — Back wages — Discrimination — Arbitrary action		SC/FR/303/2013	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_303_2013.pdf
sc-appeal-175-2016	18 November 2022	Kodituwakku v. Piyadasa and Others	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, J.; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; P. Padman Surasena, J.	Title to land — Adverse possession — Prescriptive title — License — Burden of proof — Paper title — Exercise of title rights — Forged document — Cursus curiae	Facts The Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent instituted an action in the District Court of Kegalle seeking a declaration of title and the ejectment of the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant from the property known as Arambahena. The Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent claimed that her father, Alexander Reid, was the original owner who transferred the land to his three sons, including the 2nd and 3rd Defendants-Respondents, via Deed No. 5746. Upon the death of one brother, his share devolved to the remaining siblings. The Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent alleged that the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant occupied the land under a license granted by Alexander Reid via an informal agreement marked P-2. The 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant denied the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent's title, claiming he occupied a different property called Egodahena, which he acquired via Deed No. 3813 from one Punchi Banda. He further asserted title through prescription based on long-term possession. The District Court dismissed the action, finding the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent failed to prove title and that the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant had established possession. The Court of Appeal subsequently set aside the District Court judgment, holding that the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent had proven her title. The 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law by granting the relief prayed for by the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent in the plaint. Whether the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent successfully established her title to the land in a rei vindicatio action. Whether the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant established a prescriptive title to the land under Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance. Applicable Law Statutes: Prescription Ordinance No. 22 Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 17 Cases Referred to: D.A. Wanigaratne v. Juwanis Appuhamy - [65-nlr-167] Dharmadasa v. Jayasena - [1997/v3-sri-lr-327] Hariette v. Pathmasiri - [1996/v1-sri-lr-358] Hassan v. Romanishamy - [66-clw-vol-lxvi] de Silva v. Commissioner General of Inland Revenue - [80-nlr-292] Jayasinghe Pathman v. Korale Kankanamge Somapala - [sc-appeal-06/2014] The Sri Lanka Ports Authority and Another v. Jugolinija-Boal East - [1981/v1-sri-lr-18] Analysis Issue 1: Proof of Title Rule applied: In a rei vindicatio action, the burden of proof lies on the plaintiff to establish the title pleaded. Court's reasoning: The Court examined the documentary evidence, including Deed P-1, and evidence of the exercise of ownership rights by the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondentâ€™s predecessor, Alexander Reid. This included previous lease agreements and court decrees (P-5, P-6) where Reidâ€™s ownership was recognized. The Court found that the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent and her predecessors actively protected their rights, thereby establishing her title as a co-owner. Finding: The Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent successfully proved her title to the land. Issue 2: Prescriptive Title Rule applied: Section 3 of the Prescription Ordinance No. 22; the principle that possession must be hostile, adverse, and irreconcilable with the rights of the true owner. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant entered the land as a licensee under agreement P-2. Mere occupation or cultivation is insufficient for prescription; the possession must be with the intention of holding as owner. The Court found that the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant failed to show his possession was hostile to the true owner, as he was a mere occupant. Finding: The 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant failed to establish prescriptive title. Issue 3: Admissibility of Document P-2 Rule applied: The cursus curiae of original civil courts and Section 3(a)(ii) of the Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 17. Court's reasoning: The document P-2 was produced at trial and not objected to at the close of the case. Under the established cursus curiae and the amended Civil Procedure Code, such documents are admitted as evidence without requiring further proof. The 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellantâ€™s attempt to challenge the validity of P-2 was rejected. Finding: Document P-2 is accepted as proven evidence. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing: the establishment of the Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent's title and the validity of the license agreement (P-2) directly negate the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant's claim of adverse possession. Because the 1st Defendant-Respondent-Appellant was a licensee, his possession could not be "hostile" or "adverse" to the owner, rendering the prescriptive claim legally unsustainable. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed, and the judgment of the Court of Appeal is affirmed. The Plaintiff-Appellant-Respondent is entitled to the relief prayed for in the plaint. Keywords Title to land — Adverse possession — Prescriptive title — License — Burden of proof — Paper title — Exercise of title rights — Forged document — Cursus curiae		SC/APPEAL/175/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_175_2016.pdf
sc-spl-la-224-2020	18 November 2022	Sri Lanka Telecome PLC v. Wijeweera	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Kumudini Wickremasinghe, J.	Special leave to appeal — Supreme Court Rules 1990 — Mandatory rules — Tender of documents — Certified copy of judgment — Due diligence — Extraordinary delay — Covid pandemic — Political unrest	Facts The Petitioner, Sri Lanka Telecom PLC, filed an application for special leave to appeal against a judgment of the Court of Appeal dated 21st September 2020. Upon the matter coming up for support, the Petitioner sought leave to tender a copy of the impugned Court of Appeal judgment, which had not been filed with the original application. The Petitioner-Respondent raised preliminary objections, arguing that the Petitioner failed to reserve the right to tender the judgment at a later stage and that the application to tender the document was made after an excessive delay of two years and eighteen days. The Petitioner contended that the delay was attributable to the COVID-19 pandemic and political unrest, and that the Respondent was already aware of the contents of the judgment. Issues Whether the failure to tender a copy of the impugned judgment with the petition for special leave to appeal constitutes a fatal non-compliance with Rule 2 of the Supreme Court Rules 1990. Whether the Petitioner demonstrated sufficient cause under the proviso to Rule 2 of the Supreme Court Rules 1990 to justify the late filing of the impugned judgment. Applicable Law Statutes: Supreme Court Rules 1990 Cases Referred to: Mary Nona v. Fransina - [1988/v2-sri-lr-250] Mohamed Haniffa Rasheed Ali v. Khan Mohamed Ali - [Mohamed Haniffa Rasheed Ali v. Khan Mohamed Ali and another (2)] Ceylon Electricity Board v. Ranjith Fonseka - [2008/v1-sri-lr-1] Attorney General v. Williams Silva - [1992/v1-sri-lr-44] Analysis Issue 1: Mandatory nature of Rule 2 Rule applied: Rule 2 of the Supreme Court Rules 1990. Court's reasoning: The court held that Rule 2 makes it mandatory for a petitioner to file a certified or uncertified copy of the impugned judgment or order at the time of filing the petition. The court emphasized that this requirement is essential for the Supreme Court to ascertain the legality of the order under review. Citing Mohamed Haniffa Rasheed Ali v. Khan Mohamed Ali, the court noted that procedural rules are enacted for the due administration of justice and must be strictly followed, even by the State. Finding: The failure to tender the judgment with the petition constitutes a non-compliance with a mandatory procedural requirement. Issue 2: Justification for late filing Rule applied: Proviso to Rule 2 of the Supreme Court Rules 1990. Court's reasoning: The proviso allows for late filing only if the petitioner prays for permission to tender the document at a later stage and satisfies the court that they exercised due diligence and were prevented by circumstances beyond their control. The court found that the Petitioner failed to specifically pray for such permission in the petition. Furthermore, the court rejected the argument that the COVID-19 pandemic or political unrest caused the delay, noting that the Petitioner was able to file other documents during the same period. The delay of two years and eighteen days was deemed extraordinary and inexcusable. Finding: The Petitioner failed to satisfy the requirements of the proviso to Rule 2, and the delay was not justified. Interaction of Issues The findings on these issues are cumulative; the mandatory nature of Rule 2 established the necessity of the document, while the failure to satisfy the proviso rendered the Petitioner's attempt to cure the defect legally insufficient. The court's determination that the rule is mandatory precluded the court from exercising discretion to overlook the procedural lapse, especially given the lack of due diligence. Conclusion The preliminary objections are upheld. The application for special leave to appeal is dismissed. Keywords Special leave to appeal — Supreme Court Rules 1990 — Mandatory rules — Tender of documents — Certified copy of judgment — Due diligence — Extraordinary delay — Covid pandemic — Political unrest		SC/SPL LA/224/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_spl_la_224_2020.pdf
sc-fr-23-2021	18 November 2022	Maduwanthi v. Perera and Others	Janak De Silva, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; K.K. Wickremasinghe, J.; Janak De Silva, J.	Transfer of public officers — Annual transfer scheme — Legitimate expectation — Exigency of service — Malice — Conflict of interest — Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Public Service Commission Rules — Investigation of misconduct	Facts The Petitioner, a Grade I officer of the Sri Lanka Administrative Service, served as the Divisional Secretary of Matale from 2014 until her transfer in 2021. In 2019, she applied for an annual transfer, requesting a posting to Dambulla, Ukuwela, or Gangawatakorale. Although an initial transfer order designated her for Dambulla, this was deferred for one year. Subsequently, the 12th Respondent recommended against her appointment to Dambulla due to a pending inquiry regarding a land transaction involving the Petitioner's husband. On 05.01.2021, the Petitioner was transferred to the Internal Administration Section of the Ministry of Public Services, Provincial Councils and Local Government. The Petitioner challenged this transfer, alleging it was made without exigency of service, lacked Public Service Commission approval, and was motivated by malice. The Respondents contended that the transfer was necessary to facilitate investigations into the Petitioner's alleged misconduct, including the Dambulla land transaction and other administrative irregularities. Issues Whether the transfer of the Petitioner to the Internal Administration Section of the Ministry of Public Services, Provincial Councils and Local Government violated the Constitution or the Public Service Commission Procedural Rules. Whether the Petitioner had a legitimate expectation to be appointed as the Divisional Secretary of Dambulla. Whether the transfer was tainted by malice on the part of the 1st Respondent. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 14(1)(g), 17, 126. Public Administration Circular No. 18/2019. Public Service Commission Procedural Rules, Rules 218-III, 222-III. Cases Referred to: L. C. H. Peiris v. The Commissioner of Inland Revenue - [65-nlr-457] Kumaranatunga v. Samarasinghe - [1983/v2-sri-lr-63] Edirisuriya v. Navaratnam - [1985/v1-sri-lr-100] Seneviratne v. Urban Council, Kegalle - [2001/v3-sri-lr-105] Liyanage v. Ratnasiri - [2013/v1-sri-lr-6] Jayasinghe v. The National Institute of Fisheries and Nautical Engineering - [2002/v1-sri-lr-277] Gascoigne v. Gascoigne - [1918/1-kb-223] Tinker v. Tinker - [1970/1-all-er-540] Noble Resources International Pte Limited v. Hon. Ranjith Siyambalapitiya - [sc-appeal-394/2015] Analysis Issue 1: Validity of the transfer Rule applied: Public Service Commission Procedural Rules 218-III and 222-III. Court's reasoning: The court found that the transfer was initiated to facilitate investigations into alleged misconduct. Under Rule 222-III, an appointing authority may transfer an officer on disciplinary grounds if their presence in a station might obstruct an investigation. Even if the transfer order cited the wrong provision, the court held that an order is valid if it is supported by any correct empowering provision. Finding: The transfer was lawful and in accordance with the Public Service Commission Procedural Rules. Issue 2: Legitimate expectation Rule applied: Annual Transfer Circular (P11). Court's reasoning: The court determined that the Public Service Commission never issued a final order appointing the Petitioner to Dambulla. The initial transfer order was deferred, and subsequent investigations into a conflict of interest regarding state land in Dambulla provided a valid administrative basis to deny the appointment. Finding: The Petitioner did not have a legitimate expectation to be appointed to Dambulla. Issue 3: Allegations of malice Rule applied: Principles of evidence and the Audi alteram partem rule. Court's reasoning: The court rejected the Petitioner's evidence of tape recordings as they were not produced with the petition, denying the 1st Respondent an opportunity to respond. Furthermore, the court found that the Respondents provided cogent evidence of misconduct regarding the Dambulla land transaction, which justified the administrative actions taken against the Petitioner independently of any alleged personal animosity. Finding: The transfer was not a malicious act. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected; the Petitionerâ€™s failure to disclose material facts regarding her husband's business interests in Dambulla undermined her claim of legitimate expectation and her credibility. Her unmeritorious conduct in the land transaction justified the administrative decision to transfer her to prevent interference with investigations, thereby rendering the transfer lawful under the Procedural Rules and negating the claim of malice. Conclusion The application is dismissed. The court further directed the Registrar to forward the pleadings to the Commission to Investigate Allegations of Bribery or Corruption for further investigation. Keywords Transfer of public officers — Annual transfer scheme — Legitimate expectation — Exigency of service — Malice — Conflict of interest — Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Public Service Commission Rules — Investigation of misconduct		SC/FR/23/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_23_2021.pdf
sc-appeal-180-2011	21 November 2022	Sanjeewani v. Hewavitharanage Podimenike	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	S. Thurairaja, J; Kumuduni Wickremasinghe, J; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Constructive trust — Trusts Ordinance — Section 83 — Failure to cite section in judgment — Prejudice to substantial rights — Failure of justice — Revision of judgment — District Court judgment — High Court decision	Facts The Plaintiff, Wedikkarayalage Nirosha Sanjeewani, instituted an action in the District Court of Kegalle against the Defendant, Hewavitharanage Podimenike, seeking a declaration of title to a land, ejectment of the Defendant, and damages. The Plaintiff asserted title based on a deed of transfer and a subsequent deed of rectification executed by the Defendant. The Defendant contested the action, arguing that the deed was not an outright transfer but security for a loan provided by the Plaintiff's husband. The Defendant claimed that the Plaintiff held the property subject to a constructive trust as there was no intention to transfer the beneficial interest. Following a trial that spanned nearly a decade, the District Judge delivered a judgment in favor of the Defendant. The Plaintiff appealed this decision to the High Court of Civil Appeal of Kegalle. The High Court set aside the District Court judgment and ordered a retrial, reasoning that the District Judge failed to specify the section of the Trusts Ordinance under which the constructive trust was established. The Defendant subsequently appealed the High Court's decision to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the failure of the District Judge to cite the specific section of the Trusts Ordinance in the judgment rendered the judgment invalid or fatal. Whether the High Court erred in setting aside the District Court judgment and ordering a retrial on a point of law that was not raised by either party and without affording the parties an opportunity to be heard. Applicable Law Statutes: Trusts Ordinance (Chapter IX) Civil Procedure Code (Section 149) Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka (Article 138) Rent Act (Section 22(7)) Excise Ordinance (Section 26) Income Tax Ordinance (Section 80(1), Section 64(2)(b), Section 65) Cases Referred to: Wijewardena v. Lenora - [60-nlr-457] Bernedette Valangenberg v. Happuarachchige Anthony - [1990/v1-sri-lr-190] Hammed v. Cassim - [1996/v2-sri-lr-30] Solicitor-General v. Perera - [17-nlr-413] Peiris v. The Commissioner of Inland Revenue - [65-nlr-457] Leechman & Co. Ltd. v. Rangalla Consolidated Ltd - [1981/v2-sri-lr-373] Kumaranatunga v. Samarasinghe - [1983/v2-sri-lr-63] Jayawardane v. Ran Aweera - [2004/v3-sri-lr-37] Analysis Issue 1: Failure to cite the Trusts Ordinance Rule applied: The principle that an exercise of power is referable to a jurisdiction that confers validity upon it, even if the wrong provision is cited or no provision is cited at all, provided the court has the authority to act. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the failure to mention Section 83 of the Trusts Ordinance in the District Court judgment was a technicality that did not affect the legality of the decision. The trial proceeded on the clear understanding that the Defendant was asserting a constructive trust, and the District Judge provided sufficient reasons for his findings. Citing the wrong section or failing to cite a section does not invalidate a judgment if the court had the jurisdiction to grant the relief. Finding: The failure to cite the specific section was not fatal to the judgment. Issue 2: Procedural fairness and the High Court's decision Rule applied: The principle of audi alteram partem and the adversarial nature of the justice system. Court's reasoning: The High Court erred by deciding the appeal on a point not raised by the parties without giving them an opportunity to be heard. While a judge may raise a point of law, it must be done with restraint. The High Court's decision to order a retrial based on a technicality that caused no prejudice to the parties violated the right to be heard and failed to adhere to the proviso of Article 138 of the Constitution, which prohibits reversing judgments for irregularities that do not occasion a failure of justice. Finding: The High Court erred in its procedure and its decision to order a retrial. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected because the High Court's procedural error (Issue 2) was predicated on its incorrect legal assessment of the District Court's omission (Issue 1). By incorrectly identifying the omission of a statutory citation as a fatal error, the High Court improperly invoked its appellate power to order a retrial, thereby violating the principles of procedural fairness and the constitutional mandate to avoid reversing judgments that do not cause a miscarriage of justice. Conclusion The Supreme Court allowed the appeal, set aside the judgment of the High Court, and restored the judgment of the District Court. The Defendant-Respondent-Appellant was awarded costs in all three courts. Keywords Constructive trust — Trusts Ordinance — Section 83 — Failure to cite section in judgment — Prejudice to substantial rights — Failure of justice — Revision of judgment — District Court judgment — High Court decision		SC/APPEAL/180/2011	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_180_2011.pdf
sc-appeal-133-2015	21 November 2022	Film Locations (Private Limited) v. Sri Lanka Mahaweli Authority and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Kumudini Wickramasinghe, J; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Maintainability of action — Misjoinder of parties — Derivative action — Company Law — Civil Procedure Code — Essential party — Reliefs prayed for — Fundamental rights	Facts The Plaintiff, Film Locations (Private Limited), instituted an action in the District Court of Colombo against the Sri Lanka Mahaweli Authority, the Resident Project Manager of the Victoria Office, and Taprobane Studio Ranch (Private) Limited. The Plaintiff sought a declaration that the first defendant was bound by an agreement, a declaration that the third defendant was entitled to possession of certain lands, and various injunctions to prevent the first and second defendants from interfering with the third defendant's possession. The first and second defendants filed an answer seeking dismissal, arguing that the Plaintiff had not disclosed a cause of action against them and that any potential cause of action belonged to the third defendant, a separate legal entity. During the trial, the Plaintiff moved to discharge the third defendant from the proceedings, which the District Court allowed. Subsequently, the first and second defendants raised a preliminary objection, contending that the action could not be maintained as the third defendant, an essential party, had been removed. The District Court overruled this objection, but the High Court of Civil Appeal reversed this decision and dismissed the action. The Plaintiff appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in holding that no cause of action survived for the Plaintiff to proceed with the case after the third defendant was discharged. Whether the Plaintiff could maintain the action without the third defendant as a party, given the provisions of Sections 17, 18, and 22 of the Civil Procedure Code. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code, Sections 17, 18, 22, 93(2) Civil Procedure Code (Amendment) Act No. 9 of 1991 Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Survival of cause of action Rule applied: The fundamental principle of Company Law that a company is a separate legal entity and that a party cannot sue on behalf of another entity without standing (e.g., a derivative action). Court's reasoning: The Court observed that the Plaintiffâ€™s pleadings explicitly stated that the third defendant was an essential party. The reliefs sought were primarily for the benefit of the third defendant. Once the third defendant was discharged, the issues raised by the Plaintiff became moot because they concerned the rights of an entity no longer before the Court. The Court cannot adjudicate the rights of a non-party, and the Plaintiff lacked the legal standing to represent the third defendantâ€™s interests. Finding: The High Court did not err; no cause of action survived for the Plaintiff because the action was fundamentally predicated on the rights of the third defendant, who was no longer a party. Issue 2: Maintainability and procedural objections Rule applied: Sections 17, 18(1), and 22 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: Regarding Section 17, the Court held that while an action is not defeated by non-joinder, the Court can only adjudicate the rights of parties actually present. Since the Plaintiff had no standing to assert the third defendant's rights, the action could not proceed. Regarding Section 18(1), the Court noted that it is not under a duty to add parties ex mero motu when the Plaintiff himself moved to discharge the necessary party. Furthermore, the Court emphasized that Section 18 must be read with Section 93(2), which restricts the addition of parties after the trial has commenced. Finally, the Court rejected the argument based on Section 22, finding that the defendants were justified in raising the objection once the Plaintiffâ€™s actions rendered the suit fundamentally misconceived. Finding: The High Court correctly upheld the objection, as the action was procedurally and legally unsustainable. Interaction of Issues The findings on these issues are mutually reinforcing. The determination that the Plaintiff lacked the legal standing to sue on behalf of the third defendant (Issue 1) directly informs the interpretation of the procedural provisions in the Civil Procedure Code (Issue 2). Because the action was inherently flawed due to the lack of standing and the absence of an essential party, the procedural protections against dismissal for non-joinder could not be invoked by the Plaintiff to save the action. Conclusion The Supreme Court answered the questions of law in the negative and dismissed the appeal. The judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal is affirmed, and the action stands dismissed with costs. Keywords Maintainability of action — Misjoinder of parties — Derivative action — Company Law — Civil Procedure Code — Essential party — Reliefs prayed for — Fundamental rights		SC/APPEAL/133/2015	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_133_2015.pdf
sc-appeal-154-2017	21 November 2022	Wijesinghe v. Wickramarathne	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Partition action — Right of way — Prescription — Actio negatoria — Soil rights — Final decree — Amendment of pleadings — Issues in appeal — Pure question of law — Mixed question of fact and law	Facts The Plaintiff, Stella Gwendelline Hycinth Wijesinghe, instituted an action against the Defendant, Lalith Wickramarathne, in the District Court of Nugegoda seeking a declaration that lot 4, as defined in the final decree of a partition action, belonged to the parties of that action and that the Defendant possessed no right of way over said lot. The Defendant filed an amended answer seeking the dismissal of the action and asserted a cross-claim for prescriptive title to lot 4 or, alternatively, a right of way by necessity. During the trial, it was admitted that lot 4 had been designated as a road for the parties to the partition action by the final decree. The Defendant was not a party to that partition action. At the trial, the Defendant shifted his position from the pleadings to argue that lot 4 was a public road. The District Court entered judgment in favor of the Plaintiff. The Defendant appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal of Mt. Lavinia, where he abandoned his previous defenses and argued for the first time that the Plaintiffâ€™s action was an actio negatoria, which requires the plaintiff to possess soil rights. The High Court accepted this new argument, set aside the District Court judgment, and directed that judgment be entered for the Defendant. The Plaintiff subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by allowing the Defendant to introduce a new case on appeal that was not raised in the pleadings or issues at the trial. Whether the argument that the Plaintiffâ€™s action was an actio negatoria constitutes a pure question of law that may be raised for the first time on appeal. Whether the allottees of the partition action possess soil rights to lot 4, which was designated as a common road in the final decree. Applicable Law Statutes: Partition Law Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Introduction of a new case on appeal Rule applied: The principle that a party cannot present a new case before an appellate court that differs from the case presented at the trial court, unless the new ground is a pure question of law. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that the Defendant changed his position multiple times: first from a claim of prescriptive title in the pleadings to a claim of a public road in the issues, and finally to an actio negatoria argument on appeal. The Court held that a party cannot change their position to suit the occasion. Because the actio negatoria argument was not raised at the trial, the Plaintiff had no opportunity to lead evidence to address it. Finding: The High Court erred in allowing the Defendant to introduce a new case on appeal. Issue 2: Nature of the new issue Rule applied: The distinction between a pure question of law and a mixed question of fact and law. Court's reasoning: The Court determined that classifying the Plaintiffâ€™s action as an actio negatoria required an analysis of the pleadings and the evidence led at trial. Therefore, the characterization of the action was not a pure question of law but a mixed question of fact and law. Finding: The new issue raised by the Defendant was not a pure question of law and should not have been entertained on appeal. Issue 3: Soil rights to lot 4 Rule applied: The final decree of partition. Court's reasoning: The Court examined the final decree, which stated that lot 4 was a reservation for a road to be held in common by the allottees. The Court rejected the notion that the allottees lost their soil rights to the road portion of the land. It concluded that the allottees retained soil rights to lot 4 in common, and the road was intended for their benefit, not for outsiders. Finding: The allottees of the partition action possess soil rights to lot 4. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected because the determination that the actio negatoria argument was not a pure question of law rendered the High Court's intervention improper. Furthermore, even if the Court had considered the merits of the actio negatoria argument, the finding that the allottees retained soil rights to lot 4 would have defeated the Defendantâ€™s contention that the Plaintiff lacked the necessary standing to bring the action. Conclusion The Supreme Court set aside the judgment of the High Court and restored the judgment of the District Court. The appeal was allowed with costs fixed at two hundred and fifty thousand rupees. Keywords Partition action — Right of way — Prescription — Actio negatoria — Soil rights — Final decree — Amendment of pleadings — Issues in appeal — Pure question of law — Mixed question of fact and law		SC/APPEAL/154/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_154_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-233-2017	21 November 2022	Yakupitiya and Yakupitiya v. Don Buddhadasa Yakupitiya	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Usufructuary mortgage — Discharge of mortgage — Existence of mortgaged property — Compensation for improvements — Interpretation of mortgage bond — District Court judgment — High Court of Civil Appeal	Facts Kukule Kankanamge Chandrasena Yakupitiya and Edirisinghe Athukoralage Pushpalatha Yakupitiya filed an action in the District Court of Matugama against Liyanage Don Buddhadasa Yakupitiya. The plaintiffs sought to discharge a usufructuary mortgage, marked as P3, which was executed in favor of the defendant to secure a loan of Rs. 20,000. Under the terms of the mortgage, the defendant was granted possession of two boutique rooms in lieu of interest. The plaintiffs requested that upon repayment of the loan, the defendant be ejected from the premises. The defendant filed an answer requesting the dismissal of the action or, alternatively, a declaration of ownership over the boutique rooms marked 1, 2, and 3 in plan V1, or compensation for improvements made to the property. The District Court entered judgment in favor of the plaintiffs, which was subsequently affirmed by the High Court of Civil Appeal. The defendant appealed to the Supreme Court. During the proceedings, it was established that the defendant had demolished one of the original boutique rooms and constructed three new rooms, identified as 1, 2, and 3 in plan V1. The surveyorâ€™s report, marked as V3, indicated that these rooms were improvements made upon existing structures rather than entirely new constructions. Issues Whether the plaintiffs could maintain the action on the strength of the usufructuary mortgage despite the defendant's claim that the original boutique rooms were no longer in existence. Whether the defendant is entitled to compensation for the construction of the buildings marked 1, 2, and 3 in plan V1. Applicable Law Statutes: Not specified Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Maintainability of the action Rule applied: The court applied the principle that a usufructuary mortgage remains enforceable even if the physical structures subject to the mortgage undergo improvements or modifications, provided the underlying interest in the property remains. Court's reasoning: The court examined the surveyorâ€™s report V3, which was produced by the defendant. The report clarified that the rooms marked 1, 2, and 3 in plan V1 were not entirely new structures but were improvements made upon the existing structures that were the subject of the mortgage. Consequently, the court rejected the defendant's argument that the non-existence of the original rooms precluded the plaintiffs from maintaining the action. Finding: The court answered the question in the affirmative, confirming that the plaintiffs could maintain the action. Issue 2: Entitlement to compensation Rule applied: The court applied the principle of equity regarding compensation for improvements made to property by a possessor, as requested by the defendant in his pleadings. Court's reasoning: The defendant sought compensation for the improvements made to the property, specifically the rooms marked 1, 2, and 3 in plan V1. The court noted that the defendant had explicitly prayed for such compensation in his answer, calculated at Rs. 75,000 based on plan V1. The plaintiffs' counsel agreed to pay this amount during the argument. The court found this to be a fair and reasonable resolution. Finding: The court answered the question in the affirmative, holding that the defendant is entitled to Rs. 75,000 as compensation for improvements, in addition to the Rs. 20,000 loan repayment and accrued interest. Interaction of Issues The findings are complementary; the courtâ€™s determination that the action was maintainable (Issue 1) allowed for the resolution of the dispute through the discharge of the mortgage, while the finding on compensation (Issue 2) ensured that the defendant was equitably reimbursed for the improvements made to the mortgaged property, thereby resolving the entire controversy between the parties. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed subject to the variation that the plaintiffs shall pay the defendant Rs. 75,000 as compensation for improvements in addition to the loan amount. No costs are awarded. Keywords Usufructuary mortgage — Discharge of mortgage — Existence of mortgaged property — Compensation for improvements — Interpretation of mortgage bond — District Court judgment — High Court of Civil Appeal		SC/APPEAL/233/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_233_2017.pdf
sc-fr-411-2021	21 November 2022	Denethi v. Rupasinghe and Others	Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J	Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Fundamental rights — Police conduct — Attorney-at-law's professional entitlements — Obstruction of professional duties — Dispute resolution by police — Regulatory framework for police inquiries	Facts The Petitioner is an Attorney-at-Law who was retained by the 7th Respondent to represent her at an inquiry regarding a land dispute at the Boralesgamuwa Police Station. Upon arriving at the station, the Petitioner and his client were directed to the office of the 3rd Respondent, where the 1st Respondent was present. After the Petitioner introduced himself and his professional capacity, the 1st Respondent ordered him to leave the room. When the Petitioner refused, the 1st Respondent allegedly acted in a hostile and abusive manner. The Petitioner claims that the 1st Respondent threatened him with arrest for obstruction of duty, threatened to place him in a cell, stated that the police would object to his appearance in court, and ordered other officers to seize his mobile phone. The Petitioner recorded the interaction and submitted a transcript of the event to the Court. The Petitioner alleged that this conduct infringed his fundamental rights under Articles 11, 12(1), and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the conduct of the 1st Respondent towards the Petitioner constituted an infringement of the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Articles 11, 12(1), and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Whether there is a need for a comprehensive, legally enforceable regulatory framework governing police inquiries and the role of Attorneys-at-Law in such proceedings. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 11, 12(1), 14(1)(g), 17, 126 Police Ordinance, Section 55 Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Infringement of Fundamental Rights Rule applied: Articles 11, 12(1), and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka. Court's reasoning: The Court reviewed the transcript of the interaction between the Petitioner and the 1st Respondent. The Court observed that the 1st Respondent acted in an offensive, improper, and undignified manner. This conduct effectively hampered the Petitioner from discharging his professional services on behalf of his client. The Court noted that such obstructions not only impact the rights of the Attorney-at-Law but also potentially infringe upon the rights of suspects to access legal counsel. Finding: The 1st Respondent's conduct was improper and interfered with the Petitioner's professional entitlements. Issue 2: Need for a Regulatory Framework Rule applied: Section 55 of the Police Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that the Police currently lack a clear legal, regulatory, or administrative framework for conducting inquiries into civil disputes. While such inquiries are intended to prevent the escalation of disputes, the absence of rules leads to arbitrary conduct. The Court, with the agreement of the Petitioner, the Senior Deputy Solicitor General, and the President of the Bar Association of Sri Lanka, determined that a formal framework is necessary to govern the conduct of police inquiries, the participation of legal counsel, and the rights of suspects to access attorneys. Finding: The Inspector General of Police is directed to establish a committee to formulate a comprehensive regulatory framework to be promulgated as Rules under the Police Ordinance. Interaction of Issues The Court's finding that the 1st Respondentâ€™s conduct was improper directly necessitates the creation of a regulatory framework. By addressing the lack of clear procedures, the Court aims to prevent future infringements of the type experienced by the Petitioner, thereby reconciling the police's role in dispute resolution with the professional rights of Attorneys-at-Law. Conclusion The Court directed the Inspector General of Police to conduct an independent inquiry into the incident and report the findings to the National Police Commission. Furthermore, the Court ordered the establishment of a committee to formulate a comprehensive regulatory framework for police inquiries and the rights of legal representation, with a report on progress due by 31st March 2023. Keywords Fundamental rights — Police conduct — Attorney-at-law's professional entitlements — Obstruction of professional duties — Dispute resolution by police — Regulatory framework for police inquiries		SC/FR/411/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_411_2021.pdf
sc-appeal-78-2021	21 November 2022	Galagedara v. Samaraweera and Samaraweera	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Ex parte trial — Default judgment — Civil Procedure Code — Section 86(2) — Section 88(1) — Mortgage Act — Purging default — Appeal against ex parte judgment — Revisionary jurisdiction	Facts The Plaintiff filed an action in the District Court of Bandarawela against the two Defendants to recover a sum of Rs. 200,000.00 lent to the mother of the Defendants, secured by a Mortgage Bond. Upon the failure of the Defendants to file an answer, the District Court fixed the matter for an ex parte trial pursuant to section 84 of the Civil Procedure Code. The Defendants subsequently attempted to file an answer by making an oral application under section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code, which the District Court refused, noting that the appropriate procedure for relief was under section 86 of the Civil Procedure Code. Following an ex parte trial conducted via affidavit evidence, the District Court dismissed the action. The Plaintiff appealed the dismissal to the High Court of Civil Appeal of Badulla. The High Court set aside the District Court judgment and directed that judgment be entered in favor of the Plaintiff. The 1st Defendant then filed a leave to appeal application before the Supreme Court against the High Court judgment. The Plaintiff raised a preliminary objection, arguing that the 1st Defendant could not maintain the appeal without first purging her default in the District Court as required by section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code. Issues Whether the 1st Defendant is precluded from maintaining an appeal against the High Court judgment without first purging her default in the District Court under section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code. Whether section 59 of the Mortgage Act No. 6 prevents a defendant in a hypothecary action from utilizing the provisions of section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code to purge default. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code Mortgage Act No. 6 Interpretation Ordinance No. 6 Cases Referred to: Arumugam v. Kumaraswamy - [2000/v3-sri-lr-55] Jana Shakthi Insurance v. Dasanayake - [2005/v1-sri-lr-299] Penchi v. Sirisena - [2012/v1-sri-lr-402] Hotel Galaxy (Pvt) Ltd v. Mercantile Hotels Management Ltd - [1987/v1-sri-lr-5] Loku Menika v. Selenduhamy - [48-nlr-353] Habibu Lebbe v. Punchi Etana - [3-clr-85] Caldera v. Santiagopulle - [22-nlr-155] Weeratne v. Secretary, D.C. Badulla - [2-clr-180] Dingirihamy v. Don Bastian - [65-nlr-549] Bank of Ceylon v. Liverpool Marine & General Insurance Co Ltd - [66-nlr-472] Nagappan v. Lankabarana Estates Ltd - [75-nlr-488] Mrs. Sirimavo Bandaranayake v. Times of Ceylon Limited - [1995/v1-sri-lr-22] Sitthi Maleena v. Nihal Ignatius Perera - [1994/v3-sri-lr-270] Australanka Exporters Pvt Ltd v. Indian Bank - [2001/v2-sri-lr-156] Analysis Issue 1: Maintainability of appeal without purging default Rule applied: Section 88(1) of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The Court held that section 88(1) creates a statutory bar against filing an appeal against a judgment entered upon default. The 1st Defendantâ€™s argument that the judgment ceased to be a default judgment because it was dismissed on the merits is rejected; the default status persists until it is formally purged. The Court emphasized that a party seeking to challenge an ex parte order must first apply to the court that made it. The Court further noted that section 839 of the Civil Procedure Code is inapplicable as it pertains to the District Court and cannot be invoked when specific provisions for relief exist. Finding: The 1st Defendant cannot maintain the appeal without first purging the default in the District Court. Issue 2: Applicability of Mortgage Act to default procedures Rule applied: Section 59 of the Mortgage Act No. 6 and Section 16(1) of the Interpretation Ordinance No. 6. Court's reasoning: The Court clarified that the version of section 59 of the Mortgage Act found in the 1980 unofficial revised edition is incorrect and does not represent the law. Relying on Sitthi Maleena v. Nihal Ignatius Perera, the Court held that the default of a defendant in a hypothecary action is governed by the current provisions of Chapter XII of the Civil Procedure Code. Under section 16(1) of the Interpretation Ordinance, references to repealed procedures in the Mortgage Act are deemed to refer to the current corresponding provisions. Finding: Section 59 of the Mortgage Act does not bar the 1st Defendant from utilizing section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code to purge default. Interaction of Issues The resolution of the second issue confirms that the 1st Defendant had a viable statutory remedy available in the District Court under section 86(2) of the Civil Procedure Code. Because this remedy was available and not pursued, the statutory bar under section 88(1) remains fully operative, reinforcing the conclusion that the appeal before the Supreme Court is premature and unsustainable. Conclusion The preliminary objection is upheld. The appeal is dismissed with costs. Keywords Ex parte trial — Default judgment — Civil Procedure Code — Section 86(2) — Section 88(1) — Mortgage Act — Purging default — Appeal against ex parte judgment — Revisionary jurisdiction		SC/APPEAL/78/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_78_2021.pdf
sc-fr-46-2021	23 November 2022	Padmasiri and Others v. Wickramaratne and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; Kumudini Wickremasinghe, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Public Service Commission — Scheme of Recruitment — Promotions in the police force — Seniority — Merit — Special promotion — Unfettered discretion — Arbitrary decision-making	Facts The Petitioners, 164 Sub Inspectors of Police, filed fundamental rights applications challenging the Scheme of Recruitment (SOR) marked P7, which governed promotions from the rank of Sub Inspector to Inspector of Police. The Petitioners alleged that the SOR violated their fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. The SOR introduced four categories for promotion: seniority, limited competitive examination, merit, and special promotion. The Petitioners contended that seniority was not given due recognition, the allocation of marks for good entries in the structured interview was discriminatory against officers in the functional division, and the special promotion category granted arbitrary and unfettered discretion to the Inspector General of Police. The Respondents raised a preliminary objection regarding the time bar under Article 126(2) of the Constitution, asserting that the application was filed more than one month after the publication of the SOR on the official police website. The Petitioners maintained they only became aware of the SOR on 05.02.2021 and filed the application on 25.02.2021. The Court consolidated this application with SC/FR/55/2021. Issues Whether the application is barred by the one-month time limit prescribed under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Whether the seniority, merit, and limited competitive examination categories in the SOR marked P7 violate Article 12(1) and Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Whether the special promotion category in the SOR marked P7, which grants discretion to the Inspector General of Police, violates Article 12(1) and Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 3, 4(d), 12(1), 14(1)(g), 15, 17, 126(1), 126(2), 126(4). Prescription Ordinance, Section 10. Supreme Court Rules 1990, Rules 44(6), 45(6). Cases Referred to: Ranaweera v. Sub Inspector Wilson Siriwardena - [2008/v1-sri-lr-260] Ranasinghe v. De Silva - [78-nlr-500] Kirthisinghe v. Perera - [23-nlr-279] Edirisuriya v. Navaratnam - [1985/v1-sri-lr-100] Siriwardena v. Brigadier Rodrigo - [1986/v1-sri-lr-384] Dayaratne v. National Savings Bank - [2002/v3-sri-lr-116] Gamaethige v. Siriwardena - [1988/v1-sri-lr-384] Mutuweeran v. The State - [5-sri-skanthas-law-reports-126] Azath Salley v. Colombo Municipal Council - [2009/v1-sri-lr-365] Perera v. Cyril Ranatunga - [1993/v1-sri-lr-39] Dharmaratne v. Sri Lanka Export Development Board - [1995/v2-sri-lr-324] State of Mysore v. Syed Mahmood - [1968-air-1113] Wasantha Disanayake v. Secretary, Ministry of Public Administration and Home Affairs - [2015/v1-sri-lr-362] Samarasinghe v. The Bank of Ceylon - [1978-79-80/v1-sri-lr-221] Jayasinghe v. The National Institute of Fisheries and Nautical Engineering - [2004/v1-sri-lr-230] Sumanadasa v. Attorney General - [2006/v3-sri-lr-202] Ganeshanantham v. Vivienne Goonewardene - [1984/v1-sri-lr-319] Centre for Environmental Justice v. Mahinda Rajapaksha - [sc-fr-109/2021] Sriyani Silva v. Iddamalgoda - [2003/v2-sri-lr-63] Piyasena v. Attorney General - [2007/v2-sri-lr-117] United States v. Wunderlich - [342-us-98] Munasinghe v. Vandergert - [2008/v2-sri-lr-223] Ariyawansa v. The Peoples Bank - [2006/v2-sri-lr-145] Royappa v. State of Tamil Nadu - [1974-air-555] Ramana Dayaram Shetty v. The International Airport Authority of India - [1979-air-1628] Ajay Hasia v. Khalid Mujib - [1981-air-487] Jaisinghani v. Union of India - [1967-air-1427] Perera v. Monetary Board of the Central Bank of Sri Lanka - [1994/v1-sri-lr-152] Wijerathna v. Sri Lanka Ports Authority - [sc-fr-256/2017] Vasudewa Nanayakkara v. Choksy - [sc-fr-209/2007] Nimal Bandara v. National Gem and Jewellery Authority - [sc-fr-118/2013] Sisira Senanayake v. Land Reform Commission - [sc-fr-190/2016] Municipal Corporation of the City of Ahmedabad v. Jan Mohammed Usmanbhai - [1986-air-1205] Liberty Cinema v. The Commissioner, Corporation of Calcutta - [1959-air-cal-45] Elmore Perera v. Major Montague Jayawickrema - [1985/v1-sri-lr-285] Syed Khalid Rizvi v. Union of India - [1992-supp-3-scr-180] Mrs. W.M.K. De Silva v. Chairman, Ceylon Fertilizer Corporation - [1989/v2-sri-lr-393] Siriwardena v. Inspector, Police Station, Ambalangoda - [sc-fr-242/2010] Ranatunga v. Commissioner General of Agrarian Development - [ca-writ-180/2017] Thames Water Authority v. Elmbridge Borough Council - [1983-1-qb-570] Regina v. Secretary of State for Transport ex parte Greater London Council - [1985-3-wlr-574] Agricultural, Horticultural and Forestry Industry Training Board v. Ayelsbury Mushrooms Ltd. - [1972-wlr-190] R. v. North Hertfordshire District Council ex parte Cobbold - [1985-3-all-er-486] Siva Sithamparam v. National Paper Corporation - [2003/v3-sri-lr-164] Pure Beverages Company Executive Officers Association v. Commissioner of Labour - [2001/v2-sri-lr-258] Analysis Issue 1: Time bar Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution and the principle lex non cogit ad impossibilia. Court's reasoning: The Court held that the one-month time limit for filing fundamental rights applications begins to run from the date of awareness of the infringement. Accepting the Petitioners' position that they became aware of the SOR on 05.02.2021, the application filed on 25.02.2021 was within the prescribed period. Finding: The application is not time-barred. Issue 2: Seniority, Merit, and Competitive Examination categories Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution regarding equal protection and the principle of meritocracy. Court's reasoning: The Court found that seniority is not the sole criterion for promotion and that merit-based criteria are essential for institutional efficiency. The Court noted that the weightage for seniority and merit can be adjusted by the authority. The allocation of marks for "good entries" was found to be accessible to officers in both territorial and functional divisions, and the scheme was not inherently discriminatory. Finding: These categories are not violative of the Constitution. Issue 3: Special promotion category Rule applied: Article 12(1) and Article 14(1)(g) of the Constitution regarding arbitrariness and the right to engage in a profession. Court's reasoning: The Court determined that the special promotion category granted the Inspector General of Police absolute, unfettered, and subjective discretion without defined guidelines or principles. Such power is contrary to the rule of law and constitutes arbitrary executive action. Finding: The special promotion provision is a nullity and violates the Petitioners' fundamental rights. Interaction of Issues The findings on the validity of the promotion categories are distinct. The Court determined that while the general promotion framework (seniority, merit, and competitive exam) is valid, the specific inclusion of an arbitrary discretionary power for special promotions taints that particular provision. The doctrine of severability allows the Court to strike down the unconstitutional special promotion provision while maintaining the remainder of the SOR. Conclusion The application is partly allowed. The Court declares the special promotion provision in the Scheme of Recruitment (P7) a nullity and directs the Respondents to revisit and revise that section. The seniority, merit, and competitive examination categories remain valid. Parties are to bear their own costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Public Service Commission — Scheme of Recruitment — Promotions in the police force — Seniority — Merit — Special promotion — Unfettered discretion — Arbitrary decision-making		SC/FR/46/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_46_2021.pdf
sc-fr-141-2017	25 November 2022	Mudalige v. National Water Supply and Drainage Board and Others	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Buwaneka Aluwihare, J.; Priyantha Jayawardena, PC, J; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.	Fundamental rights — Article 12(1) — Article 14(A) — Administrative action — Tender contract — Procurement Appeal Board — Right to Information Act — Time bar — Exceptional circumstances	Facts The Petitioner, a medical consultant, filed this application alleging the infringement of his fundamental rights under Articles 12(1) and 14(A) of the Constitution. The dispute concerns a tender contract awarded by the National Water Supply and Drainage Board to the 5th and 6th Respondents for the supply and laying of pipes for the Ambatale Water Supply System Improvement and Energy Saving Project. The Petitioner contended that the equipment provided by the successful bidders failed to meet the mandatory ISO 10804:2010 standards or equivalent, thereby endangering public safety and causing potential financial loss to the state. The tender process concluded with the Cabinet of Ministers approving the award on 05.11.2015, which was subsequently made public on 07.11.2015. The Petitioner did not challenge the award until 11.04.2017. The Petitioner argued that he initially only suspected irregularities and only sought formal information under the Right to Information Act No. 12 of 2016 on 21.03.2017. Upon receiving no response to his request by 04.04.2017, he filed the instant application. The Respondents raised a preliminary objection, asserting that the application was time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the application is time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution, having been filed more than one month after the alleged infringement. Whether the Petitioner has demonstrated exceptional circumstances to justify the delay in invoking the jurisdiction of the Supreme Court. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 12(1), 14(A), 126(2) Right to Information Act No. 12 of 2016 Cases Referred to: Edirisuriya v. Navaratnam - [1985/v1-sri-lr-100] Ilangaratne v. Kandy Municipal Council - [39-clw-107] Demuni Sriyani de Soyza v. Dharmasena Dissanayake - [sc-fr-206/2008] Gamaethige v. Siriwardena - [1988/v1-sri-lr-384] K.H.G Kithsiri v. Hon. Faizer Musthapha - [sc-fr-362/2017] Analysis Issue 1: Time-bar under Article 126(2) Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution, which mandates that an application for the infringement of fundamental rights must be filed within one month of the alleged infringement. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the final decision regarding the tender was made public on 07.11.2015. The Petitioner filed his application on 11.04.2017, approximately 17 months after the public announcement. The court reaffirmed that the one-month time limit is mandatory and jurisdictional. Finding: The application was filed well beyond the one-month period prescribed by the Constitution. Issue 2: Exceptional circumstances Rule applied: The principle of lex non cogit ad impossibilia as established in Gamaethige v. Siriwardena. Court's reasoning: The court examined whether the Petitioner was prevented from acting earlier. It found that the Petitioner waited nearly two years after the public announcement of the tender award before requesting information under the Right to Information Act. The court held that a reasonable person would have inquired about the alleged infringement much sooner. The Petitioner failed to provide evidence of any exceptional circumstances or lack of fault that would excuse the delay. Finding: No exceptional circumstances existed to warrant an extension of the mandatory time limit. Interaction of Issues The findings on the two issues are interdependent. The determination that the application was filed outside the mandatory period (Issue 1) necessitated an inquiry into whether the delay could be excused (Issue 2). Because the Petitioner failed to establish exceptional circumstances, the court concluded that it lacked the jurisdiction to entertain the application, thereby rendering the substantive allegations regarding the tender moot. Conclusion The preliminary objection raised by the Respondents is upheld. The application is dismissed in limine as it is time-barred. Keywords Fundamental rights — Article 12(1) — Article 14(A) — Administrative action — Tender contract — Procurement Appeal Board — Right to Information Act — Time bar — Exceptional circumstances		SC/APPEAL/141/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_141_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-3-2020	28 November 2022	Christhombu Wasangalwadu Lakshman Jayasiri Wijeratne v. Colombage Nandawathie De Silva Wijeratne and Others	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Jayantha Jayasuriya, PC, CJ; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Partition Act — Land Ownership — Burden of Proof — Exclusion of Land — Legal Title — Deed of Disposition — Surveyor's Report — Rights of Co-owners — Interlocutory Decree — Defined Allotment — Ceiling on Housing Property Law — Legal Proceedings — Evidence — Boundary Disputes — Dismissal of Action	Facts The Plaintiff-Appellant-Petitioner-Appellant (hereinafter referred to as the Appellant) instituted the instant action in the District Court of Mount Lavinia against the 1-4 Defendant-Respondent-Respondents to partition the land called 'Kongahawatte' in extent of 14.76 perches, morefully described in the 2nd Schedule to the Plaint. The 1-3 Respondents as co-owners acquiesced to the said partition between the Plaintiff (undivided 5/15 share, subject to the life interest of 1st and 3rd Respondents), the 1st Defendant-Respondent (undivided 7/15 share) and the 2nd Respondent (undivided 3/15 share), on Deeds. The Appellant claimed that the 4th Defendant-Respondent (hereinafter referred to as the 4th Respondent) has no title to the land claimed in extent of 4.64 perches as shown in Plan No. 748, and building (Assessment No. 126/2C), morefully described in the 3rd Schedule to the Plaint and pleaded that the 4th Respondent is in illegal possession of the said premises. The 4th Respondent in her statement of claim is seeking, inter alia, to exclude Lot No. 1 of the Preliminary Plan No. 2517 (Plan ‘X’), including Premises No. 126/2C (the land shown as lot 1 in Plan 2517), the property described in the Deed of Disposition No. 15935 (marked ‘X8’), and identified as Lot 1 in title Plan No. 748 (marked ‘4V2’), in extent of 4.64 perches, which is shown as part of the corpus to be partitioned in extent of 14.76 perches as described in the 2nd Schedule. At the conclusion of the trial, the learned District Judge by Judgment dated 08/01/2016, dismissed the Appellant’s action stating that the Appellant has not established the rights of the co-owners, including himself, but permitted the 4th Respondent’s claim to exclude the land depicted in the said lot 1 of Preliminary Plan No. 2517. Aggrieved by the said Judgment, the Appellant by Case No. WP/HCCA/MT/33/2016 (F) preferred an appeal to the Civil Appellate High Court of Mount Lavinia. The appellate court by its Judgment dated 03/10/2018, held that the Appellant has failed to establish his rights to the land and that of the co-owners and therefore, is not entitled to a Judgment in terms of Section 26(2) of the Partition Act and accordingly dismissed the action. However, the Court was of the view that the 4th Respondent was successful in establishing her entitlement to exclude the said Lot 1 of the said corpus as decided by the trial judge. The Appellant is before this Court challenging the said Judgement dated 03/10/2018. This Court by Order dated 13/01/2020, granted Leave to Appeal on the question of law stated in sub paragraph (3) in paragraph 22 of the Petition of Appeal dated 12/11/2018, which states as follows; 'Did the learned High Court Judges err in law and fact in not considering the strict burden of proof is on the 4th Defendant who claim for an exclusion of the portion of the Lot 1 in his title Plan No. 748.' At this stage it is pertinent to place on record that the Plaintiff’s action was dismissed by the learned District Court Judge by Judgment dated 19/11/2014, prior to the impugned Judgment dated 08/01/2016. Being aggrieved by the said Judgment dated 19/11/2014, the Plaintiff preferred an Appeal Bearing No. WP/HCCA/MT/62/11 (F) to the Civil Appeal High Court. Having considered submissions of both Counsel, the appellate court by Judgment dated 19/11/2014, sent the case for trial de novo for the limited purpose of re-considering Plan No. 1015, and