 came into existence. It was the position of the 4th Respondent that she claims only the exclusion of lot 1 in Plan 748 (4V2) described in the 3rd Schedule to the Plaint and in the schedule to the 4th Respondent’s statement of claim. It is contended that the said lot 1 according to the boundaries and extent is identical with the boundaries of lot 1 in the Preliminary Plan No. 2517 (Plan X). It is revealed that after the demise of the original owner of the land in the 1st Schedule to the Plaint, the said land was subdivided into two lots A and B by his heirs as described in Plan No. 1015, dated 29/03/1953. Lot B, described in the 2nd Schedule to the Plaint was sold to the 1st Respondent. The husband of the 4th Respondent one Wilmet Chandrapala was a tenant of the house standing on a part of Lot B and had come into occupation by Deed of Disposition No. 15935 issued by the Department of National Housing. The said Wilmet Chandrapala gifted the said property to his wife the 4th Respondent by Deed No. 98, dated 07/09/1995 which is pleaded as part of the corpus that is sought to be partitioned, described in the 3rd Schedule to the Plaint. In this context, the learned Presidents Counsel for the 4th Defendant has drawn attention of Court to the 2nd Schedule to the Plaint which describes the corpus in the following manner; —''''wxl 1015 orK msUqf¾ len,s wxl î orK bvug udhsï''''˜ And the 3rd Schedule to the Plaint which describes the portion which the 4th Defendant is allegedly in wrongful possession as; —''''jßmkï wxl 25 ^fmroS 126$2iS& orkakd jQ foam,g ta'ã'tï'fÊ' rEmisxy n,h,;a ñkskafodare ;ek úiska j¾I 1993 la jQ cQ,s ui 22 jk osk uek idok ,o wxl 748 orK msUqf¾ len,s wxl 1g udhsï W;=rg by; lS ie,eiafï jßmkï wxl 126$1 .,aj, mdr	Rohan Sahabandu, PC with Nathasha Fernando and Chathurika Elvitigala for the Plaintiff-Appellant-Petitioner-Appellant. Jagath Wickramanayake, PC with Pujanee de Alwis instructed by Renuka Edirisinghe for the substituted 4a Defendant-Respondent-Respondent-Respondents.	SC/APPEAL/3/2020	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_3_2020.pdf
sc-appeal-53-2022	30 November 2022	Dona Thilaka v. Attorney General	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	Appeal against order of Court of Appeal — Exceptional circumstances — Bail application — Poisons, Opium and Dangerous Drugs Ordinance — Section 83 — Credibility of witness — Morality as a yardstick — Drug trafficking offence — Heroin possession — Previous convictions	Facts The Accused-Respondent, Madapathage Dona Thilaka Alias Shyamali, was arrested on 2nd February 2018 for the possession of heroin. Following an investigation, she was indicted in the High Court of Colombo for possessing and trafficking 43.723 grams of heroin. The Accused-Respondent filed multiple bail applications in the High Court, all of which were refused on the basis that she failed to demonstrate exceptional circumstances as required by Section 83 of the Poisons, Opium and Dangerous Drugs Ordinance. The Accused-Respondent contended that the arrest of the main investigating officer, Sub Inspector Udara Chathuranga, on suspicion of involvement in a separate drug-related offence constituted an exceptional circumstance. Upon the High Court's refusal, the Accused-Respondent filed a revision application in the Court of Appeal. The Court of Appeal allowed the application and granted bail, citing concerns regarding the morality of keeping the accused in remand given the potential unreliability of the investigating officer and delays caused by the COVID-19 pandemic. The Attorney General subsequently appealed this decision to the Supreme Court. It was further noted that the Accused-Respondent had failed to disclose two previous drug-related convictions during her revision application. Issues Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law by considering morality as a yardstick or an exceptional ground for granting bail under the Poisons, Opium and Dangerous Drugs Ordinance. Whether the Court of Appeal erred in law by holding that the credibility of a witness constitutes an exceptional circumstance for the purpose of granting bail. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 128 Poisons, Opium and Dangerous Drugs Ordinance (as amended by Act No. 13 of 1984), Sections 54A, 54B, 83 Conventions Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances Act No. 1 Cases Referred to: Ramu Thamodarampillai v. The Attorney General - [2004/v3-sri-lr-180] Cader (On Behalf of Rashid Khan) v. Officer-In-Charge Narcotics Bureau - [2006/v3-sri-lr-74] Tudor Perera v. AG - [sc-appeal-23/75] Kumara De Silva And 2 Others v. Attorney General - [2010/v2-sri-lr-169] Analysis Issue 1: Morality as a yardstick for bail Rule applied: Section 83(1) of the Poisons, Opium and Dangerous Drugs Ordinance, which requires "exceptional circumstances" for the grant of bail in cases involving Sections 54A or 54B. Court's reasoning: The Court held that morality and law are distinct concepts. Morality is not an essential criterion for legality, and using it as a yardstick for judicial decisions creates unclear precedents. Furthermore, the Accused-Respondent suppressed material facts regarding her two previous drug-related convictions, which the Court of Appeal acknowledged but failed to weigh appropriately. The Court emphasized that the repetitive nature of such crimes and the difficulty of detection are significant factors against granting bail. Finding: The Court of Appeal erred in law by using morality as a basis for granting bail, as there is no legal foundation for such a standard in the context of the Ordinance. Issue 2: Witness credibility as an exceptional circumstance Rule applied: Section 83 of the Poisons, Opium and Dangerous Drugs Ordinance and the principle that credibility is a question of fact for the trial judge. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that the investigating officer's arrest pertained to an unrelated case and he was not a convict at the time of the bail hearing. Credibility is a matter for the trial court to determine based on evidence, not for an appellate court during a bail application. Moreover, the character of a witness in an official capacity regarding an unrelated matter does not constitute an "exceptional circumstance" under the Ordinance. Finding: The Court of Appeal erred in law; witness credibility is not a relevant ground for establishing exceptional circumstances for bail. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues reinforce the conclusion that the Court of Appeal applied improper criteria to the statutory requirement of "exceptional circumstances." By improperly elevating morality and witness credibility to the status of exceptional grounds, the Court of Appeal bypassed the strict legislative intent of the Ordinance, which is further underscored by the Accused-Respondent's failure to disclose her criminal history. Conclusion The appeal is allowed and the bail order granted by the Court of Appeal is set aside. The High Court is directed to take the Accused-Respondent back into custody and to conclude the trial expeditiously. Keywords Appeal against order of Court of Appeal — Exceptional circumstances — Bail application — Poisons, Opium and Dangerous Drugs Ordinance — Section 83 — Credibility of witness — Morality as a yardstick — Drug trafficking offence — Heroin possession — Previous convictions		SC/APPEAL/53/2022	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_53_2022.pdf
sc-appeal-160/2016	2 December 2022	Bertha v. Appu and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Partition action — Substitution of deceased parties — Per incuriam — Stare decisis — Binding precedent — Statutory provisions	Facts The plaintiff initiated a partition action in the District Court of Kuliyapitiya on 07.01.1966. The District Court delivered its judgment on 27.10.2003. Following an appeal by the 16th defendant, the High Court of Civil Appeal of Kurunegala dismissed the appeal on 21.07.2011. Nearly one year after the High Court judgment, the substituted 2nd defendant filed an application in the High Court of Civil Appeal seeking to set aside the previous judgments on the grounds of per incuriam and requesting a retrial. The applicant contended that the District Court's analysis of evidence and share allocation were erroneous. Furthermore, the applicant argued that the judgments were vitiated because several parties had died pending the action and the court had failed to effect substitution of their legal representatives. The High Court of Civil Appeal dismissed this application, relying on the principle that the failure to substitute deceased parties does not invalidate a partition decree. The substituted 2nd defendant subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the judgment of the Supreme Court in Karunawathie v. Piyasena was given per incuriam. Whether an inferior court may decline to follow a decision of a superior court on the ground that it was given per incuriam. Applicable Law Statutes: Partition Law No. 21 of 1977 Partition (Amendment) Act No. 17 of 1997 Evidence Ordinance Cases Referred to: Jane Nona v. Surabiel - [2013/v1-sri-lr-346] Karunawathie v. Piyasena - [2011/v1-sri-lr-171] Bandahamy v. Senanayake - [62-nlr-313] Gunaratne Menike v. Jayatilaka Banda - [1995/v1-sri-lr-152] Mary Beatrice v. Seneviratne - [1997/v1-sri-lr-197] Quinn v. Leathem - [1901] AC 495 Broome v. Cassell & Co Ltd - [1972] AC 1027 Walker Sons & Co UK Ltd v. Gunatilake - [1978-79-80/v1-sri-lr-231] Billimoria v. Minister of Lands and Land Development - [1978-79-80/v1-sri-lr-10] Ganeshanantham v. Vivienne Goonewardene - [1984/v1-sri-lr-319] Jeyaraj Fernandopulle v. Premachandra De Silva - [1996/v1-sri-lr-70] Gunasena v. Bandaratilleke - [2000/v1-sri-lr-292] Stassen Exports Ltd. v. Lipton Ltd. - [2009/v2-sri-lr-172] Young v. Bristol Aeroplane Co. Ltd. - [1944] KB 718 Moosajee v. Carolis Silva - [70-nlr-217] Neate v. de Abrew - [5-scc-126] Ostime v. Australian Provident Society - [1959] 2 A.E.R. 245 Scrutton Ltd. v. Midland Silicones Ltd. - [1962] 1 A.E.R. 12 Bonulami v. Home Secretary - [1985] QB 675 Morrelle Ltd. v. Wakeling - [1955] 2 QB 389 Nicholas v. Penny - [1950] 2 KB 466 Farook v. Attorney General - [2006/v3-sri-lr-174] Weerappan v. The Queen - [76-nlr-109] Sitti Nufeesa v. Chandrasena - [ca-appeal-654/2000] Davis v. Johnson - [1979] AC 264 Farrell v. Alexander - [1976] 1 QB 345 Campbell College, Belfast v. Northern Ireland Valuation Commissioner - [1964] 1 WLR 912 William Singho v. Japin Perera - [sc-hc-cala-145/2011] Wilson v. Sumanawathie - [ca-535/95/f] Mervin Silva v. Anil Shantha Samarasinghe - [sc-appeal-45/2010] Velupillai v. The Chairman, Urban District Council - [39-nlr-464] Rookes v. Barnard - [1964] AC 1129 E. Hulton & Co. v. Jones - [1910] AC 20 Ley v. Hamilton - [153-lt-384] Jones v. Secretary of State - [1972] 1 All ER 145 Ramanathan Chettiar v. Wickramarachchi - [1978-79/v2-sri-lr-395] Galle Municipal Council v. Galle Festival - [ca/phc/155/2010] Sirimal v. Board of Directors of the Co-operative Wholesale Establishment - [2003/v2-sri-lr-23] R. v. North and East Devon Health Authority - [2000] 2 WLR 622 Dugdale v. D. - [1872] LR 14 Eq 234 Analysis Issue 1: Whether the judgment in Karunawathie v. Piyasena was per incuriam Rule applied: Section 48(1)(b), 48(6), and 81(9) of the Partition Law No. 21 of 1977 (as amended). Court's reasoning: The court found that the Karunawathie decision failed to consider express statutory provisions which stipulate that the failure to substitute heirs or legal representatives of a party who dies pending a partition action does not invalidate the proceedings or the decree. The Karunawathie court relied on irrelevant foreign authorities instead of the clear mandate of the Partition Law. Finding: The judgment in Karunawathie v. Piyasena was given per incuriam. Issue 2: Whether an inferior court may decline to follow a per incuriam decision Rule applied: The doctrine of stare decisis and the exception for per incuriam decisions. Court's reasoning: The court reasoned that stare decisis is not a rigid rule intended to perpetuate legal error. When a superior court decision is ex facie per incuriam due to ignorance of a statute, it ceases to be a binding precedent. Lower courts have an obligation to uphold the rule of law and the express will of the legislature over erroneous precedents. Finding: Yes, a lower court may decline to follow a decision of a superior court if the defect (per incuriam) is clear on the face of the judgment. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing. By determining that Karunawathie was per incuriam due to the neglect of specific statutory provisions, the court established the legal basis for the second issue, confirming that the hierarchy of courts does not compel adherence to decisions that contradict the clear letter of the law. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed. The Supreme Court affirmed that Karunawathie v. Piyasena was decided per incuriam and that lower courts are not bound to follow such precedents when they are demonstrably contrary to express statutory provisions. Keywords Partition action — Substitution of deceased parties — Per incuriam — Stare decisis — Binding precedent — Statutory provisions			
sc-appeal-108-2019	2 December 2022	Amaradasa v. Dilrukshi and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Contractual obligation — Repayment of debt — Jewellery as security — Written agreement — Interpretation of evidence — High Court review — District Court judgment — Settlement of dispute — Meaningless and false stand	Facts The plaintiff filed an action in the District Court of Gampaha to recover a sum of Rs. 200,000 borrowed by the defendant for house construction. The defendant contended that the plaintiff's wife had previously given her money as a wedding gift, which she was later pressured to return. The defendant alleged that because she could not repay the gift, the plaintiff's wife provided her with jewellery to pawn, and the document P1 was signed as security for that jewellery transaction. The District Court entered judgment in favor of the plaintiff, finding the loan for house construction and the jewellery dispute to be separate transactions. The High Court of Civil Appeal of Gampaha subsequently set aside the District Court judgment, concluding that the simultaneous dates of documents P1 and V1 supported the defendant's version of events. The plaintiff appealed this decision to the Supreme Court. The defendant did not appear before the Supreme Court despite receiving notice. Issues Whether the High Court erred in failing to appreciate that the execution of documents on the same day does not necessarily establish that the underlying transactions are identical. Whether the High Court disregarded or misunderstood the evidence presented at trial in setting aside the District Court judgment. Applicable Law Statutes: Not specified Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Correlation of transactions Rule applied: The court applied the principle of evidentiary assessment regarding the independence of distinct financial transactions. Court's reasoning: The court examined the defendant's claim that P1 (the loan agreement) was security for a jewellery transaction (V1). The court found the defendant's narrative illogical, noting that if the plaintiff's wife intended to satisfy her son, she could have pawned the jewellery herself rather than involving the defendant. The court concluded that there was no factual or logical connection between the loan for house construction and the separate jewellery dispute. Finding: The High Court erred in assuming that the identical dates of P1 and V1 proved the transactions were linked. Issue 2: Evaluation of evidence Rule applied: The court applied the standard of appellate review regarding the sufficiency of reasons provided by a lower appellate court. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court found the High Courtâ€™s judgment to be "completely unsatisfactory" because it failed to provide acceptable reasons for overturning the District Court's findings. The High Court had asserted that P1 served as security for the jewellery without providing any evidentiary basis for that conclusion. The Supreme Court determined that the District Courtâ€™s assessment of the evidence was sound and that the defendantâ€™s position was "meaningless and false." Finding: The High Court disregarded the evidence and failed to provide a reasoned basis for its decision. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are mutually reinforcing. The courtâ€™s determination that the transactions were distinct (Issue 1) directly undermined the High Courtâ€™s primary justification for its ruling. Consequently, the failure to recognize this lack of correlation led the High Court to misinterpret the evidence (Issue 2), necessitating the restoration of the District Court's original judgment. Conclusion The Supreme Court answered both questions of law in the affirmative, set aside the judgment of the High Court, and restored the judgment of the District Court. The plaintiff is entitled to costs in all three courts. Keywords Contractual obligation — Repayment of debt — Jewellery as security — Written agreement — Interpretation of evidence — High Court review — District Court judgment — Settlement of dispute — Meaningless and false stand		SC/APPEAL/108/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_108_2019.pdf
sc-chc-appeal-33-2013	05 December 2022	Sri Lanka Savings Bank Ltd v. Good Value Importers (pvt) Ltd and Good Value Distributors (pvt) Ltd	L. T. B. Dehideniya, J.	L. T. B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu N. B. Fernando, PC, J.; S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	Civil Procedure Code — High Court of Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No 10 of 1996 — loan recovery — privity of contract — locus standi — Evidence Ordinance — certified copies — burden of proof — banking transactions — financial irregularities — appeal dismissal — judgment proof	Facts The case revolves around an appeal from a judgment of the Commercial High Court concerning a loan recovery action initiated by the Sri Lanka Savings Bank Ltd (the Appellant) against Good Value Importers (pvt) Ltd and Good Value Distributors (pvt) Ltd (the Respondents). The Appellant claimed that the 1st Respondent had obtained a loan from its predecessor, the Pramuka Saving and Development Bank, and failed to repay it. The 2nd Respondent acted as the guarantor for this loan. The Respondents denied liability, asserting that the cause of action was prescribed, there was no privity of contract, and the Appellant lacked locus standi. During the trial, the Appellant presented two witnesses and submitted various documents (P1 to P16) to substantiate its claim. However, the Respondents objected to all documents except P1 and P3, demanding proof for the others. After cross-examination, the Respondents chose not to present any evidence. The Appellant's case hinged on the assertion that the Respondents had not denied the authenticity of the documents and that the agreements were signed by them. The High Court Judge ultimately dismissed the Appellant's action, concluding that the Appellant failed to prove that the Respondents were in arrears. The Judge noted that while the 1st Respondent had entered into an agreement for the loan, the date of granting the loan was not established, leading to the dismissal of the case. Issues The primary issues in this case can be framed as follows: Whether the Appellant proved the existence of the loan and the arrears owed by the Respondents? Whether the Respondents admitted the averments in the plaint? Whether the Appellant had locus standi to bring the action? Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code; High Court of Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No 10 of 1996; Evidence Ordinance. Cases Referred to: Benedict and Others vs. Monetary Board of Central Bank of Sri Lanka and Others - [2003] 3 Sri. L. R 69. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the Appellant proved the existence of the loan and the arrears owed by the Respondents? Rule applied: The burden of proof lies with the Appellant to establish the existence of the loan and the arrears. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court examined the evidence presented by the Appellant, particularly focusing on the documents marked as P1 to P16. The High Court Judge had dismissed the Appellant's case on the grounds that the Appellant failed to prove that the Respondents were in arrears of payment. The Judge noted that while the Appellant had marked the documents subject to proof, it did not call any witnesses to substantiate the authenticity of these documents, particularly the certified copy of the ledger (P8). The Respondents had objected to the admissibility of this document, arguing that it was not proven. The Appellant's counsel contended that under Section 90(C) of the Evidence Ordinance, certified copies of bankers' books need not be proved. However, the court highlighted that the credibility of the Pramuka Saving and Development Bank's operations was questionable due to prior findings of financial irregularities. The court referenced the case of Benedict and Others vs. Monetary Board of Central Bank of Sri Lanka, which revealed significant mismanagement within the Pramuka Bank. The court concluded that the Appellant had not sufficiently established the normal course of business for the bank, thus failing to prove the arrears owed by the Respondents. Finding: The Supreme Court upheld the High Court's finding that the Appellant did not prove the existence of the loan and the arrears owed by the Respondents. Issue 2: Whether the Respondents admitted the averments in the plaint? Rule applied: The principle of admissions in pleadings. Court's reasoning: The Supreme Court analyzed the admissions made by the Respondents at the commencement of the trial. It was noted that the Respondents had only admitted the jurisdiction of the court and one specific paragraph of the plaint, while denying knowledge of other critical averments. The court emphasized that the burden of proof rested on the Appellant, as the Respondents had not admitted the majority of the claims made in the plaint. The court further clarified that the Respondents' denial of knowledge regarding the loan agreement and other related facts meant that the Appellant could not rely on any supposed admissions to bolster its case. Finding: The Supreme Court concluded that the Respondents did not admit the averments in the plaint, reinforcing the Appellant's burden to prove its claims. Issue 3: Whether the Appellant had locus standi to bring the action? Rule applied: The principle of locus standi in relation to successors in interest. Court's reasoning: The Appellant argued that it had locus standi as the successor of the Pramuka Savings and Development Bank, which had granted the loan. The court acknowledged that the Central Bank of Sri Lanka had vested the banking operations of the Pramuka Bank with the Appellant. However, the court also noted that the Appellant's ability to prove the loan and the arrears was critical to establishing its standing. Since the Appellant failed to prove the existence of the loan and the arrears, the court found that the Respondents' objection regarding locus standi was ultimately moot. Finding: The Supreme Court determined that while the Appellant had locus standi, it did not succeed in proving its case. Interaction of Issues The issues of proving the existence of the loan and the arrears, the admissions made by the Respondents, and the Appellant's locus standi are interrelated. The Appellant's failure to prove the loan and the arrears directly impacted its standing in court. The Respondents' admissions, or lack thereof, further complicated the Appellant's position, as the burden of proof remained firmly on the Appellant throughout the proceedings. Conclusion The Supreme Court dismissed the appeal, affirming the High Court's judgment that the Appellant had failed to prove its case. The court emphasized the importance of establishing the existence of the loan and the arrears owed by the Respondents, which the Appellant could not do. The dismissal was made without costs, reflecting the court's view on the merits of the case. Keywords Civil Procedure Code — High Court of Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No 10 of 1996 — loan recovery — privity of contract — locus standi — Evidence Ordinance — certified copies — burden of proof — banking transactions — financial irregularities — appeal dismissal — judgment proof	Kamal Dissanayake with Sureni Amaratunga instructed by Ms. Mayomi Ranawaka for the Plaintiff-Appellant. S. P. Sriskantha with Prasanna Sriskantha & shown Tissera for the Defendant-Respondents.	SC/FR/33/2013	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_33_2013.pdf
sc-spl-la-86/2020	12 December 2022	Waruna Priyanka v. Commercial Bank of Ceylon PLC	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	E.A.G.R. Amarasekara, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Preliminary objection — Time limit for filing application — Supreme Court Rules — Article 128 of the Constitution — Industrial Disputes Act — Section 31DD(1) — Covid-19 pandemic — Supreme Court (Temporary Provisions) Rules 2020 — Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid-19) (Temporary Provisions) Act No. 17 — Exclusion of time period	Facts The Petitioner, D.H. Waruna Priyanka, was employed by the Respondent, Commercial Bank of Ceylon PLC, as a clerk in 1990 and later served as a branch manager. Following a domestic inquiry into twenty charges of misconduct, the Respondent terminated the Petitioner's services on 24th January 2014. The Petitioner challenged this termination before the Labour Tribunal, which dismissed his application on 6th July 2018. The Petitioner subsequently appealed to the Provincial High Court of the Western Province, which dismissed the appeal on 25th February 2020. The Petitioner filed an application for leave to appeal to the Supreme Court on 29th June 2020. The Respondent raised a preliminary objection, contending that the application was filed out of time and should be dismissed in limine. The Petitioner argued that the delay was caused by the Covid-19 pandemic and sought an exclusion of time under the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid-19) (Temporary Provisions) Act No. 17 of 2021. Issues Whether the application for leave to appeal was filed within the mandatory six-week time period prescribed by Rule 7 of the Supreme Court Rules 1990. Whether the Petitioner is entitled to an additional exclusion of time under Section 2(1) of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid-19) (Temporary Provisions) Act No. 17 of 2021, notwithstanding the exclusions already granted by the Supreme Court (Temporary Provisions) Rules 2020. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka Industrial Disputes Act High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 19 Supreme Court Rules 1990 Supreme Court (Temporary Provisions) Rules 2020 Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid-19) (Temporary Provisions) Act No. 17 of 2021 Cases Referred to: Asia Broadcasting Corporation (Private) Limited v Kaluappu Hannadi Lalith Priyantha - [sc-appeal-50/2020] Priyanthi Chandrika Jinadasa v Pathma Hemamali - [2011/v1-sri-lr-337] L.A. Sudath Rohana v Mohamed Zeena - [sc-hc-ca-la-111/2010] Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid19) (Temporary Provisions) Bill - [sc-sd-24/2021] Analysis Issue 1: Timeliness of the application Rule applied: Rule 7 of the Supreme Court Rules 1990, which mandates that applications for leave to appeal must be filed within six weeks of the judgment. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that while the application fell under Part 1C of the Supreme Court Rules, established precedent confirms that the six-week time limit in Rule 7 applies to such appeals. The High Court judgment was delivered on 25th February 2020. Even after accounting for the automatic time exclusion provided by the Supreme Court (Temporary Provisions) Rules 2020 (16th March 2020 to 18th May 2020), the deadline for filing was 10th June 2020. The Petitioner filed on 29th June 2020, which is outside the prescribed period. Finding: The application was filed out of time. Issue 2: Applicability of the Covid-19 (Temporary Provisions) Act Rule applied: Section 2(1) and Section 2(2) of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid-19) (Temporary Provisions) Act No. 17 of 2021. Court's reasoning: Section 2(2) of the Act explicitly excludes from the relief granted in Section 2(1) any application to which the Supreme Court (Temporary Provisions) Rules 2020 already apply. The Court reasoned that the Legislature intended for parties to receive relief either through the Rules or the Act, but not both. Since the Petitioner already benefited from the automatic exclusion under the Rules, he is ineligible for further discretionary relief under Section 2(1). Furthermore, the Court held that Section 2(2)(b) does not empower the Court to grant additional time in the absence of new Rules promulgated under Article 136. Finding: The Petitioner is not entitled to further exclusion of time under the Act. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing; the determination that the application is subject to the mandatory time limits of Rule 7 (Issue 1) triggers the exclusionary provisions of Section 2(2) of the Covid-19 Act (Issue 2). Because the Petitioner already received the benefit of the Supreme Court (Temporary Provisions) Rules, the statutory bar in Section 2(2) prevents the Court from granting further relief, thereby confirming that the application remains time-barred. Conclusion The preliminary objection is upheld. The application for leave to appeal is dismissed in limine as it was filed out of time. No order is made as to costs. Keywords Preliminary objection — Time limit for filing application — Supreme Court Rules — Article 128 of the Constitution — Industrial Disputes Act — Section 31DD(1) — Covid-19 pandemic — Supreme Court (Temporary Provisions) Rules 2020 — Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid-19) (Temporary Provisions) Act No. 17 — Exclusion of time period			
sc-fr-591/2012	14 December 2022	Ismail and Others v. Ranugge and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Janak De Silva, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Scheme of Recruitment — Service Minute — Public Administration Circular No.6/2006 — Time bar — Senior Statisticians — Public Service Commission	Facts The Petitioners are eighteen citizens employed as Senior Statisticians at the Department of Census and Statistics. They were appointed following an open competitive examination held in February 2006. Following their appointment, the Petitioners became aware of administrative moves to draft a new Scheme of Recruitment that would consolidate the positions of Senior Statistician and Statistician. The Petitioners sought to participate in discussions regarding this new scheme but were largely excluded or denied direct representation. In May 2012, the Petitioners were formally notified by the Department that a new Scheme of Recruitment had been approved by the Public Service Commission. The Petitioners contended that this new scheme was irrational and violated their fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution, specifically by creating promotional disadvantages for them compared to other officers. The Petitioners filed the instant application on 9th October 2012, seeking to quash the new Scheme of Recruitment. The Respondents raised a preliminary objection, asserting that the application was filed out of time as it exceeded the one-month period stipulated by Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Issues Whether the Petitioners' application for the infringement of fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution was filed within the mandatory one-month time limit prescribed by Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 17, 126, 126(2) Cases Referred to: Gamaethige v. Siriwardana - [1988/v1-sri-lr-384] Demuni Sriyani De Soyza v. Dharmasena Dissanayake - [sc-fr-206/2008] Ilangaratne v. Kandy Municipal Council - [1995-balj-vi-1-10] Analysis Issue 1: Compliance with the one-month time limit Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution, which mandates that an application for the infringement of fundamental rights must be filed within one month of the alleged infringement or the date the petitioner becomes aware of the infringement. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that the Petitioners were informed of the approval of the new Scheme of Recruitment by letter dated 6th May 2012 and were provided with a copy of the scheme by letter dated 11th May 2012. Consequently, the Petitioners had knowledge of the alleged infringement in May 2012. The application was filed on 9th October 2012, which is approximately four months after the Petitioners became aware of the alleged violation. The Court noted that the time limit in Article 126(2) is mandatory and jurisdictional. The Petitioners failed to provide any evidence or valid justification for the delay in filing the application. The Court further noted that the Petitioners' earlier complaint to the Human Rights Commission in February 2012 concerned a draft scheme and did not toll the time limit for challenging the final approved scheme. Finding: The application was filed out of time, and the Court lacks the jurisdiction to entertain it. Conclusion The preliminary objection raised by the Respondents is upheld. The application is dismissed as it is time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Scheme of Recruitment — Service Minute — Public Administration Circular No.6/2006 — Time bar — Senior Statisticians — Public Service Commission			
sc-fr-452-2019	14 December 2022	Kandambi v. State Timber Corporation and Others	Janak De Silva, J.	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; Kumuduni Wickremasinghe, J; Janak De Silva, J.	Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Interview process — Meritocracy — Kakistocracy — Promotion — Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act — Time bar objection	Facts Thilangani Kandambi joined the State Timber Corporation as a Clerk-Grade IV in 1983 and eventually served as an Assistant Director. In 2016, the State Timber Corporation invited internal applications for the post of Deputy Manager (Human Resources). The Petitioner participated in the interview process held on 24 March 2016. Following the interviews, the 11th and 12th Respondents were selected and appointed to the position. The Petitioner alleged that the interview process was conducted unfairly and that she was denied marks to prevent her appointment. She subsequently filed a complaint with the Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka on 9 June 2016. The Commission issued a recommendation on 16 September 2019, which the State Timber Corporation refused to implement by letter dated 17 October 2019. The Petitioner then invoked the jurisdiction of the Supreme Court on 15 November 2019. Issues Whether the Petitionerâ€™s application was time-barred under Article 126(2) of the Constitution. Whether the interview process and the subsequent denial of the promotion to the Petitioner constituted an infringement of her fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Articles 12(1), 17, 126(2), 126(4) Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act No. 21 of 1996, Sections 13(1), 14 Cases Referred to: Gamaethige v. Siriwardena - [1988/v1-sri-lr-384] Siriwardena v. Rodrigo - [Siriwardena v. Rodrigo] Romesh Coorey v. Jayalath - [2008/v2-sri-lr-43] Alles v. Road Passenger Services Authority of the Western Province - [sc-appeal-448/2009] Subasinghe v. Inspector General of Police - [sc-spl-16/1999] Kariyawasam v. Southern Provincial Road Development Authority - [2007/v2-sri-lr-33] Ranaweera v. Sub-Inspector Wilson Siriwardene - [2008/v1-sri-lr-260] K.H.G. Kithsiri v. Faizer Musthapha - [sc-fr-362/2017] Wanasinghe v. Kamal Paliskara - [sc-fr-216/2014] Alagaratnam Manoranjan v. G.A. Chandrasiri - [sc-fr-261/2013] Analysis Issue 1: Time Bar Rule applied: Article 126(2) of the Constitution and Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act No. 21 of 1996. Court's reasoning: The Court determined that the time limit for filing an application begins when the infringement occurs or when the petitioner gains knowledge of it. The Petitioner became aware of the promotions on 3 June 2016. Under Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act, the period during which an inquiry is pending before the Commission is excluded from the one-month limitation period. The Court held that the time stopped running when the Commission began its inquiry and that the Petitioner was not required to file her application until the deadline set by the Commission for the implementation of its recommendation had expired. Finding: The application was filed within the prescribed period. Issue 2: Interview Process Rule applied: Article 12(1) of the Constitution (Right to Equality). Court's reasoning: The Court relied on the uncontradicted affidavit of a former employee, which indicated that the 11th and 12th Respondents were promoted based on extraneous considerations, such as impending retirement and persistent requests, rather than merit. The Petitioner had scored higher in experience, educational qualifications, and service records, but was marked down in the "personality" category. The Court found that the State Timber Corporation failed to produce the mark sheets or evidence from the interview panel to justify the scores. Finding: The decision to promote the 11th and 12th Respondents was arbitrary and based on extraneous considerations, infringing the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1). Interaction of Issues The findings on the time bar and the merits are linked by the procedural history of the case. The Courtâ€™s determination that the Petitioner was entitled to the benefit of Section 13(1) of the Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act allowed the Court to reach the merits of the case, which ultimately revealed that the administrative action taken by the 1st Respondent was arbitrary and lacked a merit-based foundation. Conclusion The Court declared that the 1st Respondent infringed the Petitioner's fundamental rights under Article 12(1) of the Constitution. The Court directed the 1st Respondent to promote the Petitioner to the post of Deputy Manager (Human Resources) with effect from the date the 11th and 12th Respondents were promoted, including all back wages and statutory dues, and ordered the payment of costs. Keywords Fundamental rights — Equality before the law — Administrative action — Interview process — Meritocracy — Kakistocracy — Promotion — Human Rights Commission of Sri Lanka Act — Time bar objection		SC/FR/452/2019	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_452_2019.pdf
sc-appeal-47-2021	14 December 2022	Somawathie v. Upul and Others	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; Janak De Silva, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Leave to appeal — Failure to answer issues — District Court judgment — High Court judgment — Judicial Service Commission — Additional District Judge — Compliance with Supreme Court direction	Facts The Plaintiff-Respondent instituted action in the District Court of Monaragala in 1996 seeking a declaration of title to land, ejectment of the Defendants-Appellants, and damages. During the trial, which commenced on 17 February 2000, 27 issues were framed by the parties. The District Judge delivered a judgment in 2007, but only answered 23 of the 27 issues. The Defendants-Appellants appealed this decision to the Civil Appellate High Court, which dismissed the appeal. Upon a subsequent leave to appeal application, the Supreme Court set aside the judgments of the District Court and the High Court on 18 January 2016. The Supreme Court directed the District Judge to pronounce judgment based on the 27 issues framed at the trial that commenced on 17 February 2000. Following this direction, the Judicial Service Commission appointed the original trial judge, who had since been promoted to the High Court, to act as an Additional District Judge to deliver the judgment. The judge subsequently delivered a judgment answering all 27 issues. The Defendants-Appellants appealed this judgment to the High Court, which dismissed the appeal, leading to the current appeal before the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the District Judge failed to comply with the directions issued by the Supreme Court in its judgment dated 18 January 2016. Applicable Law Statutes: High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 19 of 1990 Civil Procedure Act Cases Referred to: Hebtulabhoy & Co. Ltd. v. A. L. M. Fernando, High Court Judge & Others - [1988/v1-sri-lr-191] Analysis Issue 1: Compliance with Supreme Court directions Rule applied: The Supreme Courtâ€™s previous order directing the District Judge to pronounce judgment on the 27 issues framed at the trial that commenced on 17 February 2000, and the legal principle established in Hebtulabhoy & Co. Ltd. v. A. L. M. Fernando, High Court Judge & Others regarding the competence of a High Court Judge to function as an Additional District Judge to conclude a case previously heard. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that its 2016 direction was limited to requiring the trial judge to answer the correct set of issues based on the evidence already led. It was not a mandate to conduct a trial de novo or to hear fresh evidence. The Court found that the appointment of the original judge as an Additional District Judge by the Judicial Service Commission was legally valid, as affirmed in Hebtulabhoy & Co. Ltd. v. A. L. M. Fernando, High Court Judge & Others. The Court further noted that the judge complied with the 2016 order by answering all 27 issues. The fact that the 2016 judgment reached similar conclusions to the 2007 judgment was expected, as the findings were based on the same material and evidence. Finding: The District Judge fully complied with the Supreme Court's directions, and no procedural error or prejudice to the Defendants-Appellants was established. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed with costs. The judgment of the District Court, as affirmed by the Civil Appellate High Court, is upheld. Keywords Leave to appeal — Failure to answer issues — District Court judgment — High Court judgment — Judicial Service Commission — Additional District Judge — Compliance with Supreme Court direction		SC/APPEAL/47/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_47_2021.pdf
sc-appeal-47-2008	15 December 2022	Ikram v. Officer-In-Charge, Police Station, Uragasmanhandiya and another	Achala Wengappuli, J.	Murdu Fernando, PC, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Confiscation of vehicle — Animals Act — Burden of proof — Standard of proof — Balance of probability — Credibility of witness — Cross-examination — Interested witness — Knowledge of offence	Facts The Accused-Respondent, Mohamed Buhari Mohamed Akram, was charged before the Magistrateâ€™s Court of Elpitiya for transporting a water buffalo cow without a valid permit in a lorry, in violation of Section 3(c)(1) of the Animals Act. The Accused-Respondent pleaded guilty and was convicted. Subsequently, the Applicant-Appellant-Respondent, Mohamed Buhari Ikram, who was the registered owner of the lorry, moved the Magistrateâ€™s Court for the release of the vehicle. The Magistrateâ€™s Court conducted an inquiry where the Applicant-Appellant-Respondent provided oral evidence. Following this inquiry, the Magistrate ordered the confiscation of the lorry. The Applicant-Appellant-Respondent appealed this order to the Provincial High Court of the Southern Province. The High Court set aside the confiscation order and directed the release of the vehicle to the owner. The 1st Respondent-Appellant, the Attorney General, appealed this decision to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court Judge erred in law regarding the standard of proof required for an owner to secure the release of a vehicle under the Animals Act. Whether the High Court Judge erred in law regarding the burden of proof applicable to an owner seeking the release of a vehicle under the Animals Act. Applicable Law Statutes: Animals Act (as amended), Section 3A Civil Procedure Code, Section 154(1) High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 19/1990, Section 9 Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 154P Cases Referred to: Nizar v Inspector of Police, Wattegama - [1978/v2-sri-lr-304] Faris v The Officer in Charge of Galenbindunuwewa and Another - [1992/v1-sri-lr-168] The Finance Company PLC v Priyantha Chandana & Five Others - [2010/v2-sri-lr-220] Pilapitiya v Chandrasiri and Others - [1979/v1-sri-lr-361] The Attorney General v Mary Theresa - [2011/v2-sri-lr-292] Bandaranaike v Jagathsena and Others - [1984/v2-sri-lr-397] King v Gunaratne et al - [14-clw-174] Martin Fernando v The Inspector of Police, Minuwangoda - [46-nlr-210] Rodrigo v Central Engineering Consultancy Bureau - [2009/v1-sri-lr-248] Padmatilake (Sgt) v Director General, Commission to Investigate Allegations of Bribery and Corruption - [2009/v2-sri-lr-151] Kulasiriwardena v Jayasinghe and Others - [2016/v1-sri-lr-93] Tudor Perera v AG - [sc-23/75] Analysis Issue 1: Standard of Proof Rule applied: Section 3A of the Animals Act and the principle established in The Finance Company PLC v Priyantha Chandana & Five Others. Court's reasoning: The Court held that an owner seeking to prevent the confiscation of a vehicle must establish on a "balance of probability" that they took all precautions to prevent the offence or that the vehicle was used without their knowledge. The High Court erred by applying the criminal standard of "beyond reasonable doubt" and incorrectly placing this burden on the prosecution. Finding: The High Court Judge erred in law regarding the standard of proof. Issue 2: Burden of Proof Rule applied: Section 3A of the Animals Act. Court's reasoning: The statute places the burden on the owner to satisfy the court regarding the lack of knowledge or the taking of precautions. The High Court improperly shifted this burden to the prosecution and restricted its assessment of the owner's credibility to the examination-in-chief, ignoring the contradictions revealed during cross-examination. Finding: The High Court Judge erred in law by misplacing the burden of proof and failing to consider the entire evidence. Interaction of Issues The errors regarding the standard and burden of proof were inextricably linked to the High Courtâ€™s flawed assessment of the owner's credibility. By incorrectly applying the criminal standard of proof, the High Court failed to properly evaluate the owner's admissions during cross-examination, which demonstrated his prior knowledge of the Accused-Respondent's illegal activities. Correcting the legal standard confirms that the Magistrateâ€™s original finding—that the owner failed to discharge his burden—was correct. Conclusion The appeal of the 1st Respondent-Appellant is allowed. The judgment of the Provincial High Court is set aside, and the order of the Magistrateâ€™s Court of Elpitiya confiscating the vehicle is restored. Keywords Confiscation of vehicle — Animals Act — Burden of proof — Standard of proof — Balance of probability — Credibility of witness — Cross-examination — Interested witness — Knowledge of offence		SC/APPEAL/47/2008	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_47_2008.pdf
sc-appeal-75-2013	15 December 2022	A. E. Logistic (Private) Limited v. Pearl Island Sea Foods (Private) Limited and Others	Achala Wengappuli, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; A.H.M.D. Nawaz, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser	Facts A. E. Logistic (Private) Limited, the Plaintiff-Appellant, provided freight forwarding services to the 1st Defendant-Respondent, Pearl Island Sea Foods (Private) Limited, whose directors were the 2nd and 3rd Respondents. The Appellant Company instituted action in the Commercial High Court to recover Rs. 3,612,219.00, which it claimed was the outstanding balance for services rendered between November 2008 and March 2009. The claim was supported by nine invoices and a Statement of Accounts marked P4. The Respondents denied the debt and filed a claim in reconvention for USD 27,337.42, alleging that a consignment of seafood had perished due to the Appellant Company's failure to handle the cargo properly. During the trial, the Appellant Company's witness admitted that the Statement of Accounts P4 contained inaccuracies, specifically regarding a refund of Rs. 316,966.00 received from an air carrier for a perished consignment. Although the Appellant Company attempted to clarify this during re-examination, the Commercial High Court found that the Statement of Accounts was incomplete and inaccurate. Consequently, the trial court dismissed the Appellant Company's action, concluding that the core issue regarding the specific amount owed had not been proved. The Appellant Company appealed this decision to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Commercial High Court was justified in dismissing the action on the basis that the Statement of Accounts (P4) was inaccurate and failed to prove the amount claimed under Issue No. 3. Whether the Appellant Company failed to discharge its burden of proof under Section 101 of the Evidence Ordinance and Section 150 of the Civil Procedure Code regarding the outstanding debt. Applicable Law Statutes: Evidence Ordinance, Section 101 Civil Procedure Code, Section 146(1) Civil Procedure Code, Section 146(2) Civil Procedure Code, Section 149 Civil Procedure Code, Section 150 (Explanation 2) High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) Act No. 10 of 1996, Section 9 Cases Referred to: Balapitiya Gunananda Thero v. Talalle Methananda Thero - [1997/v2-sri-lr-101] Sri Lanka Ports Authority v. Jugolinija Boal East - [1981/v1-sri-lr-18] Hanaffi v. Nallamma - [1998/v1-sri-lr-73] Fernando v. Ramanathan - [16-nlr-337] Calendar v. Fernando - [2001/v2-sri-lr-355] Seylan Bank Ltd. v. Epasinghe - [sc-appeal-sc-chc-39/06] Hameed v. Cassim - [1996/v2-sri-lr-30] Analysis Issue 1: Accuracy of Statement of Accounts and Proof of Claim Rule applied: Section 146(1) and (2) of the Civil Procedure Code regarding the duty of the court to determine issues as framed. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the Appellant Company specifically framed Issue No. 3 to recover a precise sum of Rs. 3,612,219.00. The Respondents raised an additional issue (No. 34) challenging the accuracy of the Statement of Accounts (P4). The evidence revealed that the Appellant Company had received a refund from the carrier that was not reflected in P4, rendering the document inaccurate. Despite having the opportunity to amend its pleadings or issues after the refund was discovered, the Appellant Company persisted with the original claim. Therefore, the trial court correctly determined that the claim was not proved. Finding: The Commercial High Court was justified in dismissing the action as the pivotal issue remained unproved due to the inaccuracies in the primary evidence relied upon by the Appellant. Issue 2: Burden of Proof Rule applied: Section 101 of the Evidence Ordinance and Explanation 2 of Section 150 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The burden of proof rested on the Appellant Company to establish the exact amount lawfully due. By failing to provide an accurate Statement of Accounts and failing to reconcile the discrepancies in the amount claimed, the Appellant Company failed to discharge this burden. The court emphasized that once issues are crystallized, the parties must lead evidence to support them; the Appellant Company's failure to do so meant the court could not grant the relief sought. Finding: The Appellant Company failed to discharge the burden of proof required to sustain its claim. Interaction of Issues The findings on both issues are intrinsically linked. The failure to discharge the burden of proof (Issue 2) directly resulted from the inability to substantiate the specific amount claimed in the pivotal issue (Issue 1). The inaccuracy of the Statement of Accounts (P4) served as the evidentiary basis for the court's conclusion that the Appellant Company failed to prove its case, thereby making the dismissal of the action the necessary legal consequence. Conclusion The appeal is dismissed as the Appellant Company failed to prove the amount claimed in the pivotal issue. The judgment of the Commercial High Court is affirmed, and the parties shall bear their own costs. Keywords Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Bona fide purchaser		SC/APPEAL/75/2013	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_75_2013.pdf
sc-appeal-167-2016	15 December 2022	Withanachchi v. Jinadasa and Others	A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.	S. Thurairaja, PC, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Partition of land — Admission of corpus — Identity of land — Evidence Ordinance — Withdrawal of admissions — Preliminary Plan	Facts The original Plaintiff instituted an action in the District Court of Elpitiya to partition a land known as Iddagoda Owita. The Plaintiff denied that the 10th Defendant held any rights to the corpus. In the answer, the 10th Defendant disclosed other parties seeking to intervene and claimed that a specific lot depicted as a roadway in the survey plan did not form part of the corpus. At the commencement of the trial, all parties, including the 10th Defendant, explicitly admitted that the land depicted as Lots 1, 2, and 3 in Preliminary Plan No. 2808 constituted the corpus to be partitioned. The District Court entered judgment identifying the land in the aforementioned plan as the corpus. The 10th Defendant appealed to the Civil Appellate High Court of Galle, which set aside the District Court judgment on the basis that the trial judge failed to properly identify the corpus. The Plaintiff subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court, challenging the High Court's determination that further evidence was required to identify the corpus despite the prior admissions made by the parties. Issues Whether parties are required to adduce evidence to identify the corpus in a partition action when the identity of the corpus has been explicitly admitted by all parties at the commencement of the trial. Whether an admission of fact made by a party in the pleadings and during the trial can be withdrawn or disregarded on appeal. Applicable Law Statutes: Partition Act Evidence Ordinance, Section 58 Civil Procedure Code Cases Referred to: Uvais v. Punyawathie - [1993/v2-sri-lr-46] Mariammai v. Pethrupillai - [21-nlr-200] Jayalath v. Karunathilake - [2013/v1-sri-lr-337] Analysis Issue 1: Identification of the corpus Rule applied: Section 58 of the Evidence Ordinance and the principle that admitted facts require no further proof. Court's reasoning: The Court observed that all parties, including the 10th Defendant, had explicitly admitted that the land depicted in Lots 1, 2, and 3 of Plan No. 2808 formed the corpus. Furthermore, during cross-examination, the 10th Defendant repeatedly confirmed that the surveyed land was the correct property and that it comprised the specific lots in question. The Court held that once the subject matter is admitted, no further proof of the identity of the corpus is required, as no party is burdened with adducing evidence for a fact already established by agreement. Finding: The parties are not required to adduce further evidence to identify the corpus when it has been explicitly admitted. Issue 2: Withdrawal of admissions Rule applied: The principle that admissions on questions of fact cannot be withdrawn. Court's reasoning: The Court relied on Uvais v. Punyawathie, which established that while admissions on questions of law may sometimes be withdrawn, admissions on questions of fact cannot. The Court emphasized that allowing the withdrawal of such admissions would subvert fundamental principles of the Civil Procedure Code. Citing Mariammai v. Pethrupillai, the Court noted that a party must stand by an admission made in the court below and cannot argue a contrary position on appeal. Finding: The 10th Defendant is bound by the express and unambiguous admission made regarding the identity of the corpus and cannot be permitted to digress from that assertion. Interaction of Issues The findings on these issues are mutually reinforcing. The determination that the corpus was sufficiently identified through admission (Issue 1) directly precludes the 10th Defendant from attempting to challenge the identity of the land on appeal (Issue 2). Because the admission of fact is binding, the High Courtâ€™s conclusion that the District Court failed to identify the corpus was legally erroneous. Conclusion The appeal is allowed and the judgment of the Civil Appellate High Court dated 12/03/2014 is set aside. The judgment of the District Court is restored. No costs are ordered. Keywords Partition of land — Admission of corpus — Identity of land — Evidence Ordinance — Withdrawal of admissions — Preliminary Plan		SC/APPEAL/167/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_167_2016.pdf
sc-chc-19-2002	16 December 2022	Korea-Ceylon Footwear Manufacturing Company Limited v. Coats Tootal Lanka (Private) Limited and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	contract law — exemption clause — express condition — implied condition — waiver — commercial contract — liability — damages — misrepresentation — chemical attack — suitability — burden of proof — acceptance of goods — business relationship — legal principles	Facts The plaintiff, Korea-Ceylon Footwear Manufacturing Company Limited, initiated legal proceedings against the defendant, Coats Tootal Lanka (Private) Limited, in the Commercial High Court, seeking recovery of Rs. 20,383,451.56 along with interest. The basis of the claim was that the thread supplied by the defendant on two occasions, specifically on 20 May 1994 and 4 June 1994, was defective, leading to significant damages. The plaintiff contended that a foreign buyer rejected a consignment of shoes due to discoloration caused by the dye dispersing from the thread. The plaintiff had previously paid Rs. 62,087.85 for the thread in question. In response, the defendant filed a counterclaim for Rs. 2.5 million, alleging loss of reputation due to the plaintiff's claims. After a trial, the Commercial High Court ruled in favor of the plaintiff, prompting the defendant to appeal. The plaintiff, a shoe manufacturer, argued that the thread was unsuitable for their intended use, which was substantiated by the testimony of their General Manager, Mr. Amunugama. The invoices related to the thread and the conditions of sale were presented as evidence. The defendant maintained that the plaintiff had accepted the thread under the terms specified in the invoices, which included an exemption clause limiting liability for defects. Issues The primary issues before the court were: Whether the defendant could rely on the exemption clause in the contract to limit liability for the defective thread supplied. Whether the express condition regarding the thread's resistance to chemical attack constituted an implied term of the contract, thereby overriding the exemption clause. Whether the plaintiff had waived their right to claim damages due to their continued acceptance of the thread despite previous complaints. Applicable Law Statutes: Sale of Goods Act, 1893 Cases Referred to: Photo Production Ltd v. Securicor Transport Ltd [1980] AC 826; Andrews Brothers (Bournemouth) Ltd v. Singer & Co Ltd [1934] 1 KB 17; Curtis v. Chemical Cleaning and Dyeing Co [1951] 1 KB 805; Hartley v. Hymans [1920] 3 KB 475. Analysis Issue 1: Whether the defendant could rely on the exemption clause in the contract to limit liability for the defective thread supplied. Rule applied: The court examined the validity of the exemption clause contained in the conditions of sale, particularly focusing on whether it could be enforced given the circumstances of the case. The learned High Court Judge had initially ruled that the defendant could not rely on the exemption clause due to the impression created by the defendant regarding the thread's quality. The court noted that an exemption clause is a contractual term that limits liability, and traditionally, courts are cautious in interpreting such clauses, especially when they may disadvantage a weaker party. The judgment referenced the principle that if an exemption clause is clearly worded and the contract is commercial in nature, courts may interpret it more liberally. The court also highlighted that an exemption clause and an express condition cannot coexist; one must supersede the other. The defendant argued that the plaintiff had accepted the thread under the terms specified in the invoices, which included an exemption clause that limited liability for defects. The court found that the plaintiff had indeed accepted the thread subject to the conditions outlined in the invoices, which included a clear stipulation that the purchaser must ensure the thread's suitability for its intended use. The court emphasized that the plaintiff had prior knowledge of issues with the thread, as evidenced by a previous complaint made in 1992 regarding similar problems. The court concluded that the plaintiff's continued acceptance of the thread, despite these issues, amounted to acquiescence or waiver of their right to claim damages. Finding: The court determined that the defendant could rely on the exemption clause to limit liability for the defective thread supplied. Issue 2: Whether the express condition regarding the thread's resistance to chemical attack constituted an implied term of the contract, thereby overriding the exemption clause. Rule applied: The court analyzed whether the condition stated in the defendant's promotional material (P7) regarding the thread's resistance to chemical attack was an express term of the contract. The learned High Court Judge had ruled that this condition created an impression that the thread was suitable for the plaintiff's use, thus overriding the exemption clause. However, the Supreme Court found that there was no evidence to support that P7 was an express condition of the contract between the parties. The court noted that the plaintiff had not produced P7 during the initial stages of the trial, which raised questions about its relevance. The court further stated that the defendant manufactures thread primarily for the apparel industry, and the promotional material should be interpreted in that context. The court highlighted that the plaintiff had not established that the thread was unsuitable for shoe manufacturing based on the evidence presented. The court concluded that the condition in P7 did not override the exemption clause in the invoices. Finding: The court ruled that the express condition regarding the thread's resistance to chemical attack did not constitute an implied term of the contract and did not override the exemption clause. Interaction of Issues The issues were interrelated, as the court's determination on the validity of the exemption clause directly impacted the applicability of the express condition regarding the thread's suitability. The court's analysis revealed that the plaintiff's acceptance of the thread under the specified conditions, coupled with their prior knowledge of potential issues, significantly influenced the outcome of both issues. Conclusion The Supreme Court set aside the judgment of the Commercial High Court, allowing the appeal of the defendant. The plaintiff's action was dismissed, and no order was made regarding costs. The court's decision underscored the importance of contractual terms and the implications of acceptance and waiver in commercial transactions. The ruling clarified the enforceability of exemption clauses and the necessity for parties to ensure that express conditions are clearly articulated within the contractual framework. Keywords contract law — exemption clause — express condition — implied condition — waiver — commercial contract — liability — damages — misrepresentation — chemical attack — suitability — burden of proof — acceptance of goods — business relationship — legal principles	Sanjeeva Jayawardena, P.C., with Lakmini Warusevitane for the Defendant-Appellant. Avindra Rodrigo, P.C., with Akiel Deen for the Plaintiff-Respondent.	SC/CHC APPEAL/19/2002	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_chc_apleal_19_2002.pdf
sc-appeal-167-2012	16 December 2022	Selvanathan and Others v. Jayatilleke and Others	Priyantha Jayawardena, PC J	Priyantha Jayawardena, PC J; L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Murdu Fernando, PC, J.	Excise duty — Determination of excise duty — Show cause notice — Appeal against determination — Certificate of excise duty in default — Validity of proceedings — Section 9 of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act — Section 12 of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act	Facts The 10th appellant, Ceylon Brewery PLC, was a manufacturer of beer products, while the 1st to 9th appellants served as its directors. The 1st respondent was the Director-General of Excise, and the 2nd respondent was the Assistant Director of Excise. A dispute arose regarding the calculation of excise duty on beer, specifically whether it should be based on the ex-factory price or the wholesale price. The excise authorities issued a show cause notice under Section 9(1) of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act No. 13 of 1980, to which the company responded. Subsequently, a second show cause notice was issued for a higher amount. The company later made a declaration under the Inland Revenue (Special Provisions) Act No. 10 of 2003, which was acknowledged by the Commissioner-General of Inland Revenue. Following the repeal of this Act by the Inland Revenue (Regulation of Amnesty) Act No. 10 of 2004, the Director-General of Excise reopened the inquiry and issued a final notice demanding payment of excise duty and penalties. The Director-General of Excise then filed a certificate under Section 12(1) of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act in the Magistrates Court of Fort to recover the alleged arrears. The appellants challenged these proceedings in the Court of Appeal, which dismissed their application. The appellants subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether a valid determination was made by the Director-General of Excise in terms of Section 9(2) of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act No. 13 of 1980. Whether the certificate issued under Section 12(1) of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act No. 13 of 1980 was validly issued to initiate recovery proceedings. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 128(2) Excise (Special Provisions) Act No. 13 of 1980 Inland Revenue (Special Provisions) Act No. 10 of 2003 Inland Revenue (Regulation of Amnesty) Act No. 10 of 2004 Code of Criminal Procedure Act No. 15 of 1979 Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Validity of the determination under Section 9(2) Rule applied: Section 9(2) of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act No. 13 of 1980, which requires the Director-General of Excise to consider representations and determine the amount of excise duty due. Court's reasoning: The Court examined two documents relied upon by the respondents as "determinations." It found that the final notice (P30a) was merely a notice and not a determination. Regarding the letter (P21), the Court noted that the amount demanded exceeded the sum specified in the underlying show cause notice (P16a), violating the statutory requirement that the determined amount cannot exceed the amount specified in the notice. Furthermore, P21 was issued by a Deputy Director, not the Director-General. Finding: There was no valid determination made by the Director-General of Excise in terms of Section 9(2). Issue 2: Validity of the certificate under Section 12(1) Rule applied: Section 12(1) of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act No. 13 of 1980, which allows for the issuance of a certificate for the recovery of excise duty in default. Court's reasoning: The Court held that a determination under Section 9(2) is a condition precedent to invoking Section 12. Because no valid determination existed, the excise duty could not be deemed to be in "default" as contemplated by the Act. Consequently, the certificate (P39) issued by the Director-General was ultra vires. Finding: The certificate issued under Section 12(1) was invalid and the resulting proceedings in the Magistrates Court were quashed. Interaction of Issues The findings are intrinsically linked; the invalidity of the determination under Section 9(2) directly rendered the certificate issued under Section 12(1) legally unsustainable. Without a valid determination, the statutory mechanism for recovery cannot be triggered. Conclusion The appeal is allowed and the judgment of the Court of Appeal is set aside. The Director-General of Excise is directed to consider the representations made by the appellant company regarding the second show cause notice and to make a valid determination under Section 9(2) of the Act within six months. Keywords Excise duty — Determination of excise duty — Show cause notice — Appeal against determination — Certificate of excise duty in default — Validity of proceedings — Section 9 of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act — Section 12 of the Excise (Special Provisions) Act		SC/APPEAL/167/2012	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_167_2012.pdf
sc-appeal-48/2015	16 December 2022	Asia Prepress (Pvt) Limited v. Minnette De Silva (Pvt) Limited	Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.; Arjuna Obeyesekere, J.	Contract formation — Acceptance of offer — Authority to contract — Unjust enrichment — Breach of contract — Intention to create legal relations — Meeting of minds — Limited liability company — Copyright — Publication of autobiography	Facts Asia Prepress (Pvt) Limited, the Appellant, provided typesetting, scanning, and pagination services for the publication of a book titled "Minnette De Silva - The life and work of an Asian woman architect." The Appellant instituted action in the District Court of Colombo against Minnette De Silva (Pvt) Limited, the Respondent, to recover an outstanding balance of Rs. 1,061,974.74, alleging breach of contract. The Appellant also pleaded an alternative cause of action based on unjust enrichment. The Respondent denied the existence of a contract, contending that the work was commissioned by Minnette De Silva in her personal capacity and that the Respondent was not a party to the agreement. The District Court found in favor of the Appellant, concluding that a contract existed between the parties. The Provincial High Court subsequently set aside the District Court judgment, holding that Minnette De Silva lacked authority to bind the Respondent at the time of the agreement and that the Respondent was not liable for her personal obligations. The Appellant appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether a valid contract was formed between the Appellant and the Respondent regarding the publication of the book, rendering the Respondent liable for the outstanding payment. Whether the Respondent was unjustly enriched by the services provided by the Appellant. Applicable Law Statutes: Companies Act Cases Referred to: Noorbhai v. Karuppan Chetty - [27-nlr-325] Analysis Issue 1: Formation of Contract Rule applied: The court applied the objective test for contract formation, requiring a "consensus ad idem" and an intention to create legal relations, as established in Noorbhai v. Karuppan Chetty and discussed in Weeramantryâ€™s Law of Contracts. Court's reasoning: The court analyzed the correspondence between the parties, specifically the acceptance of the Appellant's offer via document P11. Although Minnette De Silva was not a director at the time of signing P11, the court found that the Respondentâ€™s subsequent conduct—including direct communication with the Appellant, the use of official letterheads, and the issuance of payments from the Respondentâ€™s corporate account—demonstrated a clear intention to be bound. The court rejected the Respondent's argument that these payments were made on behalf of a third party, noting that the Respondent failed to lead evidence to support this claim and that the payments were consistent with an existing contractual obligation. Finding: The court held that a valid contract existed between the Appellant and the Respondent, and the Respondent is liable for the outstanding balance. Issue 2: Unjust Enrichment Rule applied: The principle of unjust enrichment as a basis for recovery where a party benefits from services rendered without compensation. Court's reasoning: The court observed that the Respondent held the copyright to the book and benefited from the Appellant's services. While the court noted that the evidence was sufficient to support a claim for unjust enrichment, it determined that this issue was secondary to the finding of a breach of contract. Finding: The court found that the Appellant had established the grounds for unjust enrichment, though the primary finding of breach of contract rendered a detailed analysis of this issue unnecessary. Interaction of Issues The court's finding that a valid contract existed between the parties resolved the dispute, making the alternative claim of unjust enrichment moot. The evidence supporting the contract (the conduct of the parties and payments made) simultaneously reinforced the conclusion that the Respondent had been unjustly enriched by the Appellant's services. Conclusion The appeal is allowed, the judgment of the High Court is set aside, and the judgment of the District Court is affirmed. The Respondent is ordered to pay the Appellant the sum of Rs. 1,061,974.74 with legal interest and costs of proceedings across all three courts. Keywords Contract formation — Acceptance of offer — Authority to contract — Unjust enrichment — Breach of contract — Intention to create legal relations — Meeting of minds — Limited liability company — Copyright — Publication of autobiography			
sc-appeal-17-2016	16 December 2022	Ratnasara Thero and Sri Sidhartha Ramaya v. Sri Lanka Land Reclamation and Development Corporation	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Kumuduni Wickremasinghe, J; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Substitution of parties — Section 404 of the Civil Procedure Code — Action rei vindicatio — Transfer of title pendente lite — Roman Dutch Law — Voet — Continuation of actions after alteration of party status — Fundamental rights — Judicial discretion	Facts The original plaintiff filed an action in the District Court of Colombo seeking a declaration of title to land, ejectment of the defendant, and damages. During the pendency of the action, the original plaintiff passed away. An application for substitution was filed under section 404 of the Civil Procedure Code to substitute Arumugam Rasalingam as the plaintiff, based on a deed of transfer executed by the original plaintiff prior to his death. The defendant filed objections to the substitution, primarily alleging that the deed was a forgery. The District Court allowed the application for substitution, and this order was not appealed by the defendant. Subsequently, during the cross-examination of the substituted plaintiff, the defendant raised new issues regarding whether the original plaintiff had transferred his rights in the land pending the action and whether the action could be maintained if such a transfer occurred. The District Court answered these issues against the substituted plaintiff, relying on Roman Dutch Law principles, and dismissed the action on the basis that a plaintiff in a rei vindicatio action must possess title until the conclusion of the case. The High Court of Civil Appeal affirmed this dismissal, leading to the present appeal. Issues Whether the defendant was precluded from reagitating the issue of the plaintiff's title after the court had already allowed the substitution of the plaintiff under section 404 of the Civil Procedure Code. Whether a rei vindicatio action must be dismissed if the plaintiff transfers title to the subject matter of the action pendente lite, notwithstanding the provisions of section 404 of the Civil Procedure Code. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code, Section 34 Civil Procedure Code, Section 404 Cases Referred to: Ponnamma v. Weerasuriya - [11-nlr-217] Silva v. Jayawardena - [43-nlr-551] Eugin Fernando v. Charles Perera - [1988/v2-sri-lr-288] Banda v. Karohamy - [50-nlr-369] Cassim v. Government Agent, Batticaloa - [69-nlr-403] Eliashamy v. Punchi Banda - [14-nlr-113] Fernando v. Appuhamy - [23-nlr-476] De Silva v. Goonetileke - [32-nlr-217] Oman Ekanayake v. Ratranhamy - [2012-blr-19] Dhammananda Thero v. Saddananda Thero - [79/v1-nlr-289] Murugesu v. Gunaratne - [ca/la/29/79] Kandasamy v. Meenambikai - [ca/la/17/79] Pless Pol v. De Soysa - [10-nlr-252] Pless Pol v. Lady De Soysa - [15-nlr-57] Daniel Silva v. Jayasekere - [46-nlr-316] Paaris v. Bridget Fernando - [1992/v1-sri-lr-36] Perera v. Ramaiah - [1997/v1-sri-lr-225] Cinemas Ltd v. Soundarajan - [1998/v2-sri-lr-16] Seneviratne v. Fernando - [2001/v3-sri-lr-72] Analysis Issue 1: Preclusion of Reagitation Rule applied: The principle of finality in litigation and the prohibition against piecemeal defense. Court's reasoning: The court held that the defendant had the opportunity to challenge the substitution based on the deed at the time of the initial application. By failing to appeal the order allowing substitution and instead raising the issue mid-trial, the defendant attempted to reagitate a settled matter. The court emphasized that litigation must have an end and that a defendant cannot take up defenses piecemeal. Finding: The defendant was precluded from reagitating the issue of title transfer as a ground for dismissal after the substitution order had become final. Issue 2: Maintenance of Action Pendente Lite Rule applied: Section 404 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The court rejected the mechanical application of the Roman Dutch Law principle (as articulated by Voet) which suggests that a rei vindicatio action must fail if title is lost pendente lite. The court reasoned that section 404 of the Civil Procedure Code provides a specific statutory mechanism for the continuation of an action following the devolution of interest. The court held that procedural and substantive laws are interwoven here, and section 404 overrides the older Roman Dutch Law rule, allowing the court to exercise discretion to permit the action to continue with the substituted party. Finding: The action can be maintained by the substituted plaintiff despite the transfer of title pendente lite. Interaction of Issues The findings are mutually reinforcing. The court's determination that the defendant was barred from re-opening the substitution issue (Issue 1) aligns with the broader interpretation of section 404 (Issue 2), which prioritizes the continuation of litigation on its merits over rigid, outdated procedural technicalities. Conclusion The appeal is allowed, and the orders of the District Court and the High Court of Civil Appeal are set aside. The trial is to proceed from the stage at which it was interrupted, with the parties permitted to raise additional issues if necessary. Keywords Substitution of parties — Section 404 of the Civil Procedure Code — Action rei vindicatio — Transfer of title pendente lite — Roman Dutch Law — Voet — Continuation of actions after alteration of party status — Fundamental rights — Judicial discretion		SC/FR/17/2016	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_fr_17_2016.pdf
sc-appeal-189-2017	16 December 2022	Edama v. Somasiri and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Yasantha Kodagoda, PC, J.; Janak De Silva, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Land ownership — Identification of land — Deeds of title — Prescriptive title — Section 66 application — District Court judgment — High Court judgment — Paper title — Adverse possession	Facts The Plaintiff, Henri Edama, initiated an action in the District Court of Bandarawela seeking a declaration of title to a land described in the first schedule of the plaint, the ejectment of the Defendant, A.L.G. Somasiri, from a portion of that land described in the second schedule, and damages. The Defendant filed an answer requesting the dismissal of the action, a declaration of title to the disputed portion via prescription and deeds, and compensation for malicious prosecution. Following a trial, the District Court entered judgment in favor of the Plaintiff. The Defendant appealed to the High Court of Civil Appeal of Badulla, which set aside the District Court judgment and dismissed the Plaintiff's action. The Plaintiff subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that the Plaintiff failed to identify the land in suit. Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that the land claimed by the Defendant tallies with the land depicted in plan V22. Whether the High Court erred in law by holding that the Plaintiff failed to prove title to the land. Applicable Law Statutes: Civil Procedure Code Cases Referred to: Not specified Analysis Issue 1: Identification of the land Rule applied: The court applied the principle that the identification of land is a mixed question of fact and law that cannot be raised for the first time on appeal. Court's reasoning: The court found that the issue of identification was not raised before the District Court. The Defendant had expressly identified the disputed land as lot 1 in plan No. 6049 in his answer. Furthermore, the surveyor who prepared plan No. 6049 testified that it was based on the superimposition of plan No. 205, which was part of the evidence (P7). The High Courtâ€™s conclusion that the land was not identified was deemed a perverse finding resulting from a failure to properly review the case record. Finding: The High Court erred in law by dismissing the action on the basis of non-identification. Issue 2: Accuracy of plan V22 Rule applied: The court applied the standard of evidentiary review regarding the consistency of land descriptions in deeds versus survey plans. Court's reasoning: The High Court incorrectly held that the Defendant's deeds tallied with plan V22. The Supreme Court noted that plan V22 was prepared seven years after the action was instituted and depicted an extent of 11.3 perches, whereas the deeds described an extent equivalent to 4.7 perches. The court emphasized that the Defendant had already identified the disputed land in plan X, rendering reliance on V22 unnecessary. Finding: The High Court erred in its assessment of the evidence regarding the land's extent and the relevance of plan V22. Issue 3: Proof of title Rule applied: The court applied the principle that an appellate court must provide reasons when reversing a trial court's finding on title, and that new factual arguments cannot be introduced for the first time on appeal. Court's reasoning: The District Court had accepted the Plaintiff's title deeds and declared him the paper title holder. The High Court failed to provide any reasoning for reversing this finding or to address the Defendant's primary claim of prescriptive title. Additionally, the Defendant's attempt to argue that the parties' deeds referred to different lands in different villages was rejected as a new factual argument that could not be raised at the Supreme Court level. Finding: The High Court erred in law by failing to justify the reversal of the District Court's findings on title. Interaction of Issues The court's findings are interconnected as the High Court's erroneous determination on the identification of the land (Issue 1) and the misinterpretation of the survey evidence (Issue 2) led to an unjustified reversal of the District Court's findings on title (Issue 3). By failing to address the core issue of prescription and ignoring the established evidence of the Plaintiff's paper title, the High Courtâ€™s judgment lacked a sound legal and factual basis. Conclusion The Supreme Court set aside the judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal of Badulla and restored the judgment of the District Court. The appeal is allowed with costs. Keywords Land ownership — Identification of land — Deeds of title — Prescriptive title — Section 66 application — District Court judgment — High Court judgment — Paper title — Adverse possession		SC/APPEAL/189/2017	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_189_2017.pdf
sc-appeal-200/2017	16 December 2022	L. Ajith Thilakaratne de Silva Seneviratne v. Central Finance PLC	Achala Wengappuli, J.	L.T.B. Dehideniya, J.; A.L. Shiran Gooneratne, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.	Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Settlement — Amended decree — Writ of execution — Section 344 of the Civil Procedure Code — Section 410 of the Civil Procedure Code — Interest on transport costs — Res judicata	Facts The Plaintiff, L. Ajith Thilakaratne de Silva, entered into a hire purchase agreement with the Defendant, Central Finance PLC, regarding a motor vehicle. Following an alleged illegal seizure of the vehicle by the Defendant, the Plaintiff instituted an action in the District Court of Chilaw claiming compensation under four causes of action. The trial Court entered judgment in favor of the Plaintiff, and an amended decree was subsequently signed on 12.01.2011. This amended decree included a paragraph (paragraph wd) awarding the Plaintiff compensation for transport costs and interest. The Defendant filed objections to the amended decree under Section 189 of the Civil Procedure Code, which the District Court dismissed on 24.10.2012. The Defendant did not appeal this order. Subsequently, the Plaintiff applied for a Writ of Execution based on the amended decree. The Defendant then filed an application under Sections 344 and 839 of the Civil Procedure Code to stay the execution and recall or amend the decree. The District Court dismissed this application on 05.06.2013, citing that the matter was res judicata and that the application exceeded the scope of Section 344. The Civil Appeal High Court set aside the District Court's order, prompting the Plaintiff to appeal to the Supreme Court. Issues Whether the Civil Appeal High Court erred in law by failing to recognize that the entitlement to relief under the amended decree had become res judicata between the parties. Whether the Civil Appeal High Court erred in its interpretation and application of Section 344 of the Civil Procedure Code regarding the scope of inquiry into the execution of a decree. Whether the Civil Appeal High Court erred in its interpretation of Sections 409, 410, and 411 of the Civil Procedure Code regarding the Plaintiff's entitlement to interest after a deposit was made in Court. Applicable Law Statutes: Constitution of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka, Article 128(2) Civil Procedure Code, Sections 189, 192(1), 217, 218, 223, 224, 225(1), 225(3), 325, 344, 394, 409, 410, 411, 412, 413, 414, 839 High Court of the Provinces (Special Provisions) (Amendment) Act No. 54 Cases Referred to: Bandara v Attygalle - [30-nlr-109] Surangi v Rodrigo - [2003/v3-sri-lr-35] Mohamed Iqbal and Another v Mohamed Sally and Another - [1995/v2-sri-lr-310] Punchibanda v Punchibanda et al. - [42-nlr-382] Roslin v Maryhamy - [1994/v1-sri-lr-262] Dharmadasa v Piyadasa and Others - [2008/B.L.R.-208] Dabera v Marikar - [1-scr-210] Tikiri Menika v Deonis - [7-nlr-337] Perera v Fernando - [32-nlr-119] Dharmasiri v Wickrematunga - [2002/v2-sri-lr-218] Jane Nona and Another v Padmakumara and Others - [2003/v2-sri-lr-118] Jamaldeen Abdul Latheef and Another v Abdul Majeed Mohamed Mansoor and Another - [ca-37/96] Hanaffi v Nallamma - [1998/v1-sri-lr-73] Marjan et al v Burah et al - [51-nlr-34] Hamid v Marikkar et al - [52-nlr-269] Jayalath et al v Abdul Razak et al - [56-nlr-145] Chinnathamby v Somasundera Aiyar - [48-nlr-515] De Silva v Industrial Finance Ltd - [2003/v2-sri-lr-193] Sirinivasa Thero v Sudassi Thero - [63-nlr-31] Ramen Chetty v Frederick Appuhamy - [9-nlr-133] Analysis Issue 1: Res Judicata and Finality Rule applied: The principle that a decree of a court of competent jurisdiction is binding until set aside by an appellate tribunal. Court's reasoning: The Court noted that the Defendant's objection to the amended decree under Section 189 was dismissed on 24.10.2012. The Defendant failed to appeal this order. Consequently, the validity of the amended decree, including the disputed paragraph, reached finality. The Defendant could not re-agitate this issue through a subsequent application under Section 344. Finding: The Civil Appeal High Court erred by reviewing matters that had already been decided and had become res judicata. Issue 2: Scope of Section 344 Rule applied: Section 344 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: Section 344 permits a court to determine questions relating to the execution of a decree. However, it does not authorize a court to re-open or interpret the underlying judgment or the decree itself, especially when the decree is in conformity with the judgment. The Defendant's attempt to challenge the inclusion of paragraph 'wd' was an indirect attack on the decree's validity, which is outside the scope of Section 344. Finding: The Civil Appeal High Court took an erroneous view of the scope of Section 344. Issue 3: Interest and Deposits Rule applied: Sections 409, 410, and 411 of the Civil Procedure Code. Court's reasoning: The Court held that these sections apply to deposits made during the pendency of an action. In this case, the deposit was made as part of a settlement after judgment. The entitlement to interest was governed by the terms of the settlement, not by the statutory provisions for pre-judgment deposits. Finding: The Civil Appeal High Court erred in its interpretation of Section 410. Interaction of Issues The findings are interconnected: because the validity of the amended decree was settled by the unappealed order of 24.10.2012, the Defendant's application under Section 344 was procedurally improper. The High Court's failure to recognize this finality led it to incorrectly apply Section 344 and misinterpret the statutory provisions regarding interest, effectively nullifying a valid, unchallenged decree. Conclusion The appeal of the Plaintiff is allowed. The judgment of the Civil Appeal High Court is set aside, and the order of the District Court dated 05.06.2013, along with the Writ of Execution dated 10.12.2012, is restored. Keywords Motor vehicle possession — Entitlement to possession — Settlement — Amended decree — Writ of execution — Section 344 of the Civil Procedure Code — Section 410 of the Civil Procedure Code — Interest on transport costs — Res judicata			
sc-appeal-76-2021	16 December 2022	Ven. Habarakada Soratha Thero v. Gunadasa and Others	Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	P. Padman Surasena, J.; Achala Wengappuli, J.; Mahinda Samayawardhena, J.	Rei vindicatio action — Buddhist temple property — Prescriptive title — Title to land — Identification of land — Buddhist Temporalities Ordinance — Prescription Ordinance — Superior title — Onus of proof	Facts The Plaintiff, a Buddhist monk, initiated a rei vindicatio action in the District Court of Galle seeking a declaration of title to a land belonging to the Sri Wardhanarama Purana Viharaya, the ejectment of the 1st Defendant, and damages. The Plaintiff relied on a title deed from 1838 and a series of subsequent lease and mortgage deeds executed between 1937 and 1999 to establish the temple's ownership. The 1st Defendant claimed prescriptive title to the land. The District Court dismissed the Plaintiff's action, finding that the Plaintiff failed to prove title and that the 1st Defendant had acquired prescriptive title. On appeal, the High Court of Civil Appeal set aside the District Court's judgment and entered judgment for the Plaintiff, excluding the claim for damages. The 1st Defendant subsequently appealed to the Supreme Court. The Supreme Court examined whether the Plaintiff had sufficiently identified the land and proved title, and whether the 1st Defendant could successfully claim prescriptive title against temple property. Issues Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in law by failing to consider that the Plaintiff failed to identify the land described in the plaint as required by law. Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in law by failing to consider that the land referred to in the title deed (P2) is different from the land described in the plaint. Whether the High Court of Civil Appeal erred in law by failing to consider that the Plaintiff failed to strictly prove title to the land. Applicable Law Statutes: Buddhist Temporalities Ordinance, Section 34 Cases Referred to: Banda v. Soyza - [1998/v1-sri-lr-255] Sarajudeen v. Abbas - [1994/v2-sri-lr-365] Waharaka alias Moratota Sobhita Thero v. Amunugama Ratnapala Thero - [1981/v1-sri-lr-201] Analysis Issue 1: Identification of the land Rule applied: The standard of proof in a rei vindicatio action is the balance of probabilities, not proof beyond reasonable doubt. Court's reasoning: The court noted that the District Judge had already accepted that the land described in the plaint was the same land depicted in the survey plan P1. The High Court did not disturb this finding. The evidence showed that the boundaries in the lease/mortgage deeds (P8-P14) tallied with the boundaries in plan P1. The court found the name "Unnansege Liyadda" (Priest's Field) to be consistent with the land's status as temple property. Finding: The land was sufficiently identified. Issue 2: Discrepancy in title deeds Rule applied: The court must consider the totality of the evidence to determine who holds the superior title. Court's reasoning: While the 1838 deed (P2) lacked a survey plan and specific boundaries, the Plaintiff established a nexus through subsequent deeds (P8-P14) that consistently referred to the land as "Kirimatimulle Paragahaowita." The court rejected the 1st Defendant's claim that the land was a "no-man's-land" and found the evidence of the 1st Defendant's daughter regarding the land's history to be unsubstantiated and false. Finding: The Plaintiff sufficiently proved title to the land. Issue 3: Prescriptive title against temple property Rule applied: Section 34 of the Buddhist Temporalities Ordinance. Court's reasoning: The court held that, as a matter of law, prescription does not operate against temple properties. Citing Waharaka alias Moratota Sobhita Thero v. Amunugama Ratnapala Thero, the court affirmed that claims for the recovery of temple property are not barred by the Prescription Ordinance. Finding: The 1st Defendant could not acquire title by prescription against the temple. Interaction of Issues The findings on identification and title were reinforced by the legal bar against prescription. Because the Plaintiff established superior title and the land was identified as temple property, the 1st Defendant's claim of prescriptive possession was rendered legally impossible under the Buddhist Temporalities Ordinance. Conclusion The Supreme Court answered the questions of law in the negative and affirmed the judgment of the High Court of Civil Appeal. The appeal was dismissed without costs, and the District Court was directed to enter judgment for the Plaintiff as prayed for in the amended plaint. Keywords Rei vindicatio action — Buddhist temple property — Prescriptive title — Title to land — Identification of land — Buddhist Temporalities Ordinance — Prescription Ordinance — Superior title — Onus of proof		SC/APPEAL/76/2021	https://supremecourt.lk/wp-content/uploads/judgements/sc_appeal_76_2021.pdf
